0.title: Fairhaven Surf Life Saving Club
0.summary: Fairhaven is a well known surf beach. The beach is patrolled during December to the Easter. The Fairhaven SLSC was established in 1958.

1.title: Beach walk
1.summary: From Sprout Creek, Eastern View, Moggs Creek, Fairhaven to the bottom of the light house there is approx 6 km of beach, featuring rolling surf and spectacular views of the Otway Ranges and Lorne.

2.title: Rock pools
2.summary: See what sort of shells and stones you can collect. Can you find a bright red sea star? You can see all sorts of sea vegetation, small fish and crabs. Look at the bird life, gulls and cormorants.

3.title: Sand dunes
3.summary: The beautiful rolling sand dunes shape the beach. 2011 has seen significant erosion due to winter storms that have bought strong winds and big waves (up to 10 feet).

4.title: Painkalac Creek
4.summary: The creek separates Aireys Inlet from Fairhaven and forms an inlet behind the sand dunes before it cuts through to the ocean. A great place to shelter from the wind and for younger children to swim.

5.title: Rocks and caves under the light house
5.summary: There are more rockpools and rocky outcrops to explore under the light house. This area is part of the marine national park. This means that all wildlife is protected and cannot be removed.

6.title: Aireys Inlet playground and picnic ground
6.summary: There is small skateboard ramp for children to ride their scooters or skateboards. There are also swings and other play equipment for children and a picnic area.

7.title: Aireys Inlet lower shops
7.summary: Pick up a coffee, newspaper or Fish and Chips! To the left of the shops, on the other side of the river, kangaroos can be seen in the early morning or at dusk.

8.title: Loutit Bay lookout
8.summary: Return to Painkalac Creek inlet and walk to the grassed area on the left. At the light house bollard turn right and walk up the signed (steep) walking track. Enjoy panaromic views on your walk up.

osm.name: Loutit Bay Lookout
osm.display_name: Loutit Bay Lookout, Surf Coast Walk, Aireys Inlet, Surf Coast Shire, Victoria, 3231, Australia

9.title: Historical homestead and building
9.summary: At the lighthouse is the original homestead for the lighthouse keeper. The Aireys Inlet area was first settled in the 1840s. The first tourists arrived in 1919.

10.title: Split Point Lighthouse
10.summary: Follow the signs and continue up the walking track. Shipping along the Victorian coast was much safer once the combination of this and other lighthouses at Cape Otway and Point Lonsdale were built.

11.title: 1. Tramway signal box
11.summary: Built in 1928 soon after the electrification of the Swanston St and St Kilda Rd cable tramways. Originally included female public toilets, roofed passenger waiting area, small store and staff toilets.

12.title: 2. City Baths
12.summary: Built in 1903, the design reflected the social conventions of the time. Men and women were segregated for all facilities; second class baths were in the basement, first class on the main floor.

osm.name: Melbourne City Baths
osm.display_name: Melbourne City Baths, Victoria Street, East End Theatre District, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

13.title: 3. Magistrates Court
13.summary: Built on the site of the earlier Supreme Court, the building retains fittings from the earlier court including the Gothic canopy that judge Sir Redmond Barry sat under during Ned Kelly trial in 1880.

14.title: 4. Old Melbourne Gaol
14.summary: Built between 1851 - 1864. As the oldest surviving penal establishment, it was the site where Ned Kelly was imprisoned, executed and buried, amongst many other criminals.

osm.name: Old Melbourne Gaol
osm.display_name: Old Melbourne Gaol, 377, Russell Street, East End Theatre District, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

15.title: 5. Eight Hour Day Monument
15.summary: Built in 1923, the monument commemorates the Eight Hour Day movement started by stonemasons in 1856 to improve working conditions - eight hours labour, eight hours rest and eight hours recreation.

16.title: 6. Trades Hall
16.summary: Built in stages from 1873 - 1926, Trades Hall is of historical and social significance as a centre of radical and working class politics and activism in Victoria for over 100 years.

osm.name: Victorian Trades Hall
osm.display_name: Victorian Trades Hall, 54, Victoria Street, Carlton, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3053, Australia

17.title: 7. Medley Hall
17.summary: Built in 1893 as a private residence, the building has since housed the Italian Club, Italian Consulate and for short time was used for a 'less reputable purpose'.

osm.name: Medley Hall
osm.display_name: Medley Hall, 48-56, Drummond Street, Carlton, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3053, Australia

18.title: 8. Lygon shop corner
18.summary: Lygon Buildings is architecturally significant as the largest and most intact terrace of nineteenth century shops in Melbourne. There are no other comparable retail structures in Melbourne.

19.title: 9. Matthais House
19.summary: A two storeyed stucco faced bluestone house of 1865-6 with many charming and unusual features - a tower and weathervane, a cantilevered cast iron balcony and delicately glazed arched windows.

20.title: 10. Sacred Heart Catholic Church
20.summary: Built in 1855-56. In the 1930s and 1940s the Church of the Sacred Heart became a primary focus for Carlton's Italian community, and this continued into the 1960s.

21.title: 11. IMAX Theatre
21.summary: IMAX is the world's largest cinema format, with a screen up to eight storeys high. Films, from documentaries to latest release movies, can be experienced in 2D or 3D.

22.title: 12. Melbourne Museum
22.summary: The museum has eight galleries, including one just for children. Highlights include a complete skeleton of a blue whale, the Bunjilaka Aboriginal Cultural Centre, a living rainforest and Phar Lap.

osm.name: Melbourne Museum
osm.display_name: Melbourne Museum, 11, Nicholson Street, Carlton, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3053, Australia

23.title: 13. Royal Exhibition Building
23.summary: The Royal Exhibition Building is the only surviving Great Hall that once housed a 19th-century international exhibition and is still used for exhibitions.

osm.name: Royal Exhibition Building
osm.display_name: Royal Exhibition Building, 9, Nicholson Street, Carlton, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3053, Australia

24.title: 14. Carlton Gardens
24.summary: Developed in 19th-century Gardenesque style, the Gardens feature symmetrically-placed garden beds, significant avenues, the path system, specimen and clusters of trees, 2 small lakes and 3 fountains.

osm.name: Carlton Gardens
osm.display_name: Carlton Gardens, East End Theatre District, Carlton, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

25.title: 15. Playground
25.summary: Wonderful playground with swings, slides and many opportunities to climb and clamber, plus small hills to roll down!

26.title: 16. Carlton Gardens Primary School
26.summary: The school is an Italian Gothic style building built in 1884 with a hipped roof central pavilion buttressed either end by slightly projecting gables.

osm.name: Carlton Gardens Primary School
osm.display_name: Carlton Gardens Primary School, 201-231, Rathdowne Street, Carlton, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3053, Australia

27.title: 17. Terrace Houses (201 - 205 Drummond Street)
27.summary: Built in 1884, Holcombe Terrace is a fine example of boom style terrace architecture and notable among the works of Norman Hitchcock.

28.title: 18. Museo Italiano
28.summary: Museo Italiano displays and interprets the experience of Italian migration, and the culture created by Italians in Australia.

osm.name: Museo Italiano
osm.display_name: Museo Italiano, 199, Faraday Street, Little Italy, Carlton, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3053, Australia

29.title: 19. La Mama Theatre
29.summary: Built in 1883, the building was used for various industrial purposes. In 1967, it was leased by Betty Burstall, teacher and theatre-lover, for use as a small theatre to nurture new Australian drama.

osm.name: La Mama Theatre
osm.display_name: La Mama Theatre, 205, Faraday Street, Little Italy, Carlton, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3053, Australia

30.title: 19. Underground public toilets
30.summary: The underground public toilets, built in 1939, are one of eleven built in Melbourne in response to public demand for public toilet facilities in Melbourne that were both sanitary and discreet.

31.title: 21. 313-315 Drummond Street
31.summary: Built in 1889, the buliding is architecturally significant for its highly unusual grotesque Gothic facade. The kangaroo-gryphon grotesques on the parapet are highly unusual and distinctive.

osm.name: Drummond Street
osm.display_name: Drummond Street, Carlton, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3053, Australia

32.title: 22. Carlton Court House
32.summary: The Carlton Court House is historically significant as part of the civic core of Drummond Street. It is directly opposite the 1878 Carlton Police Station.

osm.name: Carlton Court House Historic Reserve
osm.display_name: Carlton Court House Historic Reserve, Carlton, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3053, Australia

33.title: The Mildura Wharf
33.summary: Mildura Wharf has been a vital part of the town and inland river transport system since the 1880s. It was established by the Mildura Progress Committee in 1888 to assist the burgeoning river trade.

34.title: Railway overpass
34.summary: A short walk across the railway overpass leads to Deakin Ave or head left down to the Hugh King Drive underpass to avoid the stairs.

35.title: Prince and Princess of Wales Fountain Plaza
35.summary: This fountain is very special as it was opened by the Prince and Princess of Wales on the 29th October 1985. Many Mildura residence crowded around to see the Princess Diana.

36.title: War Memorial
36.summary:
To the left is a War Memorial commemorating those who served in Vietnam, Korea
and South East Asia.

37.title: Sculpture commemorating Alfred Deakin, Primie Minister of Australia and the initiator of the Mildura
37.summary: Sculpted by Michael Meszaros and presented to the city to mark the centenary of the irrigation colony in 1987. The memorial represents  fruit blocks and irrigation channels as seen from the air.

38.title: The Grand Hotel (to the right)
38.summary: Enter the Grand Hotel’s main entrance and turn left. To your right, you will see a display of historical photos. Through the glass doors are one of Mildura’s original Chaffey fountains.

39.title: Commodore Motel former site of the Warren boarding house
39.summary: Back in 1888, this site was a early boarding house called the Warren. A plaque marking the site can be found at the entrance to the motel’s restaurant. The Warren was demolished in 1965.

40.title: WIN TV
40.summary: Originally STV8, opening in 1966 and next door is the Sunraysia Daily, the local newspaper.

41.title: The Cultivator
41.summary:
Mildura’s earliest newspaper was the Cultivator, begun in 1888. It was a
twice-weekly publication that moved to the current Sunraysia Daily site at
22 Deakin Avenue in 1912.

42.title: Sunraysia Daily
42.summary:
Local identity, C.J De Garis bought The Cultivator along with the Mildura
Telegraph and Merbein Irrigationist and merged them into one paper, the
Sunraysia Daily, in 1920.

osm.name: Sunraysia Daily
osm.display_name: Sunraysia Daily, Midgley Lane, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

43.title: George and William Chaffey Building
43.summary:
Across the road is a single story late Victorian, red brick building, with
a brick and iron palisade fence. The building was gifted to La Trobe Uni in 2009 by Don Carrazza.

44.title: Electric Supply Department Substation No.1
44.summary: In the centre plantation, stands the Electric Supply Department Substation No.1, dating back to 1936, when the production of electricity was considered a local responsibility, rather than a state one.

45.title: Queen Elizabeth II visit to Mildura, March 25th, 1954
45.summary: When Queen Elizabeth toured Mildura in 1954, a decorative dais was erected in this area of the plantation.  Pics of this day are displayed at the Carnegie Centre. Visit to Barclays Block in Red Cliffs

46.title: Bowring's Store, corner Deakin Avenue and 8th Street - Circa 1937
46.summary: The site of the ANZ Bank was previously known as Bowring Corner and was the site of Bowring’s Store, opened in 1888. It extended into Langtree Avenue in 1961 but ceased business two decades later.

47.title: Old Mildura Post Office (LHS of Deakin Ave)
47.summary: This corner building was for over a century, the Mildura Post Office. The earliest Post Office on this site was built in 1890, with much of the current building being erected in 1923.

48.title: George V Memorial Fountain (in centre plantation)
48.summary: Crossing into the centre plantation, you will find the George V Memorial Fountain, originally erected in the gardens of the Rio Vista, home of W.B Chaffey, it was moved to its current position in 1936

49.title: Mildura Law Courts (LHS of Deakin Ave)
49.summary: Opened by Robert Hulls, Victoria’s Attorney General, on Nov 23 2004. This complex was built on the site that began as Washington Stores, before becoming Maples, before it all went up in flames in 1996

50.title: 70 Deakin Avenue (LHS of Deakin Ave)
50.summary: Once the site of the Shire Offices, beginning as a modest, timber, two roomed building before the current building was erected in 1922. In 1971, the Shire Offices were relocated to Irymple.

51.title: Carnegie Centre - Home to the Historical and Genealogical Societies (LHS of Deakin Ave)
51.summary: Constructed in 1908, as the Carnegie Library, courtesy of a 2000 pound grant made by Andrew Carnegie, in 1906, after a request from Lord Hopetoun. The tower was added in 1922 as a soldier memorial.

52.title: Civic Buildings  (LHS of Deakin Ave)
52.summary: The Civic Buildings, opened in 1958 and it’s also the site of the original Shire Hall, also known as the Mildura Town Hall.

53.title: Statue of W.B. Chaffey (in center  plantation)
53.summary: In the center  plantation is a statue of W.B. Chaffey, who died in 1926. The Paul Mountford sculpture was unveiled in 1929. A similar sculpture can be found in Renmark, SA.

54.title: Desailly Rotunda (in center  plantation)
54.summary: The centre  plantation is home to the Desailly Rotunda, named for Cr George Desailly, former Shire President, who died whilst in office in 1913.

55.title: 61 Deakin Ave - Mildura's earliest surviving building (RHS of Deakin Ave)
55.summary: On the RHS of Deakin Ave is the earliest surviving building in Mildura. It started out as Mildura’s first general store, owned by H.B Williams, in 1887. A bank altered the building appearance in 1937.

56.title: 69 Deakin Ave (RHS of Deakin Ave)
56.summary: Built in 1914, this  Edwardian building has been a restaurant, a bank, a real estate agency and other businesses, which although altered over the years, still retains some of its original charm.

57.title: Mildura Club (RHS of Deakin Ave)
57.summary: The Mildura "Gentlemen's Club" began in 1890 with Lord Ranfurly as the first President. Meetings were originally held at the Coffee Palace, until this building was completed in 1920.

58.title: Deakin Cinema Complex  (RHS of Deakin Ave)
58.summary: The Deakin Cinema complex was  established in 1975. A point of interest is that the cinema includes the original site of the Masonic Temple, built in 1907, with the façade still remaining.

59.title: Mildura Workingmans Club (LHS of Deakin Ave)
59.summary: An iconic landmark, once famous for having the world’s longest bar (which was removed in recent renovations.). Begun in 1908, it was originally a 1 story structure with a 2nd level added in 1935.

60.title: Mildura Workingmans Club  War Memorial (LHS of Deakin Ave)
60.summary: Has stood at the front of the club, since 1920, honoring Mildura’s war dead. The marble soldier is the work of A.D Thomson and the three-sided list of soldiers’ names underpins the heavy losses of WW1

61.title: Methodist Church (LHS of Deakin Ave)
61.summary: Opened in 1912, this unique church had a number of architectural influences, including Byzantine, Queen Anne, Masonic and Art Nouveau . Image: Methodist Church under construction 1911.

62.title: The Church of Christ  (RHS of Deakin Ave)
62.summary: Built in 1908, the Church of Christ was first organised by Reuben Mansell in 1890 and members met in a variety of venues until this building was completed using all voluntary labour.

63.title: War Memorial (centre plantation)
63.summary: Commemorates those who died or were killed in World War One. Erected by the Mildura Branch R. S. & S. I. L. A.

64.title: Uniting Church / St Andrew’s  (RHS of Deakin Ave)
64.summary: The Uniting Church, known as St Andrew’s, started out as a Presbyterian church and was built in 1914, at a cost of 2097 pounds. It replaced a wooden structure that had been there since 1891.

65.title: St Margaret’s Anglican Church (LSH of Deakin Ave)
65.summary: This church opened in 1902, with the addition of the sanctuary in 1934 and the vestry and bell tower in 1957 that honours the lost soldiers of World War II.

66.title: Madden Avenue
66.summary: Madden Ave was originally planned to be the principal retail district of Mildura due to easy access to the wharf. However,  Langtree, with it’s proximity to the railway proved to be more significant

osm.name: Madden Avenue
osm.display_name: Madden Avenue, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

67.title: Mildura RSL Sub Branch
67.summary: The Returned and Services League with some 1500 Sub Branches Australia wide and with a membership of 240,000 is the largest service association in Australia.

68.title: Mildura Water Tower
68.summary: As you cross over 10th street, to your right you will see one of  Mildura's Water Towers. Built in 1957, the tower provides water pressure for thousands of homes across the urban area.

69.title: Mecure Hotel
69.summary: Commercial Hotel, commonly remembered as the Wintersun and now the Mecure Hotel was built in 1925

70.title: Disused water tower
70.summary: Behind the hotel is a disused water tower, which from 1912 until 1957 operated as Mildura’s sole source of water storage. Instigated by the former First Mildura Irrigation Trust. 180000 litre capacity

71.title: Under the Clocks
71.summary: Melbourne's well known and iconic meeting place is under the clocks at Flinders Street Station. Sit on the steps and see the world go by.

72.title: Mirka Mora mosaic
72.summary: Mirka Mora made this mosaic in about 1985, it is brilliant. Do not be one of the thousands who walk past it every day without stopping.

73.title: To Birrarung Marr
73.summary: The slope down to Birrarung Marr, always fills with expectation. The sculpture of hundreds of red poles is a cracker. Go up and push the poles firmly, what a noise!

74.title: Federation Square
74.summary: There always seems to be something happening at Fed Square whether it is concerts, buskers, festivals or people lolling about. The pavers are great to sit on on a sunny afternoon.

osm.name: Federation Square
osm.display_name: Federation Square, Swanston Street, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

75.title: The Art Centre from Fed Square
75.summary: Looking over to the Art Centre spire from Fed Square.

76.title: Birrarung Marr playground
76.summary: The playground is always open. Watch kids play and enjoy the tube slides, sand pits, swinging hammocks, activity panels, rock and rope climbing features and balance beams.

77.title: Art Play
77.summary: Art Play is a great place for children it has lots of shows and creative activities for kids.

78.title: Mosaic outside art play
78.summary: I do not know what the story is behind this brightly coloured mosaic outside Art Play, but it is wonderful.

79.title: Textured path
79.summary: The winding, textured pathway of cast iron acknowledges the significance of the eel as a traditional food source for groups camped by the river.

80.title: Watching rowers from Birrarung Marr
80.summary: Sit on the seats under a shady tree watching rowers go by.

81.title: To Princes Bridge
81.summary: The gravel path on the river bank is a bit quieter. More seats and looking back to Princess Bridge.

82.title: West along the river
82.summary: From 'Angel' you can get a good look along the Yarra River

83.title: Angel
83.summary: Angel (ceramic, steel and concrete) by Deborah Halpern is an artwork commissioned by the National Gallery of Victoria. It is even more impressive than the photo suggests.

osm.name: Angel
osm.display_name: Angel, Capital City Trail Main Yarra Trail, East End Theatre District, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

84.title: Grassy hill for rolling
84.summary: There should be more grassy hills like this one in the centre of cities. Watch the number of kids who are immediately drawn to it and roll down laughing.

85.title: Walking up the slope to the bridge
85.summary: The trees and shrubs set in the stone fence as you walk up the slope to the William Barak bridge.

86.title: William Barak bridge
86.summary: A purpose built walking (and cycling) space, William Barak bridge is one of true delights of Melbourne. Beautiful and functional.

osm.name: William Barak Bridge
osm.display_name: William Barak Bridge, East End Theatre District, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

87.title: Listening to Proximities
87.summary: Proximities is a public art installation commissioned for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.  The stories and songs from 53 Commonwealth nations come out of the many, many speakers across the bridge.

88.title: Sit and watch Melbourne
88.summary: Sit on the bridge and look south to the Yarra and Tennis Centre or north to the city and listen to the trains go by underneath.

89.title: Off the bridge to the 'G'
89.summary: Coming off the bridge and walk to the MCG under the shade of magnificent old Elm trees.

90.title: The MCG
90.summary: The MCG, what a collosseum. You don't realise how massive it is until you actually see it. Even if you don't like sport, the sound of the crowd cheering will grab your attention.

91.title: Dennis Lillee
91.summary: Bronze statues do around the MCG, none more impressive than the great Dennis Lillee.

92.title: Aussie Rules
92.summary: Statue commemorating the first game of Australian Rules Football said to be played nearby on 7 August 1858.

93.title: Jolimont Station
93.summary: Its a beautiful the old train bridge. Catch a train (or tram) back to Flinders St or keep going.

osm.name: Jolimont
osm.display_name: Jolimont, Wellington Parade, East Melbourne, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3002, Australia

94.title: Watt's Cottage
94.summary: Home to early settlers in Sorrento, this house was built in 1869. The Pioneer Memorial Garden is well tended with blooms all year round. Tours available (at limited times).

95.title: Information boards and cafe
95.summary: Check out the information boards here for details about the history, local environment and features of the area. All Smiles Cafe located a short walk away from here.

96.title: Surf's up
96.summary: A good spot to watch the surf, have a picnic, go for a swim, read a book or do whatever you please.

97.title: Uphill climb towards the top
97.summary: Definitely a steep climb uphill but the scenery from the top is very worthwhile. Get your heart rate up!

98.title: Panoramic views
98.summary: A perfect spot to watch the sunset, or simply enjoy the sweeping panoramic views.

99.title: Heading down to the beach
99.summary: Follow the track, which will eventually take you towards the beach.

100.title: Fine sandy beach
100.summary: Enjoy the salty sea breezes as you feel the sand under your feet on this beautiful stretch of coastline.

101.title: Portsea Surf Lifesaving Club
101.summary: You can take a detour here if you need a toilet stop.

osm.name: Portsea Surf Lifesaving Club
osm.display_name: Portsea Surf Lifesaving Club, Back Beach Road, Portsea, Melbourne, Shire of Mornington Peninsula, Victoria, 3943, Australia

102.title: 'London Bridge'
102.summary: A great spot to explore the rockpools and wander under the 'London Bridge' (but not during high tide of course). You can continue along the beach all the way to Point Nepean if you like.

osm.name: London Bridge Road
osm.display_name: London Bridge Road, Portsea, Melbourne, Shire of Mornington Peninsula, Victoria, 3943, Australia

103.title: Public toilets and drinking fountain
103.summary: Phew! It's a pretty steep ramp that leads you up here. A convenient toilet stop and a chance to top up your water bottle before heading off again.

104.title: Start of Wilson's Folly Track
104.summary: There's a sign a near the car park marking the start of the track. Apparently Capt R Wilson simply lit a match wherever he thought the bush needed to be cleared for the army\'s weapons training areas.

105.title: Looking out to the sea
105.summary: Listen out for the twitter of small birds in this fabulous bit of coastal bushland overlooking the sea.

106.title: Unexploded bombs
106.summary: A former weapons training area. "All large unexploded ordinance has been removed but you may come across small arms such as rifle and pistol shells," which of course, you shouldn't touch.

107.title: Point Nepean Visitor Centre
107.summary: The visitor centre has plenty of local information and maps of the area. You can take a tour to the historical Fort Nepean (a buggy can transport you there). Public toilets and BBQ available here.

osm.name: Point Nepean Visitor Centre
osm.display_name: Point Nepean Visitor Centre, Defence Road, Portsea, Melbourne, Shire of Mornington Peninsula, Victoria, 3943, Australia

108.title: Mighty high fences
108.summary: You can take a short detour down to the beach via Cove Ave. Clearly residents here like their privacy but it's such a shame that the street is marred by these enormously high walls and fences.

109.title: Nature strip plantings
109.summary: Thankfully, there are patches of wonderful plants to enjoy as you walk down the street.

110.title: A little bit arty
110.summary: ... and even a bit of art to give some of these high walls a little bit of character.

111.title: On the other side
111.summary: Across the road are a row of charming cottages that reminds us of how the area used to look before the high walls and fences came along.

112.title: Bus stop
112.summary: You can catch bus number 788 back to Sorrento, or all the way back to Frankston along point Nepean Road.

113.title: Boardwalk near fishing platforms
113.summary: The boardwalks starts along the path just past the carpark on Lakeside Drive. A few fishing platforms go off the boardwalk.

114.title: Wetlands
114.summary: The inlet is on one side of the boardwalk and wetlands on the other, both have an abundance of birdlife and aquatic life.

115.title: The shared path
115.summary: The shared path is very popular with walkers and bike riders alike and is in pretty good condition.

116.title: Pelicans and piers
116.summary: There are many little jetties dotted along the path and it is hard not to spot a pelican or two perched on many of them.

117.title: Raised boardwalks
117.summary: The wonderful raised boardwalk provides a shady spot to look out to the inlet.

118.title: Mallacoota harbour
118.summary: Old and new, big and small boats (but nothing too flash!) in the Mallacoota harbour.

119.title: Coull's Inlet
119.summary: Coull's Inlet is beautiful on a still early morning.

120.title: Fishing spot
120.summary: One of the many fishing spots along the walk. Even if you are not into fishing, it's fun to watch early morning anglers.

121.title: Goat & other Islands
121.summary: Beautiful views abound on the walk. Goat Island, Rabbit Island and more...

122.title: Moored boats
122.summary: Over the summer, many camping ground visitors more theri boats along the shore. Boats for fishing, water skiing, bird watching or pleasure....

123.title: Mallacoota Foreshore Holiday Park
123.summary: The next part of the walk goes through the council caravan park, in summer there is always something to look at.

osm.name: Mallacoota Foreshore Holiday Park
osm.display_name: Mallacoota Foreshore Holiday Park, Dorron Avenue, Mallacoota, Shire of East Gippsland, Victoria, 3892, Australia

124.title: To Capt. Stevenson's Point
124.summary: If you want, you can take a short detour off the path and follow the water to Capt. Stevenson's Point (or stay on the path up above).

125.title: Capt. Stevenson's Point
125.summary: A great spot to look up the inlet or to the mouth (and watch boats go out to sea). You can even see Gabo Island from here.

126.title: Koalas
126.summary: If you look carefully you can often see Koalas in the trees, even the odd kangaroo.

127.title: Crossing the inlet
127.summary: To get across to the beach you have to wade across about 20 meteres of the inlet which is about 45 cm deep. In summer teh water is quite warm so it is very pleasant.

128.title: Dirftwood structure
128.summary: This structure that some have built in the sand dune out of driftwood has been there for a while, hope it lasts a while longer!

129.title: Mallacoota beach
129.summary: On a clear day the beach is beautiful other times it can be rugged and wild, but no less wonderful. This part is only for strong competent swimmers. But watch the surfers!

130.title: A walking beach
130.summary: The beach is certainly great for walking, but can get a bit blowy.

131.title: Patrolled beach
131.summary: This is the main swimming beach that is patrolled by life savers in the holiday season. Any one for cricket?

132.title: Bastion Point
132.summary: Rockpools to look at and a good spot for snorkling off teh rocks when the conditions are good.

osm.name: Bastion Point
osm.display_name: Bastion Point, Mallacoota, Shire of East Gippsland, Victoria, 3892, Australia

133.title: Native flowers.
133.summary: You'll come to a fork in the path. Walk this route as a loop or simply walk along the river till the end and return. Either way there is much to see. We found these feather like flowers. How lovely!

134.title: Beautiful views of the river
134.summary: There are lots of birds enjoying the river. We saw several different types of birds swimming in the river.

135.title: Duck sanctuary
135.summary: We saw a mother duck and her young ducklings nestled in a log along the river. A clever nest away from predators and people. She's hard to spot in the photo because we didn't want to get too close!

136.title: Stray fruit bat
136.summary: We spotted a stray fruit bat in one of the trees. It had clearly fallen behind from the group and was trying to remain hidden from prying eyes. We photographed it from afar so we wouldn't disturb it.

137.title: Still reflections
137.summary: A lovely view from along the river.

138.title: Ducks and more birds
138.summary: Many birds of all sorts can be found near the boat house because they're used to people feeding them, even though feeding birds is harmful (see link).

139.title: Barbeque areas
139.summary: The bbq, tables and seats are under sheltered areas. There is plenty of idyllic picnic spots in shady areas close the river. Great spot for a picnic or gathering.

140.title: Signs
140.summary: So many options! Take your pick.

141.title: Popular route
141.summary: We passed several walkers, including children, a couple with a baby (must be a hardy 4 wheeler pram!) and others using the route for exercise.

142.title: Skate Park
142.summary: Large skate park ideal for families.

osm.name: Skate Park
osm.display_name: Skate Park, Shepparton, City of Greater Shepparton, Victoria, 3630, Australia

143.title: Jetty
143.summary: A jetty to admire the scenic surrounds or do a spot of fishing.

146.title: Bridge
146.summary: Walk across the bridge and take in the beautiful surroundings.

147.title: Canoe Club
147.summary: Canoe hire available from Visitor Information Centre.Canoes can accomodate 2 adults. Kayaks also available.

148.title: Aquamoves
148.summary: Aquamoves is an aquatic and leisure centre with facilities such as gym, creche sauna, indoor and outdoor pools.

osm.name: Aquamoves
osm.display_name: Aquamoves, Tom Collins Drive, Shepparton, City of Greater Shepparton, Victoria, 3630, Australia

149.title: All Abilities Playground
149.summary: A playground suitable for children and families of all abilities.

150.title: Aquamoves
150.summary: Aquamoves is an aquatic and leisure centre with gym and areboic facilities, creche, indoor and outdoor pools.

osm.name: Aquamoves
osm.display_name: Aquamoves, Tom Collins Drive, Shepparton, City of Greater Shepparton, Victoria, 3630, Australia

151.title: Playground
151.summary: There is a playground for the children to play on. So the whole family can come to the lake and enjoy the scenery.

152.title: Fitness Station
152.summary: Fitness equipment to help you in your work out.

153.title: dogs off leash area
153.summary: Area where you can let your dog off the lead. It also has a creek.

154.title: Bird Watching
154.summary: You can spy on many different varieties of birds in the wetlands.

155.title: Fishing
155.summary: One of the many good places to fish at the lake.

156.title: Boat Ramp
156.summary: A place to put your small boat.

157.title: The beach
157.summary: One of the beaches to relax on or walk along.

158.title: Cashins Mill
158.summary: Built in the early 1850s by Hugh Kneen of Fitzroy. After James Cashin Snr died in 1873, the mill was operated by sons James and William.

osm.name: Cashins Flour Mill ruins
osm.display_name: Cashins Flour Mill ruins, Carrum to Warburton Trail, Lilydale, Melbourne, Shire of Yarra Ranges, Victoria, 3140, Australia

159.title: Farmers Market
159.summary: First Sunday of the month - 8am to 1pm. Bellbird Park (next to Lillydale Lake), Swansea Road, Lilydale.

160.title: Rivers
160.summary: Be alert for high river levels and fast flowing water which can make the Gorge hazardous.The best walking period lasts from early November until late March.

161.title: Variety of views
161.summary: The scenic walks take in a range of landscapes.

162.title: Falls
162.summary: There are three waterfalls along the track.

163.title: Australian Forest Walk
163.summary: Features all Australian plants, including sky-high trees and land-dwelling shrubs.

osm.name: Australian Forest Walk
osm.display_name: Australian Forest Walk, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3004, Australia

164.title: Eucalypts
164.summary: A collection of over 200 eucalypts; Australia's most iconic trees.

165.title: Lions Head and Separation Trees
165.summary: These trees are remnants of the River Red Gum and pre-date European settlement.

166.title: Lower Yarra River Habitat
166.summary: An ecological collection which contains Indigenous plants native to the Lower Yarra region.

167.title: Long Island
167.summary: A garden which is representative of vegetation pre-European settlement and contains many Indigenous plant species.

osm.name: Long Island
osm.display_name: Long Island, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3004, Australia

168.title: Sidney Myer Music Bowl
168.summary: Attend the free Wellbeing music concert at the Bowl at 12pm after the walk to celebrate the wellbeing of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people.

osm.name: Sidney Myer Music Bowl
osm.display_name: Sidney Myer Music Bowl, Alexandra Avenue, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3004, Australia

169.title: Smoking Ceremony
169.summary: Experience a traditional Indigenous Smoking Ceremony in the midst of the ancestral lands of Kulin nation (allocated times).

170.title: Haven General Store
170.summary: Haven shop offers drinks, food, papers, a postal service, liquor and petrol. Workers from nearby businesses often drop in and the locals catch up for a chat.

171.title: Haven Tennis Courts
171.summary: Haven has teams in the local Tennis competition in both Juniors and Seniors.  Junior "Slam and Sweat" tennis sessions are also conducted here along with midweek competitions.

172.title: Haven Recreation Reserve
172.summary: Includes the Haven Hall which is used for a variety of groups such as Playgroup, Exercise classes and the Womens circus.  The Haven Market is held here the first Saturday of the month.

173.title: Black Saturday Monument
173.summary: A monument recognising the Remlaw fire that went through Haven and cuased much damage in February 2009

174.title: Haven Primary School
174.summary: Set partly back from the road, this school provides education for a little under 100 students.  The small numbers and intimate setting is appealing to many.

osm.name: Horsham West and Haven Primary School Haven Campus
osm.display_name: Horsham West and Haven Primary School Haven Campus, 4362, Henty Highway, Haven, Rural City of Horsham, Victoria, 3401, Australia

175.title: Tasma Terrace - 2-12 Parliament Place
175.summary: The terrace is the headquarters of the National Trust. It comprised important boarding houses from the 1870s. Managing a boarding house was one of the few employment options available to early women.

176.title: the Great Petition sculpture - Burston Reserve
176.summary: This artwork represents a giant petition with 30,000 signatures offered to the Victorian Parliament in 1891 as evidence of widespread support for equal voting rights for women.

177.title: Caroline Chisholm Cairn - Burston Reserve
177.summary: Commemorates the centenary of the death of philanthropist Caroline Chisholm, who served the community by welcoming immigrants and building shelters for travellers to the goldfields at Castlemaine.

178.title: Women\'s Underground Toilet - Gordon Reserve, near Spring St
178.summary: The toilet is one of 11 erected by the City of Melbourne between 1902 and 1939. The group is now unique in Australia.

179.title: Parliament House - Spring St
179.summary: Victoria was last to grant women suffrage in 1908.A plaque in the garden honours Vida Goldstein,pioneer suffragist and first woman in the British Empire to stand for election to a national parliament.

osm.name: Parliament House
osm.display_name: Parliament House, 160, Spring Street, East Melbourne, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3002, Australia

180.title: Windsor Hotel - 111 Spring St
180.summary: Sitting over the main entrance are 2 classically inspired figures draped in robes. The female statue on the right represents Peace, while the male figure on the left represents Plenty.

181.title: The Lyceum Club - 9 Ridgeway Place
181.summary: The Lyceum, the famous professional women's club was a purpose-built place, created by and for women, in Victoria.

182.title: Grosvenor Chambers - 9 Collins St
182.summary: This building was erected specifically as artists' studios. Amongst other women who had a studio here, Jane Sutherland was regarded as the leading woman artist of the Heidelberg School.

183.title: WCTU Rooms - 15 Collins St
183.summary: The Women's Christian Temperance Union was the largest and most influential of the various women's organisations in Victoria in the late 1890s.

184.title: The Melbourne Club - 36 Collins St
184.summary: Established in 1838, the Melbourne Club is Victoria's oldest institution. Women are excluded from membership of this bastion of conservatism and one of the most exclusive organisations in Victoria.

185.title: Harley House - corner of Collins & Exhibition St
185.summary: The National Council of Women, based here for 2 decades effectively lobbied for legislation and representation on all boards and committees relating women and children's welfare and legal rights.

186.title: Alexandra Club - next to Harley House
186.summary: Founded in 1903, this is one of Australia's longest established and exclusive clubs for women. Members include Dame Elisabeth Murdoch, community worker and women's rights activist Beryl Beaurepaire.

187.title: Le Louvre - 74 Collins St
187.summary: Formerly a boutique by Lillian Wrightman promoting high fashion European designers. The boutique played a role in establishing Melbourne as the fashion capital of Australia that it has become today.

188.title: Nauru House - 80 Collins St
188.summary: The Australian Conciliation and Arbitration Commission was located here from 1979 - 2006, and women campaigners for equal pay re-enacted the 1969 chain up demonstration at the site on 31 October 1985.

osm.name: Nauru House
osm.display_name: Nauru House, 80, Collins Street, East End Theatre District, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

189.title: St Michael's Uniting Church - corner Collins & Russell St
189.summary: Women have been part of the congregation since its opening in 1867. The Uniting Church has allowed female ministers who serve in parishes, and some females have been Moderators.

190.title: Flinders Lane
190.summary: Thousands of women worked in the rag trade and endured poor working conditions such as long hours and low wages. Few buildings of the textile and clothing industries remain. Rosati's is one of them.

osm.name: Flinders Lane
osm.display_name: Flinders Lane, East End Theatre District, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

191.title: Former women's buildings - Russell St
191.summary: The city meeting place for many women's reformist groups. WCTU's first headquarters at 28 Russell St was where girls from nearby workrooms could get cheap good meals.

192.title: Scots Church - corner Russell and Collins St
192.summary: Dame Nellie Melba sang in the church choir as a child. When she died, the funeral service was held here. Women have been members of the congregation since 1874 but cannot serve as ministers.

193.title: Assembly Hall - next to Scots Church - 156 -160 Collins St
193.summary: Used for the Women\'s Parliament, which was conducted on parliamentary lines with a ministry and political parties and provided useful training in public speaking and parliamentary procedure.

194.title: Theosophical Society - 181 Collins St
194.summary: Once home to the Theosophical Society. Many women have been members of the society, and have been elected president over the years. The current Theosophical Society building is at 126-28 Russell St.

195.title: The Atheneaum - 188 Collins St
195.summary: The talented artist Clarice Beckett had large yearly exhibitions at the Athenaeum from 1924 until 1932. The building\'s facade contains a statue of Minerva, patron goddess of wisdom.

196.title: Former underground women's toilet - corner Rusell Bourke St
196.summary: Built in 1902, this was the first such toilet built as a result of the lobbying by many women, including members of the Womens Political and Social Crusade. It is now under the sculpture at the site.

197.title: Chinatown - Little Bourke St
197.summary: An early centre for prostitution and poverty, the Salvation Army established a hall in Little Bourke Street to do battle for the souls of prostitutes and larrikins in the 19th century.

osm.name: Little Bourke Street
osm.display_name: Little Bourke Street, Chinatown, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

198.title: Queen Victoria Hospital - 210 Lonsdale St
198.summary: One of only 3 hospitals in the world to be founded, managed and staffed by women. It was Australia\'s first female medical service, established by Australia\'s first female doctor in 1896.

199.title: State Library - 328 Swanston St
199.summary: Helen Garner wrote her well-known novel 'Monkey Grip' at the library. In the forecourt is the statue of Joan of Arc, the national 15th century heroine of France and saint of the Roman Catholic Church.

osm.name: State Library of Victoria
osm.display_name: State Library of Victoria, 328, Swanston Street, East End Theatre District, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

200.title: Storey Hall - 344-46 Swanston St
200.summary: Various women's organisations rented the premises, including the Women's Peace Army associated with Vida Goldstein. Purple and green are colours of the Irish and early feminists who once occupied it.

201.title: Women's Liberation Office - 16 Little La Trobe St
201.summary: Feminists from the Women's Liberation Movement Centre produced a newspaper Vashti's Voice, which promoted women's rights such as equal pay and abortion.

202.title: Welsh Church - 320 La Trobe St
202.summary: The first free dispensary for women in 1896 was set up here. In the first 3 months the clinic treated 2,000 women and children. This led to the establishment of the Queen Victoria Hospital.

osm.name: Welsh Church
osm.display_name: Welsh Church, La Trobe Street, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

203.title: YWCA's Jasper Hotel - 489 Elizabeth St
203.summary: Established in 1882, the organisation provides housing services, job placement and mentoring for many women. Inside is a plaque acknowledging Alice Henry, pioneer journalist and unionist.

204.title: Emily McPherson College (now RMIT) - 379-405 Russell St
204.summary: Established to improve the domestic skills of women at a time when there was a push for 'scientific' mothering education, also when a young woman's access to secondary education was limited.

205.title: Old Melbourne Gaol - 377 Russell St
205.summary: Ned Kelly's mother, Ellen, was a prisoner in the women's cell block when Ned was hanged in 1880. She was in trouble for aiding and abetting Ned and charged with attempted murder.

osm.name: Old Melbourne Gaol
osm.display_name: Old Melbourne Gaol, 377, Russell Street, East End Theatre District, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

206.title: City Watch House - next to the former Magistrates Court
206.summary: The first prisoner here was Beatrice Phillips, who was charged with indecent language. The National Council of Women and WCTU successfully lobbied to improve some conditions for female prisoners.

207.title: Magistrates Court - corner La Trobe and Russell St
207.summary: Jennie Baines was sentenced to 6 months' jail for repeated violations of the War Precautions Act in 1919 for flying red flags. She went on a hunger strike and was released after 4 days.

208.title: Green Latrine - corner Spring and LaTrobe St
208.summary: On 21 October 1969 Zelda D'Aprano, a feminist crusader chained herself to the Commonwealth Building (known as the 'Green Latrine', now demolished) until she was cut free by the Commonwealth police.

209.title: Princess Theatre - 163 Spring St
209.summary: Many famous actresses have performed at the theatre, including Nellie Stewart, Sibyl Thorndike, Marlene Dietrich and Marina Prior. Nellie Stewart, who starred in the first performance of 'The Mikado'.

osm.name: Princess Theatre
osm.display_name: Princess Theatre, 163, Spring Street, East End Theatre District, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

210.title: Visitor centre and restaurant
210.summary: We start the walk from the visitors centre that overlooks Jells lake.  The restaurant is open every day except Christmas Day.

211.title: Wattles in bloom
211.summary: As soon as you start wandering down to the lake you will notice some wonderful native flora to your right.

212.title: Pacific Black Duck
212.summary: Around the lake there is abundant bird life including the versatile Pacific Black Duck. It frequents all types of water and is found in all but the most arid regions of Australia.

213.title: Eurasian Coot
213.summary: The Eurasian Coot is easy to find.  Its an omnivore, and will take a variety of small live prey including the eggs of other water birds, as well as algae, vegetation, seeds and fruit.

214.title: A stroll in the park
214.summary: The path meanders along the edge of open parkland before heading into the conservation area.

215.title: By the lakeside
215.summary: When you are near the lake listen out for some of the thousands of frogs that live here.  They do not drink water, and instead absorb it through their skin.

216.title: Chestnut Teal
216.summary: When you are crossing the creek you might spot a Chestnut Teal looking for lunch.   A male teal is pictured here agitating the shallow water ..

217.title: Chestnut Teal Upended
217.summary: .. before upending to bottom feed underwater.

218.title: Wetlands
218.summary: The wetlands act as filters, sponges and reserves of water.  Though only 2% of Victoria is wetland area, it supports 33% of our endangered plants and is home to mammals, frogs, fish and insects.

219.title: Nesting Boxes
219.summary: Hollows in old trees are home to many native birds.  As there are not enough hollows for all the native species that utilise the nesting boxes dotted around the park.

220.title: The conservation area
220.summary: The conservation area immerses you in native flora, while you are serenaded by the varied songs of the birdlife it supports.

221.title: Bird Hide
221.summary: The bird hide provides a great opportunity to watch the birdlife.  The hide has an information board with pictures and descriptions of some of the birdlife you may see.  Bring your binoculars!

222.title: Purple Swamphen
222.summary: The park is home to a sizeable population of the beautiful Purple Swamphen.  The male has an elaborate courtship display, holding water weeds in his bill and bowing to the female with loud chuckles!

223.title: Enjoy the scenery of the park
223.summary: Can you hear the peace and quiet? This stretch is great for spotting birds and listening to their songs.

224.title: Drouin Civic Park
224.summary: Drouin Civic Park is set in a small valley, with a pond, fountain, rotunda, playground and public toilets. The park also includes the 'Path of Achievement'.

osm.name: Civic Park
osm.display_name: Civic Park, Drouin, Shire of Baw Baw, Victoria, Australia

225.title: Directional signage
225.summary: Directional signage is displayed along the trail to provide distances and orientation.

226.title: Pause places
226.summary: Pause places, like this one in the Drouin wetlands, includes recycled-plastic seating, rubbish bins and bike racks.

227.title: Drouin Wetlands
227.summary: Wetlands have been established through this part of the walk and the Drouin Landcare Group have planted hundreds of native trees to increase biodiversity and improve water quality and amenity.

228.title: Boardwalk
228.summary: After crossing Buln Buln road you will come to an elevated boardwalk over a creek and views across green paddocks.

229.title: View, Mt Baw Baw, Mt Worth, Strezlecki Ranges.
229.summary: There are lovely views from a number of vantage points along the trail including vistas to Mt Baw Baw, Mt Worth and the Strezlecki Ranges.

230.title: Mosaics
230.summary: Local artists created mosaics which have been set into each of the pause places along the trail.

231.title: Lardners Track Cenotaph
231.summary: Here a memorial is located in recognition to William Calder, the first Chairman of Country Roads Board, for his outstanding contribution to Victorias road network.

232.title: Pause places
232.summary: Another pause place to enjoy the views of the surrounding farms and mountain ranges.

233.title: Indigenous history
233.summary: A number of interpretive signs explain the local Indigenous history, creation stories and artwork of the Gunaikurnai, one of the Aboriginal nations of Australia.

234.title: Western Park BMX track
234.summary: The trail winds past the Western Park BMX track where you can try out the track or watch the locals on the berms.

235.title: Rotary Park
235.summary: Rotary Park is located on Latrobe Street in Warragul where you will finds a kids playground, outdoor gym equipment, public toilets, rotunda with picnic facilities, drinking fountain, and Hazel Creek.

236.title: Warragul Gateway Entrance
236.summary: The entrance of the trail will soon be marked by a large and significant piece of artwork which pays homage to local threatened species

237.title: Baw Baw Shire Council
237.summary: This walk is proudly brought to you by Baw Baw Shire Council.

osm.name: Baw Baw Shire Council Office
osm.display_name: Baw Baw Shire Council Office, McCay Drive, Drouin, Shire of Baw Baw, Victoria, 3818, Australia

238.title: Lysterfield Visitor Area
238.summary: A spot for all the family to gather and play!  Picnic, BBQ, go sailing and swimming, or head off for a leisurely walk around the whole lake.

239.title: Beach and swimming area
239.summary: This end of the lake is a designated swimming beach. The dam wall is in the background.

240.title: Boat Beach
240.summary: Sail boats launch from here, a lovely sight on your walk along this beach.

241.title: Dam Wall access
241.summary: At the end of the beach are steps to the top of the wall which begins your walk around the lake.

242.title: Trailmix Cafe and Visitor Centre
242.summary: Providing food, drinks and information as well as bike repairs, sales and hire.

243.title: Dam Wall
243.summary: From up here you can get a view over the 82ha lake which supplied fresh water to the Mornington Peninsula from 1936 till 1975.

244.title: West side of the Lake
244.summary: The tall tree canopy provides shade as you walk.

245.title: Acacia Nature Trail
245.summary: Step in here and step back in time to discover the native vegetation which once surrounded Melbourne.

osm.name: Acacia Nature Trail
osm.display_name: Acacia Nature Trail, Lysterfield, Melbourne, Shire of Yarra Ranges, Victoria, 3804, Australia

246.title: Black Wattles
246.summary: Black Wattles grow in this area and are stripped bare when their bark is eaten by the Fire Blight Beetle in Winter and Spring.

247.title: Grassy area
247.summary: Stop here for a rest or a picnic and perhaps spot an Eastern Grey Kangaroos or Black Wallaby if you are here early or at dusk.

248.title: Conservation Area
248.summary: Numerous conservation projects are underway in this park.

249.title: East side of the Lake
249.summary: Look up and see how many birds you can spot flying amongst the tree tops.

250.title: Conservation Zone
250.summary: Only walkers can use this track amongst the lush green vegetation for the final stretch of this peaceful walk.

251.title: The end or just the beginning?
251.summary: The walk is a loop around the lake.  Look out for this sign from the north end of the carpark.

252.title: Mural on wall
252.summary: Beautiful wall art and part of a program to address problem graffiti.

253.title: mosaic artworks
253.summary: Mosaic artworks in the pocket parks

254.title: Frog art work
254.summary: More stunning art work and perhaps an artistic place to rest!

256.title: Early drive-through service station
256.summary: Back from early days of the car.

258.title: Old Italian Cake and Coffee Shop
258.summary: A high street "institution" run by a lovely elderly couple.

osm.name: Lions Club of Northcote Op Shop
osm.display_name: Lions Club of Northcote Op Shop, 735, High Street, Thornbury, Melbourne, City of Darebin, Victoria, 3071, Australia

261.title: New cafe - active street frontage
261.summary: For those with an interest in urbanity, a good example of a shop activating the street.

262.title: Cafes with kerbside dining.
262.summary: More opportunities for refreshment!  Life on the street again!

263.title: South Kenginston station
263.summary: Bottle brushes line the station and are spectacular in flowering season. Listen for rosellas and parakeets.

264.title: JJ Holland Park Playground
264.summary: Set in bushy surroundings, this playground has a number of slides, climbing frames and hidey holes. There is a disabled toilet nearby.

265.title: Bill Vanina Pavillion
265.summary: Restored and extend in 2015, the Pavillion is used as a sport center eg.Football, soccer and cricket

266.title: Skate Park & Adventure Playground
266.summary: A popular place for older children with wheels! There is a public with disabled access at the Skate Park.

267.title: Kensington Community Recreation and Aquatic Centre
267.summary: This popular centre has a local gym, heated swimming pool and indoor basketball court.

268.title: Venny's
268.summary: The Venny is an adventure playground with a garden, social hub and activities. It's open for limited hours during the school term and school holidays. See link below.

269.title: Tankard's Reserve
269.summary: A fine collection of play equipment, plus a picnic shelter with table.

270.title: Newman's Reserve
270.summary: Bright and colourful, this playground is suitable for pre-school children. and has 2 slides. A great spot to sit and enjoy the scenery too.

271.title: View from Newman Reserve
271.summary: Look for double rainbow (two pots of gold?).

272.title: Open play area and basketball ring
272.summary: There is so much potential in an open play area. Cricket? Football? Egg and spoon race?

273.title: Open play area and  tennis courts
273.summary: These tennis courts  are available for hire. The key is available from the recreation centre  on Altona Street.

274.title: Newell's Paddock Lookout
274.summary: View over wetlands area. You'll often see a wide array of bird life, including swans, ducks and water fowl.

275.title: Former Stock Bridge
275.summary: This is a fine spot to admire the surrounding views.

276.title: Tidal river Bridge
276.summary: You needed to have crossed this wonderful bridge to have started the walk. On hot days you often see people jumping off the bridge or paddlers going under it.

277.title: The track
277.summary: The track is quite well maintained and mostly is quite a gentle climb.

278.title: Paddlers
278.summary: I love the view down to Tidal River, you can see them but them not you.

279.title: Norman Bay
279.summary: Norman Bay would have to be one of the best walking and playing beaches in Victoria, also great for swimming.

osm.name: Norman Bay South Track
osm.display_name: Norman Bay South Track, Tidal River, Shire of South Gippsland, Victoria, 3960, Australia

280.title: Grass Tree
280.summary: There are a lot of Grass Trees (Xanthorrhoea) around Wilsons Prom, bit only a few on this walk and this one is a beauty.

281.title: Tidal Overlook
281.summary: It is worth the short deviation off the track see the views from Tidal Overlook.

osm.name: Tidal Overlook
osm.display_name: Tidal Overlook, Shire of South Gippsland, Victoria, Australia

282.title: Rock with a view
282.summary: There is a rock just off the path with a great view of Squeeky and out to see.

283.title: View out to sea
283.summary: Could sit here all day looking out to sea.

284.title: The track
284.summary: The track appears like a shady tunnel.

285.title: Wildflowers
285.summary: Look out for wildflowers, like this little gem peaking up at you.

286.title: Life ring
286.summary: The life ring is there in case people fall off the rocks. Be careful, two young people drowned there in 1988. Best to keep to the path and you will be OK.

287.title: The Rocks
287.summary: These rocks are like a sculpture and the colour seems to change with the seasons.

288.title: To Squeaky
288.summary: The last part of the path to Squeaky, the anticipation...

osm.name: Squeaky Beach Walk
osm.display_name: Squeaky Beach Walk, Wilsons Promontory, Shire of South Gippsland, Victoria, Australia

289.title: Squeaky Beach
289.summary: Don't forget to squeak when you walk!

osm.name: Squeaky Beach
osm.display_name: Squeaky Beach, Wilsons Promontory, Shire of South Gippsland, Victoria, Australia

290.title: The sea
290.summary: Time for a dip? But be careful, it is not a patrolled beach.

291.title: Start
291.summary: You start the walk from the carpark.

292.title: No animals are allowed
292.summary: Because it's a national parks no animals are allowed.

293.title: Walking on the track
293.summary: This is how the walk feels, you will feel enclosed and enjoying nature as you walk through it.

294.title: Breath taking views
294.summary: There are numerous points to see the coastline.

295.title: Way down to the beach
295.summary: This is the point were you can walk down to the beach.

296.title: Stairs to the beach
296.summary: Be careful as you walk down to the beach as the stairs are uneven and unsafe.

297.title: Beach
297.summary: Enjoying a stroll around the beach with a picnic and a swim. You never know what you may find!

298.title: Animals
298.summary: Watch out for all type of creatures, they may just sneak up on you.

299.title: Melbourne Artists' Supplies
299.summary: This is my shop to get fancy paper, pens, paints and other bits and bobs. The staff are very helpful, and it's got a very groovy shopfront.

300.title: Mystery visitors
300.summary: Hard to tell what this wall's about, you can make up your own story to imagine which mysterious spirits might visit the people who live in this building!

301.title: Dragon
301.summary: This Chinese dragon looks like he's enjoying watching the traffic.

osm.name: Dragon Boat Restaurant
osm.display_name: Dragon Boat Restaurant, 203, Little Bourke Street, Chinatown, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

302.title: Detective stories
302.summary: There are a series of pictures here that tell a story about the man in the suit. What's this guy up to?

303.title: Robot man
303.summary: Looks like the robot man has made friends with the weird creatures to his left. Robots need friends too.

304.title: Nature's window
304.summary: Can't see the trees in the city? Check it out here.

305.title: Smell the art
305.summary: Live spray painting here if you're lucky! Otherwise come and see what you can find on these walls.

306.title: Al Pacino
