518.title: Beautiful semi-rural surrounds
518.summary: The scenery quickly changes after stepping off the Princes Highway to become a beautiful and tranquil semi-rural setting.

519.title: Cross the road here
519.summary: At this point the ‘new’ path stops – to continue you need to cross the road and head north along the footpath on the other side of Toomuc Valley Road.

520.title: Tranquil Toomuc Creek
520.summary: The Toomuc Creek is a lovely little meandering creek which starts up near the Cardinia Reservoir.

521.title: There are lots of seats along the way
521.summary: There are many nice spots to rest those weary legs.

522.title: Underneath the canopy
522.summary: It is great to be hidden from the busy streetscape under the native tree canopy.

523.title: So many birds of all shapes and sizes
523.summary: If you stop and look up you will be amazed just how many birds there are to see!

524.title: First half of the walk is along a nice new concrete path
524.summary: First half of the walk is along a nice new concrete path.

525.title: Welcome to the Community Greenhouse Corridor
525.summary: The walk starts right next to the Princes Highway, or it can be an extension of the Toomuc Creek Trail existing south of the highway.

526.title: The path is a mix of grass, concrete and gravel
526.summary: The path is a mix of grass, concrete and gravel. The first half of the walk is a concrete path and well suited to prams and wheelchairs.

527.title: Careful crossing the side strees
527.summary: There are a number of side streets that need to be crossed, make sure you look both ways!

528.title: Tick Bush
528.summary: First stop. Look for the tick bush, an evergreen shrub. Its flowers usually  appear from September to December. Did they flower earlier? Check it out

529.title: Flannel Flower
529.summary: Out of the track, you will have the chance to observe the Actinotus Helianthi. Don't forget to upload the pictures you take on the ClimateWatch app.

530.title: Gymea Lily
530.summary: Continuing on the path, you are going to see  a giant tussock-like, rosette plant.  They can reach 5m high with the flower stalk.!

531.title: White Cedar
531.summary: The White Cedar is one of only a few native Australian plants that are seasonally deciduous, although many species drop their leaves during droughts.

532.title: Fuchsia Heath
532.summary: Fuchsia Heath's flowers are long and tubular, some of them have pink-red tubed and white lobes, others are white. Spot them!

533.title: Red Spider Flower
533.summary: You might ask what is this? It's not a spider. It is a bright red, occasionally pink flower. Its spider appearance  explains its name. Keep recording for ClimateWatch app!

534.title: Frogs
534.summary: Listen for frogs. The link below will help you to recognize them and to catalouge them. Have fun!

535.title: Silky Oak
535.summary: This giant tree is just past the cafe. Silky Oaks aren't related to other oak trees at all but are actually a species of Grevilla and are very popular with birds!

536.title: Firewheel Tree
536.summary: This beautiful native tree on your righ has striking red flowers. Are they out today?

537.title: Braybrook Community Hub
537.summary: This state of the art Hub features a new library, community centre and spaces, community health services, maternal and child health services, early years centre, Men's Shed and  optometry services.

538.title: Braybrook Park
538.summary: Braybrook Park offers the community a peaceful place to walk and take in some fresh air.  Take friends and family, kick the footy or enjoy a picnic on the grass.

539.title: Paul Sadler Swimland Braybrook
539.summary: Paul Sadler Swimland has received many awards in Australia and USA, including the induction of Paul Sadler into the Australian Swim Coaches and Teachers' Association Hall of Fame. Call while it's hot!

540.title: Kinder Smith Playground
540.summary: Kinder Smith Reserve has been given a face lift, with a new concrete walking path around the oval, and fresh landscaping. The local young children will love this exciting new playground!

541.title: RecWest Braybrook
541.summary:
At RecWest Braybrook there is something for everyone in the community.
Owned by the Maribyrnong City Council and managed by YMCA Victoria, RecWest offers sport-based activities and programs for all.

osm.name: Recwest
osm.display_name: Recwest, 39, Lily Street, Braybrook, Melbourne, City of Maribyrnong, Victoria, 3019, Australia

542.title: GreenWORKS! Mural
542.summary: The GreenWORKS! project, a successful council and community collaboration, provides a strong connection between the built environment, the natural world and the place the Braybrook locals call home.

543.title: Kinder Smith Reserve
543.summary: Are you a team player? Kinder Smith Reserve is home to Sunshine Football Club, Sunshine YCW Cricket Club and RecWest Braybrook. Contact RecWest for enquiries about netball, basketball or futsal.

osm.name: Kinder Smith Reserve
osm.display_name: Kinder Smith Reserve, Braybrook, Melbourne, City of Maribyrnong, Victoria, 3019, Australia

544.title: Blue Bamboo Vietnamese Restaurant and Cafe
544.summary: Try a selection of delicious dishes from the menu and discover the tropical paradise out the back. You will want to go back for more!

545.title: Regulations
545.summary: The Conglomerate Gully Flora Reserve has its own set of legislative regulations!  They ar eposted on a sign near the start of the walk.

546.title: Information board
546.summary: An information board near the start of the walk gives a summary of the history, ecology and geology of the reserve.

547.title: Hollow tree
547.summary: This hollow tree stands by the side of the path.  Great for hide and seek.

548.title: Fallen log
548.summary: In a number of places, particularly this part of the walk, large fallen logs or trees are a feature.  They make good seats for adults and excellent play equipment for children!

549.title: Hut
549.summary: This interesting hut provides shelter - and curiosity.

550.title: Lookout
550.summary: The track starts to climb alongside a small gorge, with a stream flowing through it after rain or at wetter times of the year.  A lookout provides this view down the gorge.

551.title: Climbing
551.summary: The climb starts to get steep in this area, but that only adds to the sense of accomplishment.  Keep an eye on any under 5s though.

552.title: A taste of NT
552.summary: At times the landscape in this area is reminiscent of the northern territory, with woodland on the rocky escarpment.

553.title: Cascades
553.summary: The stream falls down the gorge, with a series of small waterfalls after rain.  The wetter it has been, the better they are. Unfortunately, was dry at the time of our visit.

554.title: Pools
554.summary: Even at the driest times, small pools remain in the streambed.  They appear to harbour life, but I'm not an entymologist.

555.title: Clearing
555.summary: At the highest point in the walk, you reach a clearing next to the stream above one of the waterfalls.

556.title: Burnt tree
556.summary: Old burnt trees and stumps are a reminder that this area has high risk of bushfire.  In the summer, check the fire risk for the day before visiting.  Do not come on a day of total fire ban.

557.title: Rocks and lichen
557.summary: In this area particularly, rocks with coloured lichen will reward those who look carefully.

558.title: It's only grass
558.summary: Native grass dominates at ground level in Conglomerate Gully.

559.title: Waves of grass
559.summary: At times the native grass seems to be rolling down the hill in waves.

560.title: Native forest
560.summary: The interplay of native trees, grass and fallen logs is perhaps the defining feature of this walk.

561.title: Wildlife
561.summary: Wildlife on this walk is not used to humans and will typically move away from you - making it difficult to photograph!  Thanks to digital enhancement, you can make out this currawong.

562.title: Water Tower
562.summary: The Water Tower is one of a few peppered around the district. Built in 1957, the tower provides water pressure for thousands of homes across the urban area and has the capacity to store 2.7 megalitres

563.title: 158 Orange Avenue
563.summary: The building is now the Guide Hall, but originally was home to the Seventh Day Adventists, and  following that the Lutheran Church. The Church outgrew the site in 1966 when two congregations merged.

osm.name: Orange Avenue
osm.display_name: Orange Avenue, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

564.title: “Valetta” 223 Eleventh St
564.summary: Built 1891 and believed to be designed by D.T. Edmunds who supervised construction of Rio Vista.  Valetta is on the corner of Henderson Place and two pillars at its entrance mark the little street.

565.title: Mildura Primary Schoo
565.summary: Opened on September 13, 1890 with 300 eager students, despite the building not yet being complete. A year later, once all works were finished, Mildura Primary was official opened.

566.title: Proudfoot House
566.summary: Built 1891 for John Proudfoot who owned a produce store in Mildura. This fine example of a late Victorian brick house was later the Presbyterian Manse for many years, before moving into private hands.

567.title: Magnolia Avenue
567.summary: There are still a number of attractive homes in this street but sadly many have been lost.

osm.name: Magnolia Avenue
osm.display_name: Magnolia Avenue, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

568.title: Lemon Avenue
568.summary: Few streets in Mildura have retained their identity as well as Lemon Ave. This area was the tradesmen’s class and 3 of the houses along Lemon Avenue predate 1900 and another 14 are pre World War I

osm.name: Lemon Avenue
osm.display_name: Lemon Avenue, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

569.title: 50 Lemon Ave
569.summary: A good example of the simple Edwardian Style. Currently a backpackers’ hostel, but its original owner was A.C Pugsley, who commissioned the home in 1902.

osm.name: Lemon Avenue
osm.display_name: Lemon Avenue, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

570.title: Kathleen Kelly Kindergarten
570.summary:
Originally started down by the river, Kathleen Kelly Kindergarten was founded by 
Kathleen Kelly  (a member of the Bowring family) as a free kindergarten for children.

osm.name: Kathleen Kelly Kindergarden
osm.display_name: Kathleen Kelly Kindergarden, Lemon Avenue, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

571.title: Mildura Settlers Club
571.summary: The ‘Setts’ as it’s commonly referred to, has been on this site since 1893. A prominent club until 1993, the 'Setts' is now  a modern office space,  popular bar, restaurant and function centre .

572.title: 77 Orange Avenue
572.summary: Original Methodist Parsonage and was designed by William Sheridan and built in 1892. It’s an unusual example of a Tudoresque Victorian brick villa.

osm.name: Orange Avenue
osm.display_name: Orange Avenue, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

573.title: Tea Tree tunnel
573.summary: A little after the start of the track is some beautifully gnarled Tea Trees that make the path look like a bit like a tunnel.

574.title: Tidal River footbridge
574.summary: From the path you can see the Tidal River footbridge. Cross the bridge to go to the tracks to Squeaky, Mt Bishop or other great walks.

575.title: First seat
575.summary: The is the first of a few seats that have been installed long the track. wonderful to sit and watch for a while.

576.title: Hello wombat
576.summary: If you take the walk at dusk you have a reasonable chance of coming across a wombat. Please don't feed the animals!

577.title: The Boadwalk
577.summary: From here on the track is a Boardwalk until the last little bit.

578.title: The first viewing platform
578.summary: There are three viewing platforms along the track that often used by people fishing.

579.title: The bend
579.summary: The boardwalk gets very close to the river at the first bend.

580.title: To Mt Obernon
580.summary: Fantastic view to My Oberon and the third viewing platform along the river.

581.title: View from the last platform
581.summary: Great view up the river from the final viewing platform.

582.title: Away from the river
582.summary: The quietest spot of the walk as you head away from the river.

583.title: Banksia stump
583.summary: Love this gnarly old stump, wonder what animals live inside?

584.title: Picnic tables
584.summary: Two picnic tables can be found next the boardwalk.

585.title: Oh dear!
585.summary: Unfortunately the Prom is being invaded by some pests, including feral deer that come to the river to drink.

586.title: Back into Tea Tree
586.summary: The final section of the boardwalk goes through a relatively youngish planting of Tea Trees.

587.title: Start at Coomoora Woodland on Serpentine Road
587.summary: There are many ways to access Coomoora Woodland. It's even on the walking/cycle trail along the Dandenong Bypass. This suburban street is a quieter access point.

588.title: Choose your own adventure!
588.summary: There are paths in Coomoora Woodland but none are signposted. It's not a huge reserve, so don't worry about getting lost. Instead, look up and take in the sounds of the birdlife above.

589.title: Home to endangered species
589.summary: Coomoora Woodland is home to a number of threatened and endangered species; the swift parrot, grey-headed flying fox and growling grass frog have all been spotted here.

590.title: Short cut
590.summary: There's a path along the back fences of houses that's good for bikes and short cuts. It takes you from the Serpentine Road entrance to the Coomoora Reserve sports ovals.

591.title: Sporting ovals
591.summary: If you fancy a run around, there's an oval here that's perfect for playing in. Cross the oval to reach Coomoora Road.

592.title: Dandenong Bypass walking/cycling pathway
592.summary: It's harder to hear the birds from the Woodlands here, with the whoosh of traffic flying by. Continue a little further to get back to the peace and quiet.

593.title: Coomoora Cricket Club
593.summary: At the time of writing this building was still under construction (November 2015). It may offer public toilets and drinking fountains in the future. Stay tuned!

594.title: Playground
594.summary: Small people might like to stop for a play before leaving Coomoora Reserve and heading out into the suburb. There are also bench seats and picnic tables nearby.

595.title: A detour through the suburbs
595.summary: Walk past the Keysborough Primary School and turn left onto Darren Road. You'll pass a milk bar along the way, if you need refreshments. Turn left at Harold Street.

596.title: Alex Nelson Reserve
596.summary: This sports ground and local reserve offers a playground and shade for sitting. There's a pavilion and ovals for sports fans to enjoy.

osm.name: Alex Nelson Reserve
osm.display_name: Alex Nelson Reserve, Springvale South, Melbourne, City of Greater Dandenong, Victoria, 3172, Australia

597.title: A lovely path through Alex Wilkie area
597.summary: Walk between the Alex Wilkie reserve lands. This public path will take you from Alex Nelson reserve to Mackay Street. Be sure to breathe in the scented bushland and look up for chattering birdlife.

598.title: Alex Wilkie Nature Reserve entrance
598.summary: Enter the Alex Wilkie Nature Reserve here on Mackay Street. This educational and cultural nature reserve is open on Fridays (9-3pm) and every third Sunday (10-5pm). Note, it is closed June to August.

599.title: Remnant bushland
599.summary: The Alex Wilkie Nature Reserve is a parcel of land that was bought by the Springvale South Community Association in 1950. Since then it has been protected. Join the ranger for a guided  bush walk.

600.title: Scented trail
600.summary: As you walk towards Mackay Street, take a breath in and smell the scented walk that's on your right. It's a separate trail in the Alex Wilkie nature reserve designed to engage all of the senses.

601.title: Play in the nearby park
601.summary: As you walk towards Springvale Road, there's another lovely park tucked behind the Mackay Street Centre. This park takes you south into suburban streets.

602.title: Where next?
602.summary: Walk or catch the 902 bus back to Coomoora Woodland, grab a bite to eat on Springvale Road or from the IGA, or cross Springvale Road and continue walking in Spring Valley Park on the other side.

603.title: Belgrave Station Sign
603.summary: Hop off at Belgrave station to begin your walk. Belgrave is a Zone 2 station easily accessible from the city.

604.title: Puffing Billy
604.summary: If you're in luck, you might catch the Puffing Billy leaving the station!

osm.name: Gembrook (Puffing Billy) Line
osm.display_name: Gembrook (Puffing Billy) Line, Belgrave - Gembrook Road, Selby, Melbourne, Shire of Yarra Ranges, Victoria, 3159, Australia

605.title: Puffing Billy tracks
605.summary: Cross the train tracks, carefully of course and preferably not in the path of an oncoming steam train.

606.title: National Parks sign
606.summary: A sure sign that you're on the right path!

607.title: Gate at start of Coles Ridge Track
607.summary: Your walk in the Dandenongs starts here! The gate at the start of Coles Ridge Track leads you in the right direction. Don't forget to breathe in the fresh air.

608.title: Coles Ridge Track
608.summary: The trees along this area are particularly scenic, particularly in the morning light.

osm.name: Coles Ridge Track
osm.display_name: Coles Ridge Track, Sherbrooke, Melbourne, Shire of Yarra Ranges, Victoria, 3160, Australia

609.title: Lots of signs
609.summary: No chance of getting lost in the woods with these many signs pointing you in the right direction.

610.title: Walking along the track
610.summary: More ferns and dappled sunlight on leaves.

611.title: Beautiful views
611.summary: Beautiful views all along the walk. A perfect spot to stop and see if you can hear the resident lyrebirds.

612.title: Even more beautiful views
612.summary: If only forests like these were all over Victoria!

613.title: Heading towards the end of the walk
613.summary: Make sure you fill your lungs with as much forest air as you can before leaving the park. Better still, come back for another visit soon!

614.title: Leave a message
614.summary: A lovely idea! Write or draw a message for the next person to see.

615.title: Snakes and ladders
615.summary: Come and play snakes and ladders! This is a colourful and fun way to play on the street.  Grown ups can play too :)

616.title: All creatures great and small
616.summary: Which animals can you find? Come along to see which creatures have been visiting the area.

617.title: Hopscotch
617.summary: Hop into it and show us your best moves.

618.title: Sports walk
618.summary: Can you name all the different sports show in this section? Can you name the sports people that play each of these games?

619.title: Track your numbers
619.summary: Maybe this is a numbers game?

620.title: Where the wild things grow
620.summary: Can you name all these animals? I think they\'re all native to Australia.  And what\'s that harvester doing amongst it all?

621.title: Track your numbers
621.summary: Is this a counting game? Make your own game up if you like.

622.title: Brimbank City Council
622.summary: This walk is proudly brought to you by Brimbank City Council.

623.title: Lucknow - Eastwood Supermarket Carpark
623.summary: Start the walk at the Lucknow - Eastwood Supermarket Carpark

624.title: Cross Howitt Avenue where safe to do so..
624.summary: Look out for cars near the supermarket carpark and cross where the school children cross for the Lucknow Primary School.

625.title: Enter the park where the busses turn to collect the Lucknow Primary School Students.
625.summary: The entry of the park starts at the bus turn area

626.title: Alfred Howitt Community Hall
626.summary: The Alfred Howitt Community Hall is where to cross the Balmoral Cres.

627.title: The new Alfred Howitt Memorial Hall

628.title: The staircase
628.summary: This is the stairway to heaven

629.title: Baarton Place has a walk that cuts through the parks
629.summary: Take the footpath and walking path through the park and Barton Place

630.title: Wetlands
630.summary: There are some wonderful wetland full of birdlife here

631.title: Wetlands and footbridges
631.summary: Wonderful wetlands here and a few picnic spots

632.title: a few water crossings
632.summary: The Backwater from the Mitchel River is here

633.title: Picnic Point
633.summary: A lovely spot for a picnic

634.title: Fishing platform
634.summary: Fishing platform are down the side of the Mitchell River Backwater and Bream are found here..

635.title: Huge old gum trees here
635.summary: There are some wonderful old gum trees in this park on this walk

636.title: Finns Road footpath is 2.5 metres wide all the way
636.summary: Finns Road footpath is 2.5 metres wide all the way

637.title: Interesting tea tree growth and creek flow
637.summary: A pleasant boardwalk through tea trees and a creek

639.title: More wetland areas with tons of cormorants and ibis and other water birds
639.summary: More wetland areas with tons of cormorants and ibis and other water birds

640.title: Lovely walks under cover
640.summary: There are a number of picnic tables under cover on this walk

641.title: Easy walking along the footpaths
641.summary: The footpaths are wide and very good (concrete)

642.title: The Nature Walk Car Park- a Heart Foundation Park Walk
642.summary: Surrounded by black box, redgum and river cooba trees, sets the scene for this nature walk.

643.title: First view of the Billabong
643.summary: The Billabong is a birdwatchers paradise. View the Australian Pelicans, herons, black swans and a variety of ducks.

644.title: Walking track across the dam wall.
644.summary: Kings Billabong took its name from the Indigenous word for still water-billabong. Local Indigenous people have enjoyed the Billabong's self supporting food supply for thousands of years.

645.title: Discover native wildlife up close.
645.summary: Walk or cycle in this dirt track through healthy woodland.

646.title: Native flowers in abundance along the Billabong bank
646.summary: Delightful flowers spread through out the bushland offering fantastic photo opportunities.

647.title: Old Pump House viewed across the water
647.summary: The Chaffey brothers selected Kings Billabong at the central water supply to establish the Mildura Irrigation Settlement.. Many trees were felled to feed the boilers of the steam powered pumps.

648.title: The Bird Hide
648.summary: Take a picnic and relax and enjoy the delightful views.

649.title: Bird Hide View
649.summary: A spectacular display of free flying birds perched peacefully on fallen trees.

650.title: Sit and ponder
650.summary: The track creates a loop and you commence your return.

651.title: One last  look before you cross the dam wall.
651.summary: This Park Walk is nearly at an end but your exploration of Kings Billabong Wildlife Reserve has only just began.

652.title: Starting off
652.summary: The walk is wonderful from the first steps!

653.title: Venus Baths
653.summary: Venus Baths is a picturesque area with a fresh water lake and many unusual rock formations. It is a wonderful spot to dip your feet in the water on a hot day.

osm.name: Venus Baths
osm.display_name: Venus Baths, Halls Gap, Shire of Northern Grampians, Victoria, 3381, Australia

654.title: Magnificent views
654.summary: Walking over the stoney outcrop gives some great views, and can be very windy on blowy days. Hold on to your hat!

655.title: Wildflowers
655.summary: In Spring there are a glorious array of wildflowers along the walk.

657.title: Splitter Falls
657.summary: Take the small detour to see Splitter Falls, it's worth it!

658.title: The bridge
658.summary: Cross the bridge, but stop and look at the creek..

659.title: The steps
659.summary: The track is full of wonderful surprises, like these steps.

660.title: Wonderland carpark sign
660.summary: Stay left, don't go to Wonderland carpark, it's only a car park!

661.title: Grand Canyon
661.summary: The aptly named Grand Canyon is a very impressive rock formation.

osm.name: Grand Canyon
osm.display_name: Grand Canyon, Halls Gap, Shire of Northern Grampians, Victoria, 3381, Australia

662.title: Cool Chamber
662.summary: The Cool Chamber is as it sounds, a nice little spot to stop on a hot day.

osm.name: Cool Chamber
osm.display_name: Cool Chamber, Wonderland Car Park to Pinnacle, Bellfield, Halls Gap, Shire of Northern Grampians, Victoria, 3381, Australia

663.title: Bridal Veil Falls
663.summary: Just the ticket of a warm day, stand under the little falls to cool off.

osm.name: Bridal Veil Falls
osm.display_name: Bridal Veil Falls, Bellfield, Shire of Northern Grampians, Victoria, Australia

664.title: Silent Street
664.summary: Another pretty impressive park of the walk.

osm.name: Silent Street
osm.display_name: Silent Street, Bellfield, Shire of Northern Grampians, Victoria, 3381, Australia

665.title: View to Lake Bellfield
665.summary: Looking down to the lake which is a local water supply and is about 5km from Halls Gap.

666.title: To Halls Gap
666.summary: Its a pretty spectacular view that is worth the walk!

osm.name: Halls Gap to Pinnacle Track
osm.display_name: Halls Gap to Pinnacle Track, Bellfield, Halls Gap, Shire of Northern Grampians, Victoria, 3381, Australia

667.title: The way down
667.summary: The start of the walk back down towards Halls Gap is a bit of a clamber over rocks, but once you are on the track it is well marked.

668.title: Over the rocks
668.summary: Keep going over the rocks. Once you get past the rocks its quicker to descend the mountain than it was to climb!

669.title: The steps
669.summary: There a few long sets of metal steps on the way down that makes it a bit easier to walk and to protect the bush.

670.title: Albert Park Primary School
670.summary: A great idea - a primary school playground that is open to all on weekends.

osm.name: Albert Park Primary School
osm.display_name: Albert Park Primary School, 2-38, Victoria Street, South Melbourne, Melbourne, City of Port Phillip, Victoria, 3205, Australia

671.title: Jock's ice-cream shop
671.summary: Jock's is famous for its ice-cream - worth a visit either on your way to or from the beach.

672.title: Fairy Tree
672.summary: A delight at any time but lit with fairy lights (of course!) at night around Christmas!

673.title: Gasworks Park
673.summary: There are artists studios, a theatre and a cafe. Every 3rd Saturday there is a Farmers' Market.  In the park you'll also come across various wonderful sculptures and installations.

osm.name: Gasworks Arts Park
osm.display_name: Gasworks Arts Park, Albert Park, Melbourne, City of Port Phillip, Victoria, Australia

674.title: Station Pier
674.summary: Cross Beaconsfield Pde, head onto the beach, take your shoes and socks off and go for a paddle.

676.title: Reserve Entrance
676.summary: At the entrance to the reserve there is a small car park.

677.title: Start of the walk
677.summary: At the start of the walk, follow the sign to the picnic and BBQ area.

678.title: Reserve Map
678.summary: When you reach the aging reserve map, turn right and follow the Hakea Circle path to Acacia Walk.

679.title: Spreading Wattle
679.summary: This wattle has needle leaves. Its lemon-cream globular flower-heads brighten the forest during the Spring season.

680.title: Austral Bracken
680.summary: It is easy to find Austral Bracken which can out-compete other plants to form a dense understorey. It creates a humid microclimate under its leaves and is food for a variety of native insects.

681.title: Local housing development
681.summary: This bird box has a fairly small hole which would suit the White-throated Treecreeper, the Red-browed Treecreeper, the Feathertail Glider and the Sugar Glider amongst others.

682.title: Common Hovea
682.summary: Keep an eye out for interesting shrubs along the route.  The Common Hovea is a slender shrub, native to Australia. The upper leaves are narrow and long while the lower leaves are oval-shaped.

683.title: Look up
683.summary: It is worth stopping to appreciate the wonderful canopy overhead and the endless shades of green on show.  It is also a good opportunity to spot some of the 88 local species of birdlife darting about.

684.title: Abundant flora
684.summary: 336 species of indigenous plants have been recorded in the Reserve.  Every visit to the reserve is rewarded by new discoveries!

685.title: Bushy Needlewood
685.summary: The prickly foliage of these understorey plants provides safe nesting sites for small birds and also provides nectar for native bees.

686.title: Walking among the trees
686.summary: Trees along the walk include Stringybark and  the 60m high Mountain Grey gums

687.title: Sumner Park
687.summary: Home of the Brunswick Zebras and general community play area. Often see many dogs running around here too.

osm.name: Sumner Park
osm.display_name: Sumner Park, Brunswick East, Melbourne, City of Merri-bek, Victoria, Australia

688.title: Bridge across to Merri Park
688.summary: You could take a quick detour over the bridge, there is a children's playground.

689.title: Kirkdale Street Park

698.title: Farmgate: Merri Creek Market Garden

699.title: Retaining wall

718.title: Blue wren
718.summary: One of the many types of birds you might see along the trail

719.title: Toilets
719.summary: Good clean toilets at the start or end of your walk are always welcome!

720.title: The path
720.summary: Nice start to the walk past the blackwood and stringy bark trees. Wallabies are often here in the evening.

721.title: The Bluff lookout path
721.summary: This walk takes you to the Bluff Lookout not the base of the falls (make sure you are on the right path, this is the easier walk).

722.title: Wildflowers
722.summary: There are many beautiful wildflowers in Spring.

723.title: Seat
723.summary: A welcome seat to sit and smell and hear the sounds of the bush.

724.title: The Bridge
724.summary: The bridge over the little gully ensures a smooth path for prams and some wheelchairs.

725.title: Grass trees
725.summary: The sandy soils supports an Australian icon the Grass Tree, Xanthorrhoea australis. When in flower they are often called Kangaroo tails as they extend into the air, looking like a roo tail.

726.title: Beatiful bush
726.summary: The bush is really beautiful with grass trees, gums and lots of undergrowth.

727.title: McKenzie Falls
727.summary: The Falls look magnificent from up here, made us want to go down to the base too.

728.title: Burnt out stump
728.summary: Love this burnt out stump, although wouldn't want have been here when there was a fire.

729.title: Point Cook Homestead
729.summary: Open from 9am to 4pm daily, this wonderfully restored homestead was built in 1857 by the Scotsman Thomas Chirnside. He later went on to build Werribee Mansion with his brother Andrew.

osm.name: Point Cook Homestead
osm.display_name: Point Cook Homestead, Point Cook, Melbourne, City of Wyndham, Victoria, 3030, Australia

730.title: Birdlife
730.summary: There are lots of bird species to spot on the walk including Pied Cormorants who live in colonies and dive underwater to catch fish.

731.title: Beach walkers
731.summary: If the tide is out, walking along the beach provides a lovely cool breeze in the summer.  As you walk there are shells to discover, birds to spot, and views of the CBD across the bay.

732.title: Red-necked Stints
732.summary: These small birds migrate from the northern hemisphere where they breed, to Victoria in summer.  They arrive in August and depart in February-March.

733.title: High-tide detour
733.summary: If the tide is in, you can walk along a wide path behind the beach, dotted with old pine trees.  It curves around Point Cook to the white beacon.

734.title: Wetlands entrance
734.summary: This is the point where you leave the beach behind and start walking along the track next to the beach.

735.title: A shorter option
735.summary: At the point you leave the beach you will see the track to a white beacon.  You can skip the Wetlands part of the walk by following this track back to the Wetlands car park.

736.title: The walking track
736.summary: The walking tracks are frequently exposed and quite sandy in places.  A good hat and sun cream are recommended.

737.title: The Tower
737.summary: There are great views from the tower platform.  Artist Bill Kelly designed it as A Monument to Migration and Aspirations - using the theme of bird migration as a symbol for human migration.

738.title: The Wetlands
738.summary: The wetlands are a migratory haven for birds, some from as far away as Siberia and Japan.  The area is home to more than 200 species of birds including rare and endangered species.

739.title: Saltmarsh flora
739.summary: If you look closely there are lots of hardy plants who find this challenging environment quite suitable for their needs including the Rounded Moon-flower and Beaded Glasswort.

740.title: The Falls
740.summary: View the falls from a viewing platform below the falls.

741.title: Car park
741.summary: park your car or bus at the car park before you head off for the walk.

742.title: New Facilities
742.summary: Since Black Saturday new facilities have been added for convenience of people walking to the falls.

743.title: The start of the walk
743.summary: Here is where you start the walk to the falls but there are also other paths for different walks.

744.title: New platform
744.summary: A new platform has been made down from the falls where you can stand over the flowing water.

745.title: Loose footpath
745.summary: be careful when walking along this path as it is made out of loose rocks and stones and there arent many rails along path.

746.title: A reminder of black saturday
746.summary: View the burnt trees and the new life that is coming out.

747.title: Old path to top viewing platform
747.summary: This was the path you use to take to the top platform above the falls. currently under construction.

748.title: Where old meets new
748.summary: Falling down trees over a running creek and surrounded by new life.

749.title: See the falls
749.summary: View Stevensons Falls from a distance.

750.title: Option for different route
750.summary: Another walk is connected to the walk to the falls, you can take this to the fern gully.

751.title: The sunrise
751.summary: No visit to Byron is complete without watching the sunrise!

752.title: Byron Bay Main Beach
752.summary: Byron Bay Main Beach is a walker's paradise. Flat, hard sand and plenty of things to look at.

osm.name: Main Beach
osm.display_name: Main Beach, Byron Bay, Byron Shire Council, New South Wales, 2481, Australia

753.title: The Pass beach
753.summary: Generally sheltered family beach and a great spot to watch surfers.

754.title: The Lookout.
754.summary: You have to clamber over rocks to get to the steps and if it is high tide wade through the water, but definitely worth the effort.

755.title: Looking to The Pass beach
755.summary: Looking back along the beach with Palm Valley behind.

756.title: Byron Bay
756.summary: It is easy to spend an hour up on the look out, a fantastic view on all sides.

osm.display_name: Byron Bay, New South Wales, 2481, Australia

757.title: Humpback Whales
757.summary: Not a great photo, but when I was here, I saw over 10 whales out to sea. Sometimes they come in quite close.

758.title: Palm Valley path
758.summary: A great walk through the bush, the path is well maintained and smooth. Suitable for prams and maybe wheelchairs, but quite steep in parts.

759.title: The Boardwalk
759.summary: The Boardwalk is fantastic and makes for easy walking. Good viewing out to sea as well.

760.title: The Kombi
760.summary: Love this artwork makes a drab electricity sub station look good. Very Byron!

761.title: Avenue of trees
761.summary: Nice avenue of trees and picnic area.

762.title: Middleton St artwork
762.summary: There is no information about this artwork, but it looks a bit like a wooden version of stonehenge.

763.title: Monumental Environmental Artwork
763.summary: Monumental Environmental Artwork is by John Dahlsen. The sign says it is temporarily installed, I hope not beacause it is a beauty. It is made out of a stump is Camphour Laurel.

764.title: Crossing Bay St
764.summary: Getting across Bay St can be diabolical. Many drivers do not pay attention & vegetation obstructs their view. There is no pedestrain crossing and some of the pram ramps don\\'t line up. Woeful!

765.title: Crossing Lawson St
765.summary: Very dangerous & inconvenient crossing. Pedestrains are forced away from crossing at the corner where they can see oncoming cars. The sign says it all, walkers are not important.

766.title: Footpath ends
766.summary: Another dangerous point for walkers, the footpath suddenly turns into a roadway.

767.title: The Shared Path
767.summary: Nice to have a shared path away from cars. Watch out for bikes, none seem to ring a bell when coming up from behind.

768.title: Byron Bay bats
768.summary: Look out for the colony of bats in the trees in Cumbebin Swamp Nature Reserve next to the path. If you cannot see them, you will smell them. Not the most pleasant of smells.

769.title: Ewingsdale Road

osm.display_name: Shirley Street, Byron Bay, Byron Shire Council, New South Wales, 2481, Australia

792.summary: The Pickering Point Trail joins to the Viaduct Road section of the Foreshore trails

793.title: Loxton Lodge Community Garden
793.summary: It's always an inspiration to see what's growing in the garden.  Sometimes it's a busy hive of activity and other times quiet and peaceful.

794.title: Milk bar
794.summary: Sometimes I buy the paper in a milk bar, often wondering how these little shops survive financially.

795.title: Retro furniture galore
795.summary:
As I approach High St, I like to look in the windows of the 2 retro furniture shops full of stuff from the 60s 
that reminds me of my childhood.

796.title: Our very own Abbey Road
796.summary: Shopping mecca, with bonus zebra crossings that remind me of the Beatles Abbey Road album.

797.title: Prahran library
797.summary: Entering the library in the old Town Hall, the air conditioning and high ceilings give relief from the heat of the day at the height of summer.  Nice and warm in winter of course!

798.title: Groceries, coffee and pizza
798.summary: Sometimes I buy fruit on the way home, or stop off for hot chocolate and cake at an old fashioned cafe or pizza in the lovely upstairs courtyard of a pub.

799.title: Cake shop
799.summary: The most creative and fabulous cakes can be found here.

800.title: Fruit trees
800.summary: The other day I spotted a vine laden with bunches of grapes. I've got my eye on the lemon tree in Union St which last summer dropped so much fruit on the pavement I had free lemons all summer!

801.title: 1. Site of Ballarat's old haymarket (Doveton/Market/Armstrong/Mair block)
801.summary: This has long been a public and central meeting place - situated at the junction of roads, and a few minutes from rail transport and Ballarat's key cultural and civic institutions.

802.title: 2. The Civic Hall, 300 Mair St,  built 1953-1956
802.summary: Multi-purpose venue, with monumental presence.   Steel frame, local Selkirks bricks.  Main Hall holds c. 1600,  Performers included INXS.  Closed 2002, reopened 2014 for community design process.

803.title: 3. Statue of playwright William Shakespeare by Andor Meszaros, by 300 Mair St
803.summary: Statue added to front of hall 1960 depicts Shakespeare receiving applause after a performance.   Hungarian visitor Karoly Nagy was so impressed he organised a replica for Budapest unveiled 2003.

804.title: 4. Ginkgo trees planted by Sir Paul & Lady Hasluck 1972, western end  skate park
804.summary: Planted during Vice-regal visit, the trees are of the ancient Ginkgo biloba species (Maidenhair tree), native to China, called living fossils as similar to fossils dating back 270 million years.

805.title: 5. Statue of Scottish writer Sir Walter Scott by Stanley Hammond, by 300 Mair St
805.summary: The centenary of gold celebrations in the early 1950s gave a renewed push to plans for a new Civic Hall so it is fitting that both the Scott & Shakespeare statues record links to Goldrush times.

806.title: 6. Lower Hall entrance, Doveton St
806.summary: The architects of the hall made clever use of the fall of the ground on the site from West to East to build the foyer of the Lower Hall under the stage of the Main Hall.  Note messages on doors.

807.title: 7. View of fly tower, Doveton St
807.summary: The tall tower like structure at the northern end of the hall is the Fly Tower. This is the part of the building designed to store and launch the sets for large scale theatrical productions.

808.title: 8. Ballarat Library upper story offices, Market St
808.summary: The relationship with the Civic Hall was considered during the design of the Ballarat Library built 1993-1994,  The  upper story offices echoes the brickwork of the Civic Hall.

809.title: 9. Mural, Civic Hall/Library Car Park, off Market St
809.summary: A colourful public art mural has been created on the back wall of the carpark.   The mural was painted in 2013 by local youth working alongside professional artist Pauline O'Shannessy-Dowling.

810.title: 10. View to railway precinct, cnr Market & Armstrong St
810.summary: The proximity to the Provincial Hotel and Railway Station beyond it is evident from this corner of the site.

811.title: 11. Skate park, Armstrong St
811.summary: The skate park was the initiative of a young Ballarat skater and was added to the site in the 1990s.  A replacement skate park was built at the Len T Fraser reserve in 2004 but this remains popular.

812.title: 12. Regent Cinema, 49 Lydiard St Nth
812.summary: The cinema's interior was rebuilt in 1943 to the design of Cowper, Murphy & Appleford after a major fire attributed to visiting American service personnel.    Murphy was later co-architect Civic Hall.

813.title: 13. Mair to Sturt Block, Lydiard St Nth, east side
813.summary: This block is now one of the most treasured in Ballarat encompassing Victorian era architectural gems.  However records show that in the 1940s this was one site proposed for a new civic hall.

814.title: 14. Site of Alfred Hall, Cnr Curtis & Grenville Sts, demolished 1956
814.summary: Site of a predecessor of the Civic Hall, constructed n 1867 on the boundaries of East & West Ballarat for Ballarat's first royal visitor and formally closed on the day the Civic Hall opened.

815.title: 15. Former Walter Davis store, 86 Bridge Mall
815.summary: An example of the commercial work of Civic Hall architect Les Coburn who remodelled the store in 1935 with distinctive art deco features.  Coburn was known for both his commercial & residential work.

816.title: 16. Site of Coliseum, Little Bridge Street (vicinity Ballarat Senior Citizen's Centre)
816.summary: Another very large hall (capacity up to 10,000) owned by the South Street Society and used for society & civic events. It burnt down in 1936 creating impetus for the building of a new public hall.

817.title: 17. Her Majesty's Theatre ('Her Maj'),17 Lydiard St South
817.summary: Historic theatre first opened in 1875.   The history of the Civic Hall intersected with that of 'Her Maj' from 1990 - 2002 as the City of Ballarat combined management of the two facilities.

818.title: 18. Ballarat Town Hall, 225 Sturt St
818.summary: The eventual design of the Civic Hall was innovative in separating hall facilities and the Council admin offices.  Architect Les Coburn was greatly interested in civic matters as long-time Councillor.

819.title: 19. Block Arcade, 321 Sturt St
819.summary: The Sturt Street entrance of the Block Arcade was remodelled by Les Coburn in 1937. Look up to the first floor to get the best view of this work, the stylised parapet and lettering.

820.title: 20. State Government Offices, Cnr Mair & Doveton Streets
820.summary: To the west of the Civic Hall is another public building - the State Government Offices opened in 1981 and known as "The Glass House" because of its distinctive glass curtain wall design.

821.title: Start of walk
821.summary: Underwood Park sign with large map of main attractions - lots of free parking.

822.title: Seating under a shady tree
822.summary: Shady seats overlooking the wedding gazebo and bridge.

824.title: Bridge
824.summary: Monet style bridge - no water lilies today.

825.title: Bush path
825.summary: A little less populated leading up to the duck ponds.

826.title: Path over duck pond
826.summary: This part of the path goes over the duck pond through the trees. There are lots of ducks, but you may have to look a little harder to find the large orange fish and the turtles.

827.title: Playground
827.summary: A shady playground for the kids - right next to tables, seats, toilets and some of the sporting fields (e.g. netball, softball). The caretaker's hut is also close by.

828.title: Dog park
828.summary: Two fenced dog parks with multiple access points. One is for smaller dogs and one is for larger dogs. Both parks have water, plastic doggy bags, bins and seats.

829.title: Daisy Painting
829.summary: All of the telephone poles have been painted with beautiful Australian scenes.

830.title: Building mural
830.summary: What a great mural! A few of the buildings in this area have been painted to blend into the scenery.

831.title: Picnic tables, BBQ and toilets
831.summary: This is a very popular picnic spot in summer. There are gas BBQs, several picnic tables and benches, and toilets. Photo by Parks Victoria.

832.title: Start of walking track
832.summary: We took Coranderrk Track, a vehicle track that follows Badger Creek. Alternate routes include Lyrebird Track and Slip Creek Track. They're roughly the same distance but have steps.

833.title: Fresh mountain air
833.summary: Fill your lungs with the fresh air from the surrounding forest. The sun dappled light made our walk truly magical!

834.title: Tree canopy
834.summary: Don't forget to look up every now and then as you might spot some local birds or simply to enjoy the view.

835.title: Popular walk, even in the middle of winter
835.summary: This walk is popular in summer as a lovely way to cool off, and in winter to enjoy the crisp and refreshing fresh air.

836.title: Colourful tree bark
836.summary: The colours of a forest are always a treat. The lush green ferns and the dew drops on them are gorgeous, while the colours of the barks of trees are varied and ever changing.

837.title: Get up close
837.summary: Forests are the perfect subject if you like photography. There's no shortage of beautiful landscapes and interesting close-ups to snap.

838.title: Badger Creek
838.summary: It's a treat to see the Creek after a rainy day as it's full and fast flowing.

839.title: Dam wall & spillway
839.summary: The dam wall was constructed in 1927, and raised in 1936. Stone came from the crest of the range via horse-drawn tramway. The east shore is a popular picnic nd recreation area

840.title: Lake track
840.summary: This section of track adjoins a flora & fauna conservation area, where local wildlife such as kangaroos may be sighted, especially in the mornings and evenings

osm.name: Lake track
osm.display_name: Lake track, Lysterfield, Melbourne, Shire of Yarra Ranges, Victoria, 3804, Australia

841.title: Mahogany track
841.summary: The track is climbing, and there are farm ruins on the east side, not connected with those at the boy's farm. Thompson track is narrow and winding, with many tree roots

osm.name: Mahogany Track
osm.display_name: Mahogany Track, Lysterfield, Melbourne, Shire of Yarra Ranges, Victoria, 3804, Australia

842.title: Boy's farm
842.summary: The former boy's farm is slightly off the main trail, with numerous ruins and the former orchard now growing untended. The boy's farm closed more than 60 years ago, yet much is still visible

843.title: Highest point
843.summary: This is the summit on this trip, the knoll to the right around 100m ASL. The descent on Lyster track is steep and rocky, but only for a short distance

844.title: Donelan's farm
844.summary: The Donelan family settled here in the 1930s, but only lived here a short time. Numerous exotic trees still grow here, and the farm dam is clear to see

845.title: Lysterfield tramway
845.summary: The walk joins the former Lysterfield tramway at this point for a long, gentle descent to the west side of the dam wall. This track is for walkers only

846.title: Lake view
846.summary: This point on the former tramway is one of the best view points of the lake on the west side. There is still something to see before rejoining the main path

847.title: Tramway display
847.summary: This static display shows the type of stone hopper used on the narrow gauge horse-drawn Lysterfield tramway. The hopper was manufactured in Leeds UK

848.title: Crayfish Bay signpost
848.summary: Crayfish Bay signpost, all you need do is decide which track to take first. I reckon, take the beach way and cliff top back there is best.

849.title: The grottos
849.summary: There a few grottos or small caves at the end of the first beach. Many a time on a rainy, cold winters day they have provided shelter.

850.title: Cape Otway Lighthouse
850.summary: The white spot in the cliff edge in the distance (middle of the photo) is the Cape Oyway Lighthouse.

851.title: Rockpools
851.summary: At low tide there are many, many rockpools to keep young and old fascinated.

852.title: Arriving at Cray Bay
852.summary: Arriving at Cray Bay at low tide, on a still warm April morning. Beautiful.

853.title: Crayfish Bay
853.summary: Crafish Bay at its best, on a very low tide, which is great for a snorkle (don't bother diving if it is not low tide).

osm.name: Crayfish Bay
osm.display_name: Crayfish Bay, Shire of Colac Otway, Victoria, Australia

854.title: Cray Bay and Otway Reef
854.summary: Climbing up the track and looking down on Cray Bay and out to the Otway Reef

855.title: The Southern Ocean
855.summary: A great spot to look out to the Southern Ocean and watch the rollers coming in.

856.title: The Cliff Top Track
856.summary: The Cliff Top Track is very narrow and sometimes a little overgrown, but a delight nonetheless.

858.title: Kensington Neighbourhood House
858.summary: Providing a variety of programs for locals. Kensington Neighbourhood House has been running for 40 years to help locals.

859.title: Women's Peace Garden
859.summary: The Garden was conceived in 1986 as a part of the International Year of Peace. Features plants symbolic of peace and colours of women's movement. It's a very relaxing place.

osm.name: Women's Peace Garden
osm.display_name: Women's Peace Garden, Kensington, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3031, Australia

860.title: 'The Back Gate' Mosaic Murals
860.summary: Under the Epsom Road Bridge. Installed in 1998. Commemorates historic Newmarket Saleyards. Animals passed the 'Back Gate' to leave the Saleyards towards the abattoir or meatworks.

861.title: Kensington Banks
861.summary: Kensington is a nice place for walking around and there are many children’s playgrounds. It's a lovely place to live because public transport is very convenient.

862.title: Community Garden
862.summary: If you're interested in renting a plot to grow your own vegetables, please contact Kensington Community Recreation Centre on 9376 1633 or kensington@ymca.org.au.

863.title: Wildlife
863.summary: Apart from birds, sometimes you can see local wildlife on apartment balconies too.

864.title: Maribyrnong River and Wetlands
864.summary: You can walk or cycle along the river to visit the wetlands, or travel to other places from here.

865.title: Starfish
865.summary: When the water is low you can see starfish on the river banks.

866.title: Bayswater Road Park
866.summary: This playground is great for children of all ages. The park also has BBQ, tables , seats and a water tap.

osm.name: Bayswater Road Park
osm.display_name: Bayswater Road Park, Kensington, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3031, Australia

867.title: Victorian houses
867.summary: Built during the reign of Queen Victoria. Many houses have been lovingly restored.

868.title: The Kiln
868.summary: When petrol rationing was introduced in 1940, charcoal was seen as a practical alternative.  This kiln is a rare example of a relatively intact charcoal burning kiln.

869.title: Friends of Kurth Kiln
869.summary: The Friends are actively engaged in maintaining the notice board, the kiln site and the tracks on this walk.

870.title: Brown Stringy-bark trees
870.summary:
This versatile tree provided food, medicines, containers, string and
tools for Aboriginal people.

871.title: The creek
871.summary: There are several great views of the creek along the walk.  Close your eyes and listen to the water running down stream.   What other sounds can you hear?

872.title: Common Heath
872.summary: The heath flowers, which mainly occur between late autumn and early spring are white, pink or red in colour.  See if you can find a pink one, it is Victorias floral emblem.

873.title: Foam build-up
873.summary: You can be forgiven for thinking it is a sign of pollution.  The foam is produced by the decomposition of a wide variety of plant material including aquatic plants and the leaves of trees.

874.title: End of Tomahawk Creek track
874.summary: The track returns to Beenak Road on the opposite side of the bridge to where we started.

875.title: Picnic Area
875.summary: After walking along the Tomahawk track, this is a great spot to relax and listen to the birds singing.   You may hear lyrebirds, honeyeaters, parrots and kookaburras.

osm.name: Kurth Kiln Picnic Area
osm.display_name: Kurth Kiln Picnic Area, Kurth Kiln Track, Gembrook, Melbourne, Shire of Cardinia, Victoria, Australia

876.title: Closer to nature
876.summary: The path narrows at times immersing you in the sights and smells of ferns, bushes and trees along the way.

877.title: Tree down
877.summary: A fallen tree has provided the opportunity for smaller plants to flourish.  Beneath the tree canopy you can find Silver Wattle, Spike Wattle, Christmas Bush, Silver Banksia and tree ferns.

878.title: Hakea
878.summary: Look out for Hakea along the route.  The nectar is used by insects and birds when it is in flower. Hakea requires fire to reproduce as the hard nut needs to be broken for the seed to be released.

879.title: Toilet on route
879.summary: This toilet might provide welcome relief along the way.  It is only a slight detour from the walking route.

880.title: The road home
880.summary: The last section of the walk is a wide gravel road leading back to the kiln.

881.title: The Heritage Peppercorn Tree
881.summary: South American Peppercorn trees were often planted near homesteads in the colonial period. The White and Clements families ran the dairy farm Flora Vale in this area from the 1840s to the early 1970s.

882.title: The Relocated Scarred Tree
882.summary: Scars on living trees are from Aboriginal people deliberately removing bark or wood.

883.title: The Possum Tree
883.summary: Years ago, major limb loss, fire and decay in this ancient river redgum (Eucalyptus camaldulensis) created a large opening with nooks and crannies for possums and birds to shelter.

884.title: possum
884.summary: Look out for some local wildlife using the habitat these tress and understory provide.

885.title: Lakeview
885.summary: Wetlands are home to aquatic and semi-aquatic indigenous plant species, water birds, frogs, fish and invertebrates. Wetlands were a major source of food, fibre and medicines for Aboriginal people.

886.title: The Fused-limb Tree
886.summary: This can happen naturally but Aboriginal people also made it happen by deliberately manipulating a growing tree. Either way, the trees are thought to have special significance.

887.title: Funky RMIT architecture
887.summary: Enjoy the views of the funky built form.  Kids love this walk too!

888.title: Burls
888.summary: A number of bulbous woody growths occur at the base of the trunk, called lignotubers or 'burls'.The Wurundjeri people sometimes removed the burls and crafted them into water containers called tarnuks.

889.title: Triple Scar and Redgum Grassy Woodlands
889.summary: Some of these redgums are well over 400 years old. Help the Friends of the Bundoora Redgums restore the grassy understory to boost biodiversity.

890.title: The 'Canoe' Tree
890.summary: The scar on this tree is probably from bark being deliberately removed to make roofing material or a small food-collection canoe.

891.title: The Staircase
891.summary: This non indigenous lemon scented gum  still provides nectar for the local possums as seen by the claw marks in its trunk.

892.title: The Resource Tree
892.summary: Trees were major food sources for the Wurundjeri people. Birds, eggs, honey and possums could all be harvested from trees. This one has an access hole.

893.title: The Rectangular Cultural Scar
893.summary: This is a highly significant tree. The scars size suggests the bark was used to build a shelter.

894.title: Frogpond
894.summary: 6 species of frogs have been recorded in Bundoora, most of which need the wetlands to survive. Frogs have been around for 190 million years and are an accurate indicator of environmental wellbeing.

895.title: Woodland View and Re-vegetation site
895.summary: The Friends of the Bundoora Redgums Inc, a volunteer organisation, has begun the long process of restoring the Redgum Grassy Woodland to its former glory. Join in!

896.title: Pedestrian path
896.summary: Coming out of the train station towards the Harbour Bridge  you will soon come to these steps - walk up them.

897.title: Business in the bridge
897.summary: The pedestrian path emerges on the other side of the railway line and you can walk alongside the start of the Harbour Bridge, which has some interesting businesses built into it, including this cafe.

898.title: Bradfield Park
898.summary: Bradfield Park runs alongside the Bridge - make sure you check out the signs explaining the interesting history of the Bridge.

osm.name: Bradfield Park
osm.display_name: Bradfield Park, Milsons Point, Lower North Shore, Sydney, North Sydney Council, New South Wales, 2061, Australia

899.title: Steps onto the Bridge
899.summary: Walk through Milsons Point train station under the Bridge, and at this point you've got the option of walking up onto it to take in the views.

900.title: Milsons Point shops
900.summary: Quite a few shops here if you need them, including more built into the Bridge itself.

901.title: Historic houses
901.summary: There are some beautiful historic houses on these very picturesque streets, including this real oldie.

902.title: Milson Park
902.summary: A nice walk down to this park, which has a small playground, toilets and access to the water.

osm.name: Milson Park
osm.display_name: Milson Park, Kirribilli, Lower North Shore, Sydney, North Sydney Council, New South Wales, 2061, Australia

903.title: Kirribilli wharf
903.summary: As an optional detour follow the signs down to the rather cute Kirribilli wharf, with a small cafe and great views.  There's even the option of taking a ferry to the city if you feel inclined.

osm.name: Jeffrey St Wharf
osm.display_name: Jeffrey St Wharf, Jefferys Street, Kirribilli, Lower North Shore, Sydney, North Sydney Council, New South Wales, 2061, Australia

904.title: Kirribilli House - Prime Minister's Sydney residence
904.summary: Not exactly Versailles, quite modest really.  However not an unpleasant place for one to reside.   Unsurprisingly, the house is not open to casual visitors, but you get this view from the street.

905.title: Lady Gowrie Lookout
905.summary: Another detour option for access to the coast (but there's more of that to come).

osm.name: Lady Gowrie Lookout
osm.display_name: Lady Gowrie Lookout, Kirribilli, Lower North Shore, Sydney, North Sydney Council, New South Wales, 2061, Australia

906.title: Down the steps

907.title: Coastal path
907.summary: A meandering coastal path offers great views of some of Australia's most famous landmarks, including the harbour, Sydney CBD and the Opera House.  And the Bridge of course.

908.title: Luna Park
908.summary: Did I mention Luna Park?  There's a pool here too.

osm.name: Luna Park
osm.display_name: Luna Park, 1, Olympic Drive, Milsons Point, Lower North Shore, Sydney, North Sydney Council, New South Wales, 2061, Australia

909.title: Lavender Bay path

910.title: Wendy's Secret Garden

918.summary: Emmetts are the local machinery and harvester company in town

921.title: A view across the billabong
921.summary: The Rupanyup Memorial Park is a great place to stay with a caravan

922.title: Walk among the native shrubs
922.summary: The flowering native shrubs are great habitat during the spring and summer months and native birds can be found here in abundance during nesting season.

923.title: Seating on the walk
923.summary: There is seating around the walk so keep an eye out

924.title: The Billabong has been stocked at various times with trout and other fish.
924.summary: A place to fish if you want to take a chance

925.title: A bridge over the culvert

926.title: Picnic Benches
926.summary: There is ample covered picnic benches near a free BBQ

927.title: BBQ in the Sound Shell
927.summary: The Rupanyup Memorial Park sound shell

928.title: Playground
928.summary: There is a wonderful playground for kiddies.

929.title: Toilets and showers
929.summary: There are toilets and showers available here

931.title: More walks under shrubs
931.summary: This scrub is generally full of wild birds

933.title: Old Rupanyup Water Tower
933.summary: This water tower used to be the source for all the towns water

934.title: Maryborough Railway Station, Station Street
934.summary: Maryborough’s iconic railway station was completed in 1890. Take some time to admire the intricate tessellated tiles, elaborate entrance hall and also the longest station platform in country Victoria.

935.title: Simson Memorial Cairn , Kennedy Street
935.summary: 1939 monument commemorating the Simson brothers: first white settlers of the Maryborough area back in 1840. Some of the stones are from the original homestead. Climb the steps for a sweeping view.

936.title: Box-Ironbark Avenue
936.summary: Walk the Box-Ironbark avenue between the tennis courts and Jubilee Oval and see if there are any blossoms attracting nectar-feeding native birds.

937.title: Lake Victoria
937.summary: Walk the willow path round Lake Victoria and pass by a playground, covered bbq facilities, Caravan Park and camping area, sporting fields, fishing boardwalk and many species of water-loving birdlife.

938.title: Outdoor Olympic Swimming Pool
938.summary: A heritage-listed 1940 Art Deco building houses the public outdoor pool area. With dense lawns, specimen trees and 3 separate pools, it’s one of Maryborough’s favourite places in the Summer months.

939.title: Princes Park historic rotunda & grandstand
939.summary: The historic rotunda was built in 1904/1905 to commemorate Maryborough’s Golden Jubilee. Look out across to the ornate grandstand and lush grass of the Princes Park sporting oval.

940.title: Memorial Gates to Princes Park
940.summary: The impressive 1885 cast-iron gates and pillars of Harcourt granite (c.1926) with the names of fallen WWI soldiers are a solemn reminder of loss in a community. Lest we forget.

941.title: Princes Park ticket box
941.summary: This quaint ticket box was built in 1908 and is the only known remaining one still in operation today.

942.title: The Bull and Mouth Hotel
942.summary: Admire one of High Street’s most ornate buildings, The Bull & Mouth Hotel. Built in 1904 with grand features, a multi-million dollar project has recently been undertaken to restore its former glory.

943.title: Site 1 - Engaging the senses
943.summary: The Market was part of the estate of the Aboriginal Wurndjeri-willam clan of the woi wurrung language group. The Market was in use 13 years before it officially opened in 1878.

944.title: Site 2 - A place to meat
944.summary: The Meat Hall or Meat, Fish and Rabbit Section as it is officially known is the oldest building on the Market site and was originally used as a wholesale meat market.

945.title: Site 4 - Deli delights
945.summary: The Dairy Hall is a wonderful intact example of an art deco building. Before modern refrigeration, marbel counter tops and special underground ventilation systems were used to keep products cool.

946.title: Site 5 - Produce and pioneers
946.summary: The real history of the Market starts with H & I Sheds and A & B Sheds - used as an outlet for Melbourne's Market gardens, which were run by the Chinese, then later by Greek and Italian communitites.

947.title: Site 6 - Melbourne's Marvellous Meat Hall
947.summary: In 1884 a new front to the Meat Market was added. The Meat Hall is both of architectural and social significance for its rarity as one of a few purpose built market buildings in existence in Australia

948.title: Site 7 - Market football
948.summary: By the 1920s, a strong sporting and social culture had developed among the stallholders and merchants at the Market. Football, cricket, bowls and golf clubs were formed with matches held in 1920 - 30s

949.title: Point 8 - Instant and delicious
949.summary: By the 1950s, food vans became a popular fixture. To satisfy the tastes of American servicemen stationed in Melbourne during World War II, cafe menus were expanded to include cola and hamburgers.

950.title: Site 9 - The Old Cemetary
950.summary: Much of the Upper Market is situated on cemetery land. Although closed in 1854, some families with vaults and reserved allotments were allowed burials up to 1917.

951.title: Site 3 - More than a facade
951.summary:
The facades are of architectural significance as are the iron gates
under the Produce Arch and between the shops and the Meat Hall.

952.title: Queen Victoria Market
952.summary: The Queen Victoria Market, established in 1878 is the largest market in Australia and one of the largest in the world. Many of the buildings are still used in trade today.

osm.name: Queen Victoria Market
osm.display_name: Queen Victoria Market, Victoria Street, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

953.title: WCTU drinking fountain
953.summary: The fountain was erected in 1901 by the Womans Christian Temperance Union, who agitated for the provision of clean drinking water in public places as part of its temperance concerns.

954.title: The Argus - corner Elizabeth and LaTrobe Street
954.summary: The building housed the Argus newspaper for 30 years. The Argus was one of Melbourne's three leading newspapers, all established the founding years of the city, until its closure in 1956.

955.title: The Welsh Church - 320 LaTrobe Street
955.summary: The first free dispensary for women in 1896 was set up here. In the first 3 months the clinic treated 2,000 women and children. This led to the establishment of the Queen Victoria Hospital.

956.title: Republic Tower - corner Queen and LaTrobe Street
956.summary: Public art where you would normally expect a billboard. Designed by Melbourne architect Nonda Katsilidis, various international artworks have featured here. Cross the street for a close-up.

957.title: Laneway street art
957.summary: Step into this laneway to see a fantastic public gallery of street art. A hidden treasure trove of quirky, odd and creative pieces guaranteed to raise your eyebrows in surprise and wonder.

958.title: Queen Victoria Market
958.summary: The Queen Victoria Market, established in 1878 is the largest market in Australia and one of the largest in the world. Many of the buildings are still used in trade today.

osm.name: Queen Victoria Market
osm.display_name: Queen Victoria Market, Victoria Street, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

959.title: WCTU drinking fountain
959.summary: The fountain was erected in 1901 by the Womans Christian Temperance Union who agitated for the provision of clean drinking water in public places as part of its temperance concerns.

960.title: The Beeches Rainforest Walk
960.summary: Taggarty Cascades is part of a longer network of walks called The Beeches Rainforest Walk. Our 20 minute walk is to the timber footbridge and back, to see the waterfall tumbling down the rocks.

961.title: A picnic spot
961.summary: There's a table near the carpark that's perfect for having a picnic if the sun is out. Watch for lyrebirds that are known to frequent the area.

962.title: Fabulous fungi
962.summary: Keep an eye out for the different varieties of fungi as you descend into the rainforest understorey.

963.title: Viewing platform
963.summary: There's a viewing point half way down the path that gives you a taste of the rambunctious river that's flowing at your side. Your ears will already know about this. It's very loud.

964.title: A lush staircase
964.summary: As you descend into the rainforest, take care on the steps in case they are wet or slippery. Admire the lush tree ferns and Myrtle Beech that thrive in this cool dark world.

965.title: Viewing bridge
965.summary: This timber bridge takes you across the Taggarty River, giving you the perfect viewing platform to watch the waves of fresh water gush beneath your feet.

966.title: Stunning waterfall
966.summary: The Taggarty Cascades is an impressive site! Such a steady flow of clear gushing water tumbling over the granite boulders and down into the rainforest below.

1031.title: The Bowls Club

1032.title: The playground

1033.title: Tennis, netball and volleyball courts

1035.title: Magnificent Morton Bay Fig

1036.title: The lawns

1092.summary: This is a popular place for taking your pooch on an enjoyable walk through native bushland, although remember to keep your furry friend on the leash.

1093.summary: A visit to this Reserve showcases the indigenous landscape that used to cover this area.

1094.summary: Whether you follow the concrete track or cut into the Reserve on one of the many natural paths, you’ll discover a healthy mix of native bushland.

1095.title: The Fringing Lily
1095.summary: Just one of the many native orchids you’re likely to see if you keep an eye out.

1096.title: Cinnamon Bells
1096.summary: This is a wonderful Reserve for fans of orchids and keen photographers, with magnificent specimens such as these.

1097.title: The Bearded Orchid
1097.summary: Yet another example of why this bushland reserve is so famous for its orchids.

1098.title: Listen for lyrebirds
1098.summary: The trail begins in the shade, walking through towering manna gums. Listen for lyrebirds and their complex bird calls ringing continuously through the forest.

1099.title: Fantastic fungi
1099.summary: Watch your step because there are several types of fungi growing along this trail. Learn more about mushrooms in Australia by the link below.

1100.title: Leary Creek
1100.summary: This trail crosses Leary Creek in two spots. Badly affected by the Black Saturday bushfires, the creek contains one of the few remaining populations of a nationally endangered fish, Barred Galaxias.

1101.title: Rest spot
1101.summary: There are a couple of benches along the trail and several interpretative signs if you'd like to know more about the flora and fauna native to this area. Look for signs of wombats digging as you rest.

1102.title: Felled gums
1102.summary: Even when felled, the beauty of these gums remain. Some of the fellings will be accidental and caused by the weather, others will be deliberate clearing efforts.

1103.title: Tiny moments
1103.summary: If you look carefully, you'll see tiny moments of interaction between the natural world, like a drop of sap that's fallen over 100 metres to land on this fern.

1104.title: Bushland renewal
1104.summary: After the Black Saturday bushfires, signs of renewal and regrowth came from the resilient tree ferns, their bright green fronds striking against a backdrop of burnt out Manna gums.

1105.title: Fungi fiefdom
1105.summary: As trail starts to descend into the tree fern groves, the fungi find themselves in a darkened paradise. At your feet, you might also notice birds foraging about, looking to feast on small insects.

1106.title: Boardwalks
1106.summary: This trail includes a fantastic boardwalk pathway through fern tree groves. In 1939, a bushfire rushed through The Beauty Spot and destroyed these very same groves, along with a popular tourist spot.

1107.title: Hideaway
1107.summary: This is a cooler spot to rest, hidden in the lush ferns and overhanging foilage. The trail is in a similar state of transition today, after being reconstructed following the Black Saturday bushfires.

1108.title: Pobblebonk frog
1108.summary: As you walk through the wetlands, listen for the call of the Pobblebonk or banjo frog, named because of the 'bonk' sound it makes, like a banjo string being plucked.

1109.title: Follow the light
1109.summary: The boardwalk resumes again, this time leading walkers in the direction of the light. Look up to spot bright-coloured parrots or wattle birds, raucously guarding their precious nectar supplies.

1110.title: Valley beyond
1110.summary: As you walk towards the carpark look out towards the other side of Marysville and the valley for a reminder of how much was lost in the bushfires and all that is now slowly regenerating each day.

1111.title: Vervet Monkeys
1111.summary: Observing the complex interactions between these highly social animals is one of the highlights of a visit to Werribee Open Range Zoo.

1112.title: Lions
1112.summary: The zoo provides a rare opportunity to see these majestic animals up close.

1113.title: Hippos
1113.summary: The zoo provides a rare opportunity to get up close to these intriguing animals. You can sit and watch the hippos along the Pula Walking trail as well as seeing them while out on Safari

1114.title: Serval
1114.summary: These slender and extremely agile cats are one of Africa's most successful hunters

1115.title: Safari Station Tours
1115.summary: Imagine being surrounded by magnificent wildlife, including rhinos, giraffes, zebras and antelopes, or taking the perfect safari photo just 30 minutes from Melbourne's city centre.

1116.title: Przewalski's horse
1116.summary: Przewalski's horse. The baby was born in 2014. It's name is Hatan. The breed is the last truly wild horse, is skittish, stubborn, naturally shy and sometimes very aggressive.

1117.title: Ibis
1117.summary: Ibis are a group of long-legged wading birds that inhabit wetlands, forests and plains. They all have long, down-curved bills, and usually feed as a group, probing mud for food.

1118.title: Rhino
1118.summary: Rhinoceros are a threatened species that have only one predator, humans, who prize them for their hooves, blood, urine and above all for their horns for use in traditional medicines.

1119.title: Ostrich
1119.summary: The ostrich is the fastest flightless bird and can reach sprinting speeds of up to 70 kilometres per hour. The ostrich also uses its wings for displays of courtship and dominance.

1120.title: Impala
1120.summary: Impala are medium sized African antelopes that inhabit savanna grasslands and woodlands in close proximity to water sources.

1203.summary: Local plants within the Waterhole Creek catchment can be used to weave useful (& exquisite) baskets that the Gunaikurnai nation is famous for.

1206.title: Snake mural

1207.title: A snake in the rain story

1208.title: Findon Road Crossing

Time to relax. Shelter, toilets and seats.

1299.title: Looking back

1396.summary: Nature has provided an archway over the path and a beautiful photo scene.

1397.summary: As the seasons change, so do the plants in bloom.

1398.summary: High up in the tree tops are the homes of many bird species.

1401.summary: Along the track, you’ll find signage (starting at the beginning of the walk) and seats every now and again for you to take in the scenery.

1402.summary: Whether you’re a keen birdwatcher or just enjoy the surprise of a fresh sighting of our feathered friends, you’ll love the number of birds you can see on this walk.

1403.title: Healthy Forest
1403.summary: As you walk along the trail, you will see wonderful old trees with detailed bark that tells its own story.

1404.title: Spot the goanna
1404.summary: A rustle in the forest floor can easily turn into the appearance of one of the many reptiles who make this their home.

1405.title: Homes in the hollows
1405.summary: There are numerous hollows beside the walking trails, and although it’s hard to guess who is at home in them, you can bet someone is.

1406.summary: A rustle in the leaf litter might just mean there’s an echidna fossicking for food. If you see one, stand still because they’re very shy creatures and will try to hide from you.

1407.title: Native orchids make for a special treat
1407.summary: Throughout the year, over 43 orchid species including sun orchids (Thelymitra sp.) produce the most exquisite flowers at specific times of year.

1408.title: Picnic time
1408.summary: Whether you choose to start or finish with a bite to eat, a meal beneath the forest canopy makes for a fabulous picnic venue.

1410.title: Enjoy the views

1411.title: The track
1411.summary: The gravel track runs off the escarpment and down to river level here.

1412.title: K Road cliffs
1412.summary: The striking red cliffs colour the horizon.  Its a great spot to watch birds too.

1413.title: A feast for your eyes
1413.summary: Layers of colour and varying landscapes make up this impressive view.

1414.summary: The bridge joins this park to Werribee Park and Werribee Mansion.
