1440.summary: Originally St Andrew’s Presbyterian Church opened June 18 1899 (Vahland designed), the Uniting Church was formed by an amalgamation of Methodist & Presbyterian Churches in 1969.

1441.title: Elmore and District Preschool
1441.summary: The Preschool was built as an Infant Welfare Centre (circa 1960s) and extended as a Preschool in 1972.

1442.title: Elmore Memorial Hall
1442.summary: In 1920 it was proposed to build a Memorial to the local service men of World War 1 & provide work for some returned service men. Refer to the information board for more details.

1443.title: Elmore CFA Fire Station
1443.summary: The Fire Station was opened on September 26 1972, replacing the one in Railway Place (1910-1972). The former site is now known as Progress Park near the Raywood Road Rail Crossing.

1444.title: Police Station
1444.summary: The current station was built recently to replace the former station which was opened in 1968. The previous station was situated diagonally across the intersection (now a private residence).

1445.title: Law Courts
1445.summary: The building next to the Police Station was built as the Law Courts but is now privately owned and used as a Solicitors and Accountants office.

1446.title: The Old Water Tower
1446.summary: Used to store the town’s water supply (pumped from the Campaspe) the pumping station was on rails to move up the bank in times of flood. The station also produced the town’s electricity until 1948.

1447.title: Coffee Palace/James’ Bakery
1447.summary: Originally a Coffee Palace & later James’s Bakery which was well known as the place for lovely bread fresh from the oven, this building (south side of Cardwell St) is now a private residence.

1448.title: Jeffrey Street
1448.summary: Named after the Jeffrey brothers who owned Burnewang Station from 1852 to 1867.

osm.name: Jeffrey Street
osm.display_name: Jeffrey Street, Elmore, City of Greater Bendigo, Victoria, 3558, Australia

1449.title: The Old Mill
1449.summary: Originally the site of the Runnymede (later Elmore) flour mill which traded for 85 years with just two owners. Demolished in 1958, The Old Mill Roadhouse is now a private residence.

1450.title: Campaspe River Walking Track
1450.summary: The Campaspe River Walking Track meanders alongside the captivating Campaspe River. Dotted along the track are information boards which highlight the unique attributes of this stretch of the river.

1451.title: Campaspe River
1451.summary: The Campaspe River rises in the Kyneton area & enters The River Murray at Echuca. Lake Eppalock (constructed by State Rivers & Water Supply Commission of Victoria 1961-64) is situated on the Campaspe.

1452.title: Campaspe River Natural Play Space
1452.summary: The Elmore Progress Association in conjunction with the City of Greater Bendigo are currently creating a natural play space on the former playground site. Parking, drink fountain & seating available.

1453.title: Campaspe River Pepper Tree Avenue
1453.summary: The Avenue of pepper trees between the Campaspe River Bridge and Childers Street along Campaspe Street was planted on August 10 1898. The trees were donated by the Elmore Water Trust.

1454.title: Senior Citizens Flats (now Public Housing)
1454.summary: The Catholic Church donated the triangle land (junction of Campaspe & Jeffrey Streets) to the former Shire of Huntly to build flats for Senior Citizens. Today they are Public Housing.

1455.title: Our Lady of the Sacred Heart Catholic Church
1455.summary: The Vahland designed Church was built in 1904. The Presbytery is next door.

1456.title: Our Lady of the Sacred Heart Convent
1456.summary: Our Lady of the Sacred Heart Convent is situated on the corner of Jeffrey and Childers Streets.

1457.title: Our Lady of the Sacred Heart Primary School
1457.summary: Our Lady of the Sacred Heart Primary School is commonly known as OLSH.

1458.title: Elmore Bush Nursing Hospital
1458.summary: The Bush Nursing Hospital, established in 1937, became the Elmore District Hospital until 1992 when smaller hospitals were amalgamated. The hospital buildings are now Elmore Primary Health Services.

1459.title: Elmore Showgrounds
1459.summary: The land immediately across the intersection was the site of the Elmore Showgrounds. A housing development is underway on this land.

1460.title: Elmore Senior Citizens
1460.summary: The Elmore Senior Citizens Clubrooms were built in 1973.

1461.title: Brummy’s Seat
1461.summary: An Elm tree with a circular seat placed around it, was known as Brummy’s Seat after Mr Bremner, blacksmith & Fire Brigade Capt, who loved to smoke his pipe & hide his tobacco in a hollow in the tree.

1462.title: Water tower
1462.summary: This water tower supplies the town and is a UV water purification plant.

1464.title: Elmore Cemetery
1464.summary: Gazetted in 1872. The earliest internment is unknown but the earliest headstone reads, ‘Henry S. Alt, Age 2, 1867.’ Murder victim, John Duggan, (Corky Jack) was buried here in 1888.

1465.title: Elmore Recreation Reserve
1465.summary: Sporting facilities include football and cricket ground, netball courts, bowling greens, golf course, tennis courts, skate park, swimming pool and light harness racing track.

1467.title: Elmore Miniature Railway/Apex Park
1467.summary: Built on the site of the Cohuna Goods yard, the Elmore Miniature Railway (EMR) line extends for 1.5kms, with the EMR station situated at Apex Park.

osm.name: Elmore Primary School
osm.display_name: Elmore Primary School, 36-42, Michie Street, Elmore, City of Greater Bendigo, Victoria, 3558, Australia

1469.title: Masonic Lodge
1469.summary: The former Masonic Lodge was built in 1922. It is now privately owned.

1470.title: St Peter’s Anglican Church
1470.summary: The Vahland designed church was built in 1877, and the Parish Centre built in 1984.

1471.title: Former Bank of NSW/Westpac
1471.summary: This double story building on the South side of the street is now privately owned and operates as Elmore Old Wares.

1472.title: Shopping Strip
1472.summary: The current main shopping strip (extending left, right and over the pedestrian crossing), connects here with the original shopping strip - Cardwell Stree.

1473.title: Campaspe Run Play Space
1473.summary: Situated in the town centre between the Railway Station & Campaspe Run, the Campaspe Run Play Space has lush lawns, parking, public toilets, picnic tables & a BBQ. A great space to enjoy a picnic.

1474.title: Post Office Bell
1474.summary: Renowned Australian bell sculptor Dr Anton Hassall was involved in the casting of the bell.  "Littel Sister Bell" is suspended in the centre and chimes on the hour. Atop sits a corella figurine.

1475.title: Painted Tiles 1997
1475.summary: Images on the tiles reference changes in Horsham city life through the seasons.  The pictures are children of the five Horsham Primary Schools individual reflections on their culture and environment

1476.title: White Hart Hotel
1476.summary: Mark Twain stayed here during a visit to Horsham in the 1880's

1477.title: 'Platanus acerifolia: Woven Nest' 2009
1477.summary: This environmental work by Michael Shiell was installed as part of the 2009 'Art is...Elemental' Festival.  Michael's art practice is deeply seated in an ephemeral environmental response to the site.

1478.title: Exchange Hotel
1478.summary: One of the local Hotels in Horsham

1479.title: Royal Hotel
1479.summary: One of the oldest hotels in town

1480.title: Original Horsham Letterbox
1480.summary: This Original Horsham Letterbox inspired the design of the Post Office Bell sculpture in Firebrace St.

1481.title: Horsham Aquatic Centre
1481.summary: The outdoor 50m  pool was built in 1957 after the Melbourne Olympics, the smaller pool  in 1968 and the indoor heated polls in 2006. Also includes gym, Recreation Hall, Creche and cafe

1482.title: Botanic Gardens, Established 1870's
1482.summary: Sir William Guilfoyle planned these gardens between 1873 and 1880.  At teh time he was curator of the Royal Melbourne Botanic Gardens and planned many rural botanical gardens

1483.title: City Oval
1483.summary: This was the original site of the showgrounds from 1879-1897 when a storm wrecked the grandstand and buildings.  The site then became a recreational reserve and later city oval.

1484.title: Wimmera Live Steam and Model Engineering Society
1484.summary: This is a miniature railway which runs on special occasions

1485.title: Sunrise along the Kangaroo Track
1485.summary: With views to the horizon, one can't avoid the delights of the 'magic hour'.

1486.title: Views across Wodonga and the Murray Valley
1486.summary: The track is solid and provides great views to the north.

1487.title: The Baranduda Range
1487.summary: Another site to walk in the distance!

1488.title: Before sunrise on Kangaroo Track
1488.summary: Macfarlanes Hill is visible in the distance.

1489.title: Tree silhouette
1489.summary: It's great how these little 'windows on nature' pop up when least expected.

1490.title: The start
1490.summary: Start at Treasury Gardens at the statue of William John Clarke near Spring St.

1491.title: The path to Fitzroy Gardens
1491.summary: Already city noises start to fade into the distance. There are lots of seats along here and the whole walk. Listen for birds.

1492.title: The gentle incline to the Fountain
1492.summary: Once you cross Lansdowne St, get the blood pumping and pick up the pace along this gentle incline to the River God Fountain.

1493.title: River God Fountain
1493.summary: There is something wonderful about the sound of the water at this fountain. Take a moment to pause and look back down the Gardens.

osm.name: River God
osm.display_name: River God, Albert Street, East Melbourne, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3002, Australia

1494.title: Grey St Fountain
1494.summary: This brilliant fountain and flower garden is about halfway.

osm.name: Grey Street Fountain
osm.display_name: Grey Street Fountain, Clarendon Street, East Melbourne, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3002, Australia

1495.title: The Rotunda
1495.summary: The Rotunda was built in 1873 and is one of a few along the walk that can provide shelter during inclement weather.

osm.name: Temple of the Winds
osm.display_name: Temple of the Winds, Clarendon Street, East Melbourne, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3002, Australia

1496.title: The Fairy Tree and Tudor Village
1496.summary: These two icons of the Gardens bring a smile to many. If you have children, why not bring them here on a weekend?

1497.title: Captain Cook's Cottage
1497.summary: Cooks' Cottage is on the left. Built in England in 1755 and said to be the oldest building in Australia, it was brought to Melbourne in 1934.

1498.title: Finish on Spring St
1498.summary: How's that for a walk? Hope you are feeling refreshed and alive and ready to face the working afternoon.

1499.title: Williamstown timeball tower
1499.summary: The Williamstown tower was built in 1849 of local bluestone. It was originally a lighthouse, and later served as a timeball tower from 1861 to 1926.

1500.title: Williamstown railway station and historic footbridge

1501.title: View to Hobsons Bay
1501.summary: Point Gellibrand Coastal and Heritage Park

1502.title: Sculpture in Cyril Curtain Reserve
1502.summary: Sculpture looking out to Hobsons Bay

1503.title: The Rocks Williamstown
1503.summary: Williamstown Football Clubrooms on Cyril Curtain Reserve

1504.title: Foreshore from Hatt Reserve walking path
1504.summary: Foreshore from Hatt Reserve walking path

1505.title: Pelicans at Williamstown Beach
1505.summary: Pelicans waiting for fish scraps from the fishermen at Williamstown Angling Club.

1506.title: Williamstown Beach
1506.summary: Williamstown Beach at Shelleys Beach Pavilion (formerly Sirens)

osm.name: Williamstown Beach
osm.display_name: Williamstown Beach, Railway Crescent, Williamstown, Melbourne, City of Hobsons Bay, Victoria, 3016, Australia

1507.title: Gloucester Reserve
1507.summary: The water here is known to locals as 'the crystal' because it is usually crystal clear and good for snorkelling.

osm.name: Gloucester Reserve
osm.display_name: Gloucester Reserve, Williamstown, Melbourne, City of Hobsons Bay, Victoria, 3016, Australia

1508.title: Fishing village
1508.summary: The fishing village made famous by artist, John Perceval, in his painting ‘Gannets diving’ 1956.

1509.title: Jawbone Flora and Fauna Reserve
1509.summary: Beach at Jawbone Flora and Fauna Reserve

osm.name: Jawbone Flora and Fauna Reserve
osm.display_name: Jawbone Flora and Fauna Reserve, Williamstown, Melbourne, City of Hobsons Bay, Victoria, 3016, Australia

1510.title: Boardwalk at Jawbone Flora and Fauna Reserve
1510.summary: Boardwalk at Jawbone Flora and Fauna Reserve  allows walkers to look around without endangering the flora and fauna.

1511.title: Bird life
1511.summary: Take your time and enjoy the swans, pelicans, gannets, ibis and many other birds that make the most of the lakes.

1513.title: Overview of Jawbone Flora and Fauna Park

1514.title: Paisley-Challis Wetlands
1514.summary: The path continues along Kororoit Creek to Altona Coastal Park and further on to Altona Beach

1515.title: Victoria State Rose Garden - november
1515.summary: 5500 roses in 6 acres . Managed by Parks Victoria, looked after by volunteers of the rose garden throughout the year. Beautiful and relaxing a great place to walk and smell the roses.  Romantic  too.

1516.title: Festoons of roses surrounding the garden.
1516.summary: In November , December the outer festoons of roses are a site to behold.

1517.title: One of the standard avenue of roses Sevilliana
1517.summary: Standand Avenue leading to the gazebo.

1518.title: The corten steel arch leading into the rose garden
1518.summary: start your walk here. The arch leads you into the rose garden.

1519.title: Gazebo in the centre of the garden
1519.summary: A focal point in the centre of the Tudor Rose garden. It is surrounded by rosees Victoria Gold and Pink Iceberg roses.

1520.title: roses in bloom
1520.summary: Rose Perfume Pefection as a standard Avenue is spectacular at the rose garded.

1521.title: Westfield Knox City
1521.summary: Our starting point and/or meeting point for this walk.  Knox City has  plenty of parking and cafes for that after-walk coffee.

1522.title: Distance Signage
1522.summary: The signage allows to gauge you are on the right track and gives you an idea of distance and time into your walk.

1523.title: Wildwood Close Playground
1523.summary: This simple playground can be a good break if you are walking with small children or you feel like a bit of swing yourself.

1524.title: Lakewood Nature Reserve
1524.summary: Lakewood Nature Reserve was part of the Scoresby Horticultural Research Station until the mid-1980s. The Reserve was formed in 1990, this allowed the protection of the native vegetation and wildlife.

osm.name: Lakewood Nature Reserve
osm.display_name: Lakewood Nature Reserve, Knoxfield, Melbourne, City of Knox, Victoria, 3180, Australia

1525.title: Shared Path
1525.summary: Please be aware that there is a shared path around the lake from this point on.

1526.title: Lake Creek
1526.summary: Take a peek at the lake for the first time here. There is potential for spotting frogs, nesting waterbirds or small fish, plus the beautiful view.

1527.title: Conservation Area
1527.summary: As meandering through the bushland track, don't forget to look into the canopy of the trees. You never know what you might see.

1528.title: Lakewood Lake
1528.summary: Constructed in 1985, the lake covers 3.3 hectares and has a maximum depth of two metres, perfect for the abandant waterbirds. The lake has a small jetty and an island to the east end.

osm.name: Lakewood Lake
osm.display_name: Lakewood Lake, Knoxfield, Melbourne, City of Knox, Victoria, Australia

1529.title: A foggy, winter view to the Kiewa Valley.
1529.summary: This vantage point is below the level of the picnic area and car park.

1530.title: Huon Hill summit
1530.summary: This is where the ascent levels out as it approaches the vehicle access picnic area.

osm.name: Huon Hill Lookout
osm.display_name: Huon Hill Lookout, Summit Track, Bandiana, City of Wodonga, Victoria, 3691, Australia

1532.title: Northward - Albury under cover
1532.summary: Views to Albury obscured by fog

1533.title: Lake Hume: where?
1533.summary: Under the sea of fog lies Lake Hume in the distance.

1534.title: Liberty Swing
1534.summary: The Liberty Swing is an accessible swing for children and adults who use a wheelchair, and gives them the ability to experience the joy and recreation of using a swing.

1535.title: Dog Park
1535.summary: A secure space to bring your dog to play or train.  It has two agility runs and biodegradable dog waste bags are provided at each entrance to the park. You will need to bring water for your dog.

1536.title: Rest area with a view
1536.summary: One of many rest areas around the park. Its a brilliant spot to sit and relax and simply take in the view.  You will often find many birds including ducks on this walk.

1537.title: Children's play area
1537.summary: A safe and fun play space for kids. Surrounded by beautiful trees that provide shade. Plenty of seating areas for mum and dad. Brilliant place for a picnic and some quality family time

1538.title: Wildlife
1538.summary: There are many beautiful birds that you are likely to come across on this walk. Of course they include ducks!

1539.title: Bryces Flat
1539.summary: A picnic area with plenty of shaded parking , this is a great place to leave your car while you walk.

osm.name: Bryces Flat Picnic Ground
osm.display_name: Bryces Flat Picnic Ground, Stepping Stones, Hepburn, Shire of Hepburn, Victoria, 3461, Australia

1540.title: The Blowhole
1540.summary: The Blowhole is a remnant of the gold rush, created to expose gold in the water, and after heavy rainfall it appears to shoot water. Unfortunately, it is currently closed due to a recent rock fall.

osm.name: The Blowhole
osm.display_name: The Blowhole, Spur Loop Walk, Hepburn, Shire of Hepburn, Victoria, 3461, Australia

1541.title: Waterholes
1541.summary: Even in the dry months of summer there are pools of clear water to dip your feet in on a hot day.

1542.title: Ruins
1542.summary: Keep an eye out and on the other side of the gully you'll spot an old stone wall, half-hidden in the bush.

1543.title: Wildlife
1543.summary: Small lizards are a common sight underfoot, and in the greener areas of the gully the odd wallaby can be spotted. Towards the end of the track you'll find this homely-looking cave on your right.

1544.title: Breakneck Gorge
1544.summary: A deep, tree-filled gorge that appears suddenly around a bend, Breakneck Gorge is a great place to watch birds in the treetops below.

1545.title: Wild Melbourne
1545.summary: This walk was completed by Wild Melbourne, a not-for-profit specialising in nature engagement and dedicated to connecting people with nature. Please visit our website to find out more.

1546.title: Space man
1546.summary: A vision of the future?  Who, what, where and how - well that's best left to the imagination.

1547.title: Worm wall
1547.summary: Wall full of lyrical whimsys.  Get up close and you'll find out who's lamenting what and other funny sayings.

1548.title: Taxi rider
1548.summary: Is the cat innocent or conspirator in this midnight adventure?

1549.title: Lemming wall
1549.summary:
Who's naming the lemmings?
Lemmings or meerkats?  Where are they going? Lemme know!

1550.title: Amnesty International wall
1550.summary: Fantastic series of wall panels describing the work of Amnesty International (it's where their office is).

1551.title: Mermaid under attack
1551.summary:
So much to marvel here.  Make sure you look up and around.  Also check out the laneway nearby too, it has lots of hidden secrets!

Thank goodness for colourful and creative types.

1552.title: Whitlam Place
1552.summary: Check out the back wall of this park. Are the pictures of local residents?

osm.name: Whitlam Place
osm.display_name: Whitlam Place, Fitzroy, Melbourne, City of Yarra, Victoria, 3065, Australia

1553.title: Playground
1553.summary: Let your child run free in this well designed playground. There is a range of different equipment for climbing, swinging and exploring. Includes a swing with harness and double-width slide.

1554.title: Bird hide and billabong
1554.summary: This bird hide is the perfect spot to have a look at who might be nestling or feeding in the water. You might like to have a look at the tree farm near the billabong to see what's growing there too.

1555.title: BBQ, seats and shade
1555.summary: This is the perfect spot for a picnic, BBQ and to refill your water bottle.

1556.title: Beautiful gum trees
1556.summary: There are many beautiful gum trees lining the side of the ovals and creek. A shady spot and a great reminder of how the looked before it was colonised.

1557.title: Don't feed the birds
1557.summary: Contrary to popular opinion, it's not healthy for ducks and birds to eat bread. This can lead to poor health, loss of hunting and foraging skills, and dependence on humans. See link below.

1558.title: Archery Club
1558.summary: Stay away from the archery paddock is archers are in action! Obviously, don't cough or sneeze too close to them either, in case ....

1559.title: Dog training
1559.summary: Furry friends of all colours and sizes are often seen in the park. It's a popular spot for dog walkers.

1560.title: Under the bridge art
1560.summary: Clearly, the artist feels an affinity with the furry creatures that frequent the area.

1561.title: Glass Creek revegetation works
1561.summary: A beautiful array of indigenous plant seedlings were recently been planted. These include River Red gums, native grasses and bottlebrushes. This area should look spectacular in a few years.

1562.title: End of path
1562.summary: The path ends rather abruptly at the road. Council have painted a section here but there is no footpath. You can continue on here carefully, or take the long and scenic route back the way you came.

1563.title: Aquamoves Lakeside Shepparton
1563.summary: First of all the path takes you past the Aquamoves swimming complex, which has a variety of different pools and playgrounds. Entry is via Tom Collins Drive.

1564.title: Greater Shepparton's All Abilities Playground
1564.summary: This playground is a good stop for the kids. It has tables and chairs, toilets, water fountains, slides and all kinds of play equipment. Children are required to have adult supervision in the park.

1565.title: The Jetty
1565.summary: A boardwalk allows you to walk out over the water. The wood can become slippery when it is wet and ther aren't guardrails all the way along it.

1566.title: Shepparton Canoe Club
1566.summary: At the waters edge near the canoe club there is a sandy beach and a small boat ramp. There is also toilets near the canoe club.

1567.title: Cafe and Greater Sheparton Visitor Information Center
1567.summary:
At the cafe there are indoor and outdoor tables as well as toilets. The cafe provides the opportunity to purchase a drink and take a break along the way.
The visitor centre is next door.

1568.title: Picnic areas
1568.summary: Along the track there a number of BBQ areas with tables and facilites.

1569.title: Skate Park
1569.summary: The skate park is a popular park for the young children and the big kids too. There are occasionally competitions held and there is always someone to watch.

1570.title: Slavonija deli
1570.summary: This deli has an unassuming exterior, but inside, it's full of delightful treats.  I particularly recommend their boreks and poppyseed rolls.  Closes around 2pm so make sure you get there early.

1571.title: Mumbai Mirch
1571.summary: Spices, sauces, pickles, herbs, snacks, pots, pans - everything you need to make a delicious Indian meal.  Next door's restaurant is simple and tasty, though service can be a bit leisurely.

1572.title: Hanna's coffee
1572.summary: Hanna opened this coffee shop maybe 4 years ago.  It's a busy place stocked with nuts, interesting biscuits, sweets and magazines.  Regular patrons are the older fellas from the former Yugoslavia.

1573.title: Cake shop
1573.summary: This shop has a fine display in the window.  Filled with cakes, rolls and a few Vietnamese buns, it's always a good place to stop to check out what's on offer.

osm.name: Victoria Cake Shop
osm.display_name: Victoria Cake Shop, 7, Alfrieda Street, St Albans East, St Albans, Melbourne, City of Brimbank, Victoria, 3021, Australia

1574.title: Vietnamese deli
1574.summary: There are all sorts of mysterious and delicious food items here.  Some are sweet, some savoury, some both sweet AND savoury!  I don't quite remember what they're called so I just point at what I want.

1575.title: Ha Noi Pho
1575.summary: Tucked in a laneway is my favourite Vietnamese restaurant.  The owner Dao is lovely and hospitable.  The pho is terrific. My favourite dish is lemongrass beef wrapped in vine leaves.

1576.title: Chinese chess
1576.summary: If you loiter long enough, you might learn how to play Chinese chess from one of the locals.  A popular pastime for the blokes visiting Alfrieda Street.

1577.title: Chilli bakery
1577.summary: I usually have an egg and salad roll from here, though there are many variations to choose from.  There is a short wait as this is probably the most popular place for Vietnamese rolls in the area.

1578.title: Fish galore
1578.summary: There are a couple of fishmongers on this side.  I try to pick sustainable fish from Australia (snapper is always yummy).

1579.title: Vietnamese grocery stores
1579.summary: This is one of many Vietnamese grocery stores in the area.  I like checking out the aisles of cans and bottles from different places.  There's plenty of fresh veg that I've never seen elsewhere too.

1580.title: Shady seats
1580.summary: Take a seat here and stop to watch the crowds go by.

1581.title: St Albans market
1581.summary: St Albans market has cheap and fresh fruit and veg.  Unfortunately there was a fire recently.  I hope it's open again soon!

osm.name: St Albans Mini Market
osm.display_name: St Albans Mini Market, Princess Street, St Albans East, St Albans, Melbourne, City of Brimbank, Victoria, 3021, Australia

1582.title: Wildlife - kookaburra & snake
1582.summary: A kookaburra chick being fed a tiger snake by its parent.

1583.title: Trail waypoint
1583.summary: Waypoint marker displaying orientation and distance of key landmark features.

1584.title: Wildlife - orb weaver spider
1584.summary: An orb weaver spider preparing its web for the evening.

1585.title: Unpaved, natural path
1585.summary: An option for the curious seeking a more natural setting when walking.

1586.title: River view
1586.summary: A view of the river as seen from the football oval.

1587.title: Parks & picnics
1587.summary: Open parklands along the river provide the perfect spots for large or small picnics

1588.title: Tree-scape view
1588.summary: A view of  the river and surrounding tree-scape extending into the distant suburbs.

1589.title: River crossings
1589.summary: One of the many bridges spanning the river.

1590.title: Running track
1590.summary: Running is frequently enjoyed along the picturesque trail.

1591.title: Wild Melbourne
1591.summary: This walk was completed by Wild Melbourne, a not-for-profit specialising in nature engagement and dedicated to connecting people with nature. Please visit our website to find out more.

1592.title: Read the sign
1592.summary: You’ll need to familiarise yourself with the rules: only walk through the green gates (& close them) then follow the orange arrows.

1593.title: Follow the orange markers
1593.summary: You could get lost at some points during this walk if you stray off the track in the grass sections (and end up in the middle of a paddock). Arrows are helpfully spotted along the fence lines.

1594.title: Olive groves
1594.summary: Just one of many agricultural pursuits that populate the agricultural profile of this region, olives are on the menu.

1595.title: Valley views
1595.summary: There are numerous views of the Latrobe Valley on this walk, from all sorts of perspectives.

1596.title: Diverse landscapes
1596.summary: As you wander through the paddocks, you come across forests of pines, grasslands, the coal country and the mountains beyond.

1597.title: Down the track
1597.summary: There’s something special about this track, as you find yourself coming close to farmhouses while at the same time finding yourself in the middle of a vast view.

1598.title: Follow the fence line
1598.summary: There are tracts of this walk that take you through mowed paddocks, mostly along the fence line but then cutting through paddocks, forests and nearby farms. It feels good to take this stroll.

1599.title: Who was CJ Tyers?
1599.summary: Once you’ve done this walk, you may wonder how Tyers got its name. Interpretative signage will give you the answers you’re looking for.

1600.title: Ring Road versus tranquility!
1600.summary: It is an interesting juxtaposition – the big busy noisy freeway versus the small peaceful walking track. I know which one I would rather be on!

1601.title: Ducks and ducklings
1601.summary: The river and wetlands is swarming with birdlife, we were lucky to be there to see this family of duck and ducklings.

1602.title: Lots of waterways in the wetlands
1602.summary: Depending on rainfall the rivers and ponds can be plentiful with lots of lush foliage surrounding them.

1603.title: Johnstone Street Reserve
1603.summary: This Reserve has it all! Big new BBQ area, skate park, playground, heaps of grassed area and even 2 flying foxes!

osm.name: Johnstone Street Reserve
osm.display_name: Johnstone Street Reserve, Jacana, Melbourne, City of Hume, Victoria, Australia

1604.title: Back to the real world - careful crossing the road
1604.summary: Back to the real world - careful crossing the road

1605.title: Great view looking back over the jaunt
1605.summary: Make sure you turn around and have a look back into the valley, you can see how far you have come.

1606.title: Careful crossing the busy road
1606.summary: There is an overpass over the Western Ring Road, however walkers need to be careful crossing the off-shoot road – there are pedestrian traffic lights.

1607.title: Turn right and cross the bridge
1607.summary: When you get to the bridge, turn right to head towards Johnstone Street Reserve. If you want to head straight check out the walk “Moonee Ponds Creek Trail – Westmeadows” as this is its starting point.

1608.title: You take the high road, I'll take the low road
1608.summary: Again, you have options where to walk! Take the low road (right hand) and follow the valley to continue with this particular route.

1609.title: Access to Jacana Station
1609.summary: When exiting/entering Jacana Station it is best to use the pedestrian tunnel under the busy Pascoe Vale Road.

1610.title: While the cars slog away above its peaceful down here!
1610.summary: At this point of the walk you are basically directly under the Western Ring Road. If you wish you can turn left here, go under the Road and head south, however to continue with this route head straigh

1611.title: So many options where to walk
1611.summary: There are lots of signs along the way showing walkers where they are where they can go – almost too many options!

1612.title: Robert Booth Reserve
1612.summary: Start at Robert Booth Reserve. Bus stop on Clow Street. The reserve offers an off-leash dog park, playgrounds, sporting fields and an athletics track.

osm.name: Robert Booth Reserve
osm.display_name: Robert Booth Reserve, Dandenong, Melbourne, City of Greater Dandenong, Victoria, Australia

1613.title: A lush start
1613.summary: This part of the walk is particularly leafy and green. Enjoy the shade!

1614.title: Watch out for trail regulars
1614.summary: This walking and cycling track covers miles north and south, so you're bound to spot cyclists and joggers in training along the creek path.

1615.title: Art sculpture
1615.summary: As you walk towards Heatherton Road, you're bound to spot the Freedom Cycle sculpture. A bright cut-out style design of a cyclist taking off out of a yellow square!

1616.title: Underpass at Heatherton Road
1616.summary: Walk up onto Heatherton Road and down to the underpass on the other side of the creek. Avoid the underpass if flooded.

1617.title: A swimming spot?
1617.summary: We're not sure if this is a good idea but we have seen it with our own eyes! Someone went for a quick dip in the wetlands and we think, lived to tell the tale.

1618.title: Handy signposts
1618.summary: If you're keen to get your bearings, there are signposts dotted along the creek trail, with distances from major roads and venues. Handy if you're keen to walk further!

1619.title: In search of shade
1619.summary: Wetlands are typically shrub-filled spots, so it's always a relief to find a huge tree offering shade for many. Stop here a while if the sun is high in the sky.

1620.title: Playground
1620.summary: This is a wonderful playground for all ages, with toilet facilities nearby.

1621.title: Covered BBQ area
1621.summary: After a long walk, catch your breath over a BBQ lunch or have a rest in the shade. We spotted two studious locals studying outdoors the day we visited. Great idea!

1622.title: Dandenong Stadium
1622.summary: One of the largest stadiums of its kind in the southern hemisphere, you might like to explore this venue, visit the cafe or use the facilities. It's said to attract 15,000 visitors each week!

1623.title: Myuna Farm (across the creek)
1623.summary: Across the creek is Myuna Farm. A popular spot for saying hello to farm animals, learning from the farmers, having a bite to eat and even taking a train ride around the property. Admission fees apply.

1624.title: The Age building
1624.summary: Check the screen at ‘The Age’ building for the news, weather and time.

1625.title: The Grand Hotel

1675.summary: Cars coming racing around the bind corner from Merri Pde, so watch out! VicRoads puts the speed limit at 60 km/h which is absolutely ridiculous. When will they learn?

1677.title: The mural

Love this mural but don't know much about it though. 

Unfortunately, the mural has now been painted over :((

1679.summary: My kids love this wild looking vegetable!

1680.summary: Despite the no cycling signs, many cyclists illegally ride in the underpass. Some don't even bother to ring their bell (very inconsiderate!). Makes it hard for kids and elderly.

1681.title: The shared path
1681.summary: They recently widened the path which is great. So many wonderful plants and animals, walkers and riders. It is always interesting, the light changes with the seasons and time of day.

1682.title: The Merri Creek
1682.summary: The joy of the sound of running water. Sometimes I walk along here at night in winter, shut my eyes and think of the bush. A saw a snake here once.

1683.title: Inner - Gary Deirmendjian, 2005
1683.summary: Made of sandstone, the installation aims to evoke and question the tensions between one's objective and subjective realities - the former striving for perspective and the latter for engagement.

1684.title: Meant To Be - Colin Langridge, 2005
1684.summary: Mean To Be is the result of developing the cooperating process of wooden construction, where bent wooden laths are shaped to form hollow containers.

1685.title: Zephyr - Tim Edwards, 2005
1685.summary: Zephyr is a sculptural self portrait by Edwards. The interface of the human and the machine is a source of contemplation acting as a metaphor for production, aspiration and restriction.

1686.title: The Comrade's Reward - William Eicholtz, 2004
1686.summary: This popular 19th century genre is reintrepreted in an eclectic and contemporary way, deliberately references antiquity and unfashionable ideas of heroism and folly within a camp and knowing artifice.

1687.title: Ether - Ari Purhonen, 2002
1687.summary: Ether embodies an optical effect produced by the natural phenomenon of light. Rotating vertically around the axis, the illusion is created by an optical interference patter within the sculpture.

1688.title: Death of white good - Alexander Knox, 2005
1688.summary: Far from the chaos of an airline crash, Death of a White Good is a picturesque ruin. It is unclear if seconds or millennia have transpired since the crash.

1689.title: As weeks go by - Laurens Tan, 2004
1689.summary: As Weeks Go By represents 4 weeks of time as they disappear before our eyes, including the opportunities built into each day as represented by randomly perforated cans.

1690.title: Meniscii - Julia Davis, 2007
1690.summary: Meniscii explores the perceptions of, and relationships between objects, spaces and places. In particular the relationship between the earth and the sky.

1691.title: Migration - Ian Burns & John Clark, 2005
1691.summary: Migration is concerned with movement and the relationship between the individual components and the mas they represent in formation.

1692.title: Meanwhile... Down South in Tasmania - Bob Jenyns, 2005
1692.summary: This sculpture explores the way in which aspects of history repeats itself, often in unexpected and ironical ways.

1693.title: Hut - Karen Ward 2000
1693.summary: Hut symbolises the house, the home, the shack, the cubby-house and he hermit's retreat. It also alludes to the potential to dream that is inherent within all of these structures.

1694.title: Fractal construction - David Jensz, 2005
1694.summary: The curved form of Fractal Construction approximates the end of a massive pipe projecting from the ground.

1695.title: Prosthetic apartment B - Richard Goodwin, 2004
1695.summary: Prosthetic Apartment B is an installation which creates a building within Werribee Park. As a site-specific work it brings the idea of habitation to a public park.

1696.title: Portal to another time and place - Deborah Halpern, 2004
1696.summary: As related by Halpern, her work is 'An arch in the shape of a face, leaning on its nose. To see something whimsical, surprising and delightful in the landscape is always inspiring'.

1697.title: Swarm - Nigel Helyer
1697.summary: Swarm consists of a series of laser cut acrylic objects closely resembling microscopic marine forms, each supporting a solar powered digital circuit, amplifier and speaker.

1698.title: Exoskeleton pod - Richard Goodwin 2000
1698.summary: Exoskeleton Pod speculate about minimum architectures and the point at which the body stops and architecture begins.

1699.title: Remannt - Mike Taylor, 2004
1699.summary: A burnt gum tree gives Remnant its primary form but the work has much to do with historical allusions as natural forces.

1700.title: Upperground - Ewen Coates, 2006
1700.summary: Upperground resembles a cathedral structure; raising questions about the relevance  of the church and evolution of traditional teachings, in an era when religion causes schisms in our world.

1701.title: Passage - Fiona Orr, 2002
1701.summary: The concept of the frame has strong associations with history, painting and museums. Orr's been developing sculptural frames over recent years and is interested in taking the frame out of the gallery.

1702.title: Rothko's chapel - Konstantin Dimopoulos, 2007
1702.summary: Rothko's Chapel is a dynamic sculpture exploring and expressing through colour, line and movement, the simple and reverential colour variations of renowned 20th century painter Mark Rothko.

1703.title: Werribee River
1703.summary: Take a rest along the river and enjoy the scenery.

1704.title: Wall - Mark Stoner, 2002-03
1704.summary: Wall is suggestive of great density and permanence; it is tough and uncompromising in its form - asserting itself within the landscape but remaining separate from it.

1705.title: Werribee Park Historic Orchard
1705.summary: Planted in the late 1800s, the orchard produced apples, quinces, pear and stone fruits.

1706.title: Werribee Park
1706.summary: Werribee Park has superbly landscaped gardens that seem to stretch on forever. In it are many heritage trees and curious plants from exotic countries.

1735.summary: Wander through a vast area of wetlands, with the You Yangs in the distance and boats bobbing in the bay to your left. It's largely unsigned and without paths, but impressive all the same.

1736.title: Werribee South Boat Ramp

1737.title: Look out for birdlife
1737.summary: Look out across to the pointy sandbank on the other side of the river mouth. Here you might spot birdlife relaxing on the shore. This area is home to flora and fauna unseen in other parts of the bay.

1738.title: JD Bellin Reserve
1738.summary: This area is adjacent to the Werribee South Boat Ramp and offers an excellent spot to have a picnic or BBQ, with new facilities, toilets and a playground for the kids.

1739.title: Boy sculpture
1739.summary: As you walk along the shared foreshore pathway, you can't miss 'Boy' a sculpture of a young child's silhouette gazing at the grasslands. This piece is part of Wyndham Council's public art collection.

1740.title: Price Reserve

1742.title: Werribee South market gardens
1742.summary: There aren't too many places in the world where vegetables grow across the road from a beach! With 41% of Victoria's food grown in this region, it's a good time to stop and savour what's around us.

1743.title: Pathways under construction

1744.title: Wyndham Harbour foreshore

1799.title: Oval Scoreboard
1799.summary: If you pass the scoreboard you know you are on the right track.

1800.title: Path and Playground
1800.summary: The first playground on the walk with lots of activities for the kids.

1801.title: Optional Detour
1801.summary: Optional scenic detour along a dirt track which brings you closer to the flora along the creek.

1802.title: Detour pathway
1802.summary: A view along the detour pathway

1803.title: Creek View
1803.summary: A view along the creek bank with signs of recent native flora revegetation work.

1804.title: Second Playground
1804.summary: Another great opportunity for the kids to sea-saw, climb and swing.

1805.title: Wooden seat
1805.summary: A beautiful carved wooden seat offers the opportunity for a rest.

1806.title: Entrance to the church grounds
1806.summary: After crossing the bridge you will see the entrance to the church grounds.

1807.title: Church Gate
1807.summary: The old church gate with the wonderful 1850s Lutheran church in the background.

1808.title: A Tree Outside Historic Ziebells Farmhouse
1808.summary: Our first view of the old 1850s farmhouse.

1809.title: Ziebells Farmhouse Gardens
1809.summary: A view of the wonderfully maintained gardens in Ziebells Farmhouse.  The buildings here represent the heart of Ziebells original 102 acre farm, built between 1851 and 1856.

1810.title: Gazebo and Barbecue
1810.summary: A optional start and end point of the walk offers the chance to enjoy a barbecue at the end of your walk.

1811.title: Library Mural
1811.summary: Part of a large mural running along the rear of the library building.

1812.title: Old Mornington Post office
1812.summary: The old Mornington Post Office is now a museum of all things postal. The inside is original and takes you back to the days of massive wall-mounted wooden telephones.

1813.title: Mornington Park to Fishermans Beach, Mornington
1813.summary: Mornington Park has a children's playground, barbecues and picnic facilities.

1814.title: Entrance to foreshore track
1814.summary: Entrance to foreshore track that winds its way behind the Mornington Bowling Club.  Single file only on a dirt track.

1815.title: Access point to water views
1815.summary: One of the many access points with seating to water views

1816.title: Mornington Bowling Club from The Esplanade
1816.summary: A friend we met on the way back along The Esplanade on the fence of Mornington Bowling Club.

1818.title: Marker 7 Europeans meet the Aboriginal people
1818.summary: This is Marker Seven - one of several we saw on the day along the path.

1819.title: A glimpse of the City of Melbourne
1819.summary: A glimpse of the City of Melbourne

1820.title: A flock of seagulls
1820.summary: A flock of seagulls on the beach near Fishermans Beach boat ramp

1822.title: Diver sculpture
1822.summary: At the entrance stands the sculpture ‘Diver’. It is carved out of bluestone and appears to be a duck diving into the bluestone paving

1823.title: Pavey’s Picnic Area
1823.summary: To the left of the entrance is Pavey’s Picnic Area where there are barbecues and a sheltered seating area.

1825.title: The Main Lookout
1825.summary: Number one is the main lookout when you first walk in.

1826.title: Stepping-stones at the Lake Crossing are number four.
1826.summary: Stepping-stones at the Lake Crossing are number four. Note the purple swamphen on the path - one of the many birds attracted to the area

1827.title: Two is the amphitheatre
1827.summary: Two is the amphitheatre, an open area where concerts sometimes are held.

1828.title: Three is the Waterfall
1828.summary: Three is the Waterfall where stormwater gathers in the park and is recycled through a series of pipes and ponds.

1829.title: At six there is a bird viewing area
1829.summary: At six there is a bird viewing area built by the Friends of Newport Lakes in 1999.

1830.title: Frog mosaic
1830.summary: There are many mosaics dotted around the park depicting the wildlife.

1831.title: The path
1831.summary: The path is gravel and steep in some areas.

1832.title: Open area
1832.summary: Open area accessible to the lake where birds feed.

1833.title: Picnic area
1833.summary: Tables are available for picnics. No shops so bring your own food. Water is available at the entrance barbecue area.

1834.title: Stepping-stones at the Lake Crossing
1834.summary: Stepping-stones at the Lake Crossing are number four.

1836.title: Newport Lakes Indigenous Nursery
1836.summary: After wandering around Newport Lakes Reserve you may be inspired to take home some vegetation. Newport Lakes Indigenous Nursery is adjacent to the carpark.

1838.title: Monkey
1838.summary: This laneway usually has a couple of illustrative pieces, mostly sprays but sometimes stencils. My favourite is this funny little monkey man. Will he still be there when you walk by?

1839.title: Darren's Owls
1839.summary: Darren Henderson is a local artist who has a thing for owls... And I love these!  See if you can spot another of his owls when you get to Wall Two 80 further in the walk

1840.title: Big Men Laughing
1840.summary: These guys are HUGE! And this vacant site where they are is the biggest graffiti canvas in Balaclava. Walk this way often for an ever changing exhibition.

1841.title: Railway Walk Brick
1841.summary: Good big brick walls here are always covered and often turned over with new pieces. Look at the detaills to see messages between artists and how they respond to eachother's work.

1842.title: Railway Walk Tin
1842.summary: If tags are your thing then this section of the railway walk is for you.

1843.title: Wall Two 80
1843.summary: Wall Two 80 is a favourite local cafe, and its big outside wall is always covered with art.

1844.title: The End of the Wall
1844.summary: It's worth walking to the end of the wall as curious little bits of street art pop up here. Paste ups, stencils, the odd diorama...

1845.title: Dragon Lane
1845.summary: This is a long way from the rest of the walk but it is worth it. On one side is a huge and amazing Chinese themed piece that is the biggest single piece I've seen. On the other is an awesome mix up!

1846.title: Tile Faces
1846.summary: I forgot to put this in the walk and can't change the map, but it's good to go for a wander through the playground at the Williams St reserve just nearby, there are sneaky tiled faces stuck on walls!

1847.title: Murchison Heritage Centre
1847.summary: Located out the side of the museum is a large pump that was used to pump water from the river for the townspeople.

1848.title: River bank gardens, boardwalk and three information lecterns
1848.summary: Discover Murchisons bygone era with images of the old streetscape, pub and paddle steamers. The boardwalk provides an impressive view of the Goulburn River.

1849.title: Aboriginal Protectorate Station
1849.summary: Signage marks the location of the protective that operated from 1840-1853. This is one of only four stations established in the then colony of Port Phillip.

1850.title: Roderick Square
1850.summary: Roderick Square was the original proposed river crossing point however, the river crossing was constructed in Robinson Street in 1871

1851.title: Murchison cemetery and the Italian Ossario (Mausoleum)
1851.summary: Grave of King Charles Tattambo, 1866, a local Aboriginal who was buried here as his dying wish was to buried in a box like a white man. The Ossario hold the remains of a number of Italians from WWII

1852.title: Longleat Wines
1852.summary: Home to a selection of delectable indulgences.

1853.title: Maffra Visitor Information Centre
1853.summary: The  Centre is located in the historic Maffra Courthouse building in Johnson Street, and is full of the most intriguing gems, crystals, fabulous fossils and fluorescent minerals.

osm.name: Maffra Visitor Information Centre
osm.display_name: Maffra Visitor Information Centre, Johnson Street, Maffra, Shire of Wellington, Victoria, 3860, Australia

1854.title: Macalister River  Country
1854.summary: The views in this area are particularly beautiful.

1855.title: Suitable for riding or walking
1855.summary: The trail is predominantly flat and easy going on packed gravel.

1856.title: Tinamba Hotel
1856.summary: First Established In 1874, the hotel is still catering for travellers - bookings essential for meals,
