osm.display_name: Great Western Hotel, Main Street, Great Western, Shire of Northern Grampians, Victoria, 3374, Australia

1861.title: Salinger's Cafe
1861.summary: Salinger's Café is the perfect spot to stop for lunch

1862.title: Petrol Station
1862.summary: Just incase you need a refill

1863.title: War Memorial Gates
1863.summary: Great Western War Memorial Park commemorates those who served in World War Two.

1868.title: Seppelt Winery
1868.summary: Walk through the Carpark and go on in for a visit. Founded in 1851 Seppelt Winery has so much history winemakers at Seppelts have been crafting wines of quality and diversity for many years.

1869.title: Seppelt Winery
1869.summary: Walk through the Carpark and go on in for a visit. Founded in 1851 Seppelt Winery has so much history winemakers at Seppelts have been crafting wines of quality and diversity for many years.

1870.title: Watch Out as you go a bit bushland, the road turns to Gravel

1871.title: Best's Winery
1871.summary: Founded in 1866,  one of Australia's oldest family owned wineries with some of the oldest vines in the country.

1872.title: Quarry St Reserve
1872.summary: A peaceful park surrounding a pond that many waterbirds have made their home. A good spot for a picnic.

osm.name: Quarry Street Reserve
osm.display_name: Quarry Street Reserve, Trentham, Shire of Hepburn, Victoria, Australia

1873.title: Stoney Creek Reserve
1873.summary: A patch of bushland along a creek which is well managed by the local community.

1874.title: Birdlife
1874.summary: Birdlife is abundant around town. Here, a flock of corellas sweeps up into the trees above a paddock beside Stoney Creek Reserve.

1875.title: Trentham Cemetery
1875.summary: Though you won’t walk through the cemetery itself, the trail passes through land owned by the cemetery, alongside its boundary fence.

osm.name: Trentham Cemetery
osm.display_name: Trentham Cemetery, Trentham, Shire of Hepburn, Victoria, Australia

1876.title: Chimney Stack
1876.summary: Just beyond the cemetery, an old chimney stack stands alone in a patch of grassland.

1877.title: Trentham Racecourse
1877.summary: All that remains of the Trentham Racecourse is this walking trail, which follows the original curve of the racetrack.

osm.name: Racecourse Road
osm.display_name: Racecourse Road, Trentham, Shire of Hepburn, Victoria, 3458, Australia

1878.title: Signage
1878.summary: Consistent signage keeps you on the right path throughout.

1879.title: Wild Melbourne
1879.summary: This walk was completed by Wild Melbourne, a not-for-profit specialising in nature engagement and dedicated to connecting people with nature. Please visit our website to find out more.

1880.title: Boardwalk at Macalister Wetland Reserve
1880.summary: This is a delightful way to discover the wild and wonderful world of a wetland.

1881.title: Cow sculptures
1881.summary: In recognition of the influence of the dairy industry and as a celebration to cows, check out this zany iron sculpture installation.

1882.title: Maffra’s Motor Vehicle Collection and Museum
1882.summary: A must for any motoring enthusiast (& even those that aren’t!), this vintage car museum showcases an extraordinary array of the beloved car.

1883.title: Remnants of the past
1883.summary: It’s hard to imagine just how much work this old truck did over the years, but it’s one more example along the trail of the previous lives of other Gippslanders.

1884.title: Walking the dog
1884.summary: You don’t have to follow the rail trail on wheels. Lots of locals use the trail as a great place to walk the pooch.

1885.title: Stratford sculptures
1885.summary: A side trip in Stratford is recommended, making sure you take the short trip beside the Avon River to enjoy the fantastic sculptures dotted along the way.

1886.title: Stratford Railway Station
1886.summary: Whether you start from the Trail’s most eastern end or return by train, this is a lovely old station to visit.

osm.name: Stratford
osm.display_name: Stratford, Railway Reserve Road, Stratford, Shire of Wellington, Victoria, Australia

1887.title: Look for the sign
1887.summary: Find your way to Tyers Primary School on Mt Hope Rd and you can’t miss the Reserve (just up from the school on the opposite side).

1888.title: A welcoming walkway
1888.summary: Enter the Reserve via the footbridge and iron gate.

1889.title: The Reserve
1889.summary: Whilst this is not a large area, it’s a tribute to one of our national botanical treasures and worth the visit.

1890.title: Sunlight streaming
1890.summary: If you time it right, you can catch the rays of the rising or setting sun at various sites in the Reserve.

1891.title: Nodding Greenhood Orchid
1891.summary: These beautiful orchids are found in the eastern states of Australia, and flower in winter and spring.

1892.title: Take a seat
1892.summary: This is a lovely spot to rest and imagine life in Jean Gailbraith’s day.

1893.title: A stand of Cherry Ballarts
1893.summary: These beautiful trees, which belong to the sandalwood family, are also known as the edible indigenous species Native Cherry (Exocarpos cupressiformis).

1894.title: The historic homestead, Dunedin
1894.summary: This is the home Jean was raised in and lived at until well past her 80th year. You can see the rooftop clearly as you look across the road from the Reserve’s gate.

1895.title: Watt's Cottage
1895.summary: Home to early settlers in Sorrento, this house was built in 1869. The Pioneer Memorial Garden is well tended with blooms all year round. Tours available (at limited times).

1896.title: Walk towards Cape Schank
1896.summary: Did you enjoy looking at the lovely cottages along the way? At the end of the road, you'll notice signs indicating a variety of walks. Keep going until you see one directing you to Cape Schank.

1897.title: Beautiful views
1897.summary: You might need to pause a few times as there are many places to appreciate the very fine views along the way.

1898.title: St Paul's beach
1898.summary: Follow the sign, it leads you down some steps to a lovely beach but check the tide. If it's high tide you might get flooded or washed away (the currents are strong here)!

1899.title: At St Paul's Beach
1899.summary: A fabulous rock formation that you can walk through. What's on the other side? Only one way to find out!

1900.title: Follow the sign to Jubilee Point
1900.summary: This is the perfect picnic spot (although it can be a bit windy). This short detour gives you great views as well as nice spots to sit and relax.

1901.title: Sorrento - Portsea Artists' Trail
1901.summary: This painting by Emanuel Phillips Fox from 1915 depicts Jubilee Point. It is Point 13 of the Sorrento-Portsea Artists' Trail.

1902.title: Walk towards Jubilee Point
1902.summary: Feels like you're heading out into the horizon!

1903.title: Jubilation at Jubilee Point
1903.summary: You'll not be disappointed by the  spectacular views!.

1904.title: Sunset views
1904.summary: We enjoyed the light and shadows cast by the late afternoon sun.

1905.title: Pram, stroller and wheelchair friendly
1905.summary: The whole loop’s surface is either concrete or high-quality boardwalk and therefore usable by all most everyone.

1906.title: BBQ and Playground
1906.summary: At the western end of the lake is this great BBQ and playground, perfect spot to bring the family.

1907.title: Friendly locals
1907.summary: It is amazing juts how many birds there are in the lake!

1908.title: Read about the native flora and fauna
1908.summary: There are plenty of signs and information sheets around the loop providing plenty of information for walkers.

1909.title: Duck feeding central!
1909.summary: The pier at the eastern end of the lake, just in front of the Cardinia Cultural Centre, is a perfect spot to feed the duck, swans and other types of birds.

1910.title: Cardinia Road Train Station is less than 1km away
1910.summary: As Cardinia Road Train Station is just under a km away, the lake is very easily accessible by public transport. The pedestrian facilities between the station and the lake and great.

1911.title: A beautiful view all the way around
1911.summary: You will be pleasantly surprised just how pleasant the views and amenity of the lake are.

1912.title: What are these two up to?
1912.summary: What are these two up to?

1913.title: Some inspiration from the Council!
1913.summary: The Council estimates the loop is 2,000 steps, which they consider is one fifth of the number of steps you should aim for per day.

1914.title: Try not to fall in!
1914.summary: Most of the walk has no guard rail, however the water depth is very shallow so do not be alarmed!

1915.title: Toilet, Carpark and Recreational Facilities
1915.summary: A good place to start and end your walking adventure. These facilities are all available to the public.

1916.title: Endeavour Fern Gully entrance and carpark
1916.summary: This is the main  entrance to Endeavour Fern Gully and more car-parking spaces are available here if necessary.

1917.title: Interpretive signage
1917.summary: Interpretive signage and markers are located along the Endeavour Fern Gully trail. There is also a picnic area, shelter and map as you enter the walking loop.

1918.title: Burnt-out hollow in a messmate stringybark
1918.summary: Have a look around and spot the burnt-out hollow in a large messmate stringybark. This is believed to have been a place where Indigenous people smoked animals for food, such as eels.

1919.title: Manna gums
1919.summary: This area in the gully boasts some impressive native trees as well as more low-lying flora.  Have a look up and see birds fly busily to and from their nests.

1920.title: Creek
1920.summary: The creek is a great place to see a variety of fungi and ferns, amongst the sounds of the water trickling and the birds humming and whistling.

1921.title: Wild Melbourne
1921.summary: This walk was completed by Wild Melbourne, a not-for-profit specialising in nature engagement and dedicated to connecting people with nature. Please visit our website to find out more

1922.title: Rupanyup Post Office
1922.summary: An old Post Office building where you can park and assemble and is a good place to start your walk

1923.title: Boydys Take Away
1923.summary:
Excellent place for a meal or some well earned cold drinks before or after your walk.
Plenty of parking in front of the shop or in the space under cover of trees in the  middle of the main street

1924.title: Rupanyup Public Toilet block
1924.summary: Brick constructed toilet facilities that are well serviced by council and clean..

1925.title: Rupanyup Supermarket
1925.summary: If you camp or stay at the local Lions run community park at the billabong you may need supplies, the Rupanyup Supermarket has some of the essentials you may need.

1926.title: Rupanyup Memoral Hall (former picture theatre)
1926.summary: The Rupanyup Memorial Hall was built in 1920 and is used for all sorts of social functions including a local emergency centre during the floods of 2010/11 and was originally a country cinema.

1927.title: Rupanyup Commercial Hotel
1927.summary:
A welcome place for some on a walk in summer is the Rupanyup Commercial Hotel and their drinks are ice cold.
Sadly, the Rupanyup Café next door has been closed for some time.

1928.title: Picnic spot (under cover)
1928.summary: There is a picnic pot under cover with good seating in the middle parking section of the street. This seating is easily found almost opposite the front of the Hotel

1929.title: New Rupanyup Police Station
1929.summary: We have a new Police Station in the town however, it is a country one man station that is often unmanned.

1930.title: Custs Store
1930.summary:
Custs Store is a replica of a traditional general store & is located in the middle area between the Rupanyup Supermarket & The Rupanyup Hardware.
It was named after one of the first shops erected.

1931.title: The old Dunmunkle Shire Council Building and now Yarriambiack Shire Office
1931.summary: This is the original building of the Shire Offices when Rupanyup was the Dunmunkle Shire, the local communities merged to being the southern end of the Yarriambiack Shire Council in the 1990s,

1932.title: Stone Memorial in Shire offices Driveway
1932.summary: There is a stone memorial with a few plaques explaining the councils history, it is to the left of the front of the building in the driveway.

1933.title: The Rupanyup RSL Hall
1933.summary: A very tidy Country RSL Hall that also has a Restored 25 Pounder Military Gun in the front yard, this is worth a look and has a memorial plaque to explain the history of the gun.

1934.title: Memorial 25 Pounder Gun at the RSL Hall
1934.summary: There is a 25 Pounder Gun in the front yard of the RSL that has this plaque to describe the restoration.

1935.title: Watch out for semi trailer grain trucks when crossing this highway
1935.summary: This walk crosses a busy highway that has two separate lanes divided by a centre median area and can make visibility an issue.

1936.title: Plenty of Parking Spots
1936.summary: There is plenty of parking around the town and ample spaces in front of the Post Office

1937.title: Watch out for semi trailer grain trucks when crossing this highway
1937.summary: This walk crosses a busy highway that has two separate lanes divided by a centre median area and can make visibility an issue.  There has been fatalities in the main street before so please take care.

1938.title: St. Philips Anglican Church
1938.summary:
Address:  74 Cromie Street, Rupanyup,  Vic.  3388.
Built 1912.

1939.title: Watch out for semi trailer grain trucks when crossing this highway
1939.summary: This walk crosses a busy highway that has two separate lanes divided by a centre median area and can make visibility an issue.

1940.title: Rupanyup Nursing Home and Doctors Surgery
1940.summary: The Rupanyup Nursing Home and Doctors Surgery provides a range of health services for the township and wider Yarriambiack Shire communities.

1941.title: Map and information board
1941.summary: At the start of the walking trails, signage provides a list of bird species, flora, ferns and orchids that you may spot along the way as well as a map indicating your walking options.

1942.title: Look and learn
1942.summary: Sharing knowledge between the ages can only be enhanced by a fantastic location, with a boardwalk over the wetland that provides a rich tapestry of aquatic plants and birdlife.

1943.title: Coral Fern Walk
1943.summary: One of three bridge crossings, take a wander through a swathe of spectacular Coral Fern (Gleichenia dicarpa) and flowering Snow Daisy Bush (Olearia lirata) woven within the tree ferns and forest.

osm.name: Coral Fern Walk
osm.display_name: Coral Fern Walk, Moe, City of Latrobe, Victoria, 3825, Australia

1944.title: Lovely misty morning
1944.summary: Springtime is renowned for the floral explosion in the Reserve, including the beautiful wattle blossom (some of which is non-native but which the Committee of Management is steadily removing).

1945.title: Superb Fairy Wren
1945.summary: Fairy-Wrens are just one species of the numerous birdlife that can be spotted in this area and makes a walk just that bit more enjoyable, especially when they stop by to spot you.

1946.title: Wonderful boardwalks
1946.summary: This is a well-kept reserve, with wide boardwalks that protect the vegetation as well as ensuring you don’t get your feet wet!

1947.title: Perfect sunset
1947.summary: You may choose to wind down at the end of the day to watch the sun sink below the horizon, reflected on the water’s surface.

1948.title: Wonderful wetlands
1948.summary: Looking through the Tall Spike Rush (Eleocharis sphacelata) is a fertile wetland. At the end of a hot day, you can find almost all the birdlife taking a dip, which is a spectacular site.

1949.title: Pink Hyacinth (Dipodium roseum)
1949.summary: This beautiful flower is one over 50 species of orchids in this Reserve, meaning there’s something in flower throughout the year.

1950.title: Planning a picnic?
1950.summary: Whether you eat first and then walk, or reflect on what you’ve seen over a tasty meal after you’ve discovered this beautiful reserve, the facilities are kept clean and comfortable.

1951.title: The Welcome Entrance
1951.summary: A beautifully constructed archway welcomes walkers to this brilliant overview of Gippsland’s history.

1952.title: An easy stroll
1952.summary: The path around Kernot Lake is user-friendly to all ages and abilities, and is populated by numerous information boards.

1953.title: Five clans: one nation
1953.summary: Gippsland’s original inhabitants, living in this region for thousands of years, are the Gunaikurnai nation with its five clans sharing the land.

1954.title: The creation story
1954.summary: This plinth tells the creation story of Boorun, the male pelican, and his wife Tuk, the female musk duck.

1955.title: A rich fabric of history
1955.summary: Settlement stories are told through both photos and text, starting with the prospective squatters who came south over the Victorian Alps to settle in the central Gippsland Plains and beyond.

1956.title: The migrant statue
1956.summary: Created by sculptor William Eicholtz, this central figure stands in the centre of the Gippsland Immigration Wall of Recognition.

1957.title: Town life
1957.summary: Learn about how the various townships were established across the region over the years.

1958.title: A captured history
1958.summary: Whatever time of day you take this walk, you will be treated to an extraordinary diversity of historical facts about Gippsland.

1959.title: Rest and read
1959.summary: Take some time to absorb the information and contemplate the photographs which, as the saying goes, prove that a picture can paint a thousand words.

1960.title: Time for a BBQ
1960.summary: An excellent venue for family and community gatherings, there are two covered areas with electric barbeques as well as a children’s playground.

1961.title: Gum trees
1961.summary: These gum trees greet you at the start of the walk.

1962.title: Pigs face flowers
1962.summary: These beautiful flowers instantly brighten up the walking path!

1963.title: Shady trees
1963.summary: There are many sheltered spots along the way. A good place for a picnic if you're bringing food and a few friends.

1964.title: Walk across the laneway
1964.summary: Cut through to the opposite side when you see a grassy laneway. This is Kennedy Court and it will take you through to Kingston Boulevard.

1965.title: Manor houses
1965.summary: Time to admire the grand houses and immaculate gardens!

1966.title: Cockatoo Community Garden
1966.summary: The Community Garden features allocated as well as communal plots and is run by the local community

1967.title: Sensory garden
1967.summary: Sensory garden is located in the Cockatoo Community Garden

1969.title: Tarra-Bulga visitor centre
1969.summary: A beautiful and peaceful area to enjoy a picnic.  Opening times for the centre are 10am-4pm during school holidays, weekends and public holidays.

1970.title: Lyrebird Track options
1970.summary: Turn left to continue this walk or turn right to take a short diversion to a gully lookout.

1971.title: Gully lookout
1971.summary: Lyrebird Ridge Track is accessible for people with disabilities and will lead you to this lookout over a fern-filled gully.

1972.title: Ash Track
1972.summary: A level and very well maintained compacted gravel pathway.

osm.name: Ash Track
osm.display_name: Ash Track, Balook, Shire of Wellington, Victoria, Australia

1973.title: Giant Mountain Ash
1973.summary: This immense tree is over 60 metres high and can you imagine how old?!

1974.title: Corrigan's Bridge Lookout
1974.summary: Another lookout which places you above the height of the fern trees below but look up and take in the magnificent height of the taller trees.

1975.title: Fern Gully Nature walk
1975.summary: This section of the walk takes you down to the bottom of the gully, past the Lyrebird pool where you might spot one having a drink and splash in summer!

1976.title: Myrtle Beech tree root
1976.summary: A rare and special look at the root system of this ancient tree.  It provides the perfect home for mosses and fungi to grow.

1977.title: Yabby
1977.summary: This fresh water crustacean was spotted swimming in the Lyrebird pool. He is well camouflaged!

1978.title: Bulga picnic shelter
1978.summary: A big wooden shelter with forest views, a place to stop and rest or enjoy a picnic.

1979.title: Track to visitors centre
1979.summary: This track is off to your left after you leave the Bulga picnic area.

1980.title: The Path
1980.summary: No a lot of shade for the fist little bit, but great to get going.

1981.title: Little bridge
1981.summary: Great bridge to cross after rain.

1982.title: View to Tidal River
1982.summary: Love it when you can see the sea from the track!

1983.title: Rocky path
1983.summary: The path gets a little rocky in parts, but it's not a problem for people steady on their feet.

1984.title: Near the top
1984.summary: Path gets a bit smoother again as you near the top.

1985.title: Looking to Mount Oberon
1985.summary: Wonderful spot to stop for lunch as it's usually sheltered from the wind the summit isn't).

1986.title: Tidal River
1986.summary: View to Tidal River and Norman Bay.

1987.title: Squeaky Beach
1987.summary: View from the summit to Squeaky Beach is definitely worth the walk!

1988.title: Tarra Valley picnic area
1988.summary: Tables, toilets and picnic shelters are provided.

osm.name: Tarra Valley Picnic Area
osm.display_name: Tarra Valley Picnic Area, Tarra Valley Rainforest Walk, Tarra Valley, Shire of Wellington, Victoria, Australia

1989.title: Ferns
1989.summary: Thirty nine species of ferns have been recorded and there are more than 200 kinds of fungi.

1990.title: Cyathea Falls
1990.summary: Meander through a rainforest gully and across trickling mountain streams to Cyathea Falls.

1991.title: Turnstile entry
1991.summary: Thanks to Parklands Albury Wodonga management, a trusty turnstile points the way

1992.title: Ascent tracks - either west or east
1992.summary: Both lead to the same junction, on either side of the fence line

1993.title: Lake Hume
1993.summary: The first glimpse of Lake Hume comes into view.

1994.title: Lake Hume
1994.summary: The expanse of Lake Hume can be appreciated once you gain some altitude

1995.title: Mahers Hill ridgeline
1995.summary: The destination is a reasonably gentle ascent

1996.title: The splendour of the Murray Valley
1996.summary: With views past Tallangatta and Corryong to the snowfields of Kosciuszko and Perisher Valley. This view alone made the walk worthwhile!

1998.title: Tyers River
1998.summary: It’s a shame how many of us haven’t visited this beautiful river, because the idyllic walk along its riverbanks is well worth your while.

1999.title: Great fishing spots
1999.summary: Whether you’re going to sling your hook or just sit and look, there are tracks leading down to the riverbank where you can spend quite a bit of time.

2000.title: Historic pipeline
2000.summary: There’s some memorabilia of times gone by in this area, including the old pipeline that transported water from the river to the township of Traralgon.

2001.title: Follow the orange markers
2001.summary: Small orange arrows are situated on trees as you make your way along the track, but make sure you don’t go further than the sign to Wirilda Track if you aren’t planning a very long walk.

2002.title: Track on the hillside
2002.summary: It’s a wonderful feeling to know you are safely balanced between the base of a large hill and the fall to the riverbank.

2003.title: A steep track
2003.summary: One of the joys of this walk is the contrasting heights and varying vegetation types that come with the changes.

2004.title: A home in the hollow
2004.summary: This burrow sits at the edge of the track, so presumably its resident waits until nightfall when the walkers have left the park before it takes its own stroll.

2005.title: Fern forest
2005.summary: The lush forest sensation hits you when look up, but also when you look down to discover a flush of ferns (also known as Fish Bone Ferns) by your feet.

2006.title: Healthy understory
2006.summary: Great swathes of Dogwood (Cassinia aculeata) can be seen as you wander along the track, as well as numerous other understorey plants.

2007.title: Rupertswood Mansion
2007.summary: Built in 1874-76 for Sir William Clarke, in 1882 a cricket match between England and a local side resulted in the presentation of a pottery urn containing 'The Ashes' of a burnt bail - 'The Ashes'.

osm.name: Rupertswood Mansion
osm.display_name: Rupertswood Mansion, Yellow Gum Boulevard, Sunbury, Melbourne, City of Hume, Victoria, 3429, Australia

2008.title: Rupertswood Lake
2008.summary: This lake was constructed by Sir Willam Clarke and included an island shaped like Australia. Today it is a nice place to feed ducks, swans and other birdlife.

osm.name: Rupertswood Lake
osm.display_name: Rupertswood Lake, Sunbury, Melbourne, City of Hume, Victoria, 3429, Australia

2009.title: Melbourne-Bendigo Railway Bridge
2009.summary: In July 1861 the Sunbury to Woodend government railway opened. This included construction of many impressive arched railway bridges. The Blind Creek bridge is listed on the Victorian Heritage Register

2010.title: Riddell Road Childrens Playground
2010.summary: This new playground was constructed in 2011 and includes many challenging activities for children.

2011.title: Clarke Oval
2011.summary: Large oval used by Sunbury Lions Football Club.

osm.name: Clarke Oval
osm.display_name: Clarke Oval, Riddell Road, Sunbury, Melbourne, City of Hume, Victoria, 3429, Australia

2012.title: Sunbury BMX and Skate Park
2012.summary: Just a little detour from the path is the Sunbury BMX and Skate Park with great facilities.

2013.title: Stewarts Lane Nature Reserve
2013.summary: Nature Reserve, look for native animals and enjoy the natural setting.

2014.title: Bridge over Livingstone Creek
2014.summary: Cross the bridge to get to the other side where the walk starts!

2015.title: Track sign
2015.summary: This walk describes the Ah Fong Loop Track but you can walk from here to the Omeo reservoir in the town center also.

2016.title: Steps Up
2016.summary: The landscape and track are very up and down as a result of the gold mining methods used.

2017.title: Claims information sign
2017.summary: Ah Fong must have been quite a character and you can learn why if you read the signs along the walk.

2018.title: The track and the cliffs
2018.summary: The cliffs have been exposed to get to the gold they were hiding.

2019.title: Starlight Claim
2019.summary: These caves were dug out by hand to get to the gold when water was unavailable.

2020.title: Gully bridge
2020.summary: Water was a vital tool for extracting the gold here so the miners dug more than 50km of ditches and channels to bring water upstream.

2021.title: Track sign
2021.summary: From here you can cross the bridge and go to Omeo or continue to your right and loop back to the start.

2022.title: Rocks
2022.summary: Possibly part of a race used to divert water to high points above the mining sites.

2023.title: Steps to Livingstone Creek
2023.summary: Go down here to get to a waterhole and sandy area.

2024.title: Livingstone Creek
2024.summary: This creek was severely impacted from muddy water being washed into it but today it looks clean and healthy.

2025.title: Sandy creek bank
2025.summary: A sandy spot  by the creek  to rest or picnic.

2027.title: The end
2027.summary: Follow the creek back to the bridge back to the beginning.

2028.title: Ocean Grove Surf Beach
2028.summary: This is a beautiful beach for walking and playing. The sand is so soft and the views of the Barwon Bluff are exquisite.

2029.title: Sand Play
2029.summary: If your kids want to play in the sand then stop for a rest. It is so therapeutic for kids to play in the sand. Try and keep your kids off the dunes  though. There is a good spot later on this walk!

2030.title: Barwon Heads Bridge
2030.summary: This bridge is great fun to photograph and the kids really love walking under it.

2031.title: Between the bridges
2031.summary: This section of beach is really fun because there is a large deposit of sand here and it is ok for kids to play here without damaging  the dune system.

2032.title: Ocean Grove Surf Beach
2032.summary: It is so nice to run in some open space!

2033.title: More sand play
2033.summary: Kids can never get enough sand play!

2034.title: Along the Barwon River
2034.summary: The tide will dictate how much sand you have to walk on but walking on the rocks is always an option!

2035.title: Take your shoes off
2035.summary: The sand is very "squelchy" and feels wonderful between your toes!

2036.title: Cut through the Caravan Park
2036.summary: You can walk through the Caravan Park to get to the road. Find a safe place to cross over to the carpark.

2037.title: BMX track
2037.summary: Hidden away, it might not look like much but when people are using the track it taks on  whole new life. Definitely worth checking out!

2038.title: Felltimber lagoon
2038.summary: Located next tot he Felltimber Community Centre, this is a peaceful spot to sit by the water. There are many ducks that will approach you - especially if you have something for them to eat.

2039.title: Wodonga Sports and Leisure Centre
2039.summary: This centre offers a wide range of activities and includes and indoor pool. Major tournaments are held here and it's home to the Wodonga Wolves CBL basketball team.

2040.title: Willow Park
2040.summary: Besides being scenic to walk through, there's  a great play ground, hidden bird houses, 2 ovals, outdoor gym gear, a BBQ area and its attached to a skate park

2041.title: Balyang Sanctuary
2041.summary: Plenty of parking available at Balyang Sanctuary. Start walk from here.

osm.name: Balyang Sanctuary
osm.display_name: Balyang Sanctuary, Newtown, Geelong, City of Greater Geelong, Victoria, 3220, Australia

2042.title: Pedestrian and cycle bridge
2042.summary: pedestrians and cyclists can use this overpass to cross the river

osm.name: Breakwater Road
osm.display_name: Breakwater Road, South Geelong, Geelong, City of Greater Geelong, Victoria, 3220, Australia

2044.title: Rowing
2044.summary: Walk past the rowing sheds. Lots of action of people on land getting ready to get into the water and lots of people already on the water!

osm.name: Barwon Rowing Club
osm.display_name: Barwon Rowing Club, Barwon Terrace, South Geelong, Geelong, City of Greater Geelong, Victoria, 3220, Australia

2045.title: Kilcunda General Store & Meikle's Pub
2045.summary: The store has gourmet breakfast and lunch, fine produce, handmade craft and a few everyday supplies. It doubles as a post office. The pub next door opens for dinner, offering fine tucker and wine.

2046.title: Crossing the road
2046.summary: Be extra careful crossing the road to the shops as huge trucks, trailers and cars tend to tear down the highway in excess of the speed limit.

2047.title: Information board
2047.summary: Start along the dirt track (also a rail trail). You'll spot a sign to the left soon afterwards. Contains useful historical info as well as details about the flora and fauna here.

2048.title: Wildflower 1
2048.summary: As you begin the walk, you'll notice the variety of plants growing on each side.

2049.title: Wildflower 2
2049.summary: If only I knew the names of all these little flowers!

2050.title: Wildflower 3
2050.summary: These are near an impressive cliff face. Don't step too far out or it's a long way (and bumpy way) down to the rocks.

2051.title: Steam driven winch
2051.summary: Somewhere around this area is a historical remnant from the area's coal mining past. Peek behind the sign to see what it looks like.

2052.title: Wildflower 4
2052.summary: These are Dianellas. I have them in my front yard. The purple flowers are great. Plus, they're a very hardy plant that will grow in the toughest environment (eg. my front yard).

2053.title: Sandy's blowhole
2053.summary: Walk down to Sandy's blowhole for a shower! The rocks here are rather strange and interesting. The waves can be quite sudden and powerful so be careful, especially if the tide is high.

2054.title: Wildflower 5
2054.summary: I've never seen this before! It's furry and feathery. How peculiar.

2055.title: Wildflower 6
2055.summary: Are these daisies? They look like daisies. There are yellow and white ones along the path too.

2056.title: Wild grasses
2056.summary: The sound of rustling grass can be quite soothing. When the wind blew (which was often where we were here), it made the field of tall grasses look like a sea of green waves.

2057.title: Wildflower 7
2057.summary: These are tiny flowers we found along the path. They are very dainty and easily missed, or trampled on! They were the size of a fingernail.

2058.title: Wildflower 8
2058.summary: Trusty tea trees. The smell of tea tree is refreshing.

2059.title: Wildflower 9
2059.summary: We found these on our way to the beach.

2060.title: Beach
2060.summary: We ended our walk here but you can keep going till you get to Punchbowl Road. Dip your toes in the water but don't freeze them off. We had a snack here then headed back the same way we came.

2061.title: Gateway Lakes precinct
2061.summary: Gateway Lakes hosts a large number of events and activities each year and is home to Wodonga’s water ski, canoe, dragon boating and rowing clubs. Take a slight detour and check it out!

2062.title: Indigenous art and history
2062.summary: Look out for the Indigenous cultural displays along the trail as you enter into Harris Road. You will learn about our local history.

2063.title: Picnic by the Murray River
2063.summary: Enjoy one of the many lovely picnic spots along the Murray River for a family picnic. Quiet, calm and very picturesque. Enjoy!

2064.title: Wildlife spotting
2064.summary: Along the nature trail, keep your eyes peeled for some local wild life – can you see a kangaroo in the long grass, some new ducklings even?

2065.title: Historic Murray River railway bridge
2065.summary: Walk under the historic Murray River railway bridge that crosses from Victoria into New South Wales. If you are lucky to have a train crossing above, you are in for a thrill as you walk below.

2066.title: Gateway Village gardens
2066.summary: Stop for some shade, possibly even spot a wedding taking place and enjoy the beautiful surrounds of Gateway Village’s gardens and pond area.

2067.title: Gateway Village precinct
2067.summary: Gateway Village has a lot on offer from yummy food, hot or refreshing beverages, art displays, theatre performances to the Hume Murray Farmer’s Market from 8am every second Saturday. Visit www.hmfb.or

2068.title: Mills Park Circuit
2068.summary: A glimpse of the green open space and lovely native trees. You are on your way.

2069.title: Time for some stretching
2069.summary: Some stretching posts have been perfectly placed to stretch your muscles ready for your walk or run.

2070.title: Beautiful path,   paved with native trees. Nearly half way.
2070.summary: Mid way and it is glorious and so relaxing. Over the rise and in the centre is a BBQ.

2071.title: Exercise point, chin ups. if you dare
2071.summary: If you want to test your strength, this is the exercise point to do so.

2072.title: BBQ spot surrounded by open green spaces
2072.summary: Perfectly situated, BBQ for the family to have lunch after the circuit walk, plenty of room to run and play and Go Fly a Kite.

2073.title: Beacon Cove Seating
2073.summary: There is plenty of seating along Beacon Cove. Sit to rest, people watch or enjoy the local fish and chips.

2074.title: Port Melbourne railway line
2074.summary: Enjoy the walking/ bicycling trail along the light rail route.

2075.title: Edwards Reserve
2075.summary: This is a lovely park that runs along the light rail, a popular spot for dogs.

2076.title: Leading Lights
2076.summary: Constructed by the Melbourne Harbor Trust in 1924 to a Trinity House design, the beacons define the centre line of the Port Melbourne Channel.

2077.title: Princes Pier
2077.summary: Built between 1912 and 1915, Princes Pier was the third major pier constructed at Port Melbourne and served as a major passenger terminal.

osm.name: Princes Pier
osm.display_name: Princes Pier, Bay Trail, Beacon Cove, Port Melbourne, Melbourne, City of Port Phillip, Victoria, 3207, Australia

2078.title: Beacon Cove
2078.summary: Cafes, restaurants, grocery store, Spirit of Tasmania ferry terminal, tram stop.

osm.name: Beacon Cove
osm.display_name: Beacon Cove, Port Melbourne, Melbourne, City of Port Phillip, Victoria, 3207, Australia

2079.title: The Patrobus monument
2079.summary: Patrobas is the only Gippsland racehorse to have won a Melbourne Cup, and the only racehorse to have won the cup, Caulfield Guineas and Derby in the same year, 1915.

2080.title: Willow Park
2080.summary: This Park is also a free overnight camping spot (maximum stay of 36 hours).

osm.name: Willow Park
osm.display_name: Willow Park, Rosedale, Shire of Wellington, Victoria, Australia

2081.title: Coffee shop, bakery etc
2081.summary: Stop for coffee or lunch at one of the eateries along the main street.

2083.title: Strath Village Shopping Center
2083.summary: It is really exciting shopping center and ranks the third busiest one in Greater Bendigo

2084.title: Walking around Kennington Reservoir
2084.summary: Fresh air and the lake is so wonderful to walk around. Perfect for a picnic with comfortable seating and shades

2085.title: Kennington Primary School
2085.summary: Located in a Hill looking down Kennington Reservoir Lake, green and fresh environment for students

2086.title: Kennington Pre - School
2086.summary: Small but lovely and green playground for children, located beside the lake

2087.title: "I only count the sunny hours" Clock
2087.summary: The old clock was constructed by the Shire of Strathfieldsaye with the assistance of The Bendigo - Strathdale Rotary Club. Opposite the Clock is Reservoir Hotel.

2088.title: Historic houses
2088.summary: I like to admire these lovely houses.  They make the town a pleasure to walk around.

2089.title: Stones
2089.summary: I like the way these stones decorate the street.

2090.title: River view
2090.summary: Our stretch of the Campaspe River is beautiful, though it did flood recently after heavy rains.

2091.title: Old historic hospital
2091.summary: My brothers and I were born here.  At present, it's future is uncertain.  Will it be sold to the developers?  Will it become a community facility?  Would be good to see it preserved.

2092.title: Wedge Street
2092.summary: Tree line boulevard.  Pretty in spring, cool in summer, stunning in autumn.  If only all our streets could look like this!

osm.name: Wedge Street
osm.display_name: Wedge Street, Kyneton, Shire of Macedon Ranges, Victoria, 3444, Australia

2093.title: Trough
2093.summary: For a time when horses and carriages were our main form of transport (apart from walking of course!).

2094.title: Brocklebank Drive
2094.summary: Always an amazing spot for a wander.  The fresh air from the trees is amazing, especially after walking up a steep hill!

osm.name: Brocklebank Drive
osm.display_name: Brocklebank Drive, Kyneton, Shire of Macedon Ranges, Victoria, 3444, Australia

2095.title: Grand old gum trees
2095.summary: Beautiful gum trees greet you as you begin your walk. If you look closely enough, you might spot the Yingabeal Aboriginal scar tree.

2096.title: Doll's House
2096.summary: An old milking shed that was later used to store artwork by Sidney Nolan, including his famous Ned Kelly series!

2097.title: Heide kitchen garden
2097.summary: A garden brimming with fresh herbs and produce used by the onsite cafe.

2098.title: Wild garden
2098.summary: This rambling cottage garden is delightful at any time, especially in the morning with the sun's rays streaming through.

2099.title: The oak tree
2099.summary: This grand old oak tree was planted in 1935. It's beautifully shady and its autumnal hues are still apparent in the middle of winter!

2100.title: Heide I
2100.summary: This is the house that the Reed family lived for 35 years. Here, many artists, including Sidney Nolan, Albert Tucker and Joy Hester came to visit, stay and create.

2101.title: Rings of Saturn, Inge King
2101.summary: Inge fled to England from Germany as a refugee, then later settled in Australia. Her other famous works include the black waves on the lawns of the NGV, and red ringed structures on EastLink.

2102.title: Heide II kitchen garden
2102.summary: A most productive kitchen garden. Stroll through here and be inspired about what to grow for your own garden :)

2103.title: Rose Walk Pavillion
2103.summary: This is the perfect place to have a seat to enjoy your surroundings, have a picnic or simply catch the rays of sunshine as they filter through the wooden grooves of this beautiful structure.

2104.title: Flowing Yarra
2104.summary: You can catch glimpses of the Yarra as you walk past in the wooded river bank. You can extend your walk by joining the path to the neighbouring Banksia Park.

2105.title: Trees for climbing
2105.summary: We discovered some grand old trees that were perfect for climbing, admiring or simply for enjoying its shade.

2106.title: Cows, Jeff Thomon
2106.summary: Perhaps the most photographed sculpture at Heide. Presumably this art work pays tribute to the history of the property as a dairy farm.

2107.title: Bee hives
2107.summary: We spotted a whole lot of bee hives! There must be an abundance of honey. We enjoyed listening to the buzz of activity near the hives (obviously you shouldn't get too close, or else...).

2108.title: Hallett Cove Beach
2108.summary: Looking from the cafe, along the beach. Those boulders  were dropped there by the melting of a continental ice-sheet at the end of the Permian era some 270 million years ago!

2109.title: Singing Honeyeaters
2109.summary: Singing Honeyeaters are plentiful in the coastal heath.

2110.title: The Amphitheatre
2110.summary: A short climb takes you to the Amphitheatre, the Sugarloaf and right into the layers of sediments.

2112.title: The Bluff
2112.summary: The path moves from beach level to the cliff tops.

2113.title: Permian Pavement
2113.summary: This sheet of rock is covered with deep scratches. "So what?", you say. Well, they were only made by a continental ice-sheet that covered Australia and Antarctica 270 million years ago.

2114.title: Permian Pavement Close-Up
2114.summary: There are only a few places in Australia you can see evidence of the permian Glaciation. Here is one, Werribee Gorge near Bacchus Marsh in Victoria is another.

2115.title: Rugged Cliffs
2115.summary: The path continues along the craggy Pre-Cambrian cliff tops.

2116.title: Boardwalks
2116.summary: Most of this walk is done on boardwalks. They are well made and designed, and take you everywhere you want to go.

2117.title: Another Layer Cake
2117.summary: Pretty sure these sediments are from the Pliocene.

2118.title: Waterfall
2118.summary: During the last Ice Age 10,000 years ago, St Vincent Gulf was a large grassy plain. This little waterfall flows over Pre-Cambrian rock, so it has been running for much longer than a mere 10,000 years.

2119.title: A hasty retreat
2119.summary: The weather was closing in - time to go!

2120.title: A last look
2120.summary: The threatening weather only made the view across the Amphitheatre even more dramatic.

2121.title: Captain Charles Sturt marker
2121.summary: About 50 metres along the Rower’s Lawn is a marker that commemorates the passing of Captain Charles Sturt through this area in 1830.

2122.title: Cureton Avenue
2122.summary: The road leading up the hill is Cureton Avenue, and is named after Stephen Cureton, the man George Chaffey first sent to the district to explore the potential of developing an irrigation colony.

osm.name: Cureton Avenue
osm.display_name: Cureton Avenue, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

2123.title: Water Play
2123.summary: Formally the Ornamental Lakes (pic attached), this area mark the site of the old Risby Sawmill, circa 1888. The area was transformed into a recreation water play are in 2015.

osm.name: Mildura Water Play Park
osm.display_name: Mildura Water Play Park, Hugh King Drive, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

2124.title: Nowingi Place - host to outdoor concerts and entertainment
2124.summary: The sound shell was given the name Nowingi, to acknowledge the tremendous community effort that went into successfully fighting against a proposed toxic waste dump in the Mallee locality of Nowingi.

2125.title: Lock Island
2125.summary: Cross over the lock and explore Lock Island. During Mildura’s temperance era (1887-early 1900’s), this island was known as Pinkie Bend, due to the amount of illegal liquor drunk on the island.

2126.title: Various Sculptures
2126.summary: Along Cueton and in the Art Centre lawns you will see significant sculptures from the Mildura Sculpture Triennials which took place between 1961 and 1988.

2127.title: Mildura Arts Centre and Cafe
2127.summary: In 1966, an art gallery and theatre were added to Rio Vista house and the whole complex became known as the Mildura Arts Centre and was officially opened by Sir Henry Bolte in November 1966.

2128.title: The Grand Hotel
2128.summary: Enter the Grand Hotel’s main entrance and turn left.  To your right, you will see a display of historical photos. Through the glass doors are one of Mildura’s original Chaffey fountains.

osm.name: The Grand Hotel
osm.display_name: The Grand Hotel, Gallagher Lane, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

2129.title: Prince and Princess of Wales Fountain Plaza
2129.summary: This fountain is very special as it was opened by the Prince and Princess of Wales on the 29th October 1985. Many Mildura residence crowded around to see the Princess Diana.

2130.title: Railway overpass
2130.summary:
A short walk across the railway overpass leads back to the riverfront, to
your car and to the end of this walk or head down to the Hugh King Drive underpass to avoid the stairs.

2131.title: The Bungalow
2131.summary: A Queen Anne style home, it is in keeping with its revered neighbor. The original owner of the Bungalow was Lancelot Conway-Gordon and later was home to J.H Shilliday. It remains a private residence.

2132.title: The Mildura Wharf
2132.summary: Mildura Wharf has been a vital part of the town and inland river transport system since the 1880s. It was established by the Mildura Progress Committee in 1888 to assist the burgeoning river trade.

2133.title: MIldura Rowing Club
2133.summary:
Rowing is a popular sport in Mildura and the club hosts an annual Easter Regatta that sees crews visit from across three states.

Attached is a photo of the Rowing Club in the 1931 floods.

osm.name: Mildura Rowing Club
osm.display_name: Mildura Rowing Club, Hugh King Drive, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

2134.title: The Powerhouse
2134.summary: The Powerhouse, which operated from the 1920’s through to the 1950’s, until the S.E.C took over Mildura’s electricity supply. It is now used by several community groups inc the Mildura Theatre Company

2135.title: Jaycee Park
2135.summary: Jaycee Park is adjacent to the Powerhouse and is a perfect spot for family fun with and fabulous play equipment, BBQ areas and shady spots. A large locomotive dominates the grassed area to the front.

osm.name: Jaycee Park
osm.display_name: Jaycee Park, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

2136.title: MIldura Lawn Tennis Club
2136.summary: One of Australia's leading tennis venues, featuring 32 world class grass courts. In 1997 some Davis Cup matches were played on these courts, and it attracts a number of tournaments each year.

osm.name: Mildura Lawn Tennis Club
osm.display_name: Mildura Lawn Tennis Club, Hugh King Drive, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

2137.title: Mildura Weir
2137.summary: Construction of the Mildura Weir began in Aug 1923 with the aims of raising both the water level & the pressure from the Mildura & Red Cliffs irrigation pumps. Picture,:View of Weir from Lock 11.

osm.name: Mildura Weir
osm.display_name: Mildura Weir, Buronga, Wentworth Shire Council, New South Wales, 2739, Australia

2138.title: Lock 11
2138.summary: Completed in 1928. Paddle steamers still pass through the lock daily. The Mildura system is the only site on the River Murray where a lock and weir are separated by an island. Image: Construction 1927

2139.title: Rio Vista House
2139.summary: Rio Vista, which is Spanish for River View, was completed in 1892 . Rio Vista was the home W.B Chaffey, built in a tangible show of his faith in the future of the district he founded.

2140.title: Old Railway Carriage Sheds

2197.summary: Enjoy the view from this shady picnic area.

2199.title: Cute bridge
2199.summary: Another opportunity to walk along the beach.

2210.title: Skewes Street Laneway Mural

2211.title: Goodstart Early Learning Centre
2211.summary: At Goodstart Braybrook, the staff strive to maintain a clean, safe and engaging environment for the children. Goodstart is  a multicultural centre with bilingual staff.

2269.title: White Necked Heron
2269.summary: With lots of wetland along the walk you have a good chance of seeing a Heron or two.  They spend lots of time standing very still, keeping a sharp eye out for frogs, insects and fish.

2270.title: Echidna
2270.summary: If you're lucky you might spot an Echidna out looking for ants, termites and other small invertebrates which it captures with its long sticky tongue.

2271.title: Walk markers
2271.summary: There are a number of markers along the way.  This walk follows sections of two walks - the Morang Wetlands Walk and the Ridge Track.

2272.title: Sheoak tree
2272.summary: The mat of fallen branchlets under sheoaks prevents the development of undergrowth.  For aboriginal people it was considered a safe place to leave children as snakes are said to avoid these areas.

2273.title: Kangaroo Apple
2273.summary: There are lots of Kangaroo Apple trees along the way, a hint of things to come further along the walk.

2274.title: Beauty on a small scale
2274.summary: The wetlands support beautiful succulents thriving in the shallow waters along the walk.

2275.title: Park view
2275.summary: The walk meanders through a diverse range of bushland and wetlands.  Along the way you get a real sense of being out in the bush.

2276.title: Eastern Grey Kangaroos
2276.summary: Eastern grey kangaroos are gregarious and form open-membership groups. The groups are made up of 2-3 females and their offspring with the same number of males of which one is dominant.

2277.title: Grasses and Sedges
2277.summary: The wetland areas support a wide variety of native grasses and sedges.  See how many different varieties you can spot along the way.

2278.title: Wetland view
2278.summary: One of several small lakes along the walk.  Each one supports a wide variety of birdlife including Black Swans, ducks, Purple Swamphens, Egrets, Grebes and Eurasian Coots.

2279.title: Black Swan and cygnets
2279.summary: Like other swans, the Black Swan is largely monogamous, pairing for life - there is apparently only a 6% divorce rate!  They also share parenting responsibilities of the cygnets.

2280.title: Dragonfly
2280.summary: Dragonflies usually patrol a particular area looking for insects to eat. Mosquitoes, flies and midges are a large part of their diet. This fact alone should endear these delightful creatures to us!

2281.title: Walking in open bushland
2281.summary: The pathway is a mix of gravel path and some more overgrown pathways like the one in this picture.  Overall the route is quite level.

2282.title: Eastern Great Egret
2282.summary: The Great Egret breeds in colonies, and often in association with cormorants, ibises and other egrets.  Their nest is a large platform of sticks, placed in a tree over the water.

2283.title: Foot bridge
2283.summary: Though the pathway is mostly quite wide at one point along the route there is a very small footbridge.  If you would rather avoid it, there is an alternative route back to the carpark.

2284.title: Hallam North Road car park
2284.summary: This car park was first provided in the 1980s, but was much enlarged for the Commonwealth Games in 2006. Sometimes crowded on weekends, it has the only toilets and water on this trip

2285.title: Down in the valley
2285.summary: This section of Valley View track is the lowest point on this trip. Watch for mountain bike riders, but also for wildlife in the mornings and evenings

2286.title: Head of the incline
2286.summary: This landing was once the top of a 1 in 10 tramway incline. A 'powerful engine' once sat here to winch the empty skips back up. What kind of engine? We don't know!

2287.title: The hidden quarry
2287.summary: A narrow defile on the right leads into the hidden quarry. This is not visible from the track, though walkers on the Rock Gardens track can look down from above

2288.title: Tramway cutting
2288.summary: Tramline track does not follow the course of the old tramway at this point. The cutting on the right shows where it went. Cuttings were rare on tramways as being expensive to escavate by hand

2289.title: Crest reservoir
2289.summary: This reservoir at the crest of the range is long out of use. What was it for? Walk from the north corner slightly west of north across Ridge track...

2290.title: Horse drinking trough
2290.summary: This cement lined drinking trough provided water for thirsty horses at the top of the long climb from the quarry. Still intact despite being out of use for over eighty years

2291.title: Lysterfield hills summit
2291.summary: The trig point marks the highest point of this range, with fine views through 360 deg, including Dandenong to the south, and the city of the north-west. The view is worth the 700 m walk

2292.title: Les Stone Park Wetlands
2292.summary: A great spot to try your hand at fishing. Even better if you have young children as it offers a safe space to teach them the skills.

2293.title: Pirate Ship
2293.summary: This play area is great. A safe space that lets the imagination run wild. Grab your eye patch and perch a bird on your shoulder and see what adventure you end up on

2294.title: Under road crossing
2294.summary: Avoid crossing this busy road by taking the optional path underneath the thoroughfare. Great low risk option for people walking with groups of children or animals.

2295.title: Football oval
2295.summary: If you are walking along this path, why not stop for a kick of football on the way. The oval is well manicured and is home to permanent AFL posts. A little friendly competition never hurt anyone...

2296.title: Nature at its finest
2296.summary: The path is edged by beautiful trees almost the whole way along. Providing much needed shade in the warmer months and an excellent display of colour in Autumn, they are also home to many types of Bird

2297.title: Bird houses
2297.summary: Someone has built and installed some unique bird houses in the trees here. They're dated and initialled. I'd love to know who did this!

2298.title: Skate Park
2298.summary: There is a skate park here that is incredibly popular and it looks like bigger and better things are on their way!

osm.name: James Scott Memorial Skate Park
osm.display_name: James Scott Memorial Skate Park, Pearce Street, Wodonga, City of Wodonga, Victoria, 3690, Australia

2299.title: Netball courts
2299.summary: For anyone wanting to spend some time at a netball court, these are tucked away at Martin Park and there is a gate from the walking track to the park

2300.title: The Aboriginal Cultural Heritage Trail
2300.summary: For those wishing to discover more about Gippsland’s rich indigenous heritage, this cultural trail is an excellent place to visit.

2301.title: Bush tucker
2301.summary: Over 27 species of native plants are included in this garden, all with important roles to play for the Gunaikurnai nation.

2302.title: A must for the keen BMX bike-rider
2302.summary: A busy place for the BMX enthusiasts and fun for others who just like to enjoy watching the skill involved.

2303.title: Picnic and play
2303.summary: A fitness station for adults and children alike, and a sheltered BBQ area for those days when a picnic enhances a lovely walk.

2304.title: Under the willow
2304.summary: One of many picnic table areas along the way is this beautifully shaded area under the Willows.

2305.title: Bev's Wonder World of Dolls
2305.summary: Open Tue-Fri from 10am to 3pm or by appointment at 31-33 The Boulevard, this is an extraordinary collection of dolls from around the world.

2306.title: Walk among the gum trees
2306.summary: Remnant vegetation is home to numerous animals, and the birdsong emanating from the canopy is a delight to hear.

2307.title: Bridge crossings
2307.summary: Along the trail, you will find bridges that can take you along the other side of the Waterhole Creek and back to the start of the walk (linked to the Gippsland Heritage Trail).

2308.title: Fertile reed bed
2308.summary: The healthy mix of reeds provides habitat for a multitude of aquatic species as well as being useful in the making of baskets.

2309.title: Box Hill shopping centre
2309.summary: This shopping centre constructed in the early 1980s has obliterated all traces of the former Box Hill station. The tramway crossed Carrington St through the centre of this roundabout

2310.title: Tramway
2310.summary: This footpath follows the alignment of the former tramway. All earthworks have long since vanished due to extensive re-modelling. A 1905 map shows an embankment along what is now Surrey Drive

2311.title: Surrey Dive
2311.summary: In its days as a swimming hole, the Surrey Dive had a fearsome reputation, and was the scene of several drownings. Today the scene is more placid, with model boats gliding across the water

2312.title: Box Hill brick works
2312.summary: Proposals to demolish the derelict brick works have been rejected as this is one of the few Hoffman-type rotating brick kilns surviving in Australia. However, neglect and vandalism have taken a toll

2313.title: Morning greeting
2313.summary: I'm not sure who this saint is but he looks like he's happy to be up early!

2314.title: Calder Reserve
2314.summary: There's a small playground here.  I wish it had a bbq and seats too.

osm.name: Calder Reserve
osm.display_name: Calder Reserve, Coburg, Melbourne, City of Merri-bek, Victoria, 3058, Australia

2315.title: School veggie garden
2315.summary: If you peek in the cracks between the fence, you'll see the school veggie garden! I think it would be good if the school had a wire fence so you can see what's growing in the garden.

2316.title: Trugo Club
2316.summary: Whats Trugo?  It sounds Italian.  Must be a good game to play if theres a whole club set up for it!

osm.name: Coburg Trugo Club (Disused)
osm.display_name: Coburg Trugo Club (Disused), Harding Street, Coburg, Melbourne, City of Merri-bek, Victoria, 3058, Australia

2317.title: Lawn Bowls Club
2317.summary: They play mostly on Saturday mornings I think.  I've seen lots of people here, in their best whites (probably why I'd never be able to play - all my whites are attracted to food stains).

2318.title: Coburg Leisure Centre
2318.summary: Coburg pool, spa and gym. Friendly staff, fun pool for kids and a much improved cafe.

osm.name: Coburg Leisure Centre
osm.display_name: Coburg Leisure Centre, Russell Street, Coburg, Melbourne, City of Merri-bek, Victoria, 3058, Australia

2319.title: Bridges Reserve

osm.name: Bridges Reserve
osm.display_name: Bridges Reserve, Coburg, Melbourne, City of Merri-bek, Victoria, 3058, Australia

2320.title: Coburg Mall

osm.name: Coburg Post Shop
osm.display_name: Coburg Post Shop, Victoria Street Mall, Coburg, Melbourne, City of Merri-bek, Victoria, 3058, Australia

2321.title: House on the corner
2321.summary: Who knows what this is! There's no explanation.  I asked a bloke passing by - his theory was that it was a house for the pigeons.  Unlikely.  The mystery continues...

2322.title: Coburg Library

osm.name: Coburg Library
osm.display_name: Coburg Library, Coburg Market, Coburg, Melbourne, City of Merri-bek, Victoria, 3058, Australia

2323.summary: You can book Vline tickets here.  Recent improvements with lots of new plants, separate lane for cyclists and better lighting and disability access.  Good work!

2324.title: Boronia/Dorset Rd intersection
2324.summary: An apparent slip by 1888 surveyors resulted in Melbourne's worst intersection before the rail line went underground. Major collisions on the crossing took place in 1926 and 1952, each claiming 9 lives

2325.title: Turner Road
2325.summary: Torrens Ave was previously Turner Rd north and south of Boronia Rd. The 1920s post office was on the south side, the 1970s post office on the north corner

2326.title: Boronia station square

2327.title: Dorset Road

2329.title: Erica Ave
2329.summary: Erica Ave became a retail area in the 1960s. It was home for many years to Boronia fire station. The fire brigade practiced in Maguire Park, where pranksters put detergent in the fountain

2330.title: Boronia Progess Hall
2330.summary: The progress hall opened in 1926, hosting local dances for many years, and rallies in World War II. Damaged by fire in the 1990s, the hall was repaired, and still hosts community events today

2331.title: "Post Office Bell" 2008
2331.summary: Dr Anton Hasell created the bell.  Hassells "'Little Sister Bell" is suspended in the centre and chimes on the hour.  Atop sits the historic 1880's Horsham Post office bell and a corella figurine.

2332.title: Jubilee Hall / Horsham Regional Art Gallery
2332.summary: Jubilee Hall was opened in June 1924, the jubilee year of the Methodist Church next door.

2333.title: Wesley Performing Arts Centre
2333.summary: Formerly the original Horsham Methodist Church (opened in 1912).  Inside still today is the original pipe organ; the diapered designs on the display pipes are outstanding.

osm.name: Wesley Performing Arts Centre
osm.display_name: Wesley Performing Arts Centre, Urquhart Street, Horsham, Rural City of Horsham, Victoria, 3400, Australia

2334.title: St Michaels and St Johns Church
2334.summary: Built in 1987; the award winning design is the work of distinguished and internationally renowned Australian architect Greg Burgess

2335.title: St Andrews Uniting Church 1962
2335.summary: Designed by architect Keith Reed.  Much of the original stone from the old church was used in constructing the new building.  The stone was quarried from McKenzie Creek

2336.title: Horsham Theatre
2336.summary: An outstanding example of the work of Bohringer, Taylor and Johnson, one of the most important and prolific cinema architectural firms in Australia

2337.title: 'Platanus acerifolia: Woven Nest' 2009
2337.summary: This environmental work by Michael Shiell was installed as part of 2009 "Art is...Elemental" Festival.

2338.title: Original Horsham Letterbox
2338.summary: This original Horsham Letterbox inspired the design of the Post Office Bell sculpture in Firebrace Street.

2339.title: Horsham Town Hall / Horsham Regional Art Gallery
2339.summary: Built in 1938/39 as a municipal complex and was designed by Melbourne architect Charles Neville Hollinshed, who also designed Her Majesty's Theatre in Melbourne

2340.title: Roof Top Ribbon 1998
2340.summary: During the 'Art is....Energy' Festival in 1998, New Zealand sculptor Jeff Thomson, "the undisputed Iron Man of Australasia", was commissioned to create a sculpture.

2341.title: Boer War - Avenue of Honour & 'Roberts' Tree 1901
2341.summary: The only avenue to commemorate the Anglo-Boer war was planted in Horsham in 1901.  The remaining elm  of the original Avenue was planted to commemorate Field Marshall Lord Roberts.

2342.title: Totem Pole 2000
2342.summary: Angie Polglaze was commissioned by the 'Art Is... A River of Time' Festival in 2000, to create this piece of Chainsaw Art.  It was carved publically and noisily during the festival.

2343.title: "Wimmera River Burnt Creek Meeting Place" 2007
2343.summary: The sculpture takes the form of a seating arrangement.  The work uses stone mosaic to depict the intersection of the Wimmera River and Burnt Creek as a meeting place of the 5 traditional owner groups.

2344.title: Painted Tiles 1997
2344.summary: Images on the tiles reference chnages in Horsham city life through the seasons.  The pictures are the children's individual reflections on their culture and environment.

2345.title: Bradbury Lane Mural 2008
2345.summary: Local visual artist Nichola Clarke worked with youth groups from the area to create the Bradbury Lane Mural.  The inspiration for participants was to paint their idea of a future Horsham.

2346.title: "Aerial" 2009
2346.summary: The metal sculptural mural "Aerial" depicts aspects of the Wimmera's unique landscape; a ravens eye view of the area made in conjunction with students of McKenzie  Creek campus of Horsham College.

2347.title: St John's Anglican Church 1957
2347.summary: Features an expansive wooden ceiling, various stained glass windows and two significant sculptures.  'Wayside Calvary' and 'Compassionate Christ'

2348.title: That view!
2348.summary: When you reach the top of the hill, make sure you spin around and take in the view. Look over the new estate and see the beautiful hills in the background.

2349.title: Fishing Lagoon
2349.summary: This beautiful lagoon, surrounded by reeds is the perfect place to stop and try your hand at fishing. Shaded by beautiful trees, the picnic area is also a good place to stop for lunch.

2426.title: The start
2426.summary: Start near the 'Princes Walk' sign in between Federation Square and Princess Bridge and walk down the path to the river.

2427.title: Path to Birrarung Marr
2427.summary: Walk down to Birrarung Marr and you soon leave the traffic sounds behind.

2428.title: View of the Yarra
2428.summary: Looking across the Yarra river to the Boathouses. If you walk in the morning or evening you will usually see rowers on the water.

2429.title: Angel
2429.summary: An iconic Melbourne Sculpture by Deborah Halpern.

2430.title: The shady path to the bridge
2430.summary: The wide shady  path is gravel for the first few hundred metres before it becomes paved near Batman Avenue. There are some toilets on the left hand side.

2431.title: Looking up the river
2431.summary: This magnificent view may help you ignore the traffic on the bridge.

2432.title: High and low path
2432.summary: Once off the bridge, you can choose the higher more shady or lower path near the waters edge.

2433.title: The steps
2433.summary: There are two sets of steps nearby. Why not go up an down them a few times to get the blood pumping!

2434.title: The high path
2434.summary: More shade on the high path and a better view across the river.

2435.title: Left before the Bridge
2435.summary: Turn left before the bridge back up to St Kilda Rd (or continue on to Southbank and cross the river at the footbridge back to Flinders St Station).

2436.title: Princess Bridge
2436.summary: Cross Princess Bridge and you are back at the start, and should feel fresh and reinvigorated!

2437.title: Foster Information Centre
2437.summary: Marvel at our local talent in Stockyard Gallery or catch up with your facebook friends with free wi-fi in the Library. Community and tourist information available 7 days a week.

2438.title: Pearl Park
2438.summary: Enjoy Harry the Miner's view of the vegetable and flower gardens or put a snag on the free bbq.

2439.title: Stockyard Creek
2439.summary: The first alluvial gold was found in the Creek in 1870.  Can you spot a platypus - about as elusive as the gold!

2440.summary: Between the South Gippsland Water Board and the Scout Hall, we dare you to dangle your skateboard over the precipice.
