2442.summary: Wrap your arms around this ol' timer.

2443.title: Foster Adventure Playground
2443.summary: Swing like a possum or climb like a koala over this large adventure playground for all ages.  Situated in the Foster Showgrounds. Public toilets available.

2444.title: Ambulance Station playground
2444.summary: Through the Tassie Tiger gate, a fire truck and ambulance are just waiting to be revved by young drivers.

2445.title: Op shops
2445.summary: There are a few op shops along this road, all with bargains to be discovered.

2446.title: Secret creek
2446.summary: This creek is quite hidden!  Don't quite know where it goes but is probably connected with the lake.

2447.title: Blackburn Lake Sanctuary
2447.summary: A beautiful lake, often with different types of birds and surrounded by a small pocket of forest.  Particularly atmospheric on foggy mornings as the mist rises from the lake.

osm.name: Blackburn Lake Sanctuary
osm.display_name: Blackburn Lake Sanctuary, Blackburn, Melbourne, City of Whitehorse, Victoria, Australia

2448.title: Whitehorse Heritage Trail
2448.summary: There are a few signs marking the trail, but I'm not sure where the Trail starts or ends!

2449.title: Playground
2449.summary: Playground recently given a bright red coat of paint.  Now it really stands out and gets the kids going.

2450.title: The Pines Senior Citizens Centre
2450.summary: I've walked past and seen dancing classes and morning tea on offer. What else do they get up to here?

osm.name: The Pines Senior Citizens Centre
osm.display_name: The Pines Senior Citizens Centre, Central Road, Blackburn, Melbourne, City of Whitehorse, Victoria, 3130, Australia

2451.title: War memorial and tennis courts
2451.summary: War memorial and local tennis courts in the background.  A pretty garden and lots of places to sit and watch what's going on.

2452.title: Blackburn library
2452.summary: Lovely library with benches and mural.

osm.name: Blackburn Library
osm.display_name: Blackburn Library, Box Hill to Ringwood Trail, Blackburn, Melbourne, City of Whitehorse, Victoria, 3130, Australia

2453.title: French cake shop
2453.summary: This French cake shop has some amazing cakes!  I once saw a queue all the way outside around Easter time.

2454.title: Op Shop
2454.summary: Bargains galore!  Great shops around this area too, including bakery, cafe, art shop, hairdressers and more.

2455.title: Rotary Saturday market
2455.summary: There's a little market outside Blackburn station every second Saturday of the month.  Fresh fruit and veg, craft, plants and other bits and pieces.

2456.title: Playground
2456.summary: Playground outside Blackburn station, a good spot for kids if you're waiting for the bus or next train.

2457.title: View of Thompson River
2457.summary:
There is a great view of the Thompson 
River and the new Pearson Crossing Bridge to your right.

2458.title: Revegetation of the Sanctuary
2458.summary: Indigenous tree planting has been completed by local primary school children and Wellington Shire Council staff.

2459.title: Superb Fairywren
2459.summary: The Superb Fairywren feasts on insects. The males are bright blue while female are brown.

2460.title: Eastern Yellow robin
2460.summary: The Eastern Yellow Robin is a common resident of Herb Guyatt Sanctuary which hunts insects.

2461.title: Azure Kingfisher
2461.summary: The Azure Kingfisher eats small fish and yabbies. You may see it as it darts between trees.

2462.title: Lush Forest
2462.summary: As you leave Mirboo North, you pass over some massive embankments and travel through a mix of remnant temperate rainforest and dry schlerophyll forest.

2463.title: The Darlimurla Station & Picnic Rotunda
2463.summary: A great place to stop to learn more about the rail trail through interpretative signage as well as finding remnants of the brick kiln used to create numerous culverts along the line.

2464.title: Cartwrights Bridge
2464.summary: A spectacular crossing over the wetlands of the Little Morwell River might entice you to take a break at the picnic table to watch out for an abundance of birdlife.

2465.title: Post-fire forest regeneration
2465.summary: This part of the trail has rebounded magnificently from the damage caused by the 2009 bushfires.

2466.title: Cows in the reeds
2466.summary: Signs of farming appear along the trail, especially when you come across a herd of cows munching on the tasty greens of the wetland reeds.

2467.title: The Rolling Hills
2467.summary: The Strezlecki Mountains became known by European settlers as “The Heartbreak Hills" due to the difficulty of eking a living from the steep, thickly forested, often sodden and remote country.

2468.title: Daisies in the meadow
2468.summary: Close to Boolarra is a lovely stretch of meadow, filled with wild flowers and swathes of daisies.

2469.title: Welcome to Boolarra
2469.summary: The old pylons of the railway are used as an archway as you enter Railway Park. As you approach, look for the interesting and historically significant brick drainage culverts under the trail.

2470.title: Playground
2470.summary: Start from the play ground south of Heidelberg round and east of Westfied reserve. Walk West along the asphalt path  avoiding left turns down the hill.

2471.title: Turn right here
2471.summary: Turn right just after the oval onto a concrete path (POI 2) between the oval and building. Cross Yarra Bend Road (a very small road) and follow the path south along Merri Creek.

2472.title: Viewing platform
2472.summary: A nice spot to stop for a picnic or to enjoy the view.

2473.title: Path towards the city
2473.summary: This (POI 3) is my preferred path into the city.  You can then take Roseneath Street West which is quite pleasant.

2474.title: Bridge over the highway
2474.summary: The second option (POI 4) appears preferable - you don't have to cross Alexander Pde, and you spend more time on park, but can be jarring once you reach Hoddle Street.

2475.title: The Rushes
2475.summary: Simply gorgeous parkland full of native plants and grasses. It also has an outdoor gym. Stop here to listen to the sound of twittering birds. Very relaxing!

2476.title: Bottle brushes
2476.summary: Bianca Boulevard's median strip is planted with flowering bottle brushes, which when in bloom, look spectacular.

2477.title: The Ruins - Davis Park Heritage Area
2477.summary: Here lie the remains of a blue stone cottage built by the Davis family in the 1850s. There used to be a cellar, dairy, irrigation channels, wells and more.  See boards for more information.

2478.title: Orchard
2478.summary: Look closely and you'll find various fruiting trees, including lemon, apple and olives. The park also has a cricket pitch outdoor gym, BBQ, seats and shelter.

2479.title: Moorookyle Avenue Park
2479.summary: This park has lots of seats and a fabulous playground. It's right next to the Moorookyle Country Club though entry is limited to Moorooklye Estate residents only.

osm.name: Moorookyle Avenue Park
osm.display_name: Moorookyle Avenue Park, Moorookyle, Tarneit, Melbourne, City of Wyndham, Victoria, 3029, Australia

2480.title: Davis Family Park
2480.summary: This park has a variety of features for outdoor recreation - ovals, basketball, playground, outdoor gym and climbing frame.

osm.name: Edmund Drive Park
osm.display_name: Edmund Drive Park, Moorookyle, Tarneit, Melbourne, City of Wyndham, Victoria, 3029, Australia

2481.title: Birds of paradise
2481.summary: Davis Family Park has fabulous plants that are colourful and unusual.

2482.title: Map of Rowville in 1981
2482.summary: The Knox Historical Society have included a map of the Rowville area from 1981. For more information on the History of Knox see the link below.

2483.title: Emerson Place Reserve
2483.summary: The walk begins at Emerson Place Reserve across the road from the Wellington Village Shopping Centre.

2484.title: Emerson Place Reserve Playground
2484.summary: Enjoy time with family at the Emerson Place Reserve Playground. Knox Council has  over 200 play spaces in parks and reserves.

2485.title: Outdoor Gym
2485.summary: The first outdoor gym in the City of Knox is now ready for everyone to use, for free! The outdoor gym consists of four separate stations in an easily accessible circuit. See website below for details.

2486.title: Liberty Avenue Reserve shared path
2486.summary: Follow the shared path toward Liberty Avenue Reserve. Knox has more than 100kms of shared paths that connect with major parks, reserves, schools and shopping precincts.

2487.title: Outdoor Gym
2487.summary: The next outdoor gym station at Jackie Close Reserve features a body dip station and two sit up benches.

2488.title: Outdoor Gym
2488.summary: The next outdoor gym station at Liberty Avenue near Magdalena Place consists of step ups, pull ups, leg raises and a stretch station.

2489.title: Outdoor Gym
2489.summary: The Liberty Avenue outdoor gym consists of a body twist, multi bars, eliptical trainer and leg press. It also features a set of instuctions on how to use the equipment.

2490.title: Liberty Avenue Reserve Playground
2490.summary: Enjoy time with family at the Liberty Avenue Reserve Playground.

2491.title: Liberty Avenue tennis and basketball courts
2491.summary: Enjoy a game of tennis or basketball at the public courts located at Liberty Avenue Reserve. Knox City Council provides a wide range of leisure and recreation facilities and programs.

2492.title: Track sign and No. 5 Brace
2492.summary: The building in the distance was a sorting plant for the coal, operating from 1909 to 1968. For hundreds of 14 year old boys this was their first place of work as they picked stones out of the coal.

2493.title: Pioneer Mines Area
2493.summary: This is where it all began. Mining commenced in 1909, producing 780,000 tons before closing in 1914. Underground workings were very shallow, evident by the depressions in this area.

2494.title: Overgrown path
2494.summary: Keep a lookout for this sign post. The red arrow points right, so take this short but narrow and overgrown path.

2495.title: Fallen tree branch
2495.summary: You may encounter a natural obstacle on this track as it takes you into the heart of the heathland.

2496.title: Western Area Haulage Line
2496.summary: A 3km rail track where skips were hauled overland by cable. Have a look for the cable on the ground. Pine trees line both sides of the track.

2497.title: Baxters Beach track
2497.summary: After you cross the road there is an option to walk to Baxters Beach. The red track to Baxters Wetland is clearly signed and heads to the right.

2498.title: Nos. 9 and 10 shafts
2498.summary: Together these mines covered an area of almost 200 hectares. Thats 160 underground cricket grounds! The coal has gone but this concrete shaft remains.

2499.title: Baxters Wetland and bird hide
2499.summary: Nesting boxes and permanent water make this a perfect home for many birds and water fowl. Watch out for Pacific Black Ducks, Purple Swamphens and White-faced Herons.

2500.title: Campbell Street track entrance
2500.summary: Leave the street and follow this gravel track back into the heathland. On the right is the Cinder Loop track which formed part of a horse drawn tramway used for transporting bricks.

2501.title: Tent Town
2501.summary: The site where 12 miners first lived when the State Coal Mine opened in 1909. By mid 1910 the township of Wonthaggi was established with the construction of 100 miners' cottages.

2502.title: Amazing large mural by Smug, 2016
2502.summary: This is a massive and striking piece of art by artist Smug, of his own grandparents.

2503.title: Uniacke Court - Art by Deb
2503.summary: Some great pieces of art by Deb, a Melbourne artist now working in te US. Some of these are from at least 2010, but still look fresh.

2504.title: Dosa Corner - Indian restaurant
2504.summary: As the name suggests, this place specialise in Dosa - thin, crispy pancakes served with a filling and a selection of tasty sauces to be mopped up. I can't go past a Masala Dosa - spicy potato filled.

2505.title: Flagstaff Gardens
2505.summary: Melbourne's oldest park and a beautiful open space. So named as it was the site of a flagstaff erected in 1840 to allow the city to communicate with the port.

osm.name: Flagstaff Gardens
osm.display_name: Flagstaff Gardens, West Melbourne, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3003, Australia

2506.title: Nomads back bar

2507.title: Muleta's cafe alleyway
2507.summary: Another MOS site, this back alley is overflowing with brightly coloured and fun pieces of art, including some great paste up work.

2508.title: Blender Lane artists studio
2508.summary: A studio, hosting some of Melbourne's most up and coming and established artists , this lane is forever being added to and evolving. An excellent spot for stencil art.

2536.summary: A very nice distant outlook from the top of the hill. A lot can be seen from here. It's 137 meters above sea level- the highest point in Melbourne's metro area.

2537.title: Lake
2537.summary: This lake (or pond) had many ducks swimming in it. The bench there was great for sitting down, relaxing, and seeing the ducks.

2538.title: Electric towers

2541.summary: Right next to the information hut and sign posts is a playground, giant chess board and picnic tables.

2545.title: Track markers

2546.title: Natures colours
2546.summary: The colors of nature change with the seasons.

2547.title: Secret falls

2548.title: Mini falls

2549.title: Hazard

2551.title: Alpine Bog track

2552.title: Zig- Zac down the mountain

2554.title: Charmichael Falls
2554.summary: As seen from the viewing platform.

2555.title: Tree tops view
2555.summary: From the viewing platform you can see for miles over the undulating mountains and tree tops.

2556.title: Alpine Bog Reserve

2557.summary: There are several ways to access these wetlands, best to jump in and start exploring.

2558.title: Keep your eyes open
2558.summary: Even a bird this small can catch your attention! This fella was chatty and chirpy, posing for a photograph.

2559.title: Pencil Park playground
2559.summary: Look out for the towering pencils in different colours. The playground nearby is great fun too.

2560.title: Covered BBQ facilities
2560.summary: With the playground nearby and so many walking paths on the horizon, this is a handy spot to have a picnic or bbq and let the little ones play.

2561.title: Keysborough Golf Club
2561.summary: Walk along the south perimeter of the parklands, you'll spot the lush greens that belong to Keysborough Golf Club. Follow this path along until you reach the start of the next wetland area.

2562.title: Tatterson Park wetlands
2562.summary: As you wander through the Tatterson Park wetlands, envious of the homes on either side, look for other homes of the watery variety. A family of black swans have taken up residence here.

2563.title: Chirpy residents
2563.summary: As you walk, see if you can spot some of the native birds in the area. Black swans are easier to see than some of the smaller varieties. While others are louder than most!

2564.title: Blue sky view
2564.summary: A footbridge in the centre of the park offers a sweeping view of the wetlands.

2565.title: Springers Leisure Centre
2565.summary: This is the perfect spot for an air-conditioned rest, a cuppa and snack. You might even shoot some hoops while you're here!

osm.name: Springers Leisure Centre
osm.display_name: Springers Leisure Centre, Lake Edge Drive, Keysborough, Melbourne, City of Greater Dandenong, Victoria, 3173, Australia

2566.title: Beautiful walking trails
2566.summary: Be sure to wear a hat on sunny days. While there are trees closer to the woodland area, it's pretty steamy in full sun along the wetlands walking track.

2567.title: Tatterson Park Community Sporting Complex
2567.summary: You can't see it right now, but if you look south to the two ovals in the distance, that's where a brand new sporting complex is set to be built in 2016. Stay tuned!

2568.title: World of Insects
2568.summary: Quite possibly the cutest playground in the world, this one features ladybugs, ants, beehives and a giant magnifying glass! The design was chosen by the community and has an environmental theme.

2569.title: Arachnophobes beware...
2569.summary: Just joking. These spiders are for climbing on! Bugs too. Another aspect of the World of Insects playground in Tattersons Park. Not everything's cute it seems.

2570.title: 20-hectare woodlands
2570.summary: Maurie Jarvis Woodland is named after a councilor and three-time local mayor who had a passion for native trees and their preservation. More than 20,000 indigenous trees were planted here in 2005.

2571.title: Transition into wetlands
2571.summary: It's here on the edge of the woodlands that the wetlands begin. A stunning transition.

2572.title: One of many playgrounds
2572.summary: This playground is closest to Lake View Boulevard. There's a big tree nearby and a duck colony too.

2573.title: Distinctly different wetland
2573.summary: Cafardi Boulevard offers a different style of wetlands, at first, as it moves away from the rich woodland of Tatterson Park. Follow the street to reach Hidden Grove.

2574.title: Dunolly Town Hall

2576.title: Original streetscape showing Coach Office and Billiards buildings
2576.summary: Original streetscape showing Coach Office and Billiards buildings and part of TP Daly General Merchant.

2578.title: London Chartered Bank
2578.summary: ‘The Welcome Stranger’ nugget was brought to Dunolly to be sold at the London Chartered Bank in Broadway. The building is now a private residence.

2579.title: McBrides Ironmonger
2579.summary: The two-storey ironmongery shop and dwelling was built in 1863 by Peter and Catherine McBride, who came to Dunolly from Scotland in 1857.

2580.title: Footers Mansion 1865

2582.summary: A very grand building that is now used as an op shop.

2583.title: Belleville 1869
2583.summary: Owned by politician James Bell and designed by a local store keeper, Thomas Tyrer.

2584.title: Original Dunolly Town Hall 1862
2584.summary: The town hall was complete with a public library and reading room, as well as council chamber and offices.

2585.title: Lock Up 1863
2585.summary: The Lock Up was built as one of the police and court buildings on the government and legal precinct on Market Street. It was used until the Dunolly Court closed in 1981.

2586.title: Police Station 1958
2586.summary: This is an example of a typical 1950s standard rural area police station.

2587.title: Land Titles Office
2587.summary: It was also a Postal and Telegraph Office 1872-91

2589.title: First Court House, County Court 1858
2589.summary: The former County Court House was constructed of coursed bluestone by James Nichols. It is now a Masonic Temple.

2591.title: Noisy Miner
2591.summary: Not to be confused with the Common Myna, the native Noisy Miners assist each other to raise their young.  They form large groups and actively defend their territory.

2592.title: Heathlands
2592.summary: The last section of the walk winds along the edge of beautiful native heathland that supports a wide variety of fauna. A large section of heathland is fenced off for conservation.

2593.title: Wooden Sculptures
2593.summary: Just as you set out on the walk you will pass by two beautiful new sculptures of native fauna.

2594.title: The track
2594.summary: The track is very level and well maintained throughout.  Just make sure you have brought a hat for sunny days.

2595.title: The Bird Hide
2595.summary: The bird hide gives you the opportunity to watch birdlife undisturbed in their natural habitat. An information board contains pictures and names of all the bird species you might see.

2596.title: Great Egret
2596.summary: There is a lot of birdlife living among the wetlands including the Great Egret (pictured), Australian Wood Ducks, Black Swans, Pelicans and many more.

2597.title: Shared path
2597.summary: You might meet the occasional cyclist traversing through the park at a very relaxed pace.

2598.title: Salinity and Trees
2598.summary: When salty groundwater comes to the surface it can be too much for some trees as this group demonstrates.  Rangers and volunteers are planting thousands of trees to keep the groundwater low.

2599.title: Kangaroo Apple
2599.summary: The Kangaroo Apple adds a wonderful splash of colour to the park when in bloom.  The fruits were eaten by Aboriginal people, but only when very ripe, as they are poisonous at other times.

2600.title: Echidna
2600.summary: If you hear a rustle in the grass it might be an Echidna out looking for lunch.  But if he hears you he will quickly try to hide.  If you see one, please keep your distance, they are very shy.

2628.summary: This book inspired sculpture is the footpath in front of Springvale Rise Primary School, I am sure it is encouraging the kids to read more!

2631.title: Silky Oak and Firewheel Tree
