2683.summary: There are a few tracks here that can also lead you to other ways around the park, but stick to the main track if you are in a wheelchair please.

2686.title: BBQ and Picnic Area
2686.summary: There is a few BBQs and picnic table under shady tree lined areas where you park the cars. There are bins and water is available here.

2687.title: Under Cover Picnice Area
2687.summary: A large picnic area is under cover and can be used in poor or wet weather

2688.title: Knobby Club Rush
2688.summary: Very hardy and successful near coasts.  It helps to bind sandy soil, is also good for getting rid of polluted water.  Aboriginal people used this in combination with sedges for weaving.

2689.title: Seat on the coast
2689.summary: As soon as you reach the beach there is a seat where you can rest for a moment.  You might spot a dolphin or banjo shark if the water is calm.

2690.title: Beach walk
2690.summary: If the tide is out you can return to Beach road via the beach.

2691.title: Dog Whelk and Cockle Shells
2691.summary: Shells can tell some interesting stories. Dog whelk (right) drill holes into cockles through their shell and then into their flesh. The flesh weakens from pressure, the shell opens. Dinner time.

2692.title: Start of the walk
2692.summary: At the start of the walk there is a very good information board giving details about the walk.

2693.title: Picnic Bench
2693.summary: Just inside the gate there is a picnic bench in a lovely setting.  A good spot for lunch when you return.

2694.title: Coastal Woodland
2694.summary: This is the last remaining section of coastal woodland on the Bellarine Peninsula.  There is a vast array of indigenous plants along the way.

2695.title: Gnarled Tree
2695.summary: This particular tree cannot be missed on the walk.  It tells the story of a hard and windswept life.

2696.title: Beetle crossing
2696.summary: Watch your step as you walk along the path.  You might encounter very interesting insects braving the open plains of the pathway to find food on the other side.

2697.title: Bench
2697.summary: A bench immersed in local flora, where you can sit and take time to spot some of the abundant wildlife that this coastal woodland supports.

2698.title: Small Leaf Clemitis
2698.summary: From July to November you will see cream, star-shaped flowers in abundance.  Male and female flowers are borne on separate plants.  The Aborigines cooked and kneaded the tap root to make dough.

2699.title: Marshes
2699.summary: Great views of water filled marches great the walker when you leave the coastal woodland.

2700.title: Pelicans
2700.summary: Look up!  Pelicans normally fish together.  They herd fish into a central position, and then plunge their bills into the water to capture a fish.

2701.title: The boardwalk
2701.summary: This fabulous boardwalk allows the walker to explore life in and around the lagoons.

2702.title: Beaded Glasswort
2702.summary: Beaded glasswort is abundant around the boardwalk. Their seeds are a major winter food source for the very rare Orange-bellied Parrots who migrate to Swan Bay from Tasmania each winter.

2703.title: Grasses and sedges
2703.summary: Grass skinks and tiny birds shelter and forage among grasses and sedges.  Butterflies lay eggs on sedges, a food source for their caterpillars.

2704.title: The Grand Hotel
2704.summary: Originally the Grand Hotel was known as the Coffee Palace.  The change of name to the Grand Hotel occurred in 1920. Head inside to see historic pictures. See walk description for more.

osm.name: The Grand Hotel
osm.display_name: The Grand Hotel, Langtree Avenue, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

2705.title: Feast Street
2705.summary: Mildura’s iconic restaurants, The new Spanish Bar and Grill, Seasons and Stefano Cellar's.  This end of Langtree Avenue is fondly known as Feast Street.

2706.title: The Mildura Brewery
2706.summary: Mildura Brewery is the original site of the ‘hard top’ Wonderland, a wintertime cinema. Its name was changed to the Astor in the 1920’s and recent renovations have preserved parts of the old cinema

2707.title: T&G building
2707.summary: The T&G building on the corner of Eighth and Langtree has a distinctive clock tower. In the 1920’s it was the site of the Zimmers Building.

osm.name: T&G Building
osm.display_name: T&G Building, Eighth Street, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

2708.title: Hudaks Bakery
2708.summary: Mildura’s bakery institution, Hudaks. It started life as Bowrings Buildings. The lane behind the building is still named Bowrings Lane.

2709.title: Shillidays Corner
2709.summary: Site of Mildura’s old department store Shillidays.  Shillidays ceased operation in the 1980’s. A short walk down from Shillidays Corner is the store Doug Haynes. It was the site of Mildura’s Bakehouse

2710.title: The Ozone
2710.summary: Where Rockmans is now located, was the site of yet another cinema, the Ozone. It closed in 1971, choosing the film ‘Ryan’s Daughter’ to say goodbye with.

2711.title: Banjo’s Bakery
2711.summary: Banjo’s Bakery was once the surgery of Mildura’s first resident dentist, Claude Sutton. Mr. Sutton practiced here for 50 years.

osm.name: Banjo's Bakery Cafe
osm.display_name: Banjo's Bakery Cafe, Langtree Mall, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

2712.title: Dr. Abramowski’s Chemist
2712.summary: Where the Bendigo Bank stands was once the site of Dr. Abramowski’s Chemist, similarly to Mr. Sutton, he was the first physician in the town and he gained an impressive reputation.

2713.title: Mildura Fire Station
2713.summary: On the left, 89 Langtree Avenue marks where the Mildura Fire Station stood from early in the 20th century until 1980, currently Tristar Medical Centre

2714.title: St. Andrews Church
2714.summary: Across 11th and left towards Deakin Ave is the Uniting Church, known as St Andrew’s. It started out as a Presbyterian church and was built in 1914, at a cost of 2097 pounds.

2715.title: Mildura Public Offices
2715.summary: Across 11th Street are the Mildura Public Offices.

2716.title: Sacred Heart Peace Memorial Roman Catholic Church.
2716.summary: Across 11th St is the  Catholic Church.  In 1896, a wooden structure was built in Pine Ave & in 1924 that building was relocated to this site. In 1921 the original brick church was built.

2717.title: Catholic Church and Presbytery
2717.summary: The neighbouring presbytery was erected in 1935. A walk inside the church is welcomed and the 14 Stations of the Cross, fine timberwork and stained glass are worth closer inspection.

2718.title: Lime Ave
2718.summary: Lime Ave was once a primarily residential street but is now an extension of the commercial centre. Places such as the Ballerina Ballroom, a popular dance spot in the 60’s are long gone.

osm.name: Lime Avenue
osm.display_name: Lime Avenue, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

2719.title: Nash Building
2719.summary: The Nash Building, named for G.A Nash, the original occupier of the building. Th building was completed in 1917, however the Nash Backery and Grocery business dates back to 1888.

osm.name: Nash's Building
osm.display_name: Nash's Building, Shillidays Lane, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

2720.title: Telephone Exchange
2720.summary: Opposite the Mildura Brewery is the Telephone Exchange. In 1910 it was the site of Wonderland, an open air cinema.  Entry was 1 shilling for adults, 1/2 for children and 2 shillings to reserve a chair

2721.title: The Rotary Children's Park
2721.summary: A nice open play area, with a miniature train track (runs seasonally check beforehand if it's running).

2722.title: Notice board
2722.summary: Some good information about the Port Phillip Heads Marine National Park - it's history, local inhabitants and aquaculture.

2723.title: Memorial Cairn
2723.summary: In 1989 a 16 year old boy was drowned trying to save his brother.

2724.title: Official start of Rambler's Walk
2724.summary: Watch out for fellow bike riders. If you're bringing your pooch, please keep your dog on a lead.

2725.title: Native trees and bushes
2725.summary: The scenery is very pleasant along Rambler's Walk. There are various indigenous plants to admire along the way.

2726.title: Fisherman's cottages to modern mansions
2726.summary: Portarlington used to be a small seaside town. There are now many enormous houses as a result of more recent developments.

2727.title: More trees and bushes
2727.summary: Some well established tall trees have been planted by residents.

2728.title: Rest stop
2728.summary: There are several benches on this walking track. Take your pick from one of these two charming blue seats and gaze out to the You Yangs and beyond.

2730.title: A small lagoon
2730.summary: These areas provide protection from strong coastal winds for birds. You might see seagulls, pelicans, cormorants or ducks. These areas are at risk of inundation with storm surges and rising sea levels

2731.title: Olive grove on the hill behind the town
2731.summary: Look to the south, between the houses and over to the hill for our local olive grove!

2732.title: Federation Square
2732.summary: Home to major cultural attractions, world-class events and an exceptional array of restaurants, bars and specialty stores, this modern piazza, opened in 2002, has become the citys meeting place.

2733.title: Bourke and Wills Statue
2733.summary: Designed by Charles Summers, costing ₤14,000, the statue was unveiled on 21 April 1865, four years after the fateful expedition. It has had many city locations and was installed here in 1994.

2734.title: Melbourne's Laneways
2734.summary: Al fresco eateries, one-off shops and cosy litte bars, nestle side-by-side in laneways threading through the city. Each arcade has its own individual character and charm - choose your own adventure.

2735.title: Southbank Promenade
2735.summary: With splendid city views this path stretches along the south side of the Yarra River from the Southgate shopping and dining complex to the glittering Crown Casino.

osm.name: Southbank Promenade
osm.display_name: Southbank Promenade, Southbank, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3006, Australia

2736.title: South Wharf Promenade
2736.summary: Situated in and around lovingly restored heritage cargo sheds on the edge of the Yarra River, this location brings together some of Melbourne's best food and beverage operators.

osm.name: South Wharf Promenade
osm.display_name: South Wharf Promenade, South Wharf, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3006, Australia

2737.title: Webb Bridge (2003)
2737.summary:
This sculptural bridge was the result of an art competition to transform a disused cargo link into an integrated artwork that could function as a pedestrian
and cyclist bridge.A great photo spot too.

osm.name: Webb Bridge
osm.display_name: Webb Bridge, Yarra’s Edge, Docklands, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3008, Australia

2738.title: Victoria Harbour
2738.summary: Home to the Cow Up A Tree sculpture this location gives visitors an insight into the water activity of Docklands. From morning, rowing crews to charter vessels there is always something happening.

osm.name: Victoria Harbour
osm.display_name: Victoria Harbour, Docklands, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3008, Australia

2739.title: NewQuay
2739.summary: Home to restaurants and cafes with cuisine from all over the world. Choose from a relaxed snack or a la carte dining. Enjoy the view across Victoria Harbour as you stroll the promenade.

osm.name: NewQuay
osm.display_name: NewQuay, Docklands, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3008, Australia

2740.title: Life can be a picnic
2740.summary: Surrounded by Mountain Grey Gums, enjoy the well-kept picnic facilities in this delightful Park.

2741.title: Home in the hollow
2741.summary: Birds such as Rosellas and mammals (including the Brush-tailed Possum) make their nests in the hollows.

2742.title: Bountiful birdlife
2742.summary: This Fantail is just one of many bird species you’ll spot, such as Honey-eaters, Eastern Spinebills and White-throated Tree-creepers.

2743.title: Take a seat
2743.summary: Spend a little time on one of the many seats you’ll find along the track and you should see and hear some of the Park’s rich wildlife.

2744.title: A wealth of orchids
2744.summary: Home to over 43 species of native orchids, such as sun orchids, the flowers are simply superb.

2745.title: Land of the Lyrebird
2745.summary: You have now entered the habitat of the superb Lyrebird. The male is renowned for its varied and powerful song – including the mimicry of other bird songs.

2746.title: The walking track
2746.summary: A rich canopy of tall trees provides shade, and the track is well-maintained so you don’t need to worry about having to clamber over logs on your walk.

2747.title: A diverse forest
2747.summary: There aren’t many stands of remnant forest remaining in the region, but here you will come across a diverse mix that includes beautiful old eucalypts.

2748.title: Spot the koala
2748.summary: The well-loved Koala is common in this section of the track, and can be seen taking a nap in the tree branches during the day.

2749.title: PepperTree Place
2749.summary: This is a beautiful community garden full of edible delights. The Monthly Edibles Swap, Cafe Cooperative and nursery are open on the first Sat each month 10 -12pm; the nursery on Weds from 10 -3pm.

2750.title: Pentridge Prison
2750.summary: The imposing bluestone walls are a reminder of the prison, now converted into a residential development. Take a walk through the area to get a glimpse of its past. Click link for detailed description.

osm.name: Pentridge Prison Main Gate
osm.display_name: Pentridge Prison Main Gate, Champ Street, Coburg, Melbourne, City of Merri-bek, Victoria, 3058, Australia

2751.title: Pentridge Village - old and new
2751.summary: An interesting contrast of colours. The brightly painted new houses and units are the complete opposite to the heavy and sombre blue stones of the former prison.

2752.title: Rocketship
2752.summary: There are 3 playgrounds at Coburg Lake Reserve. This one features a rocketship with a fancy slide that kids would love. Endless hours of fun!

2753.title: Lookout platform
2753.summary: A lovely area to sit and look out to the lake. The wooden benches display some interesting etchings / graffiti messages from locals who have made their mark here.

2754.title: The Other Tea Party
2754.summary: This set of tables and chairs are perfect for an afternoon tea party. Nearby is a fantastic playground, complete with flying fox and super cool swings.

2755.title: Outdoor Gym
2755.summary: This outdoor gym is very popular. Try out these various contraptions and give yourself a little workout.

2756.title: Coburg Olympic Swimming Pool
2756.summary: A perfect place to chill out during hot days. Entry to the pool is from Murray Road. The pool is open from 1 Dec to 31 March. Photo courtesy of Moreland City Council.

2757.title: Yam Daisies (also known as Murnong and Native Dandelion)
2757.summary: Yam Daisies are an an edible Indigenous plant. They have been planted here by the Merri & Edgars Creek Confluence Area Restoration Group. Look for the cluster of plantings south of Murray Road.

2758.title: Hidden Creek Neighbourhood House - 20 Murray Road
2758.summary: A lovely mosaic welcomes you to the House. Tucked behind the shops, the House offers courses and activities such as craft making, computer classes, women's groups and much more.

2759.title: Merri Creek Market Garden
2759.summary: Come and see what's growing this season! This organic garden is managed by CERES and has a strong volunteer program and is used for horticultural training.

2760.title: Lake view
2760.summary: There is plenty of bird life on the lake. Swans, ducks, magpies are common. You might spot cormorants and swallows too. See link below for the type of birds that visit the lake.

2761.title: Trugo Court
2761.summary: Trugo is a game created by railway workers in the 1920s. In its heyday, Trugo clubs were found in many suburbs to the north and west of Melbourne. This one will be converted to a community garden.

2762.title: Fig Tree
2762.summary: Figs are plentiful during summer. It's great that these residents have left a bit of their tree overhanging to share with passers by, but please be respectful and don't take more than your fair share.

2763.title: Indigenous nature strip
2763.summary: Here's a great way to jazz up your nature strip and bring some birds and beauty to your street!

2764.title: Rubbish in the Merri Creek
2764.summary: Plastic bags, drink bottle and various bit of rubbish continue to pollute the Creek. A good reminder to always dispose of our litter thoughtfully as they end up in waterways and affect local wildlife.

2765.title: Picnic spot
2765.summary: From the carpark there is a small footbridge across the stream and then you find this great spot for a picnic.

2766.title: Climbing frame
2766.summary: Next to the picnic spot is a very large fallen tree, great for climbing by young (and not so young) kids.

2767.title: Picnic table and bridge
2767.summary: Where the road bridge crosses the creek, there's a picnic table and a pipe intake (maybe).  Pleasant enough, but the other picnic spot is better.  You can access the walk here on foot from Jones St.

2768.title: The little things
2768.summary: This photo is of a piece of bark on the trail. Always good to keep an eye out for the little things while walking.

2769.title: Little log
2769.summary: Some smaller fallen logs provide occasional distractions for the kids.

2770.title: The joy of ambling
2770.summary: The path is wide, the forest high.  All is well with the world.

2772.title: The forest
2772.summary: Look up and this is the sort of thing you will see.

2773.title: Ampheatre
2773.summary:
Carl Stomp ampitheatre Seat 120 people
One of five used for performances and functions.

2774.title: Nobelius Track
2774.summary: Marker for start of Nobelius Track

osm.name: Nobelius Track
osm.display_name: Nobelius Track, Emerald, Melbourne, Shire of Cardinia, Victoria, 3782, Australia

2776.title: Great train race track
2776.summary: Part of the Great train race fun run track.

2777.title: Nobelius Station
2777.summary: Unused station halfway between Belgrave and Gembrook.

2778.title: Playground
2778.summary: Children's playground also suitable for teenagers.

2779.title: Fitness centre
2779.summary: Outdoor gym consists of eight different work stations.

2780.title: Puffing Billy railway line
2780.summary: Railway line for Puffing Billy along side walking track.

2781.title: Great train race track
2781.summary: Another part of the Great train race track fun run track.

2782.title: Puffing Billy railway
2782.summary: Puffing Billy railway along side walking track.

2783.title: Flora Emerald park
2783.summary: Ferns and plants of Emerald Lake.

2784.title: Packing Shed
2784.summary: Historical site where Nobelius nursery dispatched plants by train.

osm.name: Nobelius Packing Shed
osm.display_name: Nobelius Packing Shed, Crichton Road, Emerald, Melbourne, Shire of Cardinia, Victoria, 3782, Australia

2785.title: Nobelius Siding
2785.summary: Located at the end of the walking track at the Packing shed.

osm.name: Nobelius Siding
osm.display_name: Nobelius Siding, Crichton Road, Emerald, Melbourne, Shire of Cardinia, Victoria, 3782, Australia

2786.title: Former Tea Rooms
2786.summary: Opened in 1919, the tea rooms were voluntarily staffed over the summer months to provide refreshments and entertainment to picnickers. The Tea Rooms are now used for exhibitions and events.

2787.title: The Summerhouse
2787.summary: Originally built in 1872, the reconstructed version was erected in 2000, after a successful fundraising effort by the Friends of Castlemaine Botanic Gardens.

2788.title: Playspace
2788.summary: Built in 2011, this unique play area features abundant locally sourced natural materials, and reflects the history of the area (eg. gold miner's hut). There's plenty to climb on and explore!

2789.title: Assortment of trees
2789.summary: There's a wide variety of native and exotic trees to marvel at.

2790.title: Bridge
2790.summary: You can cross this bridge to take a longer track around the western end of the gardens. It's also a good spot to listen to the local frogs.

2791.title: Lake Johanna
2791.summary: The perfect spot for bird watching (please don't feed them).

2792.title: Wisteria heaven
2792.summary: Come in spring time for an especially heavenly experience. The sight, smell and colour of wisteria is simply stunning.

2793.title: Fountain
2793.summary: What botanical gardens would be complete without a fountain? This was restored in 2011, and as you can imagine, is especially popular in the warmer months.

2794.title: Riverside Park
2794.summary: BBQs, multiple playgrounds, expansive lawns, basketball half court.

osm.name: Riverside Park
osm.display_name: Riverside Park, Swan Hill, Rural City of Swan Hill, Victoria, Australia

2795.title: Milloo St Parkland
2795.summary: Boat ramp, BBQs, River Red Gums.

2797.title: Medibank Icehouse
2797.summary: A world-class ice sports and entertainment venue, containing two Olympic sized ice rinks, stadium seating for 1000, specialist winter sports gym, cafe and bar. Open daily from 9am.

2798.title: Harbour Town Shopping Centre
2798.summary: Harbour Town Melbourne, includes over 120 outlets and 70 specialty stores. Open daily from 10am. Visit the onsite tourism lounge for special shopping offers and visitor information.

2799.title: Silence (2003)
2799.summary:
Sculptor Adrian Mauriks has
described this work on NewQuay as a series of forms arousing to the mind,
appealing to memory, reminding
you of natural things: clouds, a tree, a forest.

osm.name: Silence
osm.display_name: Silence, Newquay Promenade, Docklands, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3008, Australia

2800.title: NewQuay
2800.summary: Family friendly waterfront cafes and restaurants can be found along the promenade from simple and delicious take aways to dine-in options. Enjoy the views of Victoria Harbour while you dine.

osm.name: NewQuay
osm.display_name: NewQuay, Docklands, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3008, Australia

2801.title: Etihad Stadium
2801.summary: A multi-purpose venue which hosts as many as 85 sports and entertainment events every year - AFL, rugby, soccer and cricket, plus major performing artists such as U2, Bon Jovi and ACDC.

osm.name: Marvel Stadium
osm.display_name: Marvel Stadium, 740, Bourke Street, Yarra’s Edge, Docklands, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3008, Australia

2802.title: Victoria Harbour
2802.summary: Take the time to relax and enjoy the view of the entire Harbour from the public space along the waterfront. See the in-water artwork of Ari Purhonen: 'White Caps' (2012).

osm.name: Victoria Harbour
osm.display_name: Victoria Harbour, Docklands, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3008, Australia

2803.title: Docklands Park Playground
2803.summary: A combination of art and playground, it features a big circular ring with five swings, a tunnel and two metal slides, sandpit and two stand-on spinners. Free BBQs and picnic tables are on site.

2804.title: Webb Bridge (2003)
2804.summary:
This sculptural bridge was the result of an art competition to transform a disused cargo link into an integrated artwork that could function as a pedestrian
and cyclist bridge. A great photo spot too!

osm.name: Webb Bridge
osm.display_name: Webb Bridge, Yarra’s Edge, Docklands, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3008, Australia

2805.title: Point Park
2805.summary: Situated on Yarra's Edge, Point Park is a great place for the children to run free on the green grassy knolls.Equipped with picnic tables and free BBQs, this is a great location for a gathering.

osm.name: Point Park
osm.display_name: Point Park, Yarra’s Edge, Docklands, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3008, Australia

2806.title: Nowingi Place
2806.summary: Sing a song on the outdoor stage, have a swing in the playground or grab a drink from the water fountain.

osm.name: Nowingi Place
osm.display_name: Nowingi Place, Hugh King Drive, Mildura, Rural City of Mildura, Victoria, 3500, Australia

2807.title: Mildura Bridge
2807.summary: Get a great view of the George Chaffey Bridge.

2808.title: Mildura Wharf
2808.summary: The old wooden wharf is used on a daily basis by the local paddlesteamers.

2809.title: Mildura Skatepark
2809.summary: Watch the youth perform their tricks and spins.

2810.title: The Moreton Bay Fig Tree, Carlton Gardens
2810.summary:
Wurundjeri Elder Colin Hunter Jr welcomes you to country in the video below.
From the 1920s-1940s, many legendary Aboriginal speakers such as Pastor Sir Doug Nicholls addressed gatherings here.

2811.title: The Koori Club, 43 Gertrude St
2811.summary: Established by Aboriginal artist, Lin Onus, this was a social and political meeting place during the 1960s for young people influenced by the Black Power Movement.

2812.title: Aboriginal Housing Board of Victoria, 79 Gertrude St
2812.summary: This was established in 1981 to advocate for Aboriginal families, whose needs were not being met by State housing services, resulting in high rates of eviction and homelessness.

2813.title: Victorian Aboriginal Legal Service, 11 Brunswick St
2813.summary: Established by volunteers in 1973, this service sought to combat disproportionate and unjust impacts of the legal system on Aboriginal people in Victoria.

2814.title: Victorian Aboriginal Child Care Agency, 5 Brunswick St
2814.summary: Established in 1976, this agency took steps towards healing effects of racist Government practice and policy that saw separation of Aboriginal children from their families (see: Stolen Generations).

2815.title: Atherton Gardens Housing Estate
2815.summary: During the 1980s, this was a popular and safe meeting place for homeless Aboriginal people as well as other Aboriginal people looking to find family and community. See 'Stories Around the Fire' video

osm.name: Atherton Gardens Housing Estate
osm.display_name: Atherton Gardens Housing Estate, Gertrude Street, Fitzroy, Melbourne, City of Yarra, Victoria, 3065, Australia

2816.title: Koori Information Centre, 120 Gertrude St
2816.summary: Established in the early 1980s, this was an effective coordination centre for Aboriginal political activity that eventually attracted unwarranted covert surveillance by federal police.

2817.title: Victorian Aboriginal Health Service, 136 Gertrude St
2817.summary: This was the second site of the Health Service, considered one of the largest and most important Aboriginal organisations to have emerged from Fitzroy.

2818.title: Fitzroy Stars Aboriginal Community Youth Club Gymnasium
2818.summary: The Youth Club gym (184-186 Gertrude St) was established in 1977 as a preventative health program to combat the increasing drug and alcohol problems within the metropolitan Aboriginal community.

2819.title: George Wright Hostel, 66 George St
2819.summary: This hostel was initially established as a half-way house (in 1974) to support the increasing numbers of homeless Aboriginal men in and around Fitzroy.

2820.title: Nindeebiya, 99 George St
2820.summary: Established in 1983, this was a local community meeting place where Aboriginal people could gather to practise arts & crafts, play sports and have a feed.

2821.title: Builders Arms Hotel, 211 Gertrude St
2821.summary: Known as the 'Black pub of Melbourne', this was an important social and political gathering place for Aboriginal people from the 1940s until the 1980s.

osm.name: Builders Arms Hotel
osm.display_name: Builders Arms Hotel, 211, Gertrude Street, Fitzroy, Melbourne, City of Yarra, Victoria, 3065, Australia

2822.title: Victorian Aboriginal Health Service, 229 Gertrude St
2822.summary: Established in 1973, this was the first Aboriginal community controlled health and dental service in Australia.

2823.title: Koori Kollij, 42 Cambridge St
2823.summary: Established in 1982, Koori Kollij was an Aboriginal health worker training program that forged new and enduring standards of Aboriginal healthcare in Australia.

2824.title: Victorian Aboriginal Co-operative Limited, 108 Smith St
2824.summary: Established in 1976, this co-op provided local housing and welfare services to the Aboriginal community of Melbourne.

2825.title: Pastor Doug Nicholls Church of Christ, 258 Gore St
2825.summary: In 1943, Pastor Doug Nicholls and his wife Gladys Nicholls, with support from the Church of Christ, established a church service that attracted a devoted Aboriginal congregation.

2826.title: Yarra City Council
2826.summary: This walk is proudly brought to you by Yarra City Council. This walking map provides a brief outline for each point of interest. Please click on the link below for fuller descriptions.

osm.name: Council to Homeless Persons
osm.display_name: Council to Homeless Persons, 2, Stanley Street, Collingwood, Melbourne, City of Yarra, Victoria, 3066, Australia

2827.title: Helen Street views
2827.summary: Before you turn the corner, check out the leafy street scape ahead along Helen St. For all you know, you could be in an old English village....bet you didn't expect that.

2828.title: Fancy a BBQ?
2828.summary: Underutilised BBQ facilities ready to cook up a BBQ lunch. Also public toilets if you forgot to go before you left work.

2829.title: Stop to Smell the roses
2829.summary: Take a moment to enjoy Morwell's pride and joy - the rose garden.

2832.title: Council native garden lanscape
2832.summary: You might drive past this every day and never notice how beautiful it is

2833.title: Street scape
2833.summary: Another pretty street view that you may have never noticed

2834.title: Walk start: Primrose and Albion St
2834.summary: Meet here at 8.20am to start the morning walk to school.

2835.title: Crossing Fitzgerald St
2835.summary: Always remember to stop, look, listen and think as this crossing does not have lights.

2836.title: Crossing Pascoe Vale Rd and  then Fletcher St.
2836.summary: There are two streets to cross here, they are quite busy roads but both have traffic lights.

2837.title: Flowers and frontyards
2837.summary: There are lots of interesting things to look at on the walk including flowers, trees and interesting ornamanents in front yards.

2838.title: Crossing Buckley St
2838.summary: Another busy road to cross but it has traffic lights. Always check for turning cars, they are suppose to give way but always check they have seen you as you cross.

2839.title: Along Buckley St
2839.summary: This street is a little quieter. Council has laid some new sections of footpath and ensured the old path is nice and smooth. Keep an eye out for cars coming our of driveways.

2840.title: Crossing Hutcheson St
2840.summary: Stop, look and think before crossing as they are no traffic lights here. There is a refuge in the middle of the crossing to make it safer.

2841.title: The laneway
2841.summary: Check for cars before you cross the little laneway. Council has made the laneway speed limit 10km/h which is great.

2842.title: Heritage St
2842.summary: Check before crossing this little street which is  a no through road. You are nearly at school!

osm.name: Heritage Street
osm.display_name: Heritage Street, Moonee Ponds, Melbourne, City of Moonee Valley, Victoria, 3039, Australia

2844.title: Dolphins at the beach
2844.summary: The Southern beach is a bit more windy and has litle waves for the kids to play in. You might be able to see a dolphin in this photo (black dot in the middle).

2845.title: Towards Vincentia
2845.summary: The interesting rocks form wonderful rock pools near the water.

2846.title: Round the corner
2846.summary: The inviting soft white sands beckon!

2847.title: Looking backwards
2847.summary: This walk always makes we want to sopt look where I am going, where I have come from, out to the Bay... The area is made for strolling

2848.title: Rocks to climb over
2848.summary: Love these little rocky outcrops. Kids and adults alike, climg over them

2849.title: Sand beach
2849.summary: Lots of little sandy beaches, all invite a swim!

2850.title: Towards Vincentia
2850.summary: The way the tall gum trees come down to the beach means that you can often see and hear a fantastic array of birds while you walk.

2851.title: Heidelberg Artists' Trail
2851.summary: A brief description of Arthur Streeton and his work 'Autumn' (also known as 'Eaglemont'). For the full Artists' Trail - visit http://www.artiststrail.com.au/ Below fuller description of 'Autumn'.

2852.title: Eaglemont shops
2852.summary: A pleasant shopping strip constructed between 1920 - 1960s. On Silverdale Road, there are 2 heritage listed Eucaplytups trees that are approx 200 years old - see if you can spot them.

2853.title: Impressions of Eaglemont Village circa 1930
2853.summary: Unveiled in 2004, the mural depicts the streetscape of the area.

2854.title: Tribute to the Heidelberg School of Artists
2854.summary: Gives an impression of what the area looked like before urbanisation.

2855.title: Roadside planting
2855.summary: A walk along this secret trail is a delight, thanks to community members who have planted the native bushes and tended to the seedlings on warm days!

2856.title: Bridge
2856.summary: Beware of traffic at this junction as drivers tend to speed through or around the corner. Although many pedestrians and cyclists use this area, the intersection has been a hazard for many years.

2857.title: Odenwald Road
2857.summary: Literally 'old world', the road is shady with many impressive Eucalypts and other trees lining the street.

osm.name: Odenwald Road
osm.display_name: Odenwald Road, Eaglemont, Melbourne, City of Banyule, Victoria, 3079, Australia

2858.title: To Albert Jones Reserve
2858.summary: Eaglemont is a hilly area so enjoy the down hill walk while you can!

2859.title: Albert Jones Reserve
2859.summary: Albert Jones was a local resident that set aside the land for the reserve when it was threatened by development many years ago. It has a lovely playground but no bins so please take your litter home.

osm.name: Albert Jones Reserve
osm.display_name: Albert Jones Reserve, Eaglemont, Melbourne, City of Banyule, Victoria, Australia

2860.title: Delbridge House, 55 Carlsberg Road
2860.summary: One of the most extraordinary and intact ultra-modern homes of the 1950-60s, the floating structure and all-glass appearance, was achieved only by daring structural engineering.

2861.title: Desbrowe Annear House - 38 The Eyrie
2861.summary: Built in 1903, the house was designed by Harold Dsebrowe Annear, one of Australia's leading and most innovative Arts and Crafts architects of the early twentieth century.

osm.name: Desbrowe Annear House
osm.display_name: Desbrowe Annear House, 38, The Eyrie, Eaglemont, Melbourne, City of Banyule, Victoria, 3084, Australia

2862.title: Heidelberg School of Art
2862.summary: 'The Heidelberg School' refers to artists in the 19th century who were inspired by the beautiful landscapes of the Yarra River and the unique light that typifies the Australian bush.

2863.title: Chadwick House - 32-34 The Eyrie
2863.summary: Designed by Desbrowe Annear, Chadwick House incorporated Modernist ideas and Medieval-inspired design principles and was influential in the developmentof the Art and Crafts movement in Australia.

2864.title: Steps
2864.summary: The road now turns into a pocket park full of bushes and trees. Follow the path down the steps for a walk amongst the trees. This will take you to the next house.

2865.title: Officer House - 32-34 The Eyrie
2865.summary: The third of Desbrowe Annear's designs, Officer House is of architectural significance as a particularly good example of a work displaying the early expressions of modern architecture in Australia.

2866.title: Lookout
2866.summary: A good spot to lookout towards the Yarra river and Bullen Park and imagine what the landscape used to look like.

2867.title: HIlls
2867.summary: The hills are an excellent workout. Imagine how fit you would be if you walked this area every day!

2868.title: Burnley Griffin Place
2868.summary: Named after Walter Burley Griffin and Marion Mahony Griffin, who advocated garden city planning and the idea of a neighbourhood as a physical and social planning unit.

2869.title: The Righi Reserve
2869.summary: A lovely playground with plenty of shade. Perfect for a picnic.

osm.name: The Righi Reserve
osm.display_name: The Righi Reserve, Eaglemont, Melbourne, City of Banyule, Victoria, Australia

2870.title: The Eagles - 32 Eaglemont Crescent
2870.summary: An unusual and eclectic inter-War villa with many distinctive details including vermiculated rendered panels, elliptical arched entrance porch, wrought iron balustrading and leadlighted windows.

2871.title: Dowling Avenue gardens
2871.summary: Lovely cottage gardens, and a very spectacular gum tree that looks burnt (but probably isn't).

2872.title: Cambridge Sports Reserve Trail
2872.summary: A pleasant and popular trail with walkers and dog owners. The reserve has a cricket oval, seats and shelter, tennis courts and a playground.

2873.title: Playground
2873.summary: Cute little playground for younger children, and possibly grown ups who like using some of the equipment to help them with stretches.

2874.title: Tennis Courts
2874.summary: A family oriented club catering for players of all ages and levels. There are 6 courts. Lessons available and competitions are organised to help sharpen your skills.

2875.title: Box Place Kookaburra
2875.summary: This kookaburra has found a beautiful garden to rest in. A wonderful example of a low maintenance yet delightful garden.

2876.title: Jillard Walk gardens
2876.summary: A spectacular little pocket of gardens! Take a stroll to admire the fantastic range of bushes and flowers planted here.

2877.title: Carruthers Way Gardens
2877.summary: More lovely gardens to walk past.

2878.title: Latrobe River
2878.summary: Heading east, you cross over a number of waterways but the first one across the Latrobe Valley floodplains involve an impressively long bridge utilising the old railway trusses and pylons.

2879.title: Wonderful wetlands
2879.summary: No need to wade through water to enjoy the experience of being within the midst of numerous birds and aquatic wildlife!

2880.title: The great Australian pie!
2880.summary: Welcome to Glengarry, which has a bakery famous for its tasty pies that are well worth making a stop to experience (Bushies Bakery at 19 Main Street).

2881.title: Sea of poppies
2881.summary: The diversity of agriculture in the region is beautifully illustrated by this field of poppies that are grown for medicinal purposes as well as being a superb sight in bloom.

2882.title: Wide open road
2882.summary: At Toongabbie, the trail opens up to become a wide boulevard and the historic township is worth taking a side trip to explore.

2883.title: Home is where the hearth is
2883.summary: Against a backdrop of farming enterprise, you will come across numerous examples of historic ruins that speak of this region’s rich history.

2884.title: Things you can do with a soup can
2884.summary: Just one example of the many innovative sculptures you’ll discover along the way is this upcycled representation of a cow, paying homage to the days when Cowwarr was home to a busy butter factory.

2885.title: Cowwarr Art Space
2885.summary: Internationally renowned artist-in-resident Clive Murray-White opens his studio at the Cowwarr Art Space to show interested parties the magic of transforming stone into sculpture.

2886.title: The Dawson Connection
2886.summary: Take some time to wander around the adjacent Flora Reserve before heading onto the quiet back roads towards Heyfield and then returning to the gravel path.

2887.title: Heyfield Wetlands
2887.summary: This is an excellent spot to pull over to enjoy the sound of frog song at sunset and a rich habitat for birdlife at any time of day.

osm.name: Heyfield Wetlands Trail
osm.display_name: Heyfield Wetlands Trail, Heyfield, Shire of Wellington, Victoria, 3858, Australia

2888.title: Birds Land
2888.summary: This well equipped picnic area is the starting point for this heritage walk. Birds land has BBQs, toilets and shelter, and is only a short distance from the main road in Upwey

2889.title: Lake circuit
2889.summary: The flat and well maintained paths around the two lakes are the most popular local walk. There is much birdlife, and many wayside seats at which to stop, rest, and take in the view

2890.title: Retaining wall
2890.summary: This flood mitigation basin was constructed in the early 1980s. The nearby gate is a meeting point for several tracks: Nixon Road to the north is steep

2891.title: Dargon's homestead
2891.summary: Thomas Dargon 'selected' this land and built a homestead in 1845. He drowned attempting to cross Dandenong Creek in 1862. His widow re-married, to Robert Nixon, and is buried in FT Gully cemetery

2892.title: Strettle's granite
2892.summary: Abraham Strettle purchased a property in this area in 1866 and called it 'Strettle's granite'. The view from the tors to the north and west is worth the steep climb from Dargon's track

2893.title: Abrahams track
2893.summary: This section of track is sheltered on a warm day. The farm on the other side of the fence is modern, but evidence of earlier farms is just around the corner

osm.name: Abrahams Track
osm.display_name: Abrahams Track, Lysterfield, Melbourne, Shire of Yarra Ranges, Victoria, 3158, Australia

2894.title: Sunset track
2894.summary: Sunset track descends steeply to rejoin the main trail to return to our starting point at Birds Land. The dams beside the trail are evidence of earlier farms, and now home to numerous frogs

osm.name: Sunset Track
osm.display_name: Sunset Track, Lysterfield, Melbourne, Shire of Yarra Ranges, Victoria, 3158, Australia

2895.title: Mt Gordon
2895.summary: This trail begins by walking in the direction of Mt Gordon, with a street of houses on the right and Murchison Street above on the left.

2896.title: Lyrebird prints
2896.summary: Gilberts Gully is home to many lyrebirds. Look for footprint etchings in the red earth. If you listen you might just hear their distinctive call.

2897.title: Wilks Creek
2897.summary: The first of two crossing at Wilks Creek, which was named after the engineer Clement Wilks who designed bridges and culverts in the 1860s that opened up access to the Woods Point Goldfields.

2898.title: Spongy fungi
2898.summary: As you walk, be mindful of what's beneath your feet. A pile of dry leafs can often be a home to another organism, in this case, a bright yellow fungi.

2899.title: Mixed-species forest
2899.summary: The trail continues up a small sloping hill, with tall manna gums pointing skyward and a thickening blanket of tree ferns covering the ground below.

2900.title: Crossing Wilks Creek again
2900.summary: This end of Wilks Creek is more vibrant and fast-flowing. The water is deeper and it seems more likely that other species might call this spot home.

2901.title: Native birds
2901.summary: If you're lucky, you might spot some of Australia's native birds, like this beautiful Crimson Rosella, which paused just long enough for a photograph at the end of the trail.

2902.title: Richmond station murals
2902.summary: A huge whale, by Makatron, and a whole host of other fun pieces of art to brighten up the daily commute.

2903.title: The Corner Hotel's car park
2903.summary: One of Melbourne's best known venue's for up and coming bands, this place is home to some excellent nights. During the day, check out the car park which is full of art, including a large piece by Bode

2904.title: Lou Reed tribute
2904.summary: Take a walk on the wild side and enjoy this monochrome Lou Reed tribute piece.

2905.title: Super wall
2905.summary: Need I say more? You may be lucky enough to spot an older piece of work by Adate here too.

2906.title: Racehorse mural
2906.summary: A piece of public art that is regularly defaced and then repaired, because not everyone thinks horse racing is a good thing. Pretty cave painting kind of style to my mind.

2907.title: The green wall!
2907.summary: A wall that has been covered by a number of artists, almost exclusively in shades of green. The centrepiece is a tribute by artist Dvate to his father.

2908.title: Heesco, Putos and Mysterious Al wall
2908.summary: A collection of pieces that I always ejoy seeing from the train on my way into town!

2909.title: Coe and Coe cafe
2909.summary: This place does amazing sandwiches and great coffee. A regular spot for Melbourne shock artist Lush - love him or hate him, he does make me laugh!

2910.title: Indigenous boy by Adnate
2910.summary: The eyes - I can't help but wonder what this innocent young boy is thinking whenever I see him, wonderful wall.

2911.title: Kwik Kopy
2911.summary: What a striking feature this building has been transformed into thanks to Beastman.

2912.title: Start walk in Batman Park opposite the General Store
2912.summary: At Batman Point, enjoy the view of the paddlewheels of the P.S. Ozone paddle steamer off shore and the information board. Walk north along the trail to Batman Rd. Public toilets only on foreshore.

2913.title: Batman Rd lookout over Half Moon Bay and P.S. Ozone Memorial
2913.summary: This lookout over Half Moon Bay is the highest point in Indented Head. Relax and enjoy views of the Melbourne skyline and the anchor of the Wreck of the P.S. Ozone.

2914.title: Batman Road
2914.summary: Batman Road is a wide road. Enjoy walking on the nature strip or the road edge. Go west on Batman Rd 200m to Ibbotson St or 700m to the Grassy Woodland.

osm.name: Batman Road
osm.display_name: Batman Road, Indented Head, City of Greater Geelong, Victoria, 3223, Australia

2915.title: Ibbotson St. Alternate route 800 metres to McDonald St.
2915.summary: Ibbotson Street bypasses the Grassy Woodland and connects with McDonald Street, a Moonah trees conservation area.

2916.title: Batman Road to Grassy Woodland
2916.summary: Proceed west on Batman Road to Seascape Drive and enter Seabreeze Estate with the indigenous Grassy Woodland.

2917.title: Seabreeze Estate and Seascape Drive
2917.summary: Proceed south along Seascape Drive and view the significant Grassy Woodland and the wetlands basin with its abundant birdlife.

2918.title: Grassy Woodland
2918.summary: The 13 hectares of Grassy Woodland contains River Red Gums and Coast Manna Gums plus Golden Wattle and Hedge Wattle. Sun Orchids in November.

2919.title: Glenrana Drive - 600 metres
2919.summary: Proceed south and continue to Glenrana Drive with its winding path to Ibbotson Street.

2920.title: Ibbotson Street - 300 metres
2920.summary: Once at Ibbotson Street turn south/right until the next intersection and proceed east at McDonald Street.

2921.title: McDonald Street  1 Km
2921.summary: McDonald Street is a beautiful conservation area, lined with arching Moonah trees. Due to the Moonah trees high environmental value, the street has no through traffic but welcomes pedestrians.

osm.name: McDonald Street
osm.display_name: McDonald Street, Indented Head, City of Greater Geelong, Victoria, 3223, Australia

2922.title: The Esplanade - Wrathall Reserve
2922.summary: Once at The Esplanade cross over and view the historic Batman Memorial and relax under Cypress trees in Wrathall Reserve Re-connect with the coastal trail and proceed past the BBQ shelter.

2923.title: Coastal Trail - 600 metres
2923.summary: Proceed north along the trail and view the historic boatsheds and cypress trees and the main swimming beach.

2924.title: Coastal Trail to rigging area & Hall
2924.summary: Cyclists continue behind the Boat and Yacht Club buildings on the foreshore, walkers can proceed in front to Batman Park.

2925.title: IH Boat & Yacht Clubs and Indented Head Community Hall
2925.summary: The much loved Community Hall has panoramic views of the Bay. When nearing the boat ramp look out for boating activity.

2926.title: Batman Park Camping Reserve
2926.summary: Back on the coastal trail, Batman Park has campers from November to April. The Wreck of the Ozone will come into view signifying the end of the Beach 2 Bush Walk. Public toilets and BBQ here.

2927.title: Red Gums
2927.summary: Red Gums growing along the lake shore.

2928.title: Red Gums
2928.summary: Red gums growing along the shore

2930.title: Flooding Point
2930.summary: Normally dry, but if flooding occurs this section will be difficult to pass

2931.title: Old Orphanage and School
2931.summary: This is just a view of the old school and Orphanage which is a pleasant view throughout the first part of the walk.

2932.title: Strath Village Shopping Centre
2932.summary: Just to the south of this point is the Strath Village Shopping Centre. This possesses severeal pram and wheelchair friendly Cafes.

osm.name: Strath Village Shopping Centre
osm.display_name: Strath Village Shopping Centre, Edwards Road, Kennington, Bendigo, City of Greater Bendigo, Victoria, 3550, Australia

2933.title: Kennington Reservoir
2933.summary: A Beautiful lake to walk around with good parks and paths

osm.name: Kennington Reservoir
osm.display_name: Kennington Reservoir, Kennington, Bendigo, City of Greater Bendigo, Victoria, 3550, Australia

2934.title: Strath Sporting Reserve
2934.summary: A good size sporting reserve, Great for kicking the footy or just mucking about.

2935.title: Strathdale Park
2935.summary: A nice large park with BBQ's, Toilets, a playground and plenty of Space. Great for Mucking around with the kids, picnicking or just lazing about.

osm.name: Strathdale Park
osm.display_name: Strathdale Park, Strathdale, Bendigo, City of Greater Bendigo, Victoria, 3550, Australia

2936.title: Bushland
2936.summary: This reasonable sized patch pf busland contains many paths, bot sealed and gravel to explore

2937.title: Picnic and Play
2937.summary: At the Mackey Rd carpark, you will find the Apex Bicentennial Park that provides an excellent picnic area with BBQ facilities, toilets and a playground for the young and old.

2938.title: Popular spot for model boat enthusiasts
2938.summary: The Model Boat Club has a Driver’s Stand that is a fantastic platform from which to launch your remote control miniature craft, or just watch others with the expertise.

2939.title: Over the boardwalk
2939.summary: No need to get your feet wet as you cross the wetland area that is brimming with wildlife of all descriptions.

2940.title: Walking the dog
2940.summary: You’re bound to meet a pooch or two on your travels along this walking track, and they seem to enjoy the surrounds as much as their human friends.

2941.title: Beautiful native plants populate the park
2941.summary: A dedicated Friend’s Group ensures that the vegetation within the Park is both diverse and appropriate to the area, with so many magnificent flowers such as this beautiful banksia.

2942.title: Beautiful array of birdlife
2942.summary: Mathison Park is extremely popular with birdwatchers because it provides so many habitat areas. You’re bound to meet a Moor Hen or two as you walk around Lake Hyland.

2943.title: O'Hallaron and Hare Farmhouse Site
2943.summary: A fine example of farmhouses in Hazelwood during the early 19th century. See in particular the domed wall.

2944.title: Bush tucker
2944.summary: An excellent interpretive sign provides an overview of the plants that have a range of uses for the Gunaikurnai nation that has lived in this region for thousands of years.

2945.title: Gone fishing
2945.summary: Anglers can choose from one of five fishing platforms, with the Latrobe Valley Fly Fishing Club and Associated Angling Club regularly stocking the lake with rainbow trout and redfin.

2946.title: Sensational sunset
2946.summary: This really is one of those places you can go to that will engender calm. At sunset and sunrise, Lake Hyland rings with the song of birds, frogs, insects and many other native animals.

2947.title: Outdoor gym
2947.summary: Check out the basic exercise equipment on the path and at a few pull ups or crunches to your walk

2948.title: Bird houses
2948.summary: Someone has built and installed some unique bird houses in the trees here. They're dated and initialled. I'd love to know who did this!

2949.title: Netball courts
2949.summary: For anyone wanting to spend some time at a netball court, these are tucked away at Martin Park and there is a gate from the walking track to the park

2950.title: Skate Park
2950.summary: There is a skate park here that is incredibly popular and it looks like bigger and better things are on their way!

osm.name: James Scott Memorial Skate Park
osm.display_name: James Scott Memorial Skate Park, Pearce Street, Wodonga, City of Wodonga, Victoria, 3690, Australia

2951.title: Picnic and BBQ area
2951.summary: The oval along with the children's playground and BBQ area make this a great start/end point for a walk and for a picnic with the family

2952.title: Park Beach South
2952.summary: Not for swimming (dangerous currents), but great for walking.

2953.title: Surfers on Park Beach South
2953.summary: Lots of surfers to watch, sit on the sand   on Park Beach South or the breakwater rocks.

2955.title: Yachts in the harbour
2955.summary: If you are lucky you might see a yacht coming in.

2956.title: Mosaic in the sea wall
2956.summary: Look out for the mosaic in the sea wall. I only saw one, what's the story? Who put it there?

2957.title: Along the Breakwater
2957.summary: The path is great (good for prams). Sometimes waves can splash over the breakwater, on a warm day it is a delight!.

2958.title: Eddies in the water
2958.summary: Sit on the breakwater and watch the waves curl around into this little bay. The waves form eddies and patterns in the water. Very mesmerising.

2959.title: Mutton Bird Island info
2959.summary: Nice little rest spot and information on Mutton Bird Island. It is the last of the flat, get ready to climb.

2960.title: Steps to Mutton Bird Island
2960.summary: The steps to Mutton Bird Island, this is where you start to work. But, keep going. It is worth it!

2962.title: South Solitary Island
2962.summary: Looking across to South Solitary Island. It has an historic lighthouse that you can just see.

2963.title: Corambirra Point
2963.summary: Looking across to Corambirra Point and the amazing rock formation. Boambee Beach is behind.

2964.title: Looking back to the harbour
2964.summary: Looking back to the harbour, Coffs Harbour and the many National Parks behind.

2965.title: Little Mutton Bird Island
2965.summary: Looking back at Little Mutton Bird Island.

2966.title: Onto the Eastern tip of Mutton Bird Island
2966.summary: Onto the Eastern tip of Mutton Bird Island. Smell the sea air, look out to the ocean. Heaven!

2967.title: Tip of Mutton Bird Island
2967.summary: The tip of Mutton Bird Island, this is what it is all about. It can be quite secluded and worth the walk. Sit, rest, think and smile.

2968.title: Jetty Beach
2968.summary: Jetty Beach is as good as it looks. Swim, sit, paddle, body surf or lie in the sun.

2969.title: Jetty Beach picnic area
2969.summary: The Jetty Beach picnic area has seats, toilets, water, shade and an abundance of bird life.

2970.title: Coffs Harbour Jetty
2970.summary: The Coffs Harbour Jetty is a great walk, love the sound of the boards under foot.

osm.name: Coffs Harbour Jetty
osm.display_name: Coffs Harbour Jetty, Coffs Harbour, Coffs Harbour City Council, New South Wales, 2450, Australia

2971.title: Jetty Beach from the jetty
2971.summary: Looking back onto Jetty Beach from the jetty.

2972.title: Mutton Bird Island from the jetty.
2972.summary: The end of the Jetty and Mutton Bird Island.

2973.title: Museum of the Living West
2973.summary: Melbourne's Living Museum of the West occupies these historic bluestone buildings for its office, resource centre and exhibition space.

2974.title: Willy Wagtails
2974.summary: You are sure to spot Willy Wagtails darting about.  When feeding they distract insects by wagging and fanning their tail.

2975.title: The walking route
2975.summary: The route is flat and accessible to all.  It is mostly paved and has very well maintained gravel tracks.  A short section at the end is not readily accessible by wheelchair, and can easily be avoided.

2976.title: Cumbungi
2976.summary: Around the first small pond there is lots of Cumbungi growing.  It provides protection against bank erosion and is an excellent nesting site for water birds.

2977.title: Riverside pathway
2977.summary: The path alongside the river is a wide shared path.  There are also sections of gravel path nearer the river bank as an alternative to the shared path.

2978.title: Lounging by the lake
2978.summary: This recently developed area provides some wonderful resting options, fit for giants.  There is also a cafe in the apartment block behind.

2979.title: Little Pied Cormorant
2979.summary: Cormorants and seagulls spend time resting and socialising around the moorings here.  The cormorants dive in shallow waters to find fish and crustaceans.

2980.title: Wetlands
2980.summary: Built as part of the nearby apartment development, the wetlands cleanse the stormwater entering the river and provide a habitat for wildlife.

osm.name: Frog's Hollow Wetlands
osm.display_name: Frog's Hollow Wetlands, Maribyrnong, Melbourne, City of Maribyrnong, Victoria, Australia

2981.title: Masked Lapwing (or Plover)
2981.summary: Around the lake and billabong is a feast of birdlife, including the Masked Lapwing (pictured), Eurasian Coots, Purple Moorhens, Seagulls and Ducks.

2982.title: BBQ Area
2982.summary: Near the end of the walk, and close to the car park, is a BBQ area with park benches and a drinking water fountain.  A great place for a picnic after your walk.

2983.title: History of the Land Garden
2983.summary: The gorgeous garden is a patchwork of small ornamental gardens and mosaics.  Information boards describe the many uses of the area over the years.

osm.name: History of the Land Gardens
osm.display_name: History of the Land Gardens, Maribyrnong River Trail, Maribyrnong, Melbourne, City of Maribyrnong, Victoria, 3032, Australia

2984.title: Mosaic
2984.summary: One of the many colourful mosaics in the garden, depicting Aboriginal life before European settlers arrived.

2985.title: Bluestone fords
2985.summary: The first of two bluestone fords  you can turn left here, cross the ford and turn left again when you meet the river to make a shorter version of the walk.

2986.title: Braybrook & Maidstone Neighbourhood House
2986.summary: This organisation is made up of residents who live in Braybrook and Maidstone and surrounding areas and are committed to listening to and representing local people to build a proud community.

2987.title: Wheelbarrow Garden
2987.summary: Check out some of the wonderful gardens, like the wheelbarrow garden, on the walk. Very inspiring!

2988.title: Cao Dai Vietnamese Temple
2988.summary: Cao Dai is a new religious movement founded in Vietnam. It was established in the city of Tây Ninh, southern  Vietnam in 1926. Admire the topiary dragons!

2989.title: Blooming Roundabout
2989.summary: Enjoy the view of the roundabout, planted by Maribyrnong City Council and maintained by local residents, before you turn right onto Churchill Avenue.

2990.title: Maribyrnong City Council Public Art - People
2990.summary: People created by TRUC artists, Jonathan Leahey and David Burrows and made with corten steel.

2991.title: Braybrook Library
2991.summary: Braybrook's first library has transformed the community. Young, old, and everyone in between make their way to the library to read, relax and connect with others.

2992.title: Braybrook Commons Community Garden
2992.summary: The garden was set up by Maribyrnong City Council to help improve food security in Braybrook and surrounds.  The garden members are now an incorporated group. Join up and grow your own food!

osm.name: Braybrook Commons Community Garden
osm.display_name: Braybrook Commons Community Garden, Melrose Street, Braybrook, Melbourne, City of Maribyrnong, Victoria, 3019, Australia

2993.title: Braybrook Park/Skinner Reserve
2993.summary: Enjoy a wander around the park, walking and talking with friends.  Breathe in the fresh air nine kilometres from the city centre. Join in a kick of the footy or soccer ball and get your heart rate up!

2994.title: Viewing platform
2994.summary: Before you walk down to Steavenson Falls, visit the look out for a stunning view of the valley below. The 84-metre-tall falls has a year-round flow due to its forested catchment.

2995.title: Information
2995.summary: The falls begins its descent 350 metres higher up, on the crest of the Great Dividing Range. It drops 84 metres into a catchment of 16 square kilometres and supplies the town of Marysville with water.

2996.title: A gentle path
2996.summary: Follow the gravel path down towards the falls for a spectacular view. The falls mark the most dramatic point in the journey of the Steavenson River as it flows north to the town of Buxton.

2997.title: From a distance
2997.summary: Observe the falls from a distance for a sense of just how tall they really are. Keep watch for wildlife and you may see a platypus in the river pools nearby.

2998.title: Turbine generation
2998.summary: Walk along the lower path to access the turbine generation. At the base of the falls is a small weir that collects water, sending it down a 300mm-diameter pipe to power this hydroelectric turbine.

2999.title: Water power
2999.summary: This cross flow turbine is believed to be the only one of its kind in Australia. It was upgraded after the Black Saturday bushfires so that excess power could be sent to the national power grid.

3000.title: One of the ponds
3000.summary: There a couple of ponds in the Gardens with water birds and fountains.

3001.title: Restored garden
3001.summary: Museum Victoria restored the former German Garden of the Western Forecourt in 2009, it was a carpark covered in asphalt.

3002.title: Amazing Gum tree
3002.summary: This fantastic gum tree gives a glimpse  of the types of trees that once dotted the landscape.

3003.title: Playground
3003.summary: A great playground to bring children to on the weekend?

3004.title: Basketball court
3004.summary: How about bringing a basketball and some work colleagues for a game?

3005.title: Melbourne Museum
3005.summary: You could always stop and do some step ups onto the stone benches, that will get your blood going!

osm.name: Melbourne Museum
osm.display_name: Melbourne Museum, 11, Nicholson Street, Carlton, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3053, Australia

3006.title: The Royal Exhibition Buildings
3006.summary: Completed in 1886 for the Melbourne International Exhibition it was the site of Australia's first Parliament in 1901

3007.title: Westgarth Drinking Fountain
3007.summary: Make sure you have a look at the fountain of two embracing kangaroos that was built in 1888.

3008.title: The Exhibition Fountain
3008.summary: This intricate, multi-level fountain is a sight to behold.

3010.summary: View from Port Melbourne Beach to the observation deck

3013.summary: View across Hobsons Bay to Princess Pier and the City of Melbourne

3014.title: View from the observation deck to the West Gate Bridge
3014.summary: View from the observation deck to the West Gate Bridge

3015.title: Bird life in the newly-planted vegetation
3015.summary: Bird life in the newly-planted vegetation

3017.title: Observation deck looking towards the city
3017.summary: Observation deck looking towards the city

3018.title: Sandridge Life Saving Club
3018.summary: A beach shelter at Sandridge Life Saving Club

osm.display_name: Port Melbourne Beach, Beacon Cove, Port Melbourne, Melbourne, City of Port Phillip, Victoria, 3207, Australia

3020.title: Part of the original Princes Pier from 1912
3020.summary: Part of the original Princes Pier from 1912

3021.title: Princes Pier building
3021.summary: The newly refurbished Princes Pier is well worth a wander down.

3022.title: Original Princes Pier pylons

3055.summary: If you choose to walk on the gravel path, watch out for signs providing information about plantings and other items of interest.

3056.title: Bridge to Doncaster
3056.summary: This bridge provides access across the freeway back to Doncaster.
