3187.summary: This was rebuilt in 1962.  When water is low stumps of the first bridge can be seen on the north side.  This bridge was subject to regular flooding.

3188.title: Bidjin Sign
3188.summary: The Bidjin (meaning freshwater mussel) sign is from the Wergaia indigenous language of the Wimmera.

3189.title: Jetty and Picnic Bench
3189.summary: Right near the Bidjin sign is a jetty and picnic bench where you can enjoy a peaceful rest.

3190.title: Wirringgal Sign
3190.summary: Wirringgal (meaning Golden Perch) is also from the Wergaia indigenous language.

3191.title: Jetty and Picnic Bench
3191.summary: Located just near the Wirringgal sign is another opportunity to enjoy a rest or walk along the jetty

3192.title: Yalam Sign
3192.summary: Yalam (meaning Waterhole) is the last of the three indigenous signs along this particular part of track.

3193.title: Jetty and Picnic spot
3193.summary: Located near the Yalam sign is another opportunity to enjoy a walk out close to the water and chance to rest yourlegs and enjoy a snack.

3194.title: The Capital Performing Arts Centre and Bendigo Art Gallery
3194.summary: The Capital Performing Arts Centre and Bendigo Art Gallery

3197.title: Buildings at the corner of View St and Pall Mall
3197.summary: Buildings at the corner of View St and Pall Mall

3199.title: Soldiers Memorial Museum
3199.summary: Walk along Pall Mall towards the Soldiers Memorial Museum

osm.name: Conservatory
osm.display_name: Conservatory, Bendigo Creek Trail, Bendigo, City of Greater Bendigo, Victoria, 3550, Australia

osm.name: Camp Hill Primary School
osm.display_name: Camp Hill Primary School, 50, Gaol Road, Bendigo, City of Greater Bendigo, Victoria, 3550, Australia

osm.name: Rosalind Park
osm.display_name: Rosalind Park, Bendigo, City of Greater Bendigo, Victoria, 3550, Australia

3212.title: Pause Spot One
3212.summary:
Take 5 deep breaths. What can you
See
Hear
Smell
Touch
Taste
Deep belly breathing and focus on your five senses. This is a popular way to relax and bring you into the moment

3213.title: Pause Spot Two
3213.summary:
Looking for Colours.
This can be helpful when your mind is going in circles.
Can you find something that is:
Green
Blue
Red
White
Yellow
What other colours can you see.

3214.title: Pause Spot Three
3214.summary:
Listening for Sounds
To fully in the moment we need to stop and absorb what is around us.
Listen for these sounds:
Birds 
Water 
People 
Traffic

3215.title: Pause Spot Four
3215.summary:
Take a moment to be grateful and reflect on your strength.
Say to yourself, I am strong like this tree because ............
Take a moment to be grateful and say to yourself, I am grateful for ......

3216.title: Pause spot Five
3216.summary:
Count your steps to the next pause spot.
Shift your weight from one foot to the other and walk with awareness one step at a time and count your steps until you reach your next spot.

3217.title: Pause Spot Six
3217.summary:
Congratulate yourself you have reached half way.
You achieve so many things over your lifetime. Take time to acknowledge them. Now turn and walk slowly, mindfully and enjoy the walk back.

3218.title: Big Hill Track West, Greater Bendigo National Park
3218.summary: The walk begins at the carpark for Crusoe Reservoir & Number 7 Park.

3219.title: Historic Water Race
3219.summary: The track takes you over water races, some empty…

3221.title: Track Intersection
3221.summary: Take the track to the left at this first intersection.

3222.title: Water Tank
3222.summary: After the yellow gas pipeline sign, turn right and head towards the water tank.

3223.title: Dam Wall
3223.summary: The track goes between a small empty reservoir on the left and this brick building on the right.

3224.title: Old Fence
3224.summary: At this landmark, continue straight ahead.

3225.title: Fork In The Track
3225.summary: Turn right here and continue back to the beginning. The Number 7 reservoir will be on your left.

3227.title: The Ol' Duke Hotel
3227.summary: The hotel and related buildings are a part of Portarlington's history. Enjoy music by an open fire at the National Celtic Festival.

3228.title: The Ol' Duke - Harding Street side
3228.summary: Admire the excellent restoration and redevelopment of an historic building.

3229.title: The Portarlington RSL Memorial Garden
3229.summary: This building was formerly a National Bank and houses a collection of military memorabilia.

3230.title: St Patrick's Hall
3230.summary: This church hall dating from the 1940s has unusual, harlequin glass windows and is still an important community meeting place.

3231.title: Traditional timber houses
3231.summary: This is a small enclave of traditional timber houses, especially lovely in autumn when the leaves are on the ground.

3232.title: Intersection of Harding and Smythe Streets

3233.title: Crossing Smythe Street
3233.summary: You are leaving behind timber 19th century domestic buildings for large modern mansions.

3234.title: Arlington Rise Development, turn left at the flags
3234.summary: Experience a good footpath on this side of the road.

3235.title: Across the roundabout take the upwards curving footpath
3235.summary: This path will take you to a delightful small rest place and garden, with a spectacular view over Corio Bay to the You Yangs.

3236.title: The park at the top of the hill
3236.summary: Catch your breath and take a well-earned rest here!

3237.title: Breathtaking views
3237.summary: A beautiful view at any time, but a great sunset experience! Return to Newcombe Street where there are a number of enticing places where you can enjoy your choice of food and drink.

3238.title: Train Station Precinct
3238.summary: The Visitor Centre located here and can provide loads of information about Ararat and the surrounding areas.

3239.title: Masonic Hall
3239.summary: Look for this building as you head east on the Western Highway. It’s stand out paint work makes it very easy to spot! Turn left into Queen Street.

3240.title: Langi Morgala Museum
3240.summary: This red brick and bluestone building was built in 1874 and boasts a very interesting history.  It opened as the Langi Morgala (Home of yesterday) Museum in 1970.

osm.name: Langi Morgala Museum
osm.display_name: Langi Morgala Museum, Queen Street, Ararat, Rural City of Ararat, Victoria, 3377, Australia

3241.title: Astor Cinema
3241.summary: Completed in 1938 in the art deco style, The Astor was one of the largest purpose-built cinemas in rural Victoria. It closed with the advent of television, but re-opened in 1959.

osm.name: Astor Cinema
osm.display_name: Astor Cinema, 250, Barkly Street, Ararat, Rural City of Ararat, Victoria, 3377, Australia

3242.title: Shire Hall
3242.summary: The Shire Hall was built in 1871 – arguably one of Ararat’s most distinguished buildings. The building houses a WW1 honour board and a beautiful stained glass window that honours the fallen.

osm.name: Department of Primary Industries
osm.display_name: Department of Primary Industries, Barkly Street, Ararat, Rural City of Ararat, Victoria, 3377, Australia

3243.title: Cenotaph
3243.summary: The monument was dedicated in 1930 to those who served Australia in various conflicts and in memory of those who died.

3244.title: Town Hall and War Memorial Fountain
3244.summary: The Town Hall was built in 1869. The fountain, planned to mark Queen Victoria’s diamond jubilee, also commemorates volunteers who fought in the Boer War.

3245.title: Barkly Street with Vine covered verandas
3245.summary: Barkly Street showcases many historic buildings and the vine covered verandas of the modern businesses. The first vine was planted in 1874 by Mr Grano outside his mixed business store.

3246.title: Public toilet and seat
3246.summary: Here if you need it! A small detour will take you to the Bull and Mouth Stables.  Built in 1866 these bluestone stables were described at the time as “one of the finest in the country”.

3247.title: Nurses memorial – View Point
3247.summary: The memorial was erected to the English-born nurse Edith Cavell who was executed in 1915 for assisting prisoners to escape from the Germans. Each Anzac day a nurse lays a wreath in her memory.

3248.title: Historic buildings - Vindel House
3248.summary: On the northern side of Barkly Street, pass  Vindel House. Constructed in two parts, the Sub-Treasury and Assay office in 1858 – the post office was attached in 1862. The  clock was installed in 1890.

3249.title: Water station
3249.summary: A modern and thoughtful addition to the street provides the means for walkers to refresh and refill! Leave the main drag at this point and turn left into Ingor Street.

3250.title: Gum San Chinese Heritage
3250.summary: This dramatic two-story building with its authentic Chinese tiled roof houses a fascinating selection of audio-visual and static displays. Well worth a visit!

osm.name: Gum San Chinese Heritage Museum
osm.display_name: Gum San Chinese Heritage Museum, Western Highway, Ararat, Rural City of Ararat, Victoria, 3377, Australia

3251.title: J Ward - Lunatic Asylum
3251.summary: Completed in 1861, this building was originally a goldfields prison. From 1866 to 1991 was the only institution in Victoria entirely devoted to the care of the criminally insane.

3252.title: Pyrenees House
3252.summary: Completed in 1886 in the Queen Anne style it operated as a general hospital until 1937. Since 1988 it has been used as administration offices and a nurse education centre.

3253.title: Alexandra Gardens
3253.summary: The Alexandra Gardens is home to the Active Pathway Project consisting a multi use pathway around the perimeter of the lake, two exercise stations, a wetlands boardwalk and better wayfinding signage.

osm.name: Alexandra Gardens
osm.display_name: Alexandra Gardens, Girdlestone Street, Ararat, Rural City of Ararat, Victoria, 3377, Australia

3254.title: Celebratory Coffee
3254.summary: Head back to your car after leaving the gardens, or if you are in the mood, try Fred and Bet's  for a great coffee and an indulgent treat.

3255.title: Starlight reserve
3255.summary: This reserve dates from the 1970s, but contains Aboriginal bush tucker sources, and also remains of the Rowville military camp, built in 1942 to protect Melbourne from Japanese invasion

osm.name: Starlight Reserve
osm.display_name: Starlight Reserve, Hakea Place, Rowville, Melbourne, City of Knox, Victoria, 3178, Australia

3256.title: Tirhatuan wetlands
3256.summary: This wetland is named for the homestead occupied by Rev. James Clow, first European settler in the City of Knox, 1838. The wetland are  home to much bird life, and aquatic species such as frogs

osm.name: Tirhatuan Wetlands Conservation Reserve
osm.display_name: Tirhatuan Wetlands Conservation Reserve, Illawarra Avenue, Rowville, Melbourne, City of Knox, Victoria, 3178, Australia

3257.title: incline tramway
3257.summary: This is the only incline firewood tramway in the City of Knox. The home owner has a wood fire or stove, and has constructed a 15 metre winch hauled tramway out of angle iron

3258.title: Police Road retarding basin
3258.summary: This massive retaining wall was constructed in the 1970s for flood mitigation by the Dandenong Valley Authority. The DVA was absorbed as part of Melbourne Water in the 1990s

3259.title: Magic 1278 transmission towers
3259.summary: These radio broadcast towers were constructed in the 1970s for AM radio Magic 693. Today operated by Magic 1278, transmissions from here are so powerful they can be picked up (just) in Antarctica!

3260.title: Kilcatten Park site
3260.summary: Kilcatten Park homestead was built by James Quirk in 1856, and home for many years to the Golding family. The homestead has now vanished, but exotic fruit trees still mark the site

3261.title: VFL Park
3261.summary: This arena was to be the home of Australian Rules football, staging the Grand Final and provided with its own rail line. Today, a moldering section of grandstand is all that remains

3262.title: Wonderful shady seat
3262.summary: On a warm day, this is a great seat to sit and watch the world go by.

3263.title: The playground
3263.summary: There always seems to be children in this playground.

3264.title: Looking back to Apollo Bay township
3264.summary: The path looking back to Apollo Bay township, the grassy knolls make wonderful slopes for rolling down.

3265.title: Heading towards Barham River
3265.summary: I love this part of the walk where you start to get inviting glimpses of the sea and start wondering what lies beyound the trees.

3266.title: The Barham river
3266.summary: Through the shady path and the Barham river appears, Marengo lies in the distance.

3267.title: Dogs swimming
3267.summary: Not sure if it is an official dog off leash area, but there always seems to be dogs here.

3268.title: Expansive views and little rock pools.
3268.summary: The ocean and sea breezes (sometimes gales!). The rock formations and great for hopping along and see things in the rock pools.

3269.title: Collecting cuttlefish and shells
3269.summary: Lots of things to keep children interested, shells, birds, cuttlefish shells and general stuff to pick up and look at.

3270.title: The breakwater
3270.summary: The stonework on the breakwater is truly a work of art!

3271.title: The end of the breakwater
3271.summary: Who can resist wallking to the end of the breakwater? Great fishing spot too (caught a flathead there).

3272.title: Shelterd harbour beach
3272.summary: Beautiful sheltered beach with crystal clear water. When we were there, two nesting Cape Barron Geese cmae hissing towards us.

3273.title: Craypots, fishing boats and anglers.
3273.summary: The piles of neatly stacked craypots and fishing boats in the water are really beautiful.

3274.title: Apollo Bay beach
3274.summary: The beach is most sheltered nearer the harbour and the swell gets bigger as you walk along the bay. It is a great beach for swimming, body surfing, surfing and flying kites (it can get very windy).

osm.name: Apollo Bay Harbour
osm.display_name: Apollo Bay Harbour, Apollo Bay, Shire of Colac Otway, Victoria, Australia

3275.title: The skate park
3275.summary: I love stopping and watching skaters, scooters and bike riders mucking around on the skate park.

3276.title: The seals sculpture
3276.summary: Next to the Tourist Info this is the first of many fantastic sculptures along the foreshore.

3277.title: Seat and sculptures
3277.summary: The grassy area across from the shops is a fantastic place to wander, stop, picnic and sit. If is also quite sheltered from southerly sea winds.

3278.title: North Boundary Track
3278.summary: Lookout which offers 360 views of the Churchill National Park, & you  can see all the way out to Stud Road

3279.title: Car Park Entry
3279.summary: There is parking out the front of the park on Churchill Park Drive which offers easy access to the hiking trails

3280.title: Army Track
3280.summary: You'll find many of the trails around the park quite wide with a loose gravel surface

osm.name: Army Track
osm.display_name: Army Track, Lysterfield South, Melbourne, City of Casey, Victoria, 3802, Australia

3281.title: Wildlife
3281.summary: The park has an abundance of wildlife & quite a serene & tranquil place to visit

3282.title: Fauna
3282.summary: The park is full of hidden wonders

3283.title: Escarpment
3283.summary: Taylor's Creek cuts through the so-called "new volcanic" layer of basalt that makes up most of the terrain of the Western Suburbs. You can see plenty of volcanic features like this outcrop.

3284.title: The Weir
3284.summary: This Weir has been here for a fair while, and nearby is a strange bluestone box contraption that was probably a sheep dip. Crossing over takes you to a silcrete quarry. Beautiful red gums abound.

3285.title: Native Vegetation
3285.summary: As well as magnificent gum trees, there are native grasses, wildflowers and shrubs. Brimbank Council, Melbourne Water, and the Friends of Taylor's Creek actively care for the grasslands.

3286.title: Housing
3286.summary: People who live along the creek have been making their backyards their front yards so that they can better engage with their local environment.

3287.title: Tool Scatters
3287.summary: This whole area is very important for the Marin Bulluk clan of the Wurundjeri people, and has been inhabited for ten of thousands of years. Taylor's Creek silcrete  is found for kilometres around.

3288.title: Have a seat
3288.summary: Sit on the bench and enjoy the view

3289.title: Wildlife
3289.summary: There is always plenty of birds and animals around. In this case a Meadow Argus butterfly.

3290.title: More trees
3290.summary: This stretch of the creek is particularly blessed with big trees.

3291.title: Ochre
3291.summary: As we get further downstream, we get deeper under the basalt, revealing layers of gravel, Silurian bedrock, and this amazing ochre wall.

3293.title: Up the hill
3293.summary: It's pretty steep up that hill. Have a breather on a slightly different seat.

3295.title: View across to the Wheel
3295.summary: A great place to start, if you are going to do a brisk walk, you might want to time yourself to see how fast you go for the next time you do the walk.

3296.title: Grassy lunch spot and flower bed
3296.summary: Why not stop and smell the roses? Great water side view on this lawn area makes a pleasant lunch spot.

3297.title: The wide boardwalk
3297.summary: There are quite a few seats or benches along this stretch if you need to take some notes on your walking meeting.

3298.title: Harbour Esplanade
3298.summary: A favourite leg of the walk with many other people out on a lunchtime walk. Time to talk, think or simply turn off and get some exercise.

osm.name: Harbour Esplanade
osm.display_name: Harbour Esplanade, Yarra’s Edge, Docklands, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3008, Australia

3299.title: Table Tennis
3299.summary: Anyone for Table Tennis? Bring a work colleague, some table tennis bats and balls  and have some fun!

3300.title: Cow up a tree
3300.summary: Cow up a tree by John Kelly is a wonderful public sculpture. Look up every time you walk past and see if it makes you smile.

osm.name: Cow Up a Tree
osm.display_name: Cow Up a Tree, Harbour Esplanade, Docklands, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3008, Australia

3301.title: Monument Park
3301.summary: Another interesting spot to stop for lunch. Sit on the lawn or bench look at the artworks and enjoy the view.

osm.name: Monument Park
osm.display_name: Monument Park, NewQuay, Docklands, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3008, Australia

3302.title: Silence
3302.summary: 'Silence' by Adrian Mauriks is a fibreglass sculpture along New Quay Promenade. It's nearly time to turn around. Why not pick up the pace a little and get the blood pumping?

osm.name: Silence
osm.display_name: Silence, Newquay Promenade, Docklands, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3008, Australia

3303.title: Looking South
3303.summary: Always nice to look back at where you started, or where you are going!

3304.title: The Rush Gateway - Bendigo Library Gardens
3304.summary: Start your walk under The Rush Gateway. What do the strange shapes on the top mean? Don't even think of climbing this as it is huge.

3305.title: Chancery Lane artwork
3305.summary: Drop by Chancery Lane and see if you can spot these colourful creations! There's local artwork, coffee shops and clothing boutiques to enjoy.

3306.title: Meet a Chancery Lane resident
3306.summary: Not quite a doggy in the window but you can make friends with this one - he won't bite!

3307.title: Who do you know?
3307.summary: Take a closer look to see who you might recognise on these walls.

3308.title: Shamrock Hotel - corner Pall Mall & Williamson St
3308.summary: Built in 1854. The gold miners who came to see a show allegedly threw gold nuggets at the feet of a performer one night. Hotel staff later picked them up as tips! What a great job!

3309.title: Bendigo Visitor's Information Centre - 67 Pall Mall
3309.summary: You can find lots of information about things to do here. There are brochures, displays and more. Toilets are available at the rear of the building.

3310.title: Bendigo Magistrates' Court , 71 Pall Mall
3310.summary: There are fantastic lions and gargoyles at the front of the Magistrates' Court. How many lions and gargoyles can you see? What are they doing outside the Magistrates' Court?

3311.title: Conservatory Gardens
3311.summary: Established in 1901 and home to Australia's oldest glass hothouse, and the sculpture of a man fighting a leopard being bitten by a dog! Water tap is at the rear of the gardens towards Rosalind Park.

3312.title: Rosalind Park
3312.summary: The creek was an important source of food and water for the Dja Dja Wrung people who lived in this area. This grassy woodland with River Red Gums became a goldfield, then converted into a public park.

osm.name: Rosalind Park
osm.display_name: Rosalind Park, Bendigo, City of Greater Bendigo, Victoria, 3550, Australia

3313.title: Chinatown precinct
3313.summary: Once home to the Chinese miners in Bendigo, this place gives you a taste of Chinese culture and history. It's also a great space to run around and explore! See how many lions and dragons you can find.

3314.title: Golden Dragon Museum
3314.summary: Dragons are a popular and auspicious mythical creature in Chinese culture. See these fearsome and colourful creatures up close!  Check out the fun activities if you\'re here during school holidays.

osm.name: Golden Dragon Museum
osm.display_name: Golden Dragon Museum, Bridge Street, Bendigo, City of Greater Bendigo, Victoria, 3550, Australia

3315.title: Lotus flower
3315.summary: The Lotus flower is often used as a symbol for purity and truth. Can you find the other giant flowers in the area?

3316.title: Rosalind Park Fernery
3316.summary: Enjoy the cool air as you walk through the fernery. The River Red Gums here are from the original landscape hundreds of years ago. Look up and see if you can spot a bat or two!

3317.title: Rosalind Park - resting stop
3317.summary: There are many shady areas where you can stop and have a rest, or simply run around to explore the area.

3318.title: Playground - open after school hours
3318.summary: Playground heaven! Slides, climbing decks, fireman's pole, bridges, a sandpit, and a large climbing net! Wheelchair accessible in most areas. There's also a drinking fountain here.

3319.title: Cascades fountain and waterfall
3319.summary: A cool spot for birds and people to enjoy the park. Built in the 1880s, the original structures fell apart until it was partially rebuilt in 1997.

3320.title: Peter the Rabbit
3320.summary: This Rabbit is called Peter. What's Peter looking at? What\'s he thinking? Who put him here? Why? So many interesting questions for a giant rabbit. If only he could talk.

3321.title: Bendigo Vintage Trams
3321.summary: If you're lucky you might spot the Vintage Talking Tram Tour. Hop on to join the tour but note that you'll have to stay on till it comes back to this spot again to continue your walk.

3322.title: Alexandra Fountain - Charing Cross
3322.summary: Imagine having a fountain named after you. This was named after Alexandra, Princess of Wales whose sons, Princes Albert and George, attended the opening ceremony on 5 July 1881.

3323.title: Bendigo Ice Creamery
3323.summary: Check out the many flavours available here. You can sit outside to enjoy your ice-cream while making other people jealous!

osm.name: Bendigo Ice Creamery
osm.display_name: Bendigo Ice Creamery, High Street, Bendigo, City of Greater Bendigo, Victoria, 3550, Australia

3324.title: Pennyweight Walk
3324.summary: A free gallery with fantastically colourful artwork by young local artists. Get your fix of street art here.

osm.name: Pennyweight Walk
osm.display_name: Pennyweight Walk, Bendigo, City of Greater Bendigo, Victoria, 3550, Australia

3325.title: Marysville Information Centre
3325.summary: Open daily daily from 9am to 5pm. There are public toilets, water fountains, fantastic playgrounds, BBQs and picnic tables near the information centre.

3326.title: Town history
3326.summary: The history of Marysville and its response to Black Saturday is expressed in words throughout the picnic area and playground. Keep an eye out for murals and images as you explore.

3327.title: Gallipoli Park
3327.summary: On 7 February 2009, a fire front destroyed nearly all the town's buildings. Some of the residents who survived the fire came to Gallipoli Park before being evacuated the next day.

3328.title: Into the forest
3328.summary: The path climbs as you leave Marysville, with views to your right and a gully of fern trees ahead. Tourism took off here in 1886 when the railway linked Healesville to the city,  inviting interest.

3329.title: Look up
3329.summary: As you walk, keep your eyes high to see remnants from the bushfires and signs of new life, closer to the ground at your feet. Marysville has a hidden valley feel, surrounded by mountains at all sides.

3330.title: Like the lichen
3330.summary: As well as tree ferns and mountain ash, there's also plenty of moss and lichen to admire along this walk. The mostly dark conditions suit the mossy blanket well.

3331.title: Tiny mushrooms
3331.summary: Depending on the season, you might see a mushroom or two, clinging to a tree branch or nestled in the roots below.

3332.title: Return to Marysville
3332.summary: At the end of the trail, you can visit Steavenson Falls and walk back to town the way you came. Enjoy the shade of the tall manna gums before the shorter tree ferns appear.

3333.title: New Life
3333.summary: Once back in Marysville, see the 2011 sculpture titled, 'New Life' by local artist, Bruno Torfs. The dedication reads: 'to honour the past and embrace the future'.  Bruno has a sculpture garden too.

3334.title: Meteorite Park
3334.summary: Dedicated to a meteorite that fell over Murchison on the 28 Sept 1969. See the newspaper clippings from across the globe on display. Fragments of the meteorite are on display in museums around

osm.name: Meteorite Park
osm.display_name: Meteorite Park, Murchison, City of Greater Shepparton, Victoria, Australia

3335.title: Gregorys Bridge Hotel
3335.summary: Built 1865 and 1868, it was a country hotel, large general store and cellar with stables at the rear. The tree out front was planted in 1916 and is one of Victorias finest London Plane trees.

3336.title: River bank gardens, boardwalk and three information lecterns
3336.summary: Discover Murchisons bygone era with images of the old streetscape, pub and paddle steamers. The boardwalk provides an impressive view of the Goulburn River.

3337.title: Goulburn River
3337.summary: Saw its first paddle steamer in 1875. At the time Murchison had six hotels, two flour mills and numerous stores and services.

3338.title: Murchison Heritage Centre
3338.summary: Located out the side of the museum is a large pump that was used to pump water from the river for the townspeople.

3339.title: Sparks Reserve
3339.summary: An open space with a playground, sitting area, dog poo bag dispenser and creek-side picnic spot

3340.title: New path, connecting the Darebin Creek Trail with the Main Yarra Trail
3340.summary: Look left here to see the new path to the Main Yarra Trail, via Napier Waller Reserve.  This path is due to open to the public in 2017, though it is already well-trodden.

3341.title: Bridge under Heidelberg Road
3341.summary: This terrific bridge joined Sparks Reserve with the Darebin Creek Trail, making life much easier for Fairy Hills residents wanting to walk along the creek.

3342.title: Flood-proof fencing
3342.summary: The Darebin Creek floods regularly - to avoid fence losses, the owners of creek-side properties installed cable-based fencing with pivots with water flow.

3343.title: A good spot to spot carp
3343.summary: At the annual 'catch-a-carp' day, these pest fishes are sometime spotted here - though rarely caught.

3344.title: Hill stabilisation works
3344.summary: Build on an old tip, this hill is prone to slipping.  New stabilisation works and planting will keep the hill in place.

3345.title: Ivanhoe Wetlands
3345.summary: Look across to the Ivanhoe Wetlands - constructed in 1992, they are a haven for birds and wildlife.  You can reach them via paths and stepping stones further along the creek.

3346.title: Parklands entrance - and 're-bushing'
3346.summary: Look to your right for where grass and weeds have been sprayed to make way for new planting - as part of an ongoing parkland-wide transition from grass to bush.

3347.title: Darebin Parklands map
3347.summary: Just next to the path, this map shows the main walking and cycle routes through the parklands, as well as provision for dog-off leash areas and a number of historical markers.

3348.title: A spot for everyone - seats and nesting boxes
3348.summary: As you stroll through the park, look up to see nest boxes for native birds and small animals - they are an ongoing project of the DCMC and DPA to help wildlife protect their young from predators.

3349.title: Path to the Ivanhoe Wetlands
3349.summary: Follow this path to the right to find the stepping stones over the creek - then onto the Ivanhoe Wetlands, created in 1992.

3350.title: Mount Puffalo
3350.summary: Mount Puffalo was created in 1998, and provides superb view of the park.

3351.title: Not just a duck pond
3351.summary: Part of the parklands is built over a landfill, which 'leaches' liquid - a system on ponds, reed beds, waterfalls and wetlands clean and treats the water before it reaches the creek.

3352.title: Waterfall - aerating the water
3352.summary: Lovely to look at and listen to, this waterfall plays a key role in the water treatment system - it aerates the water as it travels from one pond to another.

3353.title: Feeding the ducks - tempting, but discouraged
3353.summary: Ducks love bread, but it's not good for them - while you might not be feeding them much, please consider that you may be the tenth visitor today.

3354.title: On your bike!
3354.summary: There are numerous shared trails through the parklands, though this one provides the easiest passage for wheels of all types.

3355.title: Spend some quality time with the ducks
3355.summary: Seats like this one are dotted throughout the parklands, providing a rest stop and an opportunity to watch the water birds .

3356.title: Darebin Amphitheatre
3356.summary: A perfectly placed amphitheatre, it is a popular spot for large family picnics, concerts and festivals.

3357.title: Brand new public toilets
3357.summary: At the Separation Street entrance to the parklands, you'll find a car park and these brand new public toilets - clean, accessible and unisex.

3358.title: Keep up to date with parklands happenings
3358.summary: Want to know what's happening in the parklands?  You can check out the DPA Facebook - but if you're passing by, you're sure to find something interesting on this notice board.

3359.title: Environment Centre - learn more and meet the rangers
3359.summary: Home to the DCMC rangers and a place to learn about parklands history and management - pictured here, Ranger Pete has played a leading role in creation of the parklands over the past 25 years.

3360.title: Kensington Neighbourhood House (KNH)
3360.summary: KNH runs various activities including vocational education, English language lessons, digital literacy, arts and crafts, social groups, weekend workshops and children's activities etc etc

3361.title: 6th Melbourne Scouts
3361.summary: 6th Melbourne Scout Group has a proud 100 year history, and is the City of Melbourne’s only remaining Scout Group.

3362.title: Kumquat Tree
3362.summary: McCracken st is a delight. Many of the beautiful cottages have citrus trees and lavender bushes spilling out on to the sidewalk.

3363.title: Unnamed park.
3363.summary: This park makes a lovely addition to the walk. Often there are warbling magpies to accompany you and there is a swing set and benches to enjoy the serenity.

3364.title: Kensington Town Hall
3364.summary: The Kensington Town Hall is a beautiful old building and an important civic space for the local community.

osm.name: Kensington Town Hall
osm.display_name: Kensington Town Hall, 30, Bellair Street, Kensington, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3031, Australia

3365.title: Pepper Cafe
3365.summary: Pepper Cafe sits at the base of bustling Newmarket train station, on the popular shopping strip of Pin Oak Crescent in Flemington.

3366.title: The HV McKay Rural Discovery Centre - Campaspe Run
3366.summary: Elmore’s tribute to the Sunshine Harvester, early pioneers and the sheep and grain industries. Campaspe Run is home to Elmore’s Community Quilt and has a fabulous gift shop. Open 7 days a week.

3367.title: Overhead Railway Bridge
3367.summary: The Overhead Bridge was opened on June 16 1928 (costing £454 to build) and removed Nov 24 1980. It was sold to the Elmore Progress Association and today links Campaspe Run and the EPA Museum.

3368.title: Elmore Railway Station Water Tower
3368.summary: Built in 1870 to supply water to steam trains, the 18'x15' tower was made from locally made bricks. Water was pumped from the Campaspe River. The tower was donated to the EPA in 1972.

3369.title: Elmore Railway Station
3369.summary: Opened 1870, originally named Runnymede Railway Station, the station was renamed Elmore Railway Station in 1876. The Queen travelled by train through Elmore on her 1954 tour.

osm.name: Elmore
osm.display_name: Elmore, Northern Highway, Elmore, City of Greater Bendigo, Victoria, 3558, Australia

3370.title: Elmore Progress Association (EPA) Museum
3370.summary: Situated in the Railway Station Buildings, this volunteer run Museum is free and well worth a visit. Open Wednesdays from 9.30-2.

3371.title: Cardwell Street 1920s - Heritage sign
3371.summary: One of four signs installed as an initiative of the Elmore Progress Association. This sign features a photo of Cardwell St including the original Victoria Hotel.

3372.title: Cardwell Street
3372.summary: Gazetted as the main street. Named after Rt. Hon. Edward Cardwell, Secretary of State for the Colonies, 1864. Traffic flow altered when a new bridge was built & Margaret St was constructed in the 60s.

osm.name: Cardwell Street
osm.display_name: Cardwell Street, Elmore, City of Greater Bendigo, Victoria, 3558, Australia

3373.title: Former Bank of NSW/Westpac
3373.summary: This double story building on the South side of the street is now privately owned and operates as Elmore Old Wares.

3374.title: Elmore Plaque Project
3374.summary: Wander down Cardwell Street and learn about some of the historic buildings by reading the plaques. The Elmore Plaque Project is an initiative funded by property owners.

3375.title: Former Parson’s Store
3375.summary: This store was established in 1893 and traded as a general store until 1982. Today, Parson’s Store is used as a display area, storage and workroom for the Elmore Miniature Railway.

3376.title: Michie Street
3376.summary: Named after Hon. Sir Archibald Michie, MLC, MLA, Attorney-General.

3377.title: Athenaeum Hall
3377.summary: Built in 1885 for £800, & opened in 1886, the Athenaeum Hall was designed by W.C. Vahland & built by Mr G. Galbraith.

3378.title: Elmore Scout Hall
3378.summary: This former Methodist Church, built in 1874, was purchased as the Scout Hall in 1983.

3379.title: Michie Street Play Space
3379.summary: The Michie Street Play Space features play equipment, drink fountain, seating, shade sails and a lush lawn space at the rear.

3380.title: Clarke Street
3380.summary: Named after John Clarke, owner of Boramboot or Stewart’s Plains station from 1850-1852.

osm.name: Clarke Street
osm.display_name: Clarke Street, Elmore, City of Greater Bendigo, Victoria, 3558, Australia

3381.title: Uniting Church
3381.summary: Originally St Andrew’s Presbyterian Church (WC Vahland design) opened June 18 1899, the Uniting Church was formed by an amalgamation of Methodist and Presbyterian Churches in 1969.

3382.title: Elmore and District Preschool
3382.summary: The Preschool was built as an Infant Welfare Centre (circa 1960s) and extended as a Preschool in 1972.

3383.title: Elmore Memorial Hall
3383.summary: In 1920 it was proposed to build a Memorial to the local service men of World War 1 & provide work for some returned service men. The information board provides greater detail.

3384.title: Elmore CFA Fire Station
3384.summary: The Fire Station was opened on September 26 1972, replacing the one in Railway Place (1910-1972). The former site is now known as Progress Park near the Raywood Road Rail Crossing.

3385.title: Elmore Police Station
3385.summary: The current Station was built recently to replace the former station, opened in 1968. Before this time, the Police Station was situated diagonally across the intersection, now a private residence.

3386.title: Law Courts
3386.summary: The building next to the Police Station was built as the Law Courts but is now privately owned and used as a Solicitors and Accountants office.

3387.title: The Old Water Tower
3387.summary: Used to store the town’s water supply (pumped from the Campaspe). The pumping station was on rails to move up the bank in times of flood. The station also produced the town’s electricity until 1948.

3388.title: Coffee Palace/James’s Bakery
3388.summary: Originally a Coffee Palace & later James’s Bakery which was well known as the place for lovely bread fresh from the oven. This building (South side of Cardwell St) is now a private residence.

3389.title: Jeffrey Street
3389.summary: Named after the Jeffrey brothers who owned Burnewang Station from 1852 to 1867.

3390.title: Campaspe River
3390.summary: The Campaspe River rises in the Kyneton area & enters The River Murray at Echuca. Lake Eppalock (constructed by State Rivers & Water Supply Commission of Victoria 1961-64) is situated on the Campaspe.

3391.title: Campaspe River Natural Play Space
3391.summary: The Elmore Progress Association in conjunction with the City of Greater Bendigo are currently creating a natural play space on a former playground site. Drink fountain, seating and parking available.

3392.title: Campaspe River Walking Track
3392.summary: The Campaspe River Walking Track meanders alongside the captivating Campaspe River. Dotted along the track are information boards which highlight the unique attributes of this stretch of the river.

3393.title: Campaspe River Pepper Tree Avenue
3393.summary: The Avenue of pepper trees between the Campaspe River Bridge and Childers Street along Campaspe Street was planted on August 10 1898. The trees were donated by the Elmore Water Trust.

3394.title: Senior Citizens Flats (now Public Housing)
3394.summary: The Catholic Church donated the triangle land (junction of Campaspe & Jeffrey Streets) to the former Shire of Huntly to build flats for Senior Citizens.

3395.title: Our Lady of the Sacred Heart Catholic Church
3395.summary: The Church (WC Vahland design) was built in 1904. The Presbytery is next door.

3396.title: Elmore Senior Citizens
3396.summary: The Elmore Senior Citizens Clubrooms were built in 1973.

3397.title: Brummy’s Seat
3397.summary: An Elm tree (which has since been removed) had a circular seat placed around it and was known as Brummy’s Seat after Mr Bremner, blacksmith & Fire Brigade Captain, who loved to smoke his pipe there.

3398.title: Shopping Strip (Railway Place/Northern Highway)
3398.summary: Cardwell Street was the original main street, but with the construction of the new bridge & Margaret St, traffic flow changed & Railway Place/Northern Highway became the new main street.

3399.title: Elmore Miniature Railway/Apex Park
3399.summary: Built on the site of the Cohuna Goods yard, the Elmore Miniature Railway (EMR) line extends for 1.5kms, with the EMR station situated at Apex Park.

3400.title: Campaspe Run Play Space
3400.summary: Situated in the centre of town between the Railway station & Campaspe Run, the Play Space has lush lawns, parking, public toilets, picnic tables and a BBQ. A great space to enjoy a picnic.

3401.title: Dandenong Civic Square
3401.summary: The Civic Square is a great new meeting place and the perfect place to start and finish the walk.

3402.title: Rob's British Butcher
3402.summary: Visit Rob's British Butchers for home made UK Produce. Pork Pies, Black Pudding, Haggis, British style Bacon & Gammon, Gourmet Sausages and much more!

3403.title: Rye Crust Polish Bakery
3403.summary: Rye Crust Bakery is  family owned and operated. The Bakery makes great cakes, biscuits, pies, sweets, soups, salads, bagels, cabbage rolls, pierogi and much more

3404.title: Little India
3404.summary: Little India is the strip of Indian shops in and around Foster Street. It has a wide variety of Indian food, clothes, accessories and even an Indian museum.

3405.title: Dandenong Train Station
3405.summary: Dandenong Train Station is right in the middle of downtown Dandenong, with lots of services to and from Melbourne CBD.

3406.title: Afghan Bazaar
3406.summary: The Afghan Bazaar is the name of the strip of Afghani shops in and around Thomas Street. There is a growing number of Afghani restaurants and clothes stores here.

3407.title: Maiwand Tandory Hot Bread Bakery
3407.summary: The Bakery specialises in tasty Tandoori breads, the breads are baked right in front of customers eyes in the three in-store ovens.

3408.title: Plenty of nice seats along the way
3408.summary: The newly improved Palm Plaza provides plenty of seats and shade, great place to sit and digest!

3409.title: Dandenong Market
3409.summary: At Dandenong Market you will find almost every ingredient you can imagine—not to mention some you might never have dreamed of—making it the perfect place for anyone with a passion for cook.

osm.name: Dandenong Arcade Fish Market
osm.display_name: Dandenong Arcade Fish Market, Dandenong Arcade, Dandenong, Melbourne, City of Greater Dandenong, Victoria, 3177, Australia

3410.title: A1 Lebanese Bakery
3410.summary: The Bakery serves authentic Middle Eastern and Lebanese food as well as stocking a large range of grocery products direct from all over the Middle East and Lebanon.

3411.title: Cardinia Cultural Centre
3411.summary: Complete with cafe, toilets, a theatre and some local artwork. Also available for function hire.

3412.title: Duck feeding frenzy!
3412.summary: Throughout the loop, there are multiple piers - perfect for fishing or feeding ducks. The  pier at the eastern end of the lake, is the best spot to feed the local ducks and swans .

3413.title: Amphitheatre  and grassed area
3413.summary: A lot of local events are held in the  Amphitheatre. It is also  in front of a huge grassed area, perfect for playing sports.

3414.title: Watch your step...
3414.summary: Although most of the lake has no safety railing, the footpaths are quite wide, and the lake is very  shallow.

3415.title: Take a breather.
3415.summary: Throughout the whole loop, there is plenty of seating with amazing lake views.

3416.title: BBQ's, playground and toilets.
3416.summary: At the western end of the loop is a great picnic area and playground, complete with multiple BBQ's, toilets and tonnes of play equipment - it's the perfect place to bring the family!

3417.title: A little artwork..
3417.summary:
Huh? Where did these guys come from?

"Segmented Landscape" - Jennyfer Stratman

3418.title: Just keep walking, just keep walking..
3418.summary: The whole loop is averaged at 2,000 steps (1.5km) which is a fifth of the recommended amount of daily steps.

3419.title: Fountain
3419.summary: Have a sit down and watch the fountain for a while. Very relaxing!

3420.title: Did someone say Swans?
3420.summary: Try and spot these guys around the loop! They can be out in the open, or hiding in the reeds..

3421.title: Fishing!
3421.summary: A great pier perfect for catching fish out on the lake.

3422.title: Wheelchair and Pram friendly!
3422.summary: The entire walk is surfaced in either concreted or boardwalk. Suitable for pretty much everyone!

3423.title: Start of Guide Track
3423.summary: Its a 200m walk along Guide Track to the start of the Button-grass walk.

3424.title: Friends of Bunyip State Park
3424.summary: Friends of Bunyip State Park developed the walk over three years with the aid of Parks Victoria Community Grant funding.  For more information about the group see http://bit.ly/VTBsXk.

3425.title: Hakea
3425.summary: Look out for hakeas, particularly along the first part of the walk.  Hakeas need bushfires to propagate. The fire opens the woody fruits on the parent plant, releasing the seeds to germinate.

3426.title: Heathy Woodland
3426.summary: Walkers wandering through a forest of Silver-leaf Stringybark and Narrow-leaf Peppermint trees.  Look out for wattles, hakeas and tea-trees in the shrub.

3427.title: Skink
3427.summary: Pay attention to where you step.  You might spot a skink out enjoying the sun.  They are well camouflaged to avoid detection.

3428.title: Numbered Markers
3428.summary: For lots of detail about the abundant flora along the walk, pick up a copy of the flora notes at the beginning of the walk.  The notes have matching numbered markers along the route.

3429.title: Wet Heathland
3429.summary: Notice the dramatic changes in flora as we drop down into the wet heathland areas along the walk. You will also be treated to excellent views of the nearby Black Snake Range.

3430.title: Boardwalk
3430.summary: A boardwalk allows the waker to keep their feet dry while giving the opportunity to explore parts of the wet heathland that would otherwise be hard to access.

3431.title: Button-grass and Spike Wattle
3431.summary: Sedges, such as Button-grass, are tufted plants and over time develop quite dense and tall stools from which the leaves grow. These tufts are elevated above the water-table.

3432.title: The dam
3432.summary: The dam is feed by Button-grass creek.  Notice the many water plants and ferns that boarder the waters edge, a habitat for birds, frogs and insects.

3433.title: Make some friends
3433.summary: Say hello to these beautiful creatures on your way

3434.title: Autumn beauty
3434.summary: These beautiful trees create splendid colour in Autumn and lush cover in summer ensuring that you are shaded from the harsh summer sun. Not to mention they are pretty easy on the eyes!

3435.title: Tyre swing
3435.summary: This hidden gem has a picnic table and a tyre swing making it the perfect spot to stop, rest and play.

3436.title: Old railway
3436.summary: Take a stroll under the old railway line and take in some of our history. Make sure you turn to the right to keep on the track!

3437.title: Over path bridge
3437.summary: This is another of Wodonga's many excellent under road paths. Not only is it practical in removing the need to cross in front on traffic, but it is an engineering beauty

3438.title: Skate Park
3438.summary: There is a skate park here that is incredibly popular and it looks like bigger and better things are on their way!

osm.name: James Scott Memorial Skate Park
osm.display_name: James Scott Memorial Skate Park, Pearce Street, Wodonga, City of Wodonga, Victoria, 3690, Australia

3439.title: Oval & Playground
3439.summary: Willow park is home to an oval and play area and is great recreational hub. Perfect for a picnic of a short rest before you begin the return part of the circuit

3440.title: Netball courts
3440.summary: For anyone wanting to spend some time at a netball court, these are tucked away at Martin Park and there is a gate from the walking track to the park

3441.title: Nature at its finest
3441.summary: The path is edged by beautiful trees almost the whole way along. Providing much needed shade in the warmer months and an excellent display of colour in Autumn, they are also home to many types of Bird

3442.title: Football Oval
3442.summary: If you are walking along this path, why not stop for a kick of football on the way. The oval is well manicured and is home to permanent AFL posts. A little friendly competition never hurt anyone...

3443.title: Under road crossing
3443.summary: Avoid crossing this busy road by taking the optional path underneath the thoroughfare. Great low risk option for people walking with groups of children or animals.

3444.title: Les Stone Park Wetlands
3444.summary: A great spot to try your hand at fishing. Even better if you have young children as it offers a safe space to teach them the skills.

3445.title: Pirate Ship
3445.summary: This play area is great. A safe space that lets the imagination run wild. Grab your eye patch and perch a bird on your shoulder and see what adventure you end up on

3446.title: Map and information
3446.summary: Start off by having a look at the information board to orientate yourself. There are public toilets, barbeque and picnic tables here.

3447.title: Yarra River
3447.summary: Yarra River is a great spot for a dip on a warm day. You'll be sharing the river with the ducks and other bird life! You can launch your canoes from here.

3448.title: Begin Blue Tongue Bend Walk
3448.summary: Marker for the start of the Blue Tongue Bend Walk. Only a couple of kilometres of blissful bushland to wander through.

3449.title: Bushy goodness
3449.summary: Take a sniff or two of the fresh air around you.

3450.title: River view
3450.summary: You'll be able to glimpse the river from the track at various sections.

3451.title: Wild mushrooms tour
3451.summary: Q: Did you hear the joke about the fungus? A: I could tell it to you, but it might need time to grow on you.

3452.title: More mushies
3452.summary: Q: Why did the Fungi leave the party? A: There wasn't mushroom.

3453.title: A darker variety
3453.summary: Q: Why did the Mushroom get invited to all the parties? A: 'Cos he's a fungi!

3454.title: Stuck on you
3454.summary: Ok, I've run out of fungi jokes. This one's the biggest that I came across during the walk.

3455.title: Dappled sunlight through the forest
3455.summary: A perfect location to practice your camera taking skills, or simply enjoy the light and shadows.

3456.title: Slightly steep sections
3456.summary: There are occasional uphills and downhills on the track, perfectly manageable - just distract yourself with the scenery while you make your way up.

3457.title: Last view of mushrooms
3457.summary: Group of fungi last seen making their own stairway to heaven.

3458.title: Braybrook Community Hub
3458.summary: The hub is where it’s at in Braybrook. It offers indoor and outdoor spaces for the Braybrook community. Classes on offer at low or no cost. Join with a friend or make new friends at the hub!

osm.name: Braybrook Community Hub
osm.display_name: Braybrook Community Hub, Churchill Avenue, Braybrook, Melbourne, City of Maribyrnong, Victoria, 3019, Australia

3459.title: Braybrook Library
3459.summary: This library is buzzing with families reading and learning together. The friendly staff are happy to help with information. There are books available to borrow in Vietnamese, Chinese and English.

3460.title: Basketball and Tennis Courts
3460.summary: Gather your friends and start training for the WNBL or NBL by shooting some hoops at Braybrook Park. Or work on your tennis serve at the tennis court nearby.

3461.title: Skinner Reserve
3461.summary: Home to the Sunshine Football Club Victorian Football Association (VFA) from 1959 until 1989. The club colours were navy blue and white. The sporting oval is now used primarily for soccer.

osm.name: Skinner Reserve
osm.display_name: Skinner Reserve, Adamson Street, Braybrook, Melbourne, City of Maribyrnong, Victoria, 3019, Australia

3462.title: Dinjerra Primary School
3462.summary: Dinjerra is proudly multicultural with over 25 different nationalities represented among the student cohort. Classes are kept  small to maximise teaching and learning.

osm.name: Dinjerra Primary School
osm.display_name: Dinjerra Primary School, 44, South Road, Braybrook, Melbourne, City of Maribyrnong, Victoria, 3019, Australia

3463.title: Western English Language School (WELS)
3463.summary: WELS offers an intensive program in English Language prior to enrolment in a mainstream setting.  A Breakfast Program runs for all students at the Braybrook site.

3464.title: Braybrook Commons Community Garden
3464.summary: The Braybrook Commons Community Garden offers a shared community space for locals to come together and grow and share produce. There are individual plots and some communal beds available at low cost.

osm.name: Braybrook Commons Community Garden
osm.display_name: Braybrook Commons Community Garden, Melrose Street, Braybrook, Melbourne, City of Maribyrnong, Victoria, 3019, Australia

3465.title: Lance Reichstein Playground (photo from Council plans)
3465.summary: The Lance Reichstein playground was built in 1999 following donations from the community, businesses, council and the Lance Reichstein Foundation. It is being rebuilt following a fire in 2015.

3466.title: Double Canoe Tree
3466.summary: The Goolum Goolum Aboriginal Co-operative Ltd placed this here in 1997 after the family on whose property the tree stood at in Lubeck until 1977 donated it.

3467.title: Weir Park
3467.summary: Formerly called Jaycees Park. This was developed during the beautification in the late 60s as well as building of the new weir in 1968.

3468.title: Fitness Equipment
3468.summary: A chance to break up your walk with some exercises along the way.  Choose from 4 pieces of equipment

3469.title: Horsham Fly Fishers and Trout Anglers Club
3469.summary: Due to the drought trout fishing has not really been possible.  With the lakes now having water and fish added, trout fishing has once again become popular

3470.title: Apex Island and Playground
3470.summary: This is a man-made island built by the local Apex clubs during the river beautification of the 1960s and 70s.

3471.title: Rowing Club
3471.summary: This was built in 1976.  The club was formed in 1883 although their first regatta was not held until 1972

osm.name: Rowing Club Pontoon (Main)
osm.display_name: Rowing Club Pontoon (Main), Eastgate Drive, Horsham, Rural City of Horsham, Victoria, 3400, Australia

3472.title: Apex Club
3472.summary: This is the home of one of the local Apex clubs.  Up until the 1980s you could hire paddleboats from here.

3473.title: Old Horsham Weir and Swimming Pool Historical Sign
3473.summary: Site of Horsham Weir 1875-1959.  Used as swimming pool until the new weir was built

3474.title: Flood Markers
3474.summary: These indicate three of Horshams largest floods, in 1909, 1981 and more recently 2011.  The second is an indication of the water height of the 1909 flood if the river beautification was effective.

3475.title: Soundshell
3475.summary: The soundshell was built in 1986 and is the site of many events including the Kannamaroo Festival and Carols by Candlelight.

3476.title: Sawyer Park
3476.summary: This land was owned by the Sawyer family who ran brickworks on this site from 1874-1939. At the eastern end of the park is a relica kilm built from bricks made at the brickworks.

osm.name: Sawyer Park
osm.display_name: Sawyer Park, Memorial Drive, Horsham, Rural City of Horsham, Victoria, 3400, Australia

3477.title: Memorial Cenotaph and Vietnam Memorials
3477.summary: The Memorial Cenotaph was designed and most of the erection completed by the RSL and volunteers in the town. Opened in 2004

3478.title: History of Bridges and Tramline Historical Sign
3478.summary: A horse drawn Tramway opened in 1885 transported road-making materials from McKenzie Creek (six miles south of Horsham) on second hand railway trucks

3479.title: Seeliger's Brewery
3479.summary: Ernst Seeliger worked as a brewer in South Australia before purchasing the Wimmera Brewery from Treacy and Smith at Meadowbank near the showground.

3480.title: Swinging Bridge to Old Golf Course Sign
3480.summary: This is the site of the 4th tee of Horsham's second Golf Course. Players hit across Burnt Creek.  A pedestrian swing bridge crossed the river to reach the course.

3481.title: Old Pumping Station
3481.summary: Walk south towards the river to find the sign.  The pumphouse for Horsham's first reticulated water supply was built near this spot about 1875

3482.title: Corio Shopping Centre
3482.summary: Opened in 1973 The Corio Shopping Centre has a range of  shops, supermarkets, major banks, Centrelink, Medicare, Jobservice agencies and specialty food stores including Halal and Asian grocers

osm.name: Corio Shopping Centre
osm.display_name: Corio Shopping Centre, Caithness Crescent, Corio, Geelong, City of Greater Geelong, Victoria, 3214, Australia

3483.title: Corio Bay Medical Centre
3483.summary: The Corio Bay Medical centre cater for people from non-english speaking backgrounds and provides access to Doctors that speak many languages. The Centre is open Mon-Fi 8.30-6.00pm, Sat 8.30-12.30pm.

osm.name: Corio Bay Medical Centre
osm.display_name: Corio Bay Medical Centre, 15, Kiewa Street, Corio, Geelong, City of Greater Geelong, Victoria, 3214, Australia

3484.title: Northern Bay Secondary College Goldsworthy Campus Years 9-12
3484.summary: NBC was formed in 2011 as a result of a merger of nine schools into a multi-campus college. Today there are 5 Campus's. Four P-8 and one 9-12. Students that developed this walk attend this school.

3485.title: Library and Waterworld Site
3485.summary:
The John Drysdale Corio Library opened in 1970 and provides free universal access to local and global information sources.
Waterworld is a Council Health and fitness centre with swimming pools

3486.title: The fOrT
3486.summary: Is a youth centre for all young people aged 12-25 years. Offers activities and support to young people in the North of Geelong and youth have direct influence over the type of activities offered.

osm.name: The Fort
osm.display_name: The Fort, St Georges Road, Corio, Geelong, City of Greater Geelong, Victoria, 3214, Australia

3487.title: Stead Park
3487.summary: Stead Park is an open space reserve supporting a diverse range of formal sports and informal recreations including the first ever Pet Park for dogs to socialise.

osm.name: Stead Park Darts Club
osm.display_name: Stead Park Darts Club, Johns Street, Corio, Geelong, City of Greater Geelong, Victoria, 3214, Australia

3488.title: Detroit Cresent Shopping Centre
3488.summary: Ali Supermarket providing Halal foods, Halal butcher and Asian Food Grocer can be found here.

3489.title: Shell Club
3489.summary: Oringinally established in 1953 as a clubhouse by a handful of workers from Shell. Shell Club is now a sports and social centre with dining facilities.

3490.title: Corio Community Health
3490.summary: Provides access to a range of health services such as dental, mental health and communtiy nursing. Corio Community Health also has refugee health nurses on site.

osm.name: Corio Community Health Centre
osm.display_name: Corio Community Health Centre, Gellibrand Street, Corio, Geelong, City of Greater Geelong, Victoria, 3214, Australia

3491.title: Broad Tidal Flats
3491.summary: Port Phillip Bay is shallow on the western side, so at low tide vast areas of sand are accessible. This beach has been set aside as "Dog Friendly"

3492.title: City Views
3492.summary: From out on the flats you get broad views around the bay and some great views of the city.

3493.title: Socialising
3493.summary: Dogs (and humans) love to socialise - why not do it at the beach!

3494.title: The Old Shipwreck
3494.summary: It looks like this used to be a motorised barge.

3495.title: Rocks
3495.summary: This outcrop of volcanic rock forms a natural barrier. Most people keep to the Altona side of the rocks, and the Williamstown side has more wildlife and the shores are lined with mangroves.

3496.title: Crab
3496.summary: There are literally thousands if not millions of soldier crabs going about their business.

3498.title: A Bit of a Romp
3498.summary: A good time was had by all!

3675.summary: As you travel up the eastern side of the peak, you get fantastic views out over Corio and Port Phillip Bays.  In the distance you should be able to make out Arthurs Seat and the Melbourne CBD skyline.

3676.summary: Look down into the forest below and you'll see this monumental rock sculpture depicting Bunjil, the creator spirit of the local Wathaurong People.  It was built for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.

3677.summary: The track keeps going up, but by this point you've pretty much reached the top.  Just take it slow and enjoy the views on the way up!

3678.title: Face in the rock
3678.summary: Notice anyone, sorry anything, in the rocks? Look for a group of rocks up the hill to the left of the track and you might spot this guy amongst them.

3679.title: Lookout rock
3679.summary: Just off the track to the right is a massive rock, providing a great natural lookout through the ranges to the north

3680.title: Split rock
3680.summary: There are a lot of interesting rock formations on this walk, but I particularly liked this one, a split rock between two others.

3681.title: Rock shelter
3681.summary: As the track heads west, you start to get views opening up in that direction.  But there's also this massive rock with a large overhang space below.

3682.title: Flowering shrubs

3683.title: Lizard

3684.title: The path back

3685.title: Lookout

3825.summary: This privately owned cottage was once the residence for Primary School Headmasters. After many years abandoned, the current owners have restored its charm.

3826.summary: The site of historic Majorca Primary School (No. 764), built in 1868. This grand school was damaged in the 1985 fire but, allegedly demolished and removed before restoration assessment was made.

3827.title: Majorca Post Office, Galloways Road
3827.summary: Built in 1871, this old Post and Telegraph Office was once the key communication point in the township. With its original front counter and post boxes, it is now a private residence.

3828.title: Site of the Majorca Court House
3828.summary: Little is known about the Majorca Court House. It was demolished early in the 1900’s but the site indentation and some of the huge bluestone footings can still be seen on the vacant land.

3829.title: Former Methodist Church
3829.summary: Now a private home, this imposing Gothic styled Church overlooks the once-bustling township.

3830.title: Majorca bushland

3831.title: Church of England site
3831.summary: The St James Church of England was destroyed in the 1985 bushfires and only loose bricks remain as a sad reminder of the past.

3832.title: Standpipe and memorial trough

3834.title: Harp of Erin Hotel remains
3834.summary: The bustling Harp Of Erin Hotel remained in business from the late 1800’s until the early 1900’s, finally falling into disrepair. There are only a few bluestones remaining now.

3835.title: Former London Chartered Bank
3835.summary: Built in 1865, this grand building with block-work render and arched windows and doors is classified by the National Trust. Of note are the arched boot scrapers beside the doorway.
