3862.title: Steep incline down to the wetlands and river walk
3862.summary: Watch out the steep track as it is very difficult without an assistant pushing or good brakes.

3863.title: Beautiful Bushland
3863.summary: There are four major vegetation communities within Yellow Gum Park. They include grassy woodland, escarpment woodland, box ironbark woodland and riparian woodland.

3864.title: Walker
3864.summary: When walking allow yourself to be immersed in birdsong, the sound of the flowing river and the beautiful flora.

3865.title: A reminder of the lakes history
3865.summary: This area used to be a mineral quarry.  It closed in the early 1970s as a result of ground water seeping into the quarry hole. The ground water seepage has produced the lake we see today.

3866.title: The lake
3866.summary: The blue lake is named for its turquoise blue colour at certain times of the year and is home to birds including Eurasian coots, Purple Swamphens and Australasian Grebes.

3867.title: Australasian Grebe
3867.summary: They form small flocks during the non-breeding season and dive underwater when alarmed.

3868.title: Rainbow Lorikeet
3868.summary: Not so hard to spot with their wonderfully coloured feathers, Rainbow Lorikeets feed mainly on nectar.  Both male and female Lorikeets feed their young.

3869.title: Laughing Kookaburra
3869.summary: Kookaburras hunt by perching on branches and swooping onto their prey below.  This one has caught a small snack for lunch.  Larger prey like snakes are bashed against branches before being eaten.

3870.title: Look high and low
3870.summary: This areas environmental values are of national and state significance.  All native flora in the area must not be picked.

3871.title: Sulpher crested Cockatoo
3871.summary: You'll probably hear one before you see one.  Their loud, harsh calls can be heard from quite a distance.  They breed in hollows in old growth trees.

3872.title: White Cedar
3872.summary: Look for these deciduous trees on the left of the path as you pass the Children's Garden.

3873.title: Jacaranda
3873.summary: Stop in at the mighty Jacaranda tree on the left. What stage of its annual life cycle is it up to? Don't forget to record what you see on the ClimateWatch app or recording sheet.

3874.title: Firewheel Tree
3874.summary: This beautiful native tree on your left has striking red flowers. Are they out today?

3875.title: Illawarra Flame Tree
3875.summary: An iconic Australian tree which flowers in spring. Scientists think that these trees and others might flower earlier due to climate change, so please record what you see.

3876.title: English Oak
3876.summary: This tree can be quite tricky to find, but if you spot it, record what stage of its annual cycle it is at. Leaves falling? Flowers opening? Submit your sightings on the ClimateWatch app

3877.title: Silky Oak
3877.summary: This giant tree is just past the cafe. Silky Oaks aren't related to other oak trees at all but are actually a species of Grevilla and are very popular with birds!

3878.title: Lake
3878.summary: As you walk around the lake, look for birds. Dusky moorhens, black swans, willie wagtails, and many other ClimateWatch species love this beautiful spot.

3879.title: Silver Banksia and Victorian Christmas Bush
3879.summary: As the tip of Long Island you will find both of these native plants. Check to see if they are flowering, and be sure to smell the minty leaves of the VIC Christmas Bush

3880.title: Marri
3880.summary: The last stop on the ClimateWatch trail is the Western Australian Marri eucalypt. Check to see if it is flowering, or whether it is sporting has any gumnuts (known as honky nuts in the west).

3881.title: Native flowers and bushes
3881.summary: There are plenty of native trees and flowers planted just a few steps back from the beach.  There are a few grassy areas that are shady and away from the sand if you need refuge from the beach.

3882.title: Walk, skate or scoot
3882.summary: It's great that the paths for walkers and cyclists are separated for most of the trail. The pedestrian trail is smooth, well maintained and clearly marked.  Or you can simply walk along the beach!

3883.title: Beach as far as you can see
3883.summary: Beach with a lovely view of the sea. Read a book, have a nap, bring a picnic, build a sandcastle, go for a swim... the possibilities are endless.

3884.title: Ships ahoy - playground
3884.summary: A fabulous wooden construction that looks like a ship!  Great for kids to clamber and explore.  Plenty of shade provided as well.

3885.title: Information boards
3885.summary: Information boards are great for telling you more about the area - the birds, Indigenous culture, names of local plants etc.

3886.title: Barraimal (Emu) Constellation
3886.summary: The Emu Constellation according to the Boon Wurrung people. More information available on nearby information boards.

3887.title: Black swans
3887.summary: We saw a pair of canoodling black swans!

3888.title: Middle Brighton Baths
3888.summary: The legendary Ice Berger swimmers swim here. They swim all year around, even in winter! There is also a gym, steam room, cafe and restaurant - all housed in a lovely historic art deco building.

osm.name: Middle Brighton Baths
osm.display_name: Middle Brighton Baths, 251, Esplanade, Brighton, Melbourne, City of Bayside, Victoria, 3186, Australia

3889.title: Royal Brighton Yacht Club and dog off lead area
3889.summary: Great view of the yachts from here. This is also a dog off lead area, though off lead times do change depending on the time of year.

3890.title: Inspiration chairs
3890.summary: Take a seat and be inspired, reflect and celebrate! A nice touch - each chair has a little plaque with a theme.  This one's The Togetherness Chair

3891.title: Brighton Beach Boxes
3891.summary: The Brighton Beach Boxes are iconic. All painted in bright colours, they're popular with photographers and tourists.  Some of the boxes have wonderful artwork painted on them too.

3892.title: Mosaic
3892.summary: A few pieces of colourful mosaic can be found here.

3893.title: Drinks for 2 and 4 legged walkers!
3893.summary: There are plenty of drinking fountains throughout the walk.

3894.title: Good spot for a picnic lunch
3894.summary: Table and chairs outside the old angling club, great spot to view the ducks and other water birds

3895.title: BBQ and Playground
3895.summary: Next to the footy ground is a great playground with BBQ facilities

3896.title: Heaven for dog walking
3896.summary: There is plenty to keep even the most inquisitive dog occupied along the way.

3897.title: Careful crossing the busy road
3897.summary: Wait for green pedestrian lights before crossing, don't try to cross this road without the traffic lights.

3898.title: View from bridge
3898.summary: Looking down onto the tranquil river below the busy bridge, makes you wish you were a platypus living in peace.

3899.title: Wide open spaces
3899.summary: Wyndham Park is the perfect spot to run around, kick the footy or simply get away from it all.

3900.title: Connecting point with other walking tracks
3900.summary: You have lots of choices where to walk from here.

3901.title: Very cool new orange pedestrian bridge

3902.title: Coffee time?
3902.summary: Why not have a break and take the stairs/paths up to one of the many cafes along Watton Street

3903.title: Better than any classroom
3903.summary: The local primary school visits the park to help the kids stay active and learn about their beautiful backyard.

3904.title: Old public swimming Pool
3904.summary: Now it seems to be mainly used by the ducks

3905.title: What a view!
3905.summary: A sanctuary in the middle of Werribee

3906.title: Choose your own adventure
3906.summary: We picked the shortest route for this trip as we had a toddler in tow and the sun was getting warm by mid-morning.

3907.title: View from the top
3907.summary: The view of the surrounding valley is pretty spectacular from here.  The hill is steep so it's a great workout if you need to get your heart rate up.

3908.title: Extensive revegetation
3908.summary: Since the park was declared in 1972, a great deal of work has been done to restore the indigenous vegetation to the area. (See Parknotes)

3909.title: Picnic table and seats
3909.summary: A lovely shady spot for lunch or a cuppa.

3910.title: The Organ Pipes
3910.summary: More than a million years ago, lava from nearby volcanoes flowed into the area, cooled, hardened, then cracked, forming the columns that we see today.

3911.title: Popular walk for families with younger children
3911.summary: On our visit, we met at least 10 other children, which confirms that the walk is suitable for young ones too.

3912.title: Exploring Jacksons Creek
3912.summary: The shores of the creek is a good spot for young explorers.

3913.title: View upstream
3913.summary: The creek is cool and shady if you need a break from the heat of the sun.

3914.title: Start walk at bridge, Bluff Road end, in clockwise direction
3914.summary: Notice the lake sign made from red gum.  Timber cutting for firewood was the reason St. Leonards was originally settled by Captain George Ward Cole.

3915.title: Optional detour to Mount St Leonards, a short steep walk
3915.summary:
From the top there are expansive views over the town, bay and surrounds. 

The hill was formed when the man-made lake was excavated.

3916.title: Continue along the shaded track & notice the birds
3916.summary:
Frequently there is active bird life - swamp hens, coots, cormorants.  Can you hear frogs?  

Distance markers are painted on the track.

3917.title: Walk past the Sewerage Pump Station & take rest in the shade
3917.summary:
Around the bend behind the native trees, the Sewerage Pump takes the town waste to the Portarlington Sewerage facility. 

Now you leave the wooded area and walk towards the Recreation Reserve.

3918.title: Stroll through the 'Len Trewin Reserve'
3918.summary:
Len secured a 99 year lease when he & others started the cricket club in the 1940's.  A handmade wrought iron sign over an entrance can be seen from the road. 

Public toilets located here.

3919.title: Pass Cole St Reserve Hall & Clubrooms
3919.summary: This is a cluster of community facilities for recreation and service activities.  The long anticipated Men's Shed will be here when renovations are carried out.

3920.title: Optional detour to see wetlands
3920.summary: Cross Cole Street with care. Here you will find tennis, bocce and a children's playground.  This area is popular in summer.

3921.title: Continue along the winding track
3921.summary:
This wetland seasonally floods & attracts wading birds such as the Royal Spoonbill, herons & egrets. 

Watch for bike riders.

3922.title: Cross McBeth St to the Native Flora display board
3922.summary:
This board depicts the protected flora species in the Charles McCarthy Oval area.  This oval is used for sports training.

There is a bus shelter here but no seating.

3923.title: Retrace your steps to rejoin the Lake Track
3923.summary:
On the left, notice the Arboretum planted by St. Leonards Primary School in 1981, creating an area of native flora for the benefit of wildlife & the community. 

Pass the rear of the Bowling Club.

3924.title: Continue along Lake track clockwise
3924.summary:
Join Murradoc Road, the main access road into St. Leonards.  Geese might greet you here.  The local rule is 'Give way to geese!'
  
The bus stop here has seating.

3925.title: Follow track along McLeod St
3925.summary: This gives a viewing point to the oval across the lake. Common birds seen here are cormorants, water hens, coots and pelicans.

3926.title: Notice the picnic facilities for rest, shade & shelter
3926.summary: There are 2 free electric BBQs in the shelter, tables, a playground & toilet facilities.  A convenient place to meet with family and friends.

3927.title: Close by find an activity area
3927.summary: There is a skate park, basketball/netball rings & a sandpit area.  See the Murals on the Toilet Block, part of a community project in 2001.

3928.title: Finish lake circuit at the bridge
3928.summary: To access the beach and foreshore, leaving the lake, cross Bluff Road with care.  Enjoy water views across Port Philip Bay and activity at the Boat Ramp.

3929.title: Elevation Graph for the Walk
3929.summary: It looks worse that it actually is.

3930.title: A Joke Sign
3930.summary: The Grampians most inaccurate sign, I think. Iit’s actually about 1.4 km.

3935.title: Flat Rock and Mount Zero Car Park
3935.summary: Where the walk starts. You can see the track up to Mount Stapylton.

3936.title: Black Rock Skink
3936.summary: Egernia saxatilis - lost a bit of its tail

3941.title: Mount Zero Olives
3941.summary: Well known brand of olive oil.

3942.title: Top of Mt Zero
3942.summary: You can just see the cairn and surveyors mark

3948.title: Topograph on Mount Zero
3948.summary: An old topograph reset in a newer cairn.

3949.title: Cairn on Top of Mount Zero

3950.title: Mount Stapylton
3950.summary: You can also Hollow Mountain in the foreground. It is difficult to see.

3951.title: Wombat Creek reservoir
3951.summary: This reservoir is the water supply for Daylesford. The picnic area is on the former sawmill site. There are no toilets or drinking water

3952.title: Tramway formation
3952.summary: The 4WD track visibly becomes a former tramway at about this point. The formation is dug into the steep hillside, which is unusual as such excavation was of course expensive

3953.title: Gully tracks
3953.summary: The tramway followed a different path in some of the gullys to the modern track. At locations such as this, the former tramway can be seen clearly on both sides of the gully

3954.title: Sweeping curves
3954.summary: Some of the gullys are impressive. The broad views give some idea of the scope of the enterprise (the name of one of the sawmills)  of the men who lived an worked in these forests

3955.title: end of the line
3955.summary: The former tramway formation is clear enough, but a securely locked gate bars the way.

3956.title: The Basin shopping centre
3956.summary:
The Basin’s first shops were established in the 1920s, and the Progress Hall was erected in 1926. 
The present Mountain Hwy   shops date from 1965

3957.title: Wicks Reserve
3957.summary: Ferntree Gully Shire Council acquired 9 ha of land formerly owned by Edmund and Janet Wicks in 1942 as a reserve. The Wicks ’selected’ their land in 1873. Edmund died in 1880.

3958.title: Chandler oak
3958.summary: William Chandler planted an acorn beside Dobsons Creek in 1875 to mark the birth of his son, Archibald. Dobsons Creek has the highest ecological values of any City of Knox waterway.

3959.title: The Basin Theatre
3959.summary:
Edna Chandler, wife of William Chandler’s grand-son Fergus, founded The Basin Theatre in 1954. The Chandler family  
donated land for the building in 1973.

osm.name: The Basin Theatre
osm.display_name: The Basin Theatre, Doongalla Road, The Basin, Melbourne, City of Knox, Victoria, 3154, Australia

3960.title: Dandenong Creek
3960.summary: Dandenong Creek is of significance to the Aboriginal people as marking a ‘song-line’ placed by their creator spirit,    Bunjil. The creek crossing is a good spot for sighting wild-life.

3961.title: The Stables
3961.summary: The former stables were located below the main homestead. A small tramway used to transport construction materials from the valley for the house terminated here.

3962.title: Doongalla Homestead
3962.summary: Doongalla homestead was constructed in 1892 by Sir Matthew Davies, a well known land speculator in the 1880s land boom, who named the property ‘Invermay'. The house burned down in 1932.

osm.name: Doongalla Homestead Picnic Ground
osm.display_name: Doongalla Homestead Picnic Ground, Doongalla Road, Mount Dandenong, Melbourne, Shire of Yarra Ranges, Victoria, 3767, Australia

3963.title: Footbridge
3963.summary: An easy walk with well formed tracks.

3964.title: Heyfield
3964.summary: At then end of your walk, check out  the country town of Heyfield - well worth a visit.

osm.name: Heyfield Wetlands Trail
osm.display_name: Heyfield Wetlands Trail, Heyfield, Shire of Wellington, Victoria, 3858, Australia

3965.title: Heyfield Wetlands Information Centre
3965.summary: The Wetlands Information Centre is the home of the Neville-Smith Timber Industries display and has a wide range of souvenirs.

3966.title: Beautiful wetlands
3966.summary: Once the site of the Heyfield racecourse, the Wetlands are now the home to a number of different species of bird and animal life.

3967.title: Penrose Promenade Community Centre
3967.summary:
A fabulous community hub with excellent facilities and activities. Art and educational courses of children, tai-chi, music, cooking, cultural meet-ups.
Weekly walking group on Wednesdays 11.30am.

3968.title: Goddard Street Sports Ground
3968.summary: Complete with BBQ, seats, shelter, a much loved and much used playground, sports oval and facilities. Busy on weekends!

3969.title: Camelot Drive Park
3969.summary: This park has a playground, seats and shelter.

3970.title: View from shelter
3970.summary: A pretty good view of the trees from here!

3971.title: Wetland views
3971.summary: The wetlands are an important habitat for birds and other wildlife. Plus it's a lovely place for a walk!

3972.title: Outdoor gym
3972.summary: There are several pieces of outdoor gym equipment dotted around the wetland.

3973.title: Derrimut Road
3973.summary: A bright little spot to have a seat if you need to take a rest.

osm.name: Derrimut Road
osm.display_name: Derrimut Road, Tarneit, Melbourne, City of Wyndham, Victoria, 3029, Australia

3974.title: Which birds can you spot?
3974.summary: Pelicans and ducks are regular visitors. You may spot cormorants and purple swamp hens too. Want to identify the birds you see? Check out this app (iPhone), also available for Android.

3975.title: Seats and shelter
3975.summary: There are seats along the wetland, and shade. Very useful!

3976.title: BBQ, seats and shelter
3976.summary: Bring along a picnic or sausages for a BBQ. The park is good spot to meet your friends and neighbours too.

3977.title: Meeree Reserve
3977.summary: This reserve has a playground, BBQ, seats and shelter. There's plenty of space for ball games, kite flying and general lounging or running around. Meeree means sun in the local Aboriginal language.

3978.title: Red Sand Garden
3978.summary: The Red Sand Garden is the first sight just outside the Visitor Centre

3979.title: Rockpool Waterway
3979.summary: The Rockpool Waterway is the only place that paddling is allowed.

osm.name: Rockpool Waterway
osm.display_name: Rockpool Waterway, Cranbourne, Melbourne, City of Casey, Victoria, 3977, Australia

3980.title: Waterhole Bridge
3980.summary: Waterhole Bridge is at the end of the Rockpool Waterway

3981.title: Serpentine Path
3981.summary: The Serpentine Path leads into the Arid Garden or up Gibson Hill

3982.title: Arid Garden
3982.summary: Grass trees (formerly called black boys) in the Arid Garden

3983.title: Gibson Hill
3983.summary: View from the top of Gibson Hill across the Red Sand Garden back to the Visitor Centre

osm.name: Gibson Hill
osm.display_name: Gibson Hill, Gondwana Garden, Cranbourne, Melbourne, City of Casey, Victoria, 3977, Australia

osm.name: Gondwana Garden
osm.display_name: Gondwana Garden, Cranbourne, Melbourne, City of Casey, Victoria, 3977, Australia

3987.title: Melaleuca Spits
3987.summary: Melaleuca Spits looking back to the Waterhole Bridge

osm.name: River Bend
osm.display_name: River Bend, Cranbourne, Melbourne, City of Casey, Victoria, Australia

3992.title: Giddy up
3992.summary: It’s not uncommon to meet horse riders on the track as well as dog walkers, joggers and keen birdwatchers.

3993.title: Walk through the wetland
3993.summary: Important to the Gunaikurnai nation for their basket-weaving properties is a wetlands mix of reeds, the home of numerous birds, frogs, insects and reptiles.

3994.title: Historic railway
3994.summary: A key piece of infrastructure for the region was the introduction of the railway, signs of which are still evident on the rail trail.

3995.title: Ned Stringer Memorial
3995.summary: In honour of the first European settler to find gold in what is now called Stringers Creek, this discovery is credited with starting the Walhalla goldrush.

3996.title: Rose Garden
3996.summary: In bloom, this is a superb spot to close your eyes and breathe in the perfume of roses as you reflect on Toongabbie’s history.

3997.title: St David's Uniting Church
3997.summary: A beautifully cared-for 1895 building that features 13 different pressed metal designs on its internal walls is a great place for taking your breath away.

3998.title: Plenty of play space
3998.summary: The historic primary school has several areas dedicated to play time as well as an interpretative shelter that provides a historic map of the township.

3999.title: What a grand stand
3999.summary: Constructed in celebration of the federation of Australia, this beautiful building on the Village Green is still used for sporting events and is adjunct to an excellent BBQ and picnic facility.

4000.title: General Store
4000.summary: The General Store not only provides delicious food but has a collection of historic wagons and other farm machinery, as well as a wonderful place to picnic under the trees.

4001.title: Bridge takes you to Geelong Baseball Centre

4003.title: Take the track on far side of chapel
4003.summary: Track on far side of chapel will loop back across the creek on the other side

4004.title: Track crosses back over the creek

4006.title: beautiful section of the creek
4006.summary: This section is particularly pretty, eg. this Eucalyptus tree with beautiful big spiky seed pods!

4007.title: Norman Beach
4007.summary: Well hidden by the healthy coastal flora, the Tidal River campground is at the far end of Norman Beach.

4008.title: Coastline View
4008.summary: Leaving Norman Bay, the track hugs the coastline, providing views across Bass Strait to the horizon.

4009.title: Little Oberon Bay
4009.summary: Around the first headland is this sparkling view of the second beach on this walk.

osm.name: Little Oberon Bay
osm.display_name: Little Oberon Bay, Victoria, Australia

4010.title: Little Oberon Bay
4010.summary: After leaving the beach, the walk continues along the coast on a compacted sandy track.

osm.name: Little Oberon Bay
osm.display_name: Little Oberon Bay, Victoria, Australia

4011.title: Oberon Bay
4011.summary: Around the next headland, more beauty awaits. The campground is at the far end of this beach.

osm.name: Oberon Bay
osm.display_name: Oberon Bay, Victoria, Australia

4012.title: Orange rocks
4012.summary: Xanthoria Parietina (Common Orange Lichen) give the granite boulders their distinctive colour. There is a shallow flowing river to cross here.

4013.title: The track
4013.summary: The track varies with the landscape, sometimes narrow, sometimes wide, sometimes flat and sandy, sometimes steep and rocky!

4014.title: Granite boulders
4014.summary: A cluster of enormous boulders perched at the top of this peak. Imagine how old they are!

4015.title: View of Little Waterloo Bay
4015.summary: A breathtaking view of the East coast of the Prom.

4016.title: Boardwalk Track
4016.summary: Descending the sand dunes and over the swamps. Keep your feet dry thanks to the many boardwalk sections.

4017.title: Track to Little Waterloo Bay Beach
4017.summary: Love this part of the track, but can get a bit windy sometimes.

osm.name: Little Waterloo Bay
osm.display_name: Little Waterloo Bay, Victoria, Australia

4019.title: Little Waterloo Bay
4019.summary: At the southern end of the beach is this fresh water but it's not suitable for drinking.

osm.name: Little Waterloo Bay
osm.display_name: Little Waterloo Bay, Victoria, Australia

4020.title: Tiger Snake
4020.summary: The Prom does have a lot of snakes, and if you're lucky you might get to see one or two.

osm.name: Refuge Cove Campsite
osm.display_name: Refuge Cove Campsite, Refuge Cove-Waterloo Bay Walking Track, Wilsons Promontory, Shire of South Gippsland, Victoria, Australia

4022.title: Eltham Station underpass
4022.summary: Cross the tracks by going under the gloomy underpass.

4023.title: The ugly car park
4023.summary: Don't be put off by the ugly car park and watch out crossing the road!

4024.title: The path
4024.summary: Walk along Diamond St until you get to the path (gate in the fence), then you are set.

4025.title: Eltham Central Park
4025.summary: If it's winter, you might even get the chance to stop and watch some local footy.

osm.name: Eltham Central Park
osm.display_name: Eltham Central Park, Eltham, Melbourne, Shire of Nillumbik, Victoria, Australia

4026.title: Eltham Trestle Bridge
4026.summary: The bridge was built in 1901 and is one of the last remaining on the Melbounre train network, it's a beauty!

osm.name: Eltham Trestle Bridge
osm.display_name: Eltham Trestle Bridge, Panther Place, Eltham, Melbourne, Shire of Nillumbik, Victoria, 3095, Australia

4027.title: The Diamond Creek
4027.summary: The path snakes around the Diamond Creek (if you are very lucky, you might see a snake in summer).

4028.title: The Gate
4028.summary: I love this gate. Why is it there, what lies behind, does anyone know?

4029.title: The slippery path
4029.summary: The path is a bit slippery here in Autumn and Winter because of the fallen rotten leaves, but beautiful nonetheless.

4030.title: The tree
4030.summary: Wonderful big tree. Also there are toilets nearby. Look out for signs and paintings from the "Heidelberg School Artists Trail".

4031.title: Wingrove Park
4031.summary: A nice clearing where there are often picnicners or people playing.

osm.name: Wingrove Park
osm.display_name: Wingrove Park, Eltham, Melbourne, Shire of Nillumbik, Victoria, Australia

4032.title: Diamond Valley Railway  crossing
4032.summary: The first glimpse of the Diamond Valley Railway is the crossing on Main Rd.

4033.title: Diamond Valley Railway steam train
4033.summary: There are lots a places to watch the trains, both diesel and steam engines. Better still, jump on and go for a ride, it is not expensive.

4034.title: Como Park
4034.summary: Como Park is adjacent to the Yarra River.  The historic Como House is located on the grounds. It contains exercising equipment, playground, BBQ area, bike path  and plenty of space to kick the footy.

osm.name: Como Park
osm.display_name: Como Park, South Yarra, Melbourne, City of Stonnington, Victoria, 3141, Australia

4035.title: South Yarra Station
4035.summary: South Yarra Station is easy accessible from any train as they all stop at South Yarra. Our walk start's at South Yarra Station so it is easy to get to.

osm.name: South Yarra
osm.display_name: South Yarra, Toorak Road, South Yarra, Melbourne, City of Stonnington, Victoria, 3141, Australia

4036.title: Yarra River, walking trail
4036.summary: This is where the walking path along the Yarra River starts. This is such a nice part of the walk and one of the best key features. It it wheelchair/ pram friendly.

4037.title: Jam Factory
4037.summary: The Jam Factory is full of shops, places to eat and the cinemas.

osm.name: Jam Factory
osm.display_name: Jam Factory, 500, Chapel Street, South Yarra, Melbourne, City of Stonnington, Victoria, 3141, Australia

4038.title: Chapel Street
4038.summary: Chaple Street is full of unique shops and fine dining restaurants.

osm.name: Chapel Street
osm.display_name: Chapel Street, South Yarra, Melbourne, City of Stonnington, Victoria, 3141, Australia

4039.title: Trams
4039.summary: Trams frequently run along Toorak Road.

4040.title: Trams
4040.summary: Trams frequently run along Chapel Street.

4041.title: River Red Gum
4041.summary: Look up and marvel at the wonderful twisting branches of an old River Red Gum.  It plays an important role in stabilising river banks.

4042.title: Red Wattle Bird
4042.summary: If you spot one, notice what it is feeding on.  As a honeyeater it has a highly developed brush-tipped tongue adapted for nectar feeding.  It also eats berries and can catch insects in mid air.

4043.title: Australian Wood Ducks
4043.summary: You are sure to see Australian Wood Ducks.  They form monogamous breeding pairs that stay together year round. They nest in tree holes, above or near water, often re-using the same site.

4044.title: Kangaroo Apple
4044.summary: You can't mistake this plants kangaroo paw leaves.  The fruits were eaten by Aboriginal people, but only when very ripe, as they are said to be poisonous at other times.

4045.title: Red Rump Parrot
4045.summary: Keep your eyes out for Red Rump Parrots.  They spend a great deal of time feeding on the ground, and often call to one another.  The male (front) is very colourful.

4046.title: Maribyrnong river
4046.summary: A bluestone ford across the river gives you a chance to pause, enjoy the beautiful view, and listen to the sounds of the prolific birdlife.

osm.name: Maribyrnong River Trail
osm.display_name: Maribyrnong River Trail, Keilor East, Melbourne, City of Brimbank, Victoria, 3036, Australia

4047.title: You are not the first walker here
4047.summary: Archaeological studies have found that the Brimbank Park area is among the oldest known human-inhabited sites in Australia, with Aboriginal occupation extending back over 40,000 years.

4048.title: Taylors Creek
4048.summary: If you are lucky you might spot a long-necked tortoise with its nostrils barely above the shallows.  If it hears you, it will submerge for several minutes.

osm.name: Taylors Creek
osm.display_name: Taylors Creek, Kealba, Melbourne, City of Brimbank, Victoria, 3021, Australia

4049.title: The upper trail
4049.summary:
Most of the park is 55m below the surrounding plains.
An optional part of the walk ascends up to the edge of the park giving you wonderful views down to the parkland below.

4050.title: Willie Wagtail
4050.summary: The Willie Wagtail is common in the park. You will probably see it doing what it loves the most, chasing insects.

4051.title: River time
4051.summary: The river is very patient, and over time is has exposed layers of sandstone deposited here around 400 million years ago.

4052.title: White faced heron (and Eastern egret)
4052.summary: The heron feeds on fish, insects and amphibians. You might see it walking to disturb it's prey, searching among damp crevices or simply standing in the water and watching for movement.

4053.title: Dodd's Homestead
4053.summary: The park was operated as farmland by the Dodd family from 1860 to 1974.  This is the original Dodd homestead.

4054.title: Ruins of the old School house
4054.summary: Ruins of the old School house

4055.title: Blue Box eucalypts
4055.summary: These trees are a botanical anomaly, found only here and in East Gippsland. They are obviously very old

4056.title: Volcanic escarpments
4056.summary: The river cuts through the volcanic plain revealing the many layers of volcanic activity that have taken place over the last 5 million years or so.

4057.title: Abundant Bird Life
4057.summary: Here some of the local Red Rump Parrots

4058.title: The Old Ford
4058.summary: Supposedly where Hume and Hovell crossed the River in 1826.

4059.title: CWA Gardens
4059.summary: CWA Gardens is home to the towns historic clock, originally housed in the historic Dookie Chataeu tower and cellars, built in 1889.

4060.title: Mount Saddleback
4060.summary: The trail is set at the base of Mount Saddlback. To the South you can see Mount Major, Gentle Annie hill to the South East and to the West you will see St. Mary's Church, build in 1998.

4061.title: Branch line
4061.summary: The branch line to Katamatite was constructed by the Yarrawonga Shire in 1890 and taken over by the Victorian Railways in 1892. The railway was closed in 1986 and the rails removed shortly after.

4062.title: Willy the Wombat
4062.summary: You might be lucky to spot this local resident whose den is under the road drain.

4063.title: Various fauna and flora
4063.summary: including echidnas, blue tongue lizzards, kangaroos and even wedge tailed eagles.

4064.title: O'Donnell Gardens
4064.summary: This where our walk begins, right next to cosmopolitan Acland Street, where you can stop for a meal, coffee and cake or pick up some souvenirs from the many gift shops.

osm.name: O'Donnell Gardens
osm.display_name: O'Donnell Gardens, St Kilda, Melbourne, City of Port Phillip, Victoria, 3182, Australia

4065.title: Luna Park
4065.summary: Acclaimed as one of the world's oldest amusement parks, Luna Park has been an icon of St Kilda since it was opened in 1912 .

osm.name: Luna Park, Acland Street
osm.display_name: Luna Park, Acland Street, Carlisle Street, St Kilda, Melbourne, City of Port Phillip, Victoria, 3182, Australia

4066.title: The Palais
4066.summary: Cross Cavell St and wander along the Lower Esplanade.  Generations of Melbourne residents have come here to dance, listen to live music and even watch movies.

4067.title: Catani Arch
4067.summary: Built in 1916, it provides a great place to stop and enjoy the view and is a popular photo spot for wedding couples.

4068.title: St Kilda Sea Baths
4068.summary: ou can stop for a swim, spa or seaweed wrap here or grab a bite to eat in one of the cafes or restaurants based here.

osm.name: St Kilda Sea Baths
osm.display_name: St Kilda Sea Baths, St Kilda, Melbourne, City of Port Phillip, Victoria, 3182, Australia

4069.title: Mirka Mora Mosaic
4069.summary: Beautiful mosaic map of St Kilda by Mirka Mora, a Jewish refugee who came to Australia to avoid persecution during World War II.

4070.title: St Kilda Pier
4070.summary: home of the famous Kirby's Kiosk.  Beyond the kiosk is the breakwater - home to St Kilda's own penguin colony.  If you keep your eyes open around dusk you may see them swimming home to roost.

osm.name: Pier Road
osm.display_name: Pier Road, St Kilda, Melbourne, City of Port Phillip, Victoria, 3182, Australia

4071.title: Catani Park
4071.summary: Catani Gardens, where you can stop for a picnic or a BBQ.  If you have the time, take a walk along the Esplanade towards Port Melbourne.  Look out for kite boarders on the bay.

4072.title: The Upper Esplanade
4072.summary: The Upper Esplanade, which boasts fantastic views of Port Phillip Bay.  On Sundays there is an arts and crafts market here.

osm.name: The Esplanade
osm.display_name: The Esplanade, St Kilda, Melbourne, City of Port Phillip, Victoria, 3182, Australia

4073.title: The Upper Esplanade 2
4073.summary: From here, you can continue along the Upper Esplanade until you return to O'Donnell Gardens, or on to Fitzroy Street, where you can enjoy the food, wine and great shopping that's on offer.

osm.name: The Esplanade
osm.display_name: The Esplanade, St Kilda, Melbourne, City of Port Phillip, Victoria, 3182, Australia

4074.title: Punting on the Ornamental Lake
4074.summary: Have a coffee and lunch at the cafe just near where the punt is available to take you on a trip around the lake

4075.title: Pioneer Women's Memorial Garden

4079.title: The Lych Gate
4079.summary: One of the many entrances to the Royal Botanic Gardens

4082.title: Gardens House

osm.display_name: Gardens House, Dallas Brooks Drive, Government House, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3004, Australia

4103.title: The Old Mildura Station Homestead

4104.title: "Someday, the whole of Mildura will be as this garden," -George Chaffey
4104.summary: The Homestead garden later inspired George Chaffey to select Mildura as the site for his irrigation colony.

4105.title: Mildura Homestead Cemetery
4105.summary: The Mildura Homestead Cemetery actually consists of two adjacent graves. One solitary grave stood in the Homestead Cemetery in Mildura, for nearly 40 years.

4106.title: Entrance to where the Chaffey Women are buried
4106.summary: Just sit and relax in the quietness of this place as you journey back in time and feel the presence of our historians.

4107.title: In Honour of His Wife.
4107.summary: WB Chaffey erected this magnificent monument to honour his young wife. His wife Hattie was spoken of with affection and was well respected for her acts of kindness.

4108.title: BBQ Area

4130.title: English Oak
4130.summary: This tree can be quite tricky to find, but if you spot it, record what stage of its annual cycle it is at. Leaves falling? Flowers opening? Submit your sightings on the ClimateWatch app

4131.title: Illawarra Flame Tree
4131.summary: An iconic Australian tree which flowers in spring. Scientists think that these trees and others might flower earlier due to climate change, so please record what you see.

4132.title: Orchard Swallowtail Butterfly
4132.summary: From October through May, you will have the chance to spot their beautiful wings. Upload the image on ClimateWatch and help the science to save our environment.

4133.title: Jewel Spider

4185.title: Remains of Great Extended Hustler's Reef Goldmine - machinery foundations.
4185.summary: The mine opened in 1865 and closed in 1921. It was a kilometre deep and extended outwards up to 3 kms beneath Bendigo. The remains are the foundations for large mine machinery.

4186.title: Memorial to the 7 men killed on 2nd May 1914.
4186.summary: In May 2008 the Friends of Hustlers Reef dedicated this memorial to the men who died in 1914. In May 2014 the Bendigo commemorated the centenary of the disaster with a community history open day.

4187.title: Box Iron Bark Living Memorial Revegetation.
4187.summary: The Friends of Hustler's Reserve have worked hard to clear invasive weeds,  re-vegetate with local indigenous plants and reinforce eroded paths re-using existing materials from the site.

4188.title: Remains of Great Extended Hustler's Reef Gold Mine.
4188.summary: It's undergone a significant clean up since this photo was taken in 2013 & is considerably less spooky. Remains of foundations for boilers, compressors and sidewinders litter the Bendigo landscape.

4189.title: Gentle rise
4189.summary: Bendigo is spotted with mullock hills covered in light scrub. In late winter they are often ablaze in wattle gold & are always filled with native birds. The Bendigo Bird Guide is linked below.

4190.title: Memorial to Goldfield Widows.
4190.summary: Situated at the Eastern end of the Reserve is another memorial - this one for the 100’s of widows who lost their husbands through mining accidents or miners phthisis (silicosis).

4191.title: Boundry Arms Hotel.
4191.summary: Not only does this pub have cold beer and a good feed but there is also a huge range of classic old photos of Bendigo's mining heyday available for close inspection.

4192.title: Beautiful Houses and Incredible Views.
4192.summary: Extend your walk out of the Reserve to follow the curve of Moore St, and see beautiful old homes and clear views of Bendigo. If you're able, head into town to climb the Poppet Head in Rosalind Park.

4193.title: Paper Plane Crash Site.
4193.summary: Someone crashed a huge iron paper plane  into their front yard! The sculpture is a local novelty. No photo out of interest for the homeowner's privacy but I do recommend a look - kids will love it!

4194.title: Remember - Frederick James Chinn.
4194.summary: Born in Bendigo in 1888 he was the eighth child of Annie Yates and James Chinn. Frederick was 26 years old and unmarried. He was buried at Kangaroo Flat Cemetery and his headstone can still be viewed.

4195.title: Remember - William Ryan.
4195.summary: Also 26 and unmarried he left behind his parents John and Jessie.

4196.title: Remember - William Crowther Blair.
4196.summary: The oldest of those killed in the blast. Born in Ballarat he was forty years old when the explosion widowed his wife Catherine and three children.

4197.title: Remember - Matthew George Forster.
4197.summary: At 28 Matthew left behind his wife Maud with two children. Although she remarried two years later and moved to Collingwood, she eventually returned to Bendigo to be buried with Matthew.

4198.title: Remember - Herbert John Thomas.
4198.summary: At 30 Herbert was 8 years younger than his father John when he was also killed in an  explosion at Hustler's. Herbert was 15 & had 4 siblings.His wife Ethel was left with 3 children when he died.

4199.title: Remember - Leslie Duncan Martin.
4199.summary: Leslie was 23 and the youngest of those killed. He was buried with his older brother Murdock who had been killed nine years earlier aged just 18 at the Clarence United Mine.

4200.title: Remember - John Henry Campbell.
4200.summary: The explosion left 31 year old John's wife widowed with two children and after his death, she delivered their daughter Ida. Margaret went on to bury Ida with John just five years later.

4201.title: Poppet Head
4201.summary:
This used to be the site where a replica of a poppet head from the mining days was situated. 
It was used for mining Antimony at the Ringwood Antimony mine. A plaque remains.

4202.title: Miner's Cottage
4202.summary:
A replica of a miner's cottage from the days of Antimony mining stood here but was destroyed by fire. 
What remains is a plaque and board providing information.

4203.summary: Bring your family, a picnic and some ball games and have fun!

4230.summary: View along the creek from the bridge

4231.title: Start of the gravel track
4231.summary: One of only a few small uphill sections on the walk.

4232.title: Wandering through the trees
4232.summary: Wandering through the clusters of trees.

4233.title: Down to the bridge
4233.summary: The short hill down to the pedestrian bridge cna look a lot bigger depending on your point of view.

4234.title: A fine creek view
4234.summary: A fine view of the flora growing in and along the creek from the small pedestrian bridge.

4235.title: The bridge
4235.summary: The new pedestrian bridge that allows us to cross the creek and return along the opposite bank to the starting point of the walk.

4236.title: Common Reed
4236.summary: Look out for the semi-aquatic Common Reed along the creek.  It provides a habitat for certain birds and the leaves were used by aboriginal people to weave baskets.

4237.title: Cumbungi
4237.summary: Look out for Cumbungi along the creek.  It is a good frog habitat.  Aboriginal people used to harvest the roots which can be cleaned, steamed and roasted.

4238.title: A hidden gem
4238.summary: A view along the east side of the creek.  Feels just like being in the countryside.  A hidden gem.

4239.title: Walking in nature
4239.summary: Trees and abundant vegetation along the eastern slopes next to the creek.

4240.title: Grand old tree
4240.summary: Remnant Eucalypts form part of the vegetation, giving you an indication of the forest that used to embrace this creek.

4241.title: Walking over water
4241.summary: No need to get your feet wet as you cross the bridges along the trail.

4242.title: Place for a picnic
4242.summary: Take a hamper and enjoy the grasslands alongside the Eel Hole Creek.

4243.title: Painted Poles
4243.summary: See the beautiful images painted by local school children expressing what they learnt on a field trip connecting the sciences to the arts

4244.title: The wetlands
4244.summary: Cast a fishing line or just enjoy the view on the platform built over the water.

4245.title: Walk or ride
4245.summary: Sections of the trail are user-friendly to walkers and bike-riders alike.

4246.title: Main Lake
4246.summary: This is 'Main Lake' it's fairly large and one of my favourite attraction sites in the sanctuary. You might also spot a duck in there. You might also want to find a small bridge that crosses this lake.

4247.title: Manna Gum Isthmus
4247.summary: This is an interesting red river gum tree that's 300+ years old and provides homes to possums, bats and nesting birds. It's also a primary feature for visiting in the sanctuary.

4248.title: Willis Billabong
4248.summary: This is Willis Billabong and was quite covered by trees, branches and plants. I spotted a few magpies there.

4249.title: Galaxiella Billabong
4249.summary: Spotted another Billabong. This one looked very unique with a nice distinctive dark coloured water and what seems to me to be purplish pink coloured leaves.

4250.title: Dismantled Car
4250.summary: Something quite unexpected- A car. This old dismantled car near close to the track can't be missed, I think it adds a creative element with the natural surrounding. It sure caught me by surprise.

4251.title: Twin Ponds
4251.summary: There're two ponds on each side of the track. This picture is the one of the left. It was an interesting contrast to the other wetlands. The water was different, but interesting - choc brown and foamy

4252.title: Iron Barks Hut
4252.summary: A fantastic hut- highlight of the sanctuary for me. This hut is equipped with a gas barbeque for public use with all wooded seats and tablets. It's metal sheltered and makes a nice place for relaxing.

4253.title: Weir Park
4253.summary: This was developed during beautification in the late 60s.  This is where Barnes Boulevard terminated pre 1985

osm.name: Weir Park
osm.display_name: Weir Park, Horsham, Rural City of Horsham, Victoria, 3400, Australia

4254.title: weir
4254.summary: The new weir was built in the 1967/68.  Prior to this the weir was located further upstream where there was also a bathing hole.

osm.name: Weir
osm.display_name: Weir, Boardwalk, Horsham, Rural City of Horsham, Victoria, 3400, Australia

4255.title: Wetlands
4255.summary: The wetlands provide a natural setting for local flora and fauna.

osm.name: Weir Park Wetlands Walk
osm.display_name: Weir Park Wetlands Walk, Horsham, Rural City of Horsham, Victoria, 3400, Australia

4256.title: Bird Hide
4256.summary: One of two bird hides that can be used to search for the various birds who inhabit this area.

4257.title: Bird Hide
4257.summary: Another bird hide providing an opportunity to see the various birds who visit or live in this area.

4258.title: Boardwalk
4258.summary: Downstream this is a chance to cross over the river and explore what the other side has to offer.  The track continues east on the other side and meets back at the base of the weir.

osm.name: Boardwalk
osm.display_name: Boardwalk, Horsham, Rural City of Horsham, Victoria, 3400, Australia

4259.title: Weir Boardwalk
4259.summary: This provides an opportunity to explore the other side of the river.  The track continues on the other side and can meet up west at the downstream boardwalk

osm.name: Weir
osm.display_name: Weir, Boardwalk, Horsham, Rural City of Horsham, Victoria, 3400, Australia

4260.title: Trentham Railway Station
4260.summary: Disused train carriages still sit on the tracks at the old Trentham Railway Station, which you can walk around from the ground.

4261.title: Old Railway Sleepers
4261.summary: Watch out for the railway sleepers underfoot along this section of the trail, which are slightly uneven footing.

4262.title: Footbridge
4262.summary: A good point to turn around if you’re after a shorter walk.

4263.title: Resting Point
4263.summary: Take a break at the bench and see if you can notice the difference between the older growth and younger forests on either side of the path.

4264.title: Old Bridge
4264.summary: Following the diversion around the disused bridge will give you a great view of the wooden structure.

4265.title: Lyonville
4265.summary: The trail ends (or begins, depending on your direction) at the site of the former Lyonville Railway Station. There is parking at both ends of the track.

4266.title: Wild Melbourne
4266.summary: This walk was completed by Wild Melbourne, a not-for-profit specialising in nature engagement and dedicated to connecting people with nature. Please visit our website to find out more.

4267.title: St Kilda Town Hall
4267.summary: St Kilda Town Hall, home of most Port Phillip Council staff and services such as rates, events, immunisations, planning.

osm.name: St Kilda Town Hall
osm.display_name: St Kilda Town Hall, Carlisle Street, St Kilda, Melbourne, City of Port Phillip, Victoria, 3182, Australia

4268.title: The Local Taphouse
4268.summary: Over 100 beers and food served on the rooftop.

osm.name: The Local Taphouse
osm.display_name: The Local Taphouse, Carlisle Street, St Kilda, Melbourne, City of Port Phillip, Victoria, 3182, Australia

4269.title: Raised crossings
4269.summary: The yellow raised crossings on the side streets off Carlisle seem to be doing a great job of giving pedestrians priority. yay!

4270.title: Inkerman St bottle brush
4270.summary: In Walktober the bottle brush are glowing red up and down Inkerman.

4271.title: Lady of St Kilda
4271.summary: Look up to see the Lady of St Kilda artwork on the Balaclava railway bridge  (or look right to see people queuing on the street for Las Chicas- linseed soy and dandelion latte highly recommended)

4272.title: Kids' side of the park
4272.summary: Great playground for kids of all ages on this side of Alma Park. Highlights include the curly red slide, mosaic cave, and giant flying fox.

4273.title: Flying fox
4273.summary: It is a big flying fox! This is also a good spot to indulge in some real estate envy- wouldn't it be great to live in a flat backing onto Alma Park?

4274.title: Nature strips
4274.summary: A couple of personalised nature strips on Hammerdale Ave.

4275.title: Stormwater treatment
4275.summary: Check out the water sensitive urban design planting at the Alma Road end of the playground.

4276.title: Treed path
4276.summary: This path is surrounded by bushy flowering shrubs.

4277.title: Dog park
4277.summary: Dogs can be let off leash on both sides of the path west of the railway line.

4278.title: Neighbours Cafe
4278.summary: Some commissioned street art on both facades of Neighbours Cafe. It also has a surprisingly quiet garden out back if you fancy lunch in the sun.

4279.title: Kensington Railway Station
4279.summary: Originally opened by the Melbourne & Essendon Railway Company in 1860, it became a critical transport link for livestock. The signal box was built in 1897, Platform 1 in 1888 & platform 2 in 1905.

osm.name: Kensington
osm.display_name: Kensington, Bellair Street, Kensington, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3031, Australia

4280.title: Islington House  166-168 Bellair St
4280.summary: ‘Islington’ (1891), was the Kensington Property Exchange. Owned & built by James Wales, a former councillor & mayor in 1899. It was used as a set for the TV show ‘The Sullivans’.

4281.title: Plumbers House  156 Bellair St
4281.summary: Bill Pearce set up a plumbing business in the 1940s. The only gear he could afford was carried on his bike. By the turn of the century Bill was still here with a workshop out back. The façade remains.

4282.title: Kuruc House  114 Bellair St
4282.summary: Kuruc House (1898), architects Ussher & Kemp, is an early example of a Queen Anne villa & was occupied by surgeon Joseph Moss until 1910. It continued to be used as a doctor’s clinic until 1973.

4283.title: Hal Porter House  86 Bellair St
4283.summary: Hal Porter’s memoir "Watcher on the Cast-Iron Balcony" describes his early memories of growing up before WWI at 86 Bellair St, including his walk to Kensington Primary along the cobbled back lanes.

4284.title: Kensington Town Hall  24 – 40 Bellair St
4284.summary: Flemington & Kensington Town Hall (1901). Architecturally, it expresses grand intentions in a small scale. It became a social hub with dances, weddings, women’s groups & an infant welfare centre.

4285.title: Newmarket Saleyards (1861-1987)/Now Community High School
4285.summary: By 1888 almost ½ million animals passed annually through the Newmarket saleyards. In the 20th century it became the world’s biggest livestock auction market. Associated industries created many jobs.

4286.title: 6th Melbourne Scout Hall  55 McCracken St
4286.summary: The 135 year old hall, at the rear, used by the scouts since the 1920’s was formerly used by both Anglicans and Methodists before either church was built. Restored with community involvement in 2014.

4287.title: Kensington Primary School
4287.summary: Kensington State School No.2374 opened in 1881 with an initial enrolment of 228 children, which grew to 1,000 by 1898.  In 1914 the State School was the second largest in Victoria.

osm.name: Kensington Primary School
osm.display_name: Kensington Primary School, 62-74, McCracken Street, Kensington, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3031, Australia

4288.title: Christ Church Uniting
4288.summary: The vacant lot is where the original timber Church (1882) stood. This served as Sunday school until burnt down in the 1970’s. Current Church was built 1889, now a combined Anglican and Uniting Church.

4289.title: Hardiman’s Hotel
4289.summary: The former Clarence Hotel built in the late 1870’s by the Hardiman family. Designed to look like an ocean liner, rebranded in the 40’s by Tim Hardiman and renovated by new owners in 1998.

4290.title: Holy Rosary Catholic Church
4290.summary: In 1902 the first Holy Rosary Church opened on Derby Street. It was replaced in 1928 by this Church which first celebrated Mass, and was officially opened, on Christmas Day that year.

4291.title: Holy Rosary Primary School
4291.summary: A Catholic primary school, Holy Rosary, opened at the parish hall in 1916 and moved to its present location in 1927.

osm.name: Holy Rosary Primary School
osm.display_name: Holy Rosary Primary School, 37-43, Gower Street, Kensington, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3031, Australia

4292.title: Wolseley Parade Streetscape
4292.summary: Wolseley Parade, Kensington is considered to be one of the most desirable streets in Melbourne. It is very typical of the suburb and its development over the Victorian era.

4293.title: Wallaby and joey
4293.summary: The wallabies around the camping area are quite tame, including this one with a joey!

4294.title: Goanna
4294.summary: In the warmer months you might see goannas. like this one.

4295.title: Little creek
4295.summary: The path leads down to a little creek.

4296.title: The creek
4296.summary: This is not the Bittangabee Creek!

4297.title: Steps
4297.summary: A gentle climb up a small hill.

4298.title: The ruins
4298.summary: The beginnings of a stone house that was never completed. Some believe it was constructed by the Imlay brothers.

4299.title: Wombat burrows
4299.summary: There are many wombat burrows around, but you need to walk at night to see them.

4300.title: Anthills
4300.summary: Anthills like this can be found across Ben Boyd.

4301.title: Bittangebee Creek
4301.summary: The creek is a wonderful place to stop or climb along the rocks along the creek bed.

4302.title: Heath
4302.summary: This is the floral emblem of Victoria, but also found in NSW.

4303.title: Top of the lagoon
4303.summary: When walking back, cut down to the lagoon to this point. b

4304.title: Soldier crabs
4304.summary: If you are lucky you will see thousands of soldier crabs walking along the shore, an amazing sight!

4305.title: Rock pools
4305.summary: Lots of rock pools to look at.

4306.title: The lagoon
4306.summary: The lagoon looking out to see. The is a wonderful little sandy beach round the corner that is great of swimming.

4307.title: Three Businessmen Who Brought Their Own Lunch: Batman, Swanston and Hoddle
4307.summary: These figures by Alison Weaver and Paul Quinn were installed in Swanston St. the first public sculpture in Melbourne since Vault was removed from the City Square in 1981

4308.title: Time and Tide
4308.summary: Akio Makigawa (born Japan 1948 - died in Perth 1999) has public sculptures in most Australian capital cities and several more in Melbourne.

4309.title: Architectural Fragment
4309.summary: Petrus Spronk 1992 sculpture is beloved by Melbourne's skateboard riders. It is also a fun piece of post-modernism quoting the neo-classical facade of the State Library.

4310.title: La Trobe
4310.summary: Governor La Trobe by Peter Corlett, 2006. This is the only Peter Corlett sculpture on this walk but he has may more around Melbourne, its suburbs and the rest of the world.

osm.name: La Trobe Place
osm.display_name: La Trobe Place, East End Theatre District, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3000, Australia

4311.title: Larry La Trobe
4311.summary: Pam Irving’s bronze dog, “Larry La Trobe” was install in 1993 and stolen in 1995. The current sculpture a new edition cast from the original mould.

4312.title: Warin
4312.summary: The wooden wombat, “Warin” was carved in situ in 2002 by Des McKenna. Another one for children to climb on.

4313.title: Loretta Quinn, Beyond the Ocean of Existence, 1993
4313.summary: Loretta Quinn is the brother of Paul Quinn one of the sculptors of The Three Businessmen. Nearby there are painted pole by indigenous artists, Maree Clarke and Sonja Hodge

4314.title: Burke and Wills Monument
4314.summary: This is the fourth location for that this monument has stood in Melbourne since 1865. It was originally cast in Charles Summers studio in Collins St. now the location of Burlington Chambers

4315.title: Street art sculptures in Hosier Lane
4315.summary: Along with all the aerosol art there are some unofficial street art sculptures in this lane. You will have to look carefully to find them.

4316.title: Paul Montford, The Water Nypmh, 1920
4316.summary: Paul Montford brought this sculpture with him when he emigrated to Australia in 1923. It was the first public sculpture bought by Melbourne City Council.

4317.title: Inge King, Forward Surge 1972-74
4317.summary: Installed in 1981 this modern fits perfectly into the curved architecture of the Arts Centre and Hamer Hall. The curves also delight children who try to climb them.

4318.title: Matthew Flinders Memorial
4318.summary: The sculptor Charles Web Gilbert, like to do everything himself, from the modelling to the casting of the sculptures.

4319.title: George VII Memorial
4319.summary: The sculptor Bertram Mackennal was born in Fitzroy but became Australia's first international art star.

4320.title: The Phoenix
4320.summary: Originally large curved feathers, or flames, were once attached at several points over the body of the sculpture. These have broken off and only fragments of two remain.

4321.title: The Pathfinder
4321.summary: An edition of English/Australian sculptor John Robinson 1974 bronze sculpture of a hammer thrower.  Only six years after this sculpture the Melbourne City Council installed Vault in the City Square.

osm.name: The Pathfinder Sculpture
osm.display_name: The Pathfinder Sculpture, St Kilda Road, Melbourne, City of Melbourne, Victoria, 3004, Australia

4322.title: Apollo and Hercules
4322.summary: Politician and newspaper proprietor, Theodore Fink  acquired these marble copies of classical sculpture on a holiday in Rome.

4323.title: Tom Bass, The Genie, 1973
4323.summary: This sculpture is purpose built for children to play on. Sydney sculptor Tom Bass has several other sculptures around Melbourne and at Melbourne University.

4324.title: Vault, Ron Robertson-Swann
4324.summary: In 1980 this sculpture was in the City Square and Melbourne was divided by the controversy over this sculpture. In 1981 it was moved to Batman Park by the Yarra River.

4325.title: The Public Purse,  Simon Perry
4325.summary: In 1994, the City of Melbourne added what was described in the design brief as “unique and distinctive forms of street seating” in the streets, The Public Purse was one of them.

4326.title: The Preston Market
4326.summary: We love the Preston Market because it is really muilti-cultural. There is a great lolly store that sells American lollies. It is really cheap place where you can chill out.

4327.title: Mai Lan Bakery
4327.summary: One of our friend's dad found this bakery in the Age, and it was voted the best pork rolls in Melbourne. We went there to try something new and they was amazing! They are only $3.50 a roll.

osm.name: Mai Lan Bakery
osm.display_name: Mai Lan Bakery, 435, High Street, Preston, Melbourne, City of Darebin, Victoria, 3072, Australia

4328.title: High Street, Preston
4328.summary: This stretch of High St (between Murray Rd and Gower St) is really cool. They have all these bargain stores. The vibes you get there are really chill.

osm.name: High Street
osm.display_name: High Street, Preston, Melbourne, City of Darebin, Victoria, 3072, Australia

4329.title: Tram Stop to take you down to Arthurton Road
4329.summary: We took the 86 tram to get to Arthurton Road, the trams go down High Street really often so it is easy to just jump on a tram.

4330.title: Arthurton Road Stop Off
4330.summary: Make sure you get off at this tram stop so you can walk down to CERES!

4331.title: CERES
4331.summary: CERES has a really natural feeling. Anyone can just hang out there. The food is great and the hot chocolates are pretty good, organic too! The markets on Saturdays are really fun too.

osm.name: CERES Environmental Park
osm.display_name: CERES Environmental Park, CERES Community Gardens, Brunswick East, Melbourne, City of Merri-bek, Victoria, 3057, Australia

4332.title: Merri Park
4332.summary: Merri Park is fun and right next to Northcote High. There is a cool playground in the park that not bad for teens to hang out on after school hours.

osm.name: Merri Park
osm.display_name: Merri Park, Ruckers Hill, Northcote, Melbourne, City of Darebin, Victoria, Australia

4333.title: Juline's Noodle Shop
4333.summary: Juline's makes the best chips ever, so addictive! It is like our little community milk bar.

4334.title: Jump on the 112 tram to take you to Brunswick Street!
4334.summary: There is a tram stop right in front of Juline's Noodle Shop - so really easy to jump on that to take you down to Fitzroy.

4335.title: Fitzroy Pool
4335.summary: Just down the road from this marker towards Smith Street is our favourite pool. It costs only $2.10 to get in. So cheap and there are never lots of people. They have night sessions too!

osm.name: Fitzroy Pool/Alexandra Parade
osm.display_name: Fitzroy Pool/Alexandra Parade, Alexandra Parade, Fitzroy, Melbourne, City of Yarra, Victoria, 3065, Australia

4336.title: Brunswick Street, Fitzroy
4336.summary: We wish that more streets were like Brunswick St. It's got cool clothes shops, 2nd-hand shop called "Hunter Gatherer\". Heaps of parks nearby too and cheap food!

osm.name: Brunswick Street
osm.display_name: Brunswick Street, Fitzroy, Melbourne, City of Yarra, Victoria, 3065, Australia

4337.title: San Churros
4337.summary: We finished up our walk at San Churros to reward ourselves. It's one of our favourite places to get something yum to eat.

4338.title: National Storage
4338.summary: Striking monochrome throws and characters really brighten up this corner. Be careful of the level crossing!

4339.title: Bowie, Cash and a Clockwork Orange fence
4339.summary: This homeowner clearly had a great time in the seventies!

4340.title: Melbourne Bowls club
4340.summary: Established in 1864, this bowls club is an institution. Good cold beers at reasonable prices too.

4341.title: Artists Lane
4341.summary: This laneway is overflowing with wow making artworks. Change is the only constant, but keep your eyes peeled for works by Mysterious Al, Unwell Bunny, Kaff-eine or Heesco.

osm.name: Artists Lane
osm.display_name: Artists Lane, Windsor, Melbourne, City of Stonnington, Victoria, 3181, Australia

4342.title: Shame Mural and Ming the Merciless
4342.summary: Putos is a prolific artist with a very recognisable style.

4343.title: Classic Adnate, LucyLucy and Urban Cake Lady
4343.summary: Some classic works that have stuck around for a long while, catch them before they're gone!

4344.title: Saigon Sally Laneway
4344.summary: A great Asian diner style restaurant with great artwork, inside and out.

4345.title: Goddess Saraswati
4345.summary: The Hindu goddess of the arts - how appropriate - classic by Deb.

4346.title: River Red Gum
4346.summary: Look up and marvel at the wonderful twisting branches of an old River Red Gum.  It plays an important role in stabilising river banks.

4347.title: Walking tracks
4347.summary: The walking tracks are mostly level with a few gentle uphill sections.  Some sections are very open.  On a sunny day make sure to bring a hat and a bottle of water.

4348.title: Butterflies
4348.summary: As you walk in the summer months, hundreds of butterflies will be out, dancing among the shrubs and trees.

4349.title: Stumpy-tailed Lizard
4349.summary: If you hear a rumble in the grass as you walk you might spot a lizard out finding a nice spot for sunbaking.

4350.title: Dilwinia in flower
4350.summary: Dilwinia is just one of many native flowers on the walk that show their true colours during Spring.

4351.title: Eastern Grey Kangaroos
4351.summary: At birth, the infant immediately climbs into its mother's pouch and does not emerge for two months. Until they reach 10 or 11 months of age, threatened joeys, will dive for the safety of mom's pouch.

4352.title: Living Legends
4352.summary: Just in front of the Homestead are real Living Legends! Established to bring retired champion horses back to the public, the front paddocks are home to some of Australia's finest retired racehorses.

4353.title: The Woodlands Homestead
4353.summary: Originally imported and erected by the Greene family in 1842, and extended by later owners, the homestead is a unique example of design, construction and decoration from that era.

4354.title: A turn in the road
4354.summary: After leaving the homestead, keep an eye out for these posts.  The path turns left up a small incline immediately afterwards.

4355.title: The parklands
4355.summary: The park contains a landscape that has changed little since pastoral settlement in the 1840s.  Large areas of little-disturbed grassy woodland provides habitat for kangaroos.

4356.title: The Eastern Rosella
4356.summary: There is a great diversity of birdlife in the park.  Some are easy to spot like the colourful Eastern Rosella.  Other tiny birds that nest in bushes near the creek require a little more patience.

4357.title: Map
4357.summary: At the main car park is a map of the Reserve, giving you a clear overview of your walking options.

4358.title: The Walking Tracks
4358.summary: Each track is named after one of the birds you’re likely to see on your stroll and it’s clear that the Reserve is being steadily revegetated.

4359.title: Dog walkers' paradise
4359.summary: The Crinigan Reserve is an extremely popular place to indulge your pooch in an enjoyable walk, but please keep your furry friend on a leash at all times.

4360.title: Crossing the water
4360.summary: This boardwalk in the Reserve takes you across waterway and onto Lion’s Dam.

4361.title: Bring your binoculars
4361.summary: Bird-watching is a well known activity in the Reserve, with a bountiful array of species to spot.

4362.title: White earned honeyeater
4362.summary: Found in eastern and southern Australia, it lives in dry eucalypt forests and woodlands. Find out more and hear its bird call in the link below.

4363.title: Eastern Spinebill
4363.summary: This gorgeous bird has a long fine and curved bill, with distinctive markings. It is found in eastern and southern Australia. Find out more in the link below.

4364.title: Waxlip Orchid
4364.summary: The Reserve is home to 30 different types of orchids, including this beautiful Waxlip Orchid (Glossodia Major). It flowers in late winter to early spring, and is found in heath land and open forests.

4365.title: A world of wetlands
4365.summary: The Lions, Hospital, Wallaby and Tortoise Dams occupy space in this bushland reserve, creating a rich wetland environment.

4366.title: Rest and relax
4366.summary: You can sit by the water, watch the wildlife and even have a picnic while enjoying the serenity.

4367.title: Town Pier - now the Port Melbourne Yacht Club
4367.summary: Black coal arrived here from Newcastle. Town Pier was the first significant pier structure in the early settlement of Sandridge. It was demolished in the 1950s.

4368.title: Morley's Coal Depot
4368.summary: This handsome coal store was one of the businesses owned by William Morley, the first mayor of Sandridge. Blue stone was preferred to timber as fire was a recurrent danger.

4369.title: Railway Line
4369.summary: The coal was conveyed by rail pulled by a dray up Dow St. Recent works to create a raingarden revealed the old tram tracks

4370.title: Sandridge Bay Towers
4370.summary: The former Harpers Starch Factory with its distinctive chimney - a significant landmark through the 20th century.

4371.title: Esplanade East
4371.summary: The coal continued its journey along Esplanade East - the eastern edge of the former Sandridge Lagoon. It is said that during the depression, coal would fall from the wagons accidentally on purpose

osm.name: Esplanade East
osm.display_name: Esplanade East, Port Melbourne, Melbourne, City of Port Phillip, Victoria, 3207, Australia

4372.title: Gasholders
4372.summary: Huge gasholders stored the gas.  The gas was contained in a huge bell that rested on water. The level would rise up or down, depending on how much was in storage.

4373.title: The Weighbridge
4373.summary: This is where the coal was brought into the Gasworks and weighed. In the thirties, workers gathered at the entrance in the hope of getting any work at all.

4374.title: Brick Wall
4374.summary: I love the patterning of this brick wall and the colours in the bricks. Contemplate the size and the length of the walls around Gasworks and imagine them being built brick by brick.

4375.title: Solar!
4375.summary: Note the solar panels appearing on houses in this neighbourhood. At one time, the Gasworks management had to pay to clean the neighbouring houses from grit and grime.

4376.title: Mill Park Softball Reserve
4376.summary: There is lots of room for softball, baseball or any other sport

4377.title: Back on the walking path
4377.summary: Say goodbye to suburbia and hello walking path

4378.title: Careful crossing the road!
4378.summary: Please look both ways before crossing Manning Clarke Road

4379.title: Car park is accessible off Morang Road
4379.summary: If you choose to drive this is a good parking spot, however why not catch the train and walk from South Morang Train Station which is only 1km away!

4380.title: Transfer for walking path to footpath
4380.summary: This part of the walk follows the residential streets

4381.title: Mill Park Leisure and Services Centre
4381.summary: Mill Park Leisure and Services Centre: "...a contemporary aquatics and recreation facilty..."

4382.title: Morand Drive
4382.summary: This short section of the walk is on the footpath next to Morang Drive

4383.title: Turn right (south) here!
4383.summary: Turn right here if you which to finish the Mill Park Reserve Walk loop

4384.title: BBQ and covered picnic area
4384.summary: This is a great spot near the playground for a BBQ or picnic with plenty of shade

4385.title: Plenty of seats for tired legs
4385.summary: Thre are plenty of seats for tired legs all around the loop

4386.title: Playground
4386.summary: There is a nice playground here which is a perfect spot for the kids to play while you have a breather!

4387.title: Lots of native flora
4387.summary: There are many native trees planted or protected along the walk. The signs explain what type trees you are looking at.

4388.title: Continue the loop or go elsewhere
4388.summary: There are plenty of signs to let you know where you are and where you can go. At this point you can leave the loop by heading north or east onto other paths

4389.title: Residential Street
4389.summary: This section of the walk takes you along a residential street, there are good footpaths  along both side

4390.title: The Stables Playground
4390.summary: This playground is huge and very cool! Hours of fun for everyone!

4391.title: Plenty of seats
4391.summary: There are plenty of seats along the way, both shaded and sunny
